INSERT INTO `application` (`application-id`, `study-id`, `row`, `date`) VALUES
(1, 1, 'Paul instructed his son in the faith (Timothy) to remain at Ephesus to regulate the teachings of the newly saved church; a similar assignment continues for us today. The big question to every TACEF member is, “Can you be trusted to preserve the move of revival in your local church? “Many of us easily get distracted when we are entrusted with the responsibility of carrying the burden of the vision. The activities in the church and personal ambition often shift our minds away from the primary reason why God caused us to remain in the church. Many have taken on many assignments that God did not give to them in a quest to please people or to gain prominence, at the detriment of the principal reason of defending the Gospel and mandate of revival. Some will even sacrifice the fellowship meeting time to attend other activities that can give them financial and political benefits.', '2018-02-15 13:00:14'),
(2, 1, 'Beloved, can you be trusted to uphold and defend the cause of revival on your campus or in your local church, even when others have left. It is very sad these days when we see a TACEFite leave the mandate of discipleship to church activities in a quest for personal gain.<br/>Paul’s effort in Ephesus did not waste away even in his absence, unlike many of us whose fellowship collapse as soon as some leaders exit, relocate, or gain admission. We must have a strong sense of service that whatever work is committed into our care must not collapse or be reduced in our hands, just as young Timothy stood firm on the assignment of preserving God’s move in Ephesus.\n', '2018-02-15 13:00:14'),
(3, 2, 'Today, certain individuals peddle false teachings for many reasons. One of the more common motives in our modern era is money. These “pastors” and “teachers” know that if they tell their disciples what they want to hear and make it sound good, they will “deceive the hearts of the simple” (Rom. 16:17–18). They do not serve our Lord Jesus but their own belly, and use enticing words and fair speeches to deceive their flock into parting with their money. Their preaching is to a “god” who is like a money-doubler. They will tell you to sow one to get millions, not out of a cheerful or a ready heart but more out of covetousness and total greed. All these are gross misapplication of sowing and reaping bountifully (2 Cor. 9:6).', '2018-02-15 13:05:48'),
(4, 2, 'No wonder many “men of God” today unapologetically parade the wealth they have amassed from their flock over the years, showing off their many houses, luxurious cars, etc. Nothing is wrong with wealth, as God Himself gives us richly all things to enjoy (1 Tim. 6:17), and one of TACEF’s 3Ws is of course wealth; the error we are referring to here is getting money by using false doctrines to mislead people. This falsehood can only bring the judgement of God.', '2018-02-15 13:05:48'),
(5, 2, 'As a fellowship, we strongly encourage ourselves to stand against all the “white garment church” practices that some people are now bringing into the church. We must stand firm, in maturity and in wisdom against erroneous teachings like using eggs, brooms, and other elements to pray. These are nothing but modern forms of witchcraft. Never join a minister who asks you to go to a particular junction to pray in the middle of the night or those who give you some strange names to pray with, names that are different from the only name we have been given in heaven and on earth—the Lord Jesus!', '2018-02-15 13:05:48'),
(6, 2, 'Be careful also when you hear men whose prayers are full of quotes from traditions, proverbs, and mythologies not based on the Bible. For a Yoruba speaker, be alarmed when a preacher prays like, “Odoodun la n ri orogbo . . .” The preacher is alluding that our continued existence is guaranteed on the basis that ordinary bitter kola yields its seed on annual basis and not on the fact that our lives are hidden in Christ and Christ in God (Col. 3:3). What a disastrous error of idolatry—comparing and placing God side by side with what He created!', '2018-02-15 13:05:48'),
(7, 2, 'No man of God, no matter how popular or how celebrated, is greater than the Word of God. Be warned and be not deceived even when they say, “God told me.” Ask if it is the same God of the Bible or another God that we do not know. It is not an act of pride but an act of spiritual survival!', '2018-02-15 13:05:48'),
(8, 3, 'How healthy are our local fellowships today? What spiritual meals are we feeding on and can we discern which is junk or poison?', '2018-02-15 13:11:07'),
(9, 3, 'Sound doctrine, like a good meal must be well cooked in the crucibles of grace and must be certified to be balanced diet. The cook must also be confirmed to be a true and experienced cook who has good testimony. How many of us will be willing to eat food cooked by kids during their daddy and mummy playtime? We know good cooking takes experience; hence, we all have nostalgia for our parents and grandparents’ food even in old age.', '2018-02-15 13:11:07'),
(10, 3, 'In our spiritual growth, we must raise fellowships where the total Gospel is preached with Biblical balance to ensure we have sound spiritual environment that breeds healthy, spiritual taste.', '2018-02-15 13:11:07'),
(11, 3, 'Law as seen in this study is an example of extreme teaching that breeds error – when we focus on the Gospel that forces people to talk, relate, eat or dress in a particular way without an inner conviction or an external reality that is underpinned by an inner grace. Can you imagine a sister who comes to fellowship with a heart of criticism against another sister who is wearing earring? It will then shock you on the wedding day of this criticising sister when she is fully colour-coated by facial designers and with designer beads dangling on her ear and neck – of course, for the first time! The question is, “Who is deceiving who?” Law breeds pretence, fake and double lives; it cuts our hearts from the grace of God and shift our focus from the major unto minor.', '2018-02-15 13:11:07'),
(12, 3, 'Extreme teaching is like feeding only on carbohydrates and expecting to have normal growth. It will not happen! Except we add protein, vitamin, and other body health essentials. There must be a balance where holiness, sanctification, moderation, prayer, faith, intercession, consecration, baptism of the Holy Spirit, righteous living, sacrificial living/giving, discipleship, divine blessing, prophetic, divine leading, rapture, excellence in life, and other Biblical teachings are taught in perfect balance without adding or taking from the Word of God.', '2018-02-15 13:11:07'),
(13, 3, 'Let us make effort to be a balanced Christian who is thoroughly furnished unto every good work.', '2018-02-15 13:11:07'),
(14, 4, 'The magnitude of God’s grace showered upon undeserving sinners, through the suffering of His Son Jesus Christ, is something that we should all continue to stand in total wonder of, no matter how long since we were saved. Many years of walking in His grace and mercy can slowly cause us to forget that we were once filthy, depraved sinners until the Lord Jesus rescued us. The popular hymn “Amazing Grace” was written by a man called John Newton, who is a practical example of our lesson today.', '2018-02-15 13:17:09'),
(15, 4, 'John Newton was a wild, drunken sailor. His language was so foul that the captain, hardly a model of piety, rebuked him! He was often put in irons and whipped for his rebellion. He became a slave trader, falling even further into sin. He narrowly escaped death a number of times. Finally, after nearly perishing in a severe storm at sea, he turned to God and was saved. Even so, he remained in slave trading for a few years. Eventually, by God’s grace, he became a pastor. You probably know him for writing the hymn, “Amazing Grace.” He wrote Deuteronomy 15:15 in bold letters and put it over the mantle of his study, where he could not fail to see it: “Thou shalt remember that thou wast a bondman in the land of Egypt and the Lord thy God redeemed thee.”', '2018-02-15 13:17:09'),
(16, 4, 'He also wrote his own epitaph, which read, “John Newton, clerk, once an infidel and libertine, a servant of slaves in Africa, was, by the rich mercy of our Lord and Saviour, Jesus Christ, preserved, restored, pardoned, and appointed to preach the faith he had long laboured to destroy.” ', '2018-02-15 13:17:09'),
(17, 4, 'This amazing grace truly transforms the recipient from the inside out. Most of us have heard of people who were once murderers, armed robbers, occultists, prostitutes, and even atheists, who had encounters with the Lord and became completely new persons—on many occasions becoming great preachers of the same Gospel that saved their souls.', '2018-02-15 13:17:09'),
(18, 4, 'We should forever be indebted to God for such an unspeakable blessing through the Lord Jesus Christ our Saviour. This sense of gratitude must provoke us to reach out to others and to remain committed to the vision of revival because we are not in any way better than those who have not seen the light; grace only made the difference, hence we must be committed to see that others enjoy the same privilege.', '2018-02-15 13:17:09'),
(19, 4, 'Are you grateful for your gift of salvation? What are you doing to make this gift of salvation count for the salvation of others?', '2018-02-15 13:17:09'),
(20, 5, 'The Holy Bible abounds with examples of how God used prophetic utterances through his servants to help people overcome certain circumstances.', '2018-02-15 13:21:54'),
(21, 5, 'TACEF is a fellowship that was birthed, nurtured, and guided through the wings of the gifts of prophecies. The voice of the Lord was audibly dissected to understand various milestones in the growth and evolution of the fellowship. God’s instruction through prophecy led to specific partnerships, leadership engagement, and many expansions of the vision were downloaded through the power of prophecy, as it pleased the Lord to speak to His people every time.', '2018-02-15 13:21:54'),
(22, 5, 'It is important to note that it is God who determines when, how, and where to speak and it happens when we are in an on-going fellowship with Him or staying long in His presence. It is unbiblical to go and meet someone to prophesy on you—as if prophecy is what can be controlled or place demand on. It is a total error because unlike speaking in tongues, which we can control as we like, prophecy comes by the Spirit of God—and no man can decide to do it at will.', '2018-02-15 13:21:54'),
(23, 5, 'Prophecy comes as you stay in fellowship, prayers and fasting either alone or in the presence of other believers, as a part of a recurring cycle of a lifestyle of consecrated service unto the Lord. Do not be tricked by these lying prophets who ask people to make a prophet’s offering, so as to receive a prophecy. Prophecies are not for sale; they come by the spirit when we are living holy and honourable lives that are full of reasonable service before the Lord.', '2018-02-15 13:21:54'),
(24, 6, 'Since the earliest centuries of the Gospel being spread around the world, there have been several testimonies of how intercessory prayer played a key role and made a difference in regions that were once hostile to the Lord Jesus. Hudson Taylor was a great man of God from Britain who greatly influenced China. The following is a true story of how the intercessions of an unknown believer moved God to bring more souls to Christ through Hudson Taylor’s ministry:', '2018-02-15 13:26:59'),
(25, 6, 'A number of years ago, a man with the China Inland Mission was looking over the records of that work. At one station, the number and spiritual strength of the converts far exceeded anyone’s expectations and could not be accounted for by anything unusual or outstanding about the personnel there. The mystery was unsolved until Hudson Taylor visited England. There, at the close of his message, a gentleman from the audience came forward to greet Taylor. In the ensuing conversation, Taylor learnt that the man possessed detailed knowledge of this particular mission station. “How is it,” asked Taylor, “that you are so conversant with the conditions of that work?” “Oh,” he replied, “for four years I have corresponded with my missionary friend there. He has sent me the names of inquirers and converts, and I have daily taken these to God in prayer.” Taylor suddenly realized the answer to the mystery: the daily, specific prayers of this man in England had brought eternal fruit for God’s glory in China.', '2018-02-15 13:26:59'),
(26, 6, 'Never underestimate God’s willingness to extend His mercy to lost souls after hearing the petitions of His people. A country like Nigeria desperately needs God’s people today to stand in the gap and make a difference in the lives of our fellow citizens, and in the lives of all.', '2018-02-15 13:26:59'),
(27, 6, 'Our church needs our genuine heartfelt intercession for God’s true move to happen.', '2018-02-15 13:26:59'),
(28, 7, 'Christianity requires moderation. It is a call unto self-control, orderliness, and discipline. We cannot live in excesses or carry over the worldly practice unto Christ. As soon as we receive the Lord, He takes over as the Master and thus is in full charge of our lives. All the dogmas of women liberation, modern-day idolatry, and body attachments or tattoos that have demonic influence must be consciously dealt with.', '2018-02-15 13:31:48'),
(29, 7, 'We have a lot to learn from a recent post of Pastor Mike Bamiloye on social media, as follows:', '2018-02-15 13:31:48'),
(30, 7, '“When a sister dresses seductively ‘to kill’ and dances sensually during praises and worships, to slay, is she not a ‘hired assassin’ sent amidst us to truncate the mandate?', '2018-02-15 13:31:48'),
(31, 7, 'What do we do with our Christian sisters who seductively dress up provocatively as instruments of demonic setup against the children and men of God?', '2018-02-15 13:31:48'),
(32, 7, 'Topless blouse, tight miniskirts, transparent gowns, etc. If they were TV channels, we would turn them off. If they were computer window pop-up, we would set filters against them to prevent them from popping up.”', '2018-02-15 13:31:48'),
(33, 8, 'Below is a story that adequately describes the state of many Christians today in relation to their services to God:', '2018-02-15 13:36:14'),
(34, 8, 'A man used to visit a tiny country general store that had a clerk named Jake who seemed to be the laziest man on earth. One day he noticed that Jake wasn’t around, so he asked the proprietor, “Where’s Jake?” “Oh, Jake retired,” the proprietor answered. “Retired, huh?” the man replied. “What are you going to do to fill the vacancy?” The owner replied, “Jake didn’t leave no vacancy!” ', '2018-02-15 13:36:14'),
(35, 8, 'I’m concerned that the same thing could be said of so many Christians with regard to their services for Christ: “They didn’t leave no vacancy!” We Christians should leave a vacancy when we move on, because we are all called to serve the Lord Jesus Christ [derived from the works of Steven J. Cole]. ', '2018-02-15 13:36:14'),
(36, 8, 'The role of practical, hands-on service seems to be shunned the most. Some do desire to be pastors, teachers, and choristers, among others. But fewer and fewer want anything at all to do with sweeping and mopping floors, cleaning toilets, windows, and other similarly necessary chores.', '2018-02-15 13:36:14'),
(37, 8, 'The point is to find a place where you can help as the Lord has enabled and called you to serve. Whatever the role, God is looking at the heart and He has the right reward for those who serve according to His own terms. ', '2018-02-15 13:36:14'),
(38, 9, 'The church is the house of God where the mystery of Christ is revealed, so our conduct must indicate that we understand this mystery. This is evident in our attitude to fellowship and everything that has to do with the gathering of God’s people.', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(39, 9, 'It is lack of kingdom behaviour when we take fellowship or church items without permission. It is unbecoming when we come to the fellowship without our Bible, manual, or jotter. We do not go to school without carrying our books. How then have we become so disrespectful and lose our sense of right behaviour in the church and fellowship?', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(40, 9, 'How can we explain that the brother or sister who has been told few days before to lead a session of worship, prayer, or Bible study did not prepare well in advance as someone who has been tasked to lead God’s people on the ground of truth. This is nothing but a spiritual misbehaviour that must stop henceforth. The imperative of having the right enthusiasm is important when we are tasked with God’s work. We must be energetic, excited, and well-prepared for every opportunity given to us to do anything on this ground of truth. Never be begged, coerced, or bullied by the leader to clean the seats or take offerings. Always be excited to do it as unto the Lord.', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(41, 9, 'How can a leader come late to an executive meeting or prayer gathering and forget he owes everyone an apology? Does he think he is higher than the Lord who has gathered everyone? It is a serious concern that we are losing our sense of reasonable behaviour in the church; hence, our gathering can allow all kinds of misbehaviours, which weaken the respect of the world towards the church.', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(42, 9, 'The worst misbehaviour today is opening our altars to comedians, popular Nollywood actors, and even worldly musicians to desecrate the altar of God because we have lost what we need to draw people unto God and resort to alternatives in the use of gimmicks. If we respectfully understand that the church is a ground of truth, we will only allow these “special guests” to sit down in the pews to listen to the message that will lead to their salvation and not allow them to make a shameless mockery of the deep mystery of Christ, while we all sit and laugh away the precious legacies of the church with fun and excitement.', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(43, 9, 'May the Lord grant us a new sense of caution and respect to provoke right behaviours in the name of our Lord Jesus. Amen.', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(44, 9, '<b>MUST DO:</b> Each fellowship, subgroup and family is encouraged this week to discuss practical examples of right behaviours and decorum that must be seen  in our coming together either as family altar, fellowship, subgroup meetings or organised programmes like conventions.', '2018-02-15 20:48:42'),
(45, 10, 'Evidently, the apostasy Paul spoke of is already taking effect in our world today. Many have left the fundamental truths of the Lord Jesus Christ and have given heed to perverse doctrines.', '2018-02-15 20:55:24'),
(46, 10, 'One example is the so-called “grail message,” which has grown popular in Nigeria and many other parts of the world. The false teacher who initiated this demonic doctrine is Oskar Ernst Bernhardt, also called Ab-ru-shin, in the 1930s in Germany. This message on the surface is quite enlightening, but it explicitly denies that the Lord Jesus died for the sins of mankind. It instead teaches that He was the Son of God who was murdered after bringing light and truth to humanity. They believe that the blood of the Lord Jesus was not shed to atone for man’s sins and that salvation is only earned by obeying the will of the Creator after learning His will through many cycles of reincarnation. How erroneous is this fallacy!', '2018-02-15 20:55:24'),
(47, 10, 'The seduction of the grail message is strong but subtle, because it speaks positively on various topics concerning God, His creation, and human existence. It is no wonder that many intellectuals and academic find it to be exciting and an alternative to the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-15 20:55:24'),
(48, 10, 'Biblical prophecy points to such delusions only getting worse, as we draw closer to the end of the age. We must put on “the whole armour of God,” so that we may be able to stand against the “wiles” of the devil (Eph. 6:11).', '2018-02-15 20:55:24'),
(49, 10, 'Do not be deceived by these new doctrines; nothing is new to know other than what we have learnt in the Bible. Let us be careful of the so-called new truth that takes us away from the timeless truth.', '2018-02-15 20:55:24'),
(50, 11, 'The boxer, runner, footballer, and other athletes train rigorously with the aim of obtaining the trophy or medal one day. Nobody is training for the fun of it; there is a sense of an end. We cannot achieve much in our Christian race if we do not have a focussed view of where we are going.', '2018-02-15 21:00:01'),
(51, 11, 'It is this sense of destination that enables disciples to “strip off” those things that will only distract them from their goal. Paul showed us there are things that are not sins in themselves but are ultimately unprofitable since they do not edify spiritually (1 Cor. 10:23). In our modern era, this may include things like watching too much TV, attending too many parties (even those you are not invited to but you can “hear and branch”), spending too much time with the wrong people, too much self-promotion on social media (postings like, “See my new dress,” “I just arrived London,” “Cruising my latest car with grace”).', '2018-02-15 21:00:01'),
(52, 11, 'There is no shortcut to godliness. Disciplined exercise is the only way to travel to get to our destination. And as long as we are on this present earth we will need to continue to exercise ourselves in godliness, or else we will get out of shape. When we get out of shape, we become spiritual amoeba, with no form or consistent manner; we can become anything at any time to please anyone.', '2018-02-15 21:00:01'),
(53, 11, 'Today we live in a “quick fix,” “instant noodles” generation. Everybody wants a quick solution to the problem. As Christians, we should see that God has not provided any shortcut to holiness. Without thorough Bible study and consistent quiet time with disciplined prayer life, there will be no growth. This also goes for every other spiritual exercise like fasting and daily walk of holiness.', '2018-02-15 21:00:01'),
(54, 11, 'Develop your spiritual muscle now to be able to carry the demands of life. Many crumbled by the wayside because they only exercised themselves for a 1-km race, only to discover that the reality of life is a call unto a nonstop 50-km journey. May we not fall on the way and may our spiritual stamina, earned through consistent exercise, provide us the momentum to keep fit unto the last days, in the name of the Lord Jesus. Amen.', '2018-02-15 21:00:01'),
(55, 12, 'It is a serious concern in our times that the name of the Lord has been diminished or even blasphemed because many of us have failed to be examples of believers in every facet of our lives. They have looked down on us and have looked down on our Lord Jesus Christ because we failed to address our weaknesses. They have despised the Lord because our lives presented a weakness that contradicts the truth of what we preach. We preach that the Lord Jesus is love but our touchy, uncaring, disconnected, and lonely attitude continue to give a wrong impression of who the Lord Jesus is to our families, friends, colleagues, and neighbours.', '2018-02-15 21:04:41'),
(56, 12, 'Kingdom life does not allow excuses. Let us reflect on how odd this mandate may appear to Timothy since we do not have any control over what others might think about us. In his own case, he was an obvious victim of age discrimination, yet Paul demanded that since he was aware that this could pose a risk to how his ministry was perceived, he must behave in such a way that no one could reasonably despise his youth. He was to act with greater maturity and wisdom. Like Timothy, it is completely unacceptable for us to use our situation to justify our inability, for being young is not a license to act stupidly or immaturely. No excuse must bring any dishonour to the name of the Lord and make us an object that is looked down on by many who are meant to look up to us. If we understand that the name of the Lord can be despised by our obvious limitations (e.g., poor command of the English language, impatient reactions, dull deportment, careless speaking, occasional use of worldly slangs, excessive passion for a football club, and even a bad working culture with others), then we must make a reasonable decision to change to protect the integrity of the Gospel.', '2018-02-15 21:04:41'),
(57, 13, 'To get an illustration of the principle of necessity to correct error, let us read these words from Pastor Steven Cole:', '2018-02-16 09:11:15'),
(58, 13, '“If you’ve ever done any boating, you know how essential it is to stay on course. If you steer just a few degrees off the desired course, you can wind up far from where you wanted to go. I read once of a shipwreck that happened because a sailor broke off the small tip of his knife blade while he was cleaning the ship’s compass. He didn’t remove it, and that little bit of metal pulled the compass off its true reading, resulting in the ship’s running aground. A slight deviation, if left uncorrected, can result in great devastation.”', '2018-02-16 09:11:15'),
(59, 13, 'This is a good picture of the damage that even a small sin can cause. Paul said, “a little leaven leavens the whole lump” (1 Cor. 5:6). Many Christians have destroyed their walk with God by leaving some small sins unchecked for an extended period of time. This could have been avoided if a caring brother had confronted them and pointed out the danger by using the Scripture. We must from now on love our neighbour more practically, including the mature act of correction in a godly way and not permitting sin in their lives.', '2018-02-16 09:11:15'),
(60, 13, 'As the Lord Jesus warned us, we must always check out hearts to know the motive behind the act of correction. Is it to ridicule the individual or to help the person? Is it to raise godly standards or just to show that you are the one in charge? Is it to correct unto righteousness or to frustrate unto further iniquities?', '2018-02-16 09:11:15'),
(61, 13, 'The sincerity of the process is also proven when we do it with high sense of responsibility that we can also fall into the same error. We must be humble and not judgemental. Let us not attack the person, but instead help the person attack the problem.', '2018-02-16 09:11:15'),
(62, 13, 'Always remember the aim of the process is recovery; we want the person to be restored and thus escape the harmful consequences that sin brings.', '2018-02-16 09:11:15'),
(63, 14, 'Charles Spurgeon once had the officers of a small country church asked him to recommend a pastor for them. But the salary they were prepared to pay was so small that he wrote back to them, “The only individual I know, who could exist on such a stipend, is the angel Gabriel. He would need neither cash nor clothes; and he could come down from heaven every Sunday morning, and go back at night, so I advise you to invite him” (Autobiography [Banner of Truth], 2:108).', '2018-02-16 09:14:37'),
(64, 14, 'The obvious point that C.H. Spurgeon was making is that a pastor is a human being like the rest of us and, therefore, has material needs. They have family and children to take care of. They need food, clothing, shelter, transportation, phone expenses, pay school fees, and other necessities. If God has indeed appointed them to be leaders, discerning Christians should be able to rise and follow the demand of the Scripture that these should be well compensated and not denied of the benefits of serving the will of God.', '2018-02-16 09:14:37'),
(65, 14, 'Of necessity, every minister genuinely chosen by God is worthy of double honour, as well as our full support on consistent basis. Inasmuch as the church will pay their salaries, individual members of the church must not forget to support them on a consistent basis with gifts in cash and in kind. However, the act of support must be done with “honour,” that is, with high sense of respect and dignity, as we have learnt this week and not with the mind-set of “we are the ones paying his children school fees.” If we give with intent to disregard or scorn, we have failed the demand of honour. We must also be discreet when we give such that it is not done openly with an intent to show off.', '2018-02-16 09:14:37'),
(66, 14, 'Moreover, full-time ministers must be fully persuaded of their calling and know that they must make full proof of their full-time ministry or else they should seek for a supporting job just as Paul worked as a tentmaker. It is of necessity that full-time ministers must have a double prayer life to be deserving of any double honour. It is the impact of their labour in word and in prayer as a full-time minister that will spiritually open the doors of blessing to them, even as their spiritual consecration creates the right atmosphere where members see testimonies of genuine repentance, transformation in the lives of their children, healing, and breakthroughs, among others. Of course, no minister deserves double honour when he is not making double spiritual investment in the lives of the people who listen to him. You cannot claim to serve God in ministry on a full time basis and live a part time lifestyle!', '2018-02-16 09:14:37'),
(67, 15, 'It is a reasonable service to present our bodies healthy and in optimal state of well-being. What is the importance of a body that has become tired and weak at age 50 and cannot go far with the Lord? It is a foolish loss when a Christian dies as a result of bad health behaviour and irresponsible physical health management.', '2018-02-16 09:21:48'),
(68, 15, 'Can you imagine that some Christians, who are already above 40 do not go for annual medical checkup and are clueless about their weight or blood pressure. One of the most trending news of 2016 was Pastor E. A. Adeboye’s admonition that all RCCG pastors must go for regular medical checkup to avoid unnecessary and sudden deaths, if the proper thing is done. He has also advised that it is important we place spiritual considerations side by side with healthy lifestyle choices. At the 2017 Convention of the church, he personally led many members on a 7-km physical walk around the camp.', '2018-02-16 09:21:48'),
(69, 15, 'We must be aware of the healthy choices we make with the kind of food we eat, even when we eat. It has been proven that foods eaten late in the night are not digested and may become a basis for future sickness. How disciplined are we when it comes to sugary food and how aware are we on the healthy implications of indulgences in noodles, spaghetti, ice cream, cakes, meat pie, and other instant foods? It has been proven repeatedly that many sicknesses are caused by poor eating habits while others are caused by sinful indulgences or violation of divine laws. Ensure both sides are properly taken care of.', '2018-02-16 09:21:48'),
(70, 15, 'As Christians, we must endeavour to eat foods that are nutritionally beneficial, exercise as necessary, and abstain from illegal drugs and even self-medication that can alter or damage the natural functioning of our internal system.', '2018-02-16 09:21:48'),
(71, 15, '<b>N.B:</b> You are advised to consider a NO-JUNK challenge in the TACEF Seed of Purpose developmental programme.', '2018-02-16 09:21:48'),
(72, 16, 'It is a painful reality these days that Christians can be the worst employers and employees. The excellence and values of the kingdom are completely missing in our workplace. Many of our colleagues at work can never believe we are in any way associated with the Lord Jesus based on how we have aligned in acts of cheating, late coming, examination practices, and fraud, among others. ', '2018-02-16 09:25:49'),
(73, 16, 'Martin Luther was renowned as a great revivalist and someone who spoke about turning our work into our ministry post. He said, “The maid who sweeps her kitchen is doing the will of God just as much as the monk who prays—not because she may sing a Christian hymn as she sweeps but because God loves clean floors. The Christian shoemaker does his Christian duty not by putting little crosses on the shoes, but by making good shoes, because God is interested in good craftsmanship.”', '2018-02-16 09:25:49'),
(74, 16, 'How does the essence of the Lord Jesus Christ find expression in your work?', '2018-02-16 09:25:49'),
(75, 17, 'Prosperity is our portion in Christ and part of the covenant of salvation, just as carbohydrate is part of our body requirement for a balanced diet. If we just eat only eba, rice, and amala without other classes of food, we open ourselves up to excessive sugar. This is the fate of many Christians who have become stuck on prosperity message for too long. They are now suffering from “spiritual diabetes.” Like physical diabetes, they have many bruises and wounds of sins that are not healing up because they are perpetually ridiculing the work at Calvary.', '2018-02-16 10:02:36'),
(76, 17, 'Many of these ministers who enjoy this gain are also known not to be accountable or transparent in how they manage and dispense God’s resources in their care. It is very difficult to separate between the church account and private expenses of these ministers and this does not convey an imagery of a serious people to the world. Recent investigations in different parts of the world on these ministries have shown worrisome facts about some “unholy” acts that could have been avoided if basic governance, transparency, and accountability principles have been respected.', '2018-02-16 10:02:36'),
(77, 17, 'In administering the gift for the poor saints in Jerusalem, Paul was careful to have several other men of good reputation travel with him, “taking precaution that no one should discredit us in our administration of this generous gift; for we have regard for what is honourable, not only in the sight of the Lord, but also in the sight of men” (2 Cor. 8:20–21, NAS). Paul allowed no room for rumours to start that he was living in luxury by appropriating for himself the money, which had been given to the poor saints in Jerusalem.', '2018-02-16 10:02:36'),
(78, 17, 'Beloved, let us be clear that godliness should never be a means to gain, but our focus should be the true doctrine of the Gospel, which many lost souls are in desperate need of. Our focus is on making heaven and not on money!', '2018-02-16 10:02:36'),
(79, 18, 'Ben Carson recently shared on his social media platform a story, which is worth exploring to learn how to run the right race and not rat race.', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(80, 18, '<i>“I was jogging this morning and I noticed a person about 1/2 a kilometer ahead. I could tell he was running a little slower than me and I thought, good, I shall try to catch him. I had about a kilometer before I needed to turn off. So I started running faster and faster. </i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(81, 18, '<i>Every block, I was gaining on him just a little bit. After just a few minutes I was only about 100 meters behind him, so I really picked up the pace and pushed myself. You would have thought I was running in the last leg of an Olympic competition. I was determined to catch him. </i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(82, 18, '<i>Finally, I did it! I caught and passed him. On the inside, I felt so good. ‘I beat him.’ Of course, he didn’t even know we were racing.</i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(83, 18, '<i>After I passed him, I realized I had been so focused on competing against him that I had missed my turn. I had gone nearly six blocks past my turn and I had to turn and go back. </i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(84, 18, '<i>Isn’t that what happens in life when we focus on competing with co-workers, neighbours, friends, family, trying to outdo them or trying to prove that we are more successful or more important? </i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(85, 18, '<i>We spend our time and energy running after them and we miss out on our own paths to our God-given destinies.</i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(86, 18, '<i>The problem with unhealthy competition is that it’s a never ending cycle. There will always be somebody ahead of you, someone with a better job, nicer car, more money in the bank, more education, a prettier wife, a more handsome husband, better behaved children, etc.</i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(87, 18, '<i>But realize that “You can be the best that you can be, when you are not competing with anyone.” </i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(88, 18, '<i>Some people are insecure because they pay too much attention to what others are, where others are going, wearing and driving. </i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(89, 18, '<i>Take what God has given you, the height, weight and personality. Dress well and wear it proudly, you’ll be blessed by it. Stay focused and live a healthy life. There is no competition in Destiny.</i>', '2018-02-16 10:12:45'),
(90, 19, 'The love of money is the root of all evils and that is why having money will not solve the root problems of greed and lustful desires.', '2018-02-16 10:17:10'),
(91, 19, 'A recent statistics showed that poor people who won lotteries die prematurely. Facts say that as much as 70 per cent end up bankrupt with nothing to show for what they have won. An expert actually said, “People who were ordinary people all of a sudden become extraordinary . . . they\'re overjoyed. They lose all sense of reality. They think they\'re invincible and powerful. They think they are supermen.” They end up having nothing because of their greed to have everything, which is actually the root of the problem.', '2018-02-16 10:17:10'),
(92, 19, 'For example, in 2003, a factory worker Dennis Elwell committed suicide by drinking cyanide seven months after winning £92,000 in the U.K. lotto. Henry Patnaude of Manchester won so many pounds in a lottery and few months later was found dead by suicide.', '2018-02-16 10:17:10'),
(93, 19, 'We must deal with our greed early enough or it will set us on an unending sail of no end. May the God help us in the Lord Jesus’ name.', '2018-02-16 10:17:10'),
(94, 20, 'It is reflective to look back and see how our faith fathers fought the good fight of faith. For them, it was either the Lord Jesus or they lose their lives. They were willing to take the most ridiculous risk for the sake of the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ. Nothing was more important than the joy of dying for their Lord and Saviour. They were glad to throw away the pleasures of the world, endure the ridicule of identification, and perpetually lay hold on eternity.', '2018-02-16 10:21:41'),
(95, 20, 'Bible history has it that many Christians were fed to lions in Rome. Apostle Peter was crucified, upside down at his request, since he did not feel he was worthy to die in the same manner as his Lord. Matthew was reportedly stabbed to death in Ethiopia while James was stoned and then clubbed to death. John the beloved was thrown into boiling oil at Rome, even though he did not die.', '2018-02-16 10:21:41'),
(96, 20, 'What have you sacrificed for the Lord? How are you laying hold on eternity? How are you fighting the good fight of faith?', '2018-02-16 10:21:41'),
(97, 21, 'This is a deep reflection based on maintaining a stubborn resolve for the Lord in these last days. If we are truly persuaded by our understanding of the God that we serve, how can we be deceived at any time to compromise our integrity and testimony? The weight of Him whom we serve should deepen our sense of commitment. Be excited to know that we are dealing with the God of heaven and earth and thus we can be confident that He is able to keep us.', '2018-02-16 10:28:57'),
(98, 21, 'A story was told recently about how young Christians in Iraq are taking a stand against the Islamic State (ISIS)—even if it costs them their lives. ISIS militants gave four Iraqi children the choice of converting to Islam or death by beheading, the children chose to follow the Lord Jesus. They preserved their testimony even at risk of death. The children, all under-15, declared, “No, we love Yesua (the Iraqi name for Jesus), we have always loved Yesua, we have always followed Yesua, Yesua has always been with us.”', '2018-02-16 10:28:57'),
(99, 21, 'The terrorists beheaded all four children in most painful circumstances.', '2018-02-16 10:28:57'),
(100, 21, 'This is just one of several real-life examples of Christians who have kept the integrity of their witness under serious pressure. For many of us, the worst kind of persecution we face for our faith is at our secular workplace. But many others daily face threats of physical harm and sometimes death. Whatever the case may be, let us remain strong in the Lord Jesus Christ  as part of our reasonable service, knowing that the Sovereign God is in supreme control, and that the Lord Jesus Himself is the resurrection and the eternal life. Those who remain faithful to the end are the ones who shall be saved (Matt. 10:22).', '2018-02-16 10:28:57'),
(101, 22, 'We must remember that we are God’s stewards and will one day give account of ourselves. Let us properly prepare ourselves against the time to come and lay hold on eternal life.', '2018-02-16 10:33:56'),
(102, 22, 'A great example of having a right relationship with God that leads to good management of money, is found in the legendary oil-industry businessman and philanthropist John D. Rockefeller Sr. He is estimated to be the wealthiest American of all time. He was a devoted Baptist Christian who believed all his success came from God. In his church, he taught Sunday school, served as a trustee, a clerk, and sometimes as a janitor (sweeping, cleaning, etc).', '2018-02-16 10:33:56'),
(103, 22, 'He was a philanthropist who used every opportunity to serve his fellow man, especially the needy and less privileged. He supported many church-based organisations, missionary work, and orphanages. He was very concerned about public health and pioneered the medical research that eradicated hookworm and yellow fever. Rockefeller also knew that education would help alleviate the poverty of many. He founded the General Education Board to promote education at all levels everywhere in America and was instrumental in the founding of the University of Chicago, Rockefeller University, and Central Philippine University in the Philippines.', '2018-02-16 10:33:56'),
(104, 22, 'How are you using the wealth that God has put in your care? Your faithfulness in “little” will determine how far God can trust you with much more as a faithful and trusted treasurer of His.', '2018-02-16 10:33:56'),
(105, 23, 'There are many through the church age who were raised by God-fearing parents, but down the road came to deep personal faith in Jesus which moved them into fearless ministry. Watchman Nee (Ni Tuosheng) was a Chinese man who lived and died in the 20th century. Both his parents were Methodist Christians, and he was baptised by a bishop as an infant. But it was not until he was 17 years old that he finally surrendered his life to Christ by faith. Below is his personal testimony:', '2018-02-16 10:38:47'),
(106, 23, '“On the evening of 28th April, 1920, I was alone in my room, struggling to decide whether or not to believe in the Lord. At first I was reluctant but as I tried to pray I saw the magnitude of my sins and the reality and efficacy of Jesus as the Saviour. As I visualised the Lord\'s hands stretched out on the cross, they seemed to be welcoming me and the Lord was saying, \"I am waiting here to receive you.\" Realising the effectiveness of Christ\'s blood in cleansing my sins and being overwhelmed by such love, I accepted Him there. Previously I had laughed at people who had accepted Jesus, but that evening the experience became real for me and I wept and confessed my sins, seeking the Lord\'s forgiveness. As I made my first prayer I knew joy and peace such as I had never known before. Light seemed to flood the room and I said to the Lord, \"Oh, Lord, you have indeed been gracious to me.\"”', '2018-02-16 10:38:47'),
(107, 23, 'He became an avid witness and proclaimer of the Gospel. In 1949, the Communist Revolution began, which was very hostile towards religion and Christianity in particular. Nee was persecuted and arrested in 1952 on bogus charges and spent the last 20 years of his life in prison, representing Christ and Biblical truth without fear.', '2018-02-16 10:38:47'),
(108, 23, 'One of the popular statements that summarises this is –“our deepest fear is not that we are inadequate. Our deepest fear is that we are powerful beyond measure. It is our light, not our darkness that most frightens us. We ask ourselves, who am I to be brilliant, gorgeous, talented, and fabulous? Actually, who are you not to be? You are a child of God. Your playing small does not serve the world. There is nothing enlightened about shrinking so that other people will not feel insecure around you. We are all meant to shine, as children do. We were born to make manifest the glory of God that is within us. It is not just in some of us; it is in everyone and as we let our own light shine, we unconsciously give others permission to do the same. As we are liberated from our own fear, our presence automatically liberates others.”', '2018-02-16 10:38:47'),
(109, 24, 'A reality of our time is that we all want to be politically right and socially acceptable; hence, we keep our allegiance to the Lord Jesus Christ away from our daily living. Many are not even known at work to be born again, because they want to avoid the ridicule of being known as a genuine child of God.', '2018-02-16 10:42:30'),
(110, 24, 'Many whose lives carved the path for us never hid anything to preserve the legacy of grace that we all enjoy today. They proudly celebrated their chains and treasured their allegiance to Jesus, no matter what it cost them.', '2018-02-16 10:42:30'),
(111, 24, 'What is the importance of the Lord Jesus who saved you, if you are hiding Him from your friends? If we appreciate what the Lord has done for us, we should be bold to publicly identify with Him and be glad to accept all the ridicule that may come as a result of this.', '2018-02-16 10:42:30'),
(112, 24, 'The world never burnt a casual Christian at the stake because they are not a threat to the devil’s kingdom. But as the popular quote says, “It has become a settled principle that nothing which is good and true can be destroyed by persecution, but that the effect ultimately is to establish more firmly, and to spread more widely, that which it was designed to overthrow. It has long since passed into a proverb that ‘the blood of the martyrs is the seed of the church.’”', '2018-02-16 10:42:30'),
(113, 24, 'May our labour of bearing the shame of the Lord Jesus Christ count to preserve His faith for the next generation. Amen.', '2018-02-16 10:42:30'),
(114, 25, '\r\nCorrie ten Boom was a Christian from the Netherlands, who lived from 1892 to 1983. She was a person who knew the Lord, along with her father and some other family members. In 1940, the Nazis invaded the Netherlands and severely persecuted the Jews. Corrie and her family helped many Jews escape the Nazi holocaust during World War 2. Due to the work of an informant, she was caught and imprisoned, but continued to faithfully serve God in the concentration camp. Corrie ten Boom was mysteriously released by a “clerical error” just one week before all the women in her age group were killed by the Nazis in a gas chamber.', '2018-02-16 14:40:24'),
(115, 25, 'When a person knows the Lord, he or she can confidently entrust his entire life to God’s gracious care. We can also confidently say, “I don’t know what the future holds, but I always know that God holds my future. I really do not need to know any more than that because the one in charge has all the details.”', '2018-02-16 14:40:24'),
(116, 25, 'We need not be afraid of uncertainties, we should just trust Him to take care of us and be certain He will never cheat us, as we humbly say of the Lord in the household of TACEF. For He is our Jehovah El-sorter, the Lord that will sort our today and tomorrow for His own glory.', '2018-02-16 14:40:24'),
(117, 26, 'In our Christian journey, moment of human disappointment will come. People whom you least expect will turn their backs on you. People whom you supported in their time of need will be the ones to tell everyone not to help you in your time of need, under the excuse that you caused your own problem. Sons and daughters whom you have carried in your loins of prayers may turn their backs on you. Expect the worst from man! <b>But let not the disappointment of men cut you off from the appointment of God!</b>', '2018-02-16 14:47:13'),
(118, 26, 'In the same vein, let us strive at all times to be an Onesipherous in our own little ways. Be a brother or a sister who can be trusted at all times. Be someone who stands with others even when they do not deserve it. Be a brother who respects relationships and will go the extra mile for others. Be a child of God who respects the trust that is reposed in you and be a friend who can be relied on at all times. Let us not be a fair-weather Christian, whose allegiance to people is subject to what we can get or not get.', '2018-02-16 14:47:13'),
(119, 26, 'Let us also understand that God is calling us to “refresh” everyone we meet. God wants us to leave them better than we met them with our words, gifts, prayers, patience, presence, kindness, and sharing. Our local ministers need to be refreshed by us and same for TACEFites who are full-time ministers under the auspices of Men on the Altar (MOTA). For true relationship is not measured in the pleasantness of the good times, but the bond of love that stays even in the worst seasons.', '2018-02-16 14:47:13'),
(120, 27, 'There is a well-known man called Smith Wigglesworth who saw the grace of God work mightily in his life. The Lord’s grace continually released strength that overcame obstacles which would surely have stopped his ministry from becoming what it became. This man was born in 1859 in England into a very poor family. He had ZERO education formally, not even nursery or primary school, and had to work twelve hours a day since he was 7 years old to help support the family. This contributed to a speech problem he had—an inability to clearly express himself. He got converted as a young boy and started telling others that Jesus was real. As a young adult he still could not speak properly, so he could not preach sermons. He became a plumber but still told people about Christ here and there. ', '2018-02-16 14:56:36'),
(121, 27, 'God’s grace was always upon him, but began to take strong effect in 1882 after he married his wife Polly, who taught him how to read. Then in 1907, he had an unusual encounter with the Holy Spirit and began to preach and express himself fluently that even his wife could not believe. This was the beginning of what turned into a worldwide ministry of preaching and healing numerous sick and dying people. God’s grace healed him of appendicitis and kidney stones. With these good news were the other side of life—his daughter suffered from a lifelong deafness and he also had to deal with the unexpected deaths of his wife and son. It was only God’s grace that kept him encouraged and gave him strength to continue in service to humanity after this. He heavily influenced the Pentecostal movement, and his words and books continue to build faith in readers up till today. May we learn not to rely on our own strength, but look totally to God. He is the One who does the impossible and gives us the victory that would not have come otherwise.', '2018-02-16 14:56:36'),
(122, 28, 'We have many great examples of faithful servants of God who were not only strong in the Scriptures, but strengthened others also; who then further passed the baton down to future generations. The vision of revival we cherish today was a commitment to transfer baton by faithful men and such loop must continue for us to fully experience the totality of God’s promise to revive His church. TACEF mandate is a calling to deposit into the church both spiritually and physically and not an exploitative game of what can be gotten from the church. Hence, it is our sacred principle that must be respected—that we do not reduce the vision to a level where we have to be begging to take from the church to attend a programme. TACEFites are called to give back to the church. We are called to sow in prayers, in knowledge, and in wealth to the church and not be on queue for the next crumb for survival. If as TACEFites we appreciate what we will get from a programme, then we must learn to invest our own money, except for instances where cheerful givers are led to bless us or when we are sincerely unable to afford it.', '2018-02-16 15:08:09'),
(123, 28, 'We celebrate the labours of the faith fathers who passed on the baton faithfully. We have read of John the beloved and how he was a great mentor and teacher to many of the next generation saints who preserved the initial post-apostles’ foundation of the church after many of the original 11 disciples were killed as martyrs. The church of God has come a long way since these great men have used every opportunity to DEPOSIT in the next generation. May we be granted a fresh impetus and drive to go forth as spiritual depositor, who will go forth with God’s Word, excellent preparation, humility, human sympathy, and boldness to expand God’s kingdom through the effective ministry of the Gospel of Christ.', '2018-02-16 15:08:09'),
(124, 29, 'Hardship, toughness, and patience are the hallmark of a Christian that wants to count for the Lord when it comes to reasonable service. God deserves thoroughness and it takes patience and longsuffering to commit to the combined rigours of an athlete, a farmer, and a military man.', '2018-02-16 15:13:12'),
(125, 29, 'A story is often told of the popular Chinese bamboo tree. In its first year though, we see no visible signs of growth in spite of providing all the required water, sunlight, and fertilizer. In the second year (again), there is no growth above the soil. The third, fourth year, still show no signs of anything happening. It is like patience is being tested, and the farmer begins to wonder if all the efforts caring for and watering the tree will ever be rewarded. He starts to doubt himself and question the value of his hard labour. He may even contemplate quitting.', '2018-02-16 15:13:12'),
(126, 29, 'But then, finally, in the fifth year, something amazing happens. The Chinese bamboo tree grows 80 feet tall in just six weeks! But think for a moment, does the Chinese bamboo tree really grow 80 feet in six weeks? Did the Chinese bamboo tree lie dormant for four years only to grow exponentially in the fifth? Or, was the little tree growing underground, developing a root system strong enough to support its potential for outward growth in the fifth year and beyond? The answer is of course obvious. Had the tree not developed a strong unseen foundation it could not have sustained its life as it grew.', '2018-02-16 15:13:12'),
(127, 29, 'As we labour in hardship in the mandate of reasonable service, we learn how to patiently toil towards worthwhile dreams and goals, building strong character while overcoming adversity and challenge because these tough paths prepare for us a strong internal foundation to handle success.', '2018-02-16 15:13:12'),
(128, 29, 'The exercise in Chinese bamboo plant is not for the microwave generation that wants to plant a seed today and reap the fruits the next day. There is no quick fix when it comes to the Chinese bamboo plant and the same principles for those who want to last in the scheme of heavenly race.', '2018-02-16 15:13:12'),
(129, 30, 'We all admire some great men of God on the pulpit, but oftentimes, we do not know some of the personal challenges they are individually facing. Some are bleeding with pain, yet they remain true to preaching about who the Lord Jesus is and what He can do. They never lowered the efficacy of the Gospel to their condition.', '2018-02-16 15:21:03'),
(130, 30, 'We have heard of many who had sickness in their bodies, which they were trusting God for to heal, yet they continued to minister about healings, with God proving Himself. A popular man of God, whom the Lord used to bless many families with the fruit of the womb, waited for many years for the same miracle, yet his situation did not reduce the quality of the Gospel of Christ he preached. He boldly spoke of God’s power to give children and never allowed his personal sentiment to reduce what God could do through him.', '2018-02-16 15:21:03'),
(131, 30, 'There are rough and tough sides of ministry, but none must replace our message or reduce our level of commitment and consecration to the Lord. Always remember that God will always be true to Himself at all times and the message we carry must continue undiluted no matter the circumstance of the messenger.', '2018-02-16 15:21:03'),
(132, 31, 'Martin Luther was a German Christian who showed himself approved by diligent study of God’s Word. He was raised in a heavily Catholic atmosphere at a time when the Roman Catholic Church had the monopoly on Scriptural truth and excommunicated anyone who challenged the supreme Scriptural authority of the Pope. But Luther found many problems with Catholic doctrines, especially in the issue of “indulgences,” which was a teaching where you pay money to the priests to have your sins forgiven and deleted. After continual study of the Word, Luther correctly concluded that a person is saved by the grace of God through faith in the Lord Jesus Christ, and not through the works, which the Catholic Church prescribed. He wrote the “95 theses,” which was the beginning of the Protestant Reformation and liberty from the erroneous doctrines of that time. Without comparing the truth of God’s Word with what he was being taught, he and millions of others would have remained in error and unnecessary bondage.', '2018-02-16 20:14:51'),
(133, 31, 'Today, many churches have strayed from God’s truth to promote their own doctrines, which many unsuspecting Christians have ignorantly accepted. The surest way for us to know and do God’s will is by being diligent to rightly divide His Word personally. God has called us to be workmen who need not be ashamed, and this is part of our reasonable service unto Him and humanity.', '2018-02-16 20:14:51'),
(134, 32, 'How far we go in God is how far we have determined to go. The ultimate decider is that God has chosen to make us something in His hand, but we must decide to purge ourselves for His use. Purging ourselves is not one-off, but a continuous daily experience. Paul warned us that we must actively flee from sin and pursue after godliness, in addition to spiritual routines that support our sanctification process—prayer (1 Thess. 5:23), faith (Acts 15:9), thought life (Phil. 4:8), and practical obedience to the words of the New Covenant. As we flee sin and pursue godliness with “them that call on the Lord out of a pure heart,” we will slowly but surely begin to cease from being conformed to this world, and will be transformed by the renewing of our minds more and more into the image of Christ (Rom. 12:2). ', '2018-02-16 20:19:23'),
(135, 32, 'As we purge ourselves and ponder on our own role in God’s house, it is important for us to remember that some people’s roles are more visible—and others have less visible parts to play. Yet everyone’s role is important and of great consequence. The nose is not necessarily better than the hand. If those working behind the scenes fail to do their part, those with more visible roles would not be able to do theirs. Let us not ever let the devil plagues us into thinking our role is unimportant because it is less visible than those of others. Our part is very important in God’s house! Let us just do our part unto honour and not unto dishonour!', '2018-02-16 20:19:23'),
(136, 32, 'In conclusion, we must also note that that the vessel is not to be honoured, but the vessel is to bring honour to the Lord. The vessel is not an end in itself; it is only a means to an end. God must always be the focus of our service and the fact that we are gold or silver vessels must not blind our eyes that being honourable does not mean we own the honour but ”He” that we represent.', '2018-02-16 20:19:23'),
(137, 33, 'It is painful these days when you hear people close their mind to the Lord Jesus because of the disagreeable approach of some believers in their attempt to preach the Gospel in a most quarrelsome way. We go extreme to the point that we make the Good News look like bad news to a man whose heart is closed. Many born-again wives have lost their homes because they wanted to force their unbelieving husbands to accept their new faith without any application of divine wisdom and caution. Many thought they have special heart-converting machine and have thus frustrated the cause of the Gospel instead of helping it.', '2018-02-16 20:23:56'),
(138, 0, 'A story was told about Lee Strobel born Jan. 25, 1952 (65 years old) in Illinois, USA. He was an avowed atheist who studied Law at respected universities including a master’s degree from Yale Law School. His wife got saved but the man remained an unbeliever in God. The woman remained very close to her atheist husband and deployed the power of being gentle, which skilfully motivated the husband towards Biblical truth. Thank God that he was granted repentance and escaped from the satanic snare of Atheism. May the Lord teach us how to use God-inspired wisdom to lead our siblings, families, friends, neighbours, and many others to the Lord without debates and quarrelsome attitude. ', '2018-02-16 20:23:56'),
(139, 33, 'The impact of his salvation was momentous and of course he went even farther than the wife in his commitment. He became a church pastor from 1987 to 2000 before moving into writing and producing his TV programme, Faith Under Fire. He has written many truth-directed books including the best-selling Case for Christ.', '2018-02-16 20:23:56'),
(140, 34, 'The history of the church is filled with heretical sects whose leaders initiated false teachings that spread to unsuspecting, naïve victims. But God’s people always withstood the test of time, while those who only had a form of godliness vanished away, until a new sect arose with their own set of falsehoods and faded away with time, and so it continued to this present modern era. The false Christians of many of these sects were just as wicked and ungodly as the men were in the perilous times of the last days which Paul spoke of.', '2018-02-16 20:29:41'),
(141, 34, 'Decades ago, cult leader Jim Jones of People’s Temple in America ran a church as a community-oriented group where members were cut off from their families and relations. He attracted members through the promise of miracles, such as curing cancers and blindness, which he staged in elaborate services. He established a psychological hold over many members through isolation, intimidation, and brainwashing. He split up families, ordered members to perform manual labour for long hours, and continued to brutally interrogate and sexually abuse members. He cut off members from the outside world.', '2018-02-16 20:29:41'),
(142, 34, 'This deception culminated in this same so-called pastor committing a mass murder-suicide of 918 of his followers in Jonestown, Guyana when he ordered his members to drink a poison of cyanide as a proof of their loyalty to him. Painfully, nearly three hundred children were murdered, almost all of them by cyanide poisoning with a Flavour Aid mix.', '2018-02-16 20:29:41'),
(143, 34, 'Blessed be God that in all these erroneous moments, the real church has always remained. Just as Paul charged Timothy to commit the truth to faithful men who would be able to teach others also (2 Tim. 2:2), the responsibility is now on us. We are the faithful men of the postmodern era, and we must not only defend Biblical truths, but also transfer them to the next generation as part of our transgenerational legacy in this great house. In so doing, we will continue to triumph over counterfeit religion and expand God’s kingdom. May the Lord find faith in His people when He returns to the earth (Luke 18:8). Amen.', '2018-02-16 20:29:41'),
(144, 35, 'We all need a true shoulder to lean on; we need a leader who feeds and not a leader that milks us. It is a disaster when a leader who is meant to add to people begins to subtract from them. It is a pain to heaven when a leader borrows money from the people he leads or defiles young ones under him using deceptive scriptures to play on their ignorance. Do not become a satanic midwife who kills young saints in your care before they grow to their best in God.', '2018-02-16 20:34:22'),
(145, 35, 'True leaders provide mentorship platform that expand the capacity of others through godly example that cannot be questioned in all areas of life: spiritual, moral, emotional, financial, marital, and so forth. A modern practical example of the power of godly mentorship is found in the incredible Bible teacher known as Witness Lee. He was born in China in 1905 and was eventually mentored by Watchman Nee – another great giant in the hand of God who pushed the boundaries of the kingdom in the most dangerous places where Christianity was not allowed. Lee got saved at age 19 after being convicted by the preaching of a Chinese pastor, but his courage and spiritual strength came after meeting and interacting with Watchman Nee. The two men met for the first time in 1932 when Nee visited Yantai, Lee’s hometown. Lee would later confess in his writings that his personal relationship with God, and the proper way to study the Bible, were both revolutionized after he met Nee.', '2018-02-16 20:34:22'),
(146, 35, 'During his meetings with Nee, he began to sense that God was calling him to quit his job and serve as a full-time minister, which he did in August 1933. Only a short while after quitting his job, he received a letter from Watchman Nee that read: “Brother Witness, as for your future, I feel that you should serve the Lord with your full time. How do you feel? May the Lord lead you.” Lee was astonished and saw this letter as a great confirmation that it was God indeed who had previously spoken to him to quit secular work and serve him with all his time. From there onward, Lee began to work wholeheartedly with Nee in ministry, preaching throughout China and helping to establish local churches. ', '2018-02-16 20:34:22'),
(147, 35, 'Witness Lee went on to greatly influence Taiwan for Christ. In about six years, the number of Christians under his leadership skyrocketed from about five hundred to more than fifty thousand. He opened centres for training ministers and a book publishing company that produced Christian literature. He later travelled to England, Denmark, and eventually the United States, which became his headquarters for international ministry to many nations until his death in June 1997.', '2018-02-16 20:34:22'),
(148, 35, 'May our lives count for more as we become role models of Christ whose lives will fire and influence others for the Lord Jesus. Amen.', '2018-02-16 20:34:22'),
(149, 36, 'The purpose of the God-breathed Scriptures is for doctrine, reproof, correction, and education in righteousness, so that the man of God may be perfect, thoroughly furnished unto all good works. God is seeking for believers who have it all in one. He is seeking for completeness and total value. He wants every area of our lives to showcase the best of God. It does not glorify God when our spiritual lives are showing His glory while our careers or families are not bringing honour to Him.  We are called to be thoroughly furnished- compete and entire in every sphere of life! ', '2018-02-16 20:39:56'),
(150, 36, 'Moreover, we must be confident of the veracity and timeless validity of the Word of God. Science that once opposed Bible facts has now come to appreciate many things that the Bible has spoken about many years before modern inventions. We have explored a list of this in one of our previous studies.', '2018-02-16 20:39:56'),
(151, 37, 'It is imperative that Christians remain in their post of service, whether in season (good times) or out of season (bad times). The following is an excerpt from Open Doors UK, regarding the situation of churches in Northern Nigeria in 2014. Many ministers are still facing similar challenges till this day in the region.', '2018-02-16 20:46:22'),
(152, 37, 'a)	<b>Threat of violence.</b> Thousands have been killed by Boko Haram since their insurgence began in 2009. Rev. Samuel Dali, President of the Church of the Brethren in Nigeria, has said, \"Dozens of our churches have already been completely razed down and many pastors killed... If the situation does not stop, there is a real danger of eliminating churches in north-eastern Nigeria.\"', '2018-02-16 20:46:22'),
(153, 37, 'b)	<b>Need for provision.</b> Many pastors are providing for victims of attack physically as well as spiritually. \"On one particular day following an attack on a village, 56 people came to my house, looking into my eyes for help. As a spiritual father, I prayed with them and then fed them for the next three days with the food I had left in my house. I had nothing left to feed them or my family, but the people kept coming,\" shared Rev. Posat.', '2018-02-16 20:46:22'),
(154, 37, 'c)	<b>Dwindling number.</b> In Yobe state, where the battle against Boko Haram is particularly fierce, a church that once had 600 members now has just 50. It can be hard for this small congregation to function.', '2018-02-16 20:46:22'),
(155, 37, 'd)	<b>Dilemma over whether to stay or go.</b> In Yobe state and Borno state, numbers of pastors have been drastically reduced; some were killed, some were abducted, and others were forced to give up and close their churches as their members left the area. But incredibly, many are choosing to stay and serve their broken communities. They know that without anyone to lead it, the church in northern Nigeria could die. \"We shall remain here to uphold the flag of the Gospel in the presence of our persecutors,\" says one pastor, Peter Wakawa (http://www.opendoorsuk.org/news/stories/nigeria_141003.php).', '2018-02-16 20:46:22'),
(156, 37, 'These strong and faithful men of God have chosen to remain steadfast in their calling. They are watching in all things, enduring afflictions, doing the work of evangelists, and making full proof of their ministry. We have to keep them in our prayers, and may we also be consistent in doing what the Lord has called each of us to do, which is our reasonable service.', '2018-02-16 20:46:22'),
(157, 38, 'Paul got to a moment when he could boldly say he finished his race. He was very sure and convinced there was nothing more for him to do. It was a hundred percent and nothing less. How will you feel as a student writing a major examination and you have only written two out of the required five questions when the invigilator shouts, “Pens up!” Of course, you have read, you have prepared and with lots of potential, which, unfortunately, will not count as you face the painful reality of non-completion.', '2018-02-16 20:52:33'),
(158, 38, 'While Paul was at the last stage of his life, he spoke about being spent and in a readiness state to be poured forth as a man who has finished his race. As Charles Spurgeon once said, \"As Ministers of the Gospel of Christ, it is our duty and our privilege to exhaust our lives for Jesus.”', '2018-02-16 20:52:33'),
(159, 38, 'In this study also, we can appreciate Paul\'s excitement as he became closer to the end of his life. There was no fear or tension. He was happy to go “home.” He was very sure of his destination. How do we always feel about heaven? Are we scared, excited, or unsure? A story was once told of Baba Akindayomi, the founder of RCCG, and his friend on their excitement to go to heaven. Baba Akindayomi has just called his best friend to tell him that he was going home soon, having had a revelation that his place in heaven was ready. The friend replied, “Who told you that you will go home before me?” Wow! What a level of grace that the issue of death is nothing but a joke. Of course, we can understand that have walked with God to a level they were fully persuaded of their destination and the reward was waiting for them.', '2018-02-16 20:52:33'),
(160, 38, 'May we finish well and with excitement, in the Lord Jesus’ name. Amen.', '2018-02-16 20:52:33'),
(161, 39, 'We lead because others follow us and this they do in trust and belief that we genuinely have their interest at heart. We are a living being because there are other living beings around us and the degree to which we are sensitive and responsive to their well-being is the ultimate measure of the sense of living.', '2018-02-16 20:57:50'),
(162, 39, 'A Christian\'s impact will only go farther through positive, helpful and meaningful relationships. The breakthrough you may need in life may come from an old friend that you have sincerely kept contact with via regular WhatsApp messages, even when the individual consistently failed to reply repeatedly for many days. Life thrives on having the right kind of people, on whose shoulder you can climb to see farther. Kingdom pursuit becomes more meaningful when we have fellow soldiers and covenant partners who can be there for us during the shocks and surprises of life.', '2018-02-16 20:57:50'),
(163, 39, 'Inasmuch as we must never stop investing on people and building valuable relationships, we must also prepare ahead of time when the best of man behaves like a man that he is. We must prepare our hearts for the disappointments of men, because they will come. Let us brace ourselves for a season of loneliness, frustration, bitterness, and pain caused by the same people we have spent our life on. Let us always remember that only God is the only One who has promised to be with us, even till the age of time (Matt. 28:20). He is the only One who can guarantee a perpetual presence when our relationships and network of friends fail us.', '2018-02-16 20:57:50'),
(164, 39, '<b><i>No man\'s offence against us is worth trading heaven for!</i></b>', '2018-02-16 20:57:50');
INSERT INTO `introduction` (`introduction-id`, `study-id`, `row`, `date`) VALUES
(1, 1, 'While in the city of Lystra, Apostle Paul met a young disciple by the name of Timothy, who came across as a promising son of purpose whom Paul poured himself to and raised as a carrier of the kingdom mandate to the next generation (Acts 16:1–3). The discipleship journey of Paul and Timothy shows us a Biblical template of how worthy future leaders who want to count in the scheme of God must be raised with utmost sense of instruction, spiritual partnership, obedience, submission, guidance, and total mentoring.', '2018-02-15 11:13:08'),
(2, 1, 'Timothy was bicultural or half-caste, with a Greek father and a Jewish mother, who particularly laboured on her son, teaching him the Holy Scriptures, as she also was taught by her mother Lois. She raised a son beyond the challenges of inter-tribal marriage.', '2018-02-15 11:13:08'),
(3, 1, 'The relationship between Paul and Timothy blossomed amazingly, as Paul would later on begin to refer to Timothy as his own son (in the faith). Timothy became a trusted partner who accompanied Paul, Silas, and their missionary team to establish and strengthen various churches in different cities including the churches at Philippi (Phil. 2:19–22) and Thessalonica (1 Thess. 3:1–2). One such church that needed much help was the one in Ephesus, where false teachers had crept in and began to pervert the believers with false doctrines. Paul had to come to them and set things in better state. However, when he was ready to move to Macedonia, he still needed Timothy to “abide” with the Ephesian congregation to make sure only the truth of Christ would continue to be fed to the flock, until they were strong enough to stand on their own.', '2018-02-15 11:13:08'),
(4, 1, 'This introductory study looks at:', '2018-02-15 11:13:08'),
(5, 2, 'This study continues from where week one stopped with a stronger focus and emphasis on false teachings and how to deal with the problem. Ephesus was known for its rich variety of religions, philosophies, and “spiritual” inclinations. Acts 19:18–19 shows us that many Ephesians used “curious arts.” We also recall that after they believed the Gospel through the preaching of Paul and the signs that he did (Acts 19:11–12), they had no choice but to burn their books. There is little-to-no doubt that at least some of these converts were still influenced by their old lifestyle. We can see how this lingering influence can cause false doctrines to creep into the church.', '2018-02-15 11:14:45'),
(6, 2, 'That being said, it seems from our study text (especially verse 7) that Paul was more concerned with the Jewish false teachers in Ephesus who were improperly using the Law of Moses to incorrectly teach doctrines that did not agree with the New Covenant. He instructs Timothy to ignore the myths and speculations, but to focus rather on the “goal of the commandment” which is love—genuine love for God and fellow man. The issue of sound doctrine is very critical, as is evidenced by its continual mention by the Apostle Paul in his epistles to Timothy and Titus. Thus, this study considers:', '2018-02-15 11:14:45'),
(7, 3, 'The false teachers who had infiltrated the Ephesian church had so misused the Law of Moses to the point where Paul had to warn Timothy about their deceit. But it was necessary for Paul to remind him also that the Law is good “if a man use it lawfully.” The focus is that there is a right and wrong way to apply the Law in the New Testament dispensation. From 1 Timothy 1:9–10, we know for whom the Law is made and for whom it is not; from this Scriptural passage, we also know that the Law does not and cannot contradict sound doctrine. Finally, Paul spoke of the Law in accordance with the “glorious Gospel” of God, who has shown us a definite link between the Law which God gave Moses and the Gospel of grace through the Lord Jesus Christ (John 1:17). This study explains:', '2018-02-15 11:15:49'),
(8, 4, 'Paul spoke of how the Gospel was committed to his trust by God (1 Tim. 1:11). Our study text today, which immediately follows verse 11, shows his deep gratitude and appreciation for this privilege. Paul knew he had been a great sinner before God, especially through his persecution of the believers. But he said everything was a part of God’s plan so he could obtain mercy, as an example (“pattern”) of the Lord’s longsuffering (patience) with sinful humanity who would turn to faith in Christ and obtain the same mercy unto eternal life (1 Tim. 1:16). Much can be gleaned from this passage and so, the focus of study shall be:', '2018-02-15 11:16:18'),
(9, 5, 'One of the main reasons Paul left Timothy at Ephesus was to see to it that no other doctrine but the truths of the Lord Jesus Christ were being taught to the church. In this passage, he recommitted the charge (i.e., the commandment) to his young son in the faith. In addition, he also mentioned certain prophecies that were spoken about Timothy and encouraged him to use them to fight a good battle. He went on to speak of faith and a good conscience and how the absence of these would lead to spiritual shipwreck. The overall emphasis was on the challenge (warfare) which Timothy was sure to face in his Ephesian ministry. Paul used certain keys to boost his confidence and to point out the dangers that lay ahead, and how to walk in the power of prophecy to handle or avoid them. The study deals with:', '2018-02-15 11:16:48'),
(10, 6, 'In opening his first epistle to Timothy, Paul emphasised the need for teaching sound doctrine, the proper use of the Law, retaining faith, and other necessary tools to equip the young disciple fulfil his Ephesian ministry. In our study today, he shifts the focus to one of the most intimate activities a human on earth could engage in with God—prayer. And he specifically mentions four dimensions of prayer, which are not just for the benefit of the person praying but primarily for “all men,” including rulers and those in authority (1 Tim. 2:1–2). Paul showed that this kind of prayer is good in the sight of God “our Saviour” who desires for “all men” to be saved (1 Tim. 2:3–7). He continued exhorting people to pray (1 Tim. 2:8). This continuation of the instruction indicates a definite connection between our intercessions to God on behalf of and for the salvation of “all men.” God hears our prayers and shows mercy on us when we pray. This study focuses on:', '2018-02-15 11:17:27'),
(11, 7, 'This passage centres on a number of issues in relation to the proper roles of males and females in the church and, by extension, the Christian home. The gender theme begins in verse 8, where Paul specifically used the Greek word an?r which refers only to males, as opposed to anthropos which means a human being in general. Paul specified that “men” (i.e., the male) should pray everywhere. This of course does not exclude the woman from praying, but the phrase “lifting up holy hands” signifies a special responsibility on the part of the man. Other issues that are addressed include acceptable outward appearance of the women, authorization to teach, and God-ordained order of gender. The sub- topics for discussion are:', '2018-02-15 11:18:12'),
(12, 8, 'In this portion of Paul’s first letter to Timothy, he addressed the necessity for bishops and deacons in the church, and more importantly, the pre-requisites needed to qualify for each of these offices. Clearly, the office of a bishop [overseer] requires spiritual maturity, but even a deacon [“servant” who can be compared to a TACEF subgroup member] must not be immature either, and we shall see why in this study. The qualities mentioned in this passage are truly for all followers of the Lord Jesus, but those in unique positions of service and leadership are especially accountable.', '2018-02-15 11:19:15'),
(13, 8, 'The focus this week are:', '2018-02-15 11:19:15'),
(14, 9, 'In the opening verse of our text, Paul mentioned that all the previous things he had just said to Timothy from the false teachers of 1:3 to the deacons of 3:13 were in hope of Paul himself coming to Ephesus shortly, obviously, to set things in absolute order himself. However, in verse 15, he said that he might tarry long and, therefore, Timothy needed these instructions to know how to conduct himself in the church. This is a serious matter! It is worrisome today that the church is becoming an anything-goes place and we have lost our sense of order and how to behave in the church. Many have turned the church into a political platform or a place for business network. For some, they are just waiting for thanksgiving time, to flaunt their latest dress before others. May the Lord teach us how to behave properly in the church. This week, the focus are:', '2018-02-15 11:20:05'),
(15, 10, 'In this portion of his letter to Timothy, Paul prophesied by the Spirit that in the latter days (end-time or last days), there would be a departure from the true faith in Christ, and an acceptance and teaching of false doctrines fuelled by demonic spirits. Paul noted that these false teachers are hypocrites, whose consciences have been perverted. Their hearts are not right with God, but they teach an outward, exaggerated form of godliness through self-righteous abstinence from pleasure. But Paul ultimately shows Timothy (and us) how to remain strong especially seeing we are actually in the last days. The subtopics for this week are:', '2018-02-15 11:20:41'),
(16, 11, 'The focus of our study this week is the Christian’s need for godly discipline through spiritual exercise. Just as an athlete gives himself over to continual training to achieve his goal, every disciple of the Lord Jesus Christ must also continue in the training of godliness. The prize that the natural athlete strives for is only temporary, but the rewards of godliness are useful both now in the present world and in the world to come. The areas of focus of this study are:', '2018-02-15 11:21:08'),
(17, 12, 'Timothy was a young minister who Paul had left to manage the church at Ephesus. From the beginning up until this point of this epistle, Paul had given him several instructions for the successful progress. Paul said, “These things command and teach” (1 Tim. 4:11). But there was a small problem: Timothy was quite young and naturally shy and so there was a natural human tendency for the church members and others to dismiss him as unqualified to be in such a leadership role. This is a big lesson for many of us in TACEF, as this provides a valid basis on why our young age or any personality weaknesses must not diminish our ministry as incompetent, unqualified, or inexperienced. For Timothy, all the brethren at Iconium and Lystra (Timothy’s hometown) respected him and gave good report of him (Acts 16:2), but he was at Ephesus and had to prove himself as truly deserving of the huge responsibility of trust and leadership reposed on him. Paul used this portion of the epistle to encourage his “son in the faith,” starting with the timeless exhortation, “Let no man despise thy youth” (1 Tim. 4:12), or better expressed in other versions as, “Don\'t let anyone look down on you because you are young” – NIV or “Don\'t let anyone think less of you because you are young” -NLT. This study examines:', '2018-02-15 11:21:33'),
(18, 13, 'The majority of the instructions that Paul had given Timothy required making necessary corrections to properly set the church in order. But just to clarify, he instructed him here not to “rebuke” any elder, but to entreat him as a father. To entreat the elder as fathers means we must respect their age and not their misbehaviour.', '2018-02-15 11:23:10'),
(19, 13, 'The theme for our study today is the Biblical way to correct a fellow believer, especially those who are much older in age. This is particularly important for Timothy, seeing that his age might have been an issue for him as seen in our previous study. Paul was also being cautious here that in the quest to change Timothy’s shyness, he did not turn around to explode at every action, to the point of disrespecting the elders.', '2018-02-15 11:23:10'),
(20, 13, 'As we often see, an attempt to correct another Christian could go totally wrong and our quest to win can lead a soul to hell. The Bible is evidently clear on the need to correct one another. For example, God’s Word says, “Brethren, if any of you do err from the truth, and one convert him; let him know, that he which converteth the sinner from the error of his way shall save a soul from death, and shall hide a multitude of sins” (James 5:19–20). The focus for this study are:', '2018-02-15 11:23:10'),
(21, 14, 'This week, we shall study the Biblical standard on how to compensate full-time church ministers. It is quite incredible that we fully expect people of other professions such as medical doctors to be well paid for their work of saving lives in the hospital, but we question and criticise a (genuine) church leader for being well paid for his work of saving the eternal souls of human beings. Of course, we all know that our salvation is free, but we also appreciate the fact that some individuals dedicate their full attention to the work of the ministry. Paul advised here that the elders that rule well in the service of the Lord are worthy of “double honour.” The qualifications of “those who rule well” are also explained well in the right context, so that we can place reasonable leadership practice and compensation side by side. This week focus shall be:', '2018-02-15 11:23:41'),
(22, 15, 'In our last study (1 Tim. 5:17–18), Paul gave explicit instructions concerning the honouring of ministers who rule well and labour in the Word and doctrine. In our study this week, we shall see how Apostle Paul continued in the leadership instructions to the elders—but on a different tone. He addressed the issue of ungodliness in leadership, which usually results in public scandal. A number of specific areas are discussed, such as how an accusation against an elder should be dealt with, the need to publicly rebuke the guilty, judging without partiality, and caution in selecting leaders. Paul fully understood that the quality of the church leadership plays a huge role in the quality of the church as a local body. The focus for today are:', '2018-02-15 11:24:11'),
(23, 16, 'The next important issue, which Paul addressed in his first letter to Timothy, is the proper way for employees and employers to relate in a mutually beneficial master–servant relationship. Servants, who had come to faith in the Lord Jesus Christ, always have a tendency to see their secular, unbelieving masters as unworthy of their loyalty and allegiance since the Lord Jesus Himself was their Lord. But Paul instructed them on the right attitude to adopt instead and how to put things in the right perspective. There were also Christian servants whose masters were believers just like them, and Paul gave instructions about the right attitude and relationship in this sphere as well. There are a number of lessons for us to learn from this study, which apply to present-day Christians, and how we are to view our secular jobs and bosses. Many Christians who are also business owners and employers of labour will learn fundamental Biblical approach expected of us. The breakdown of study are:', '2018-02-15 11:24:49'),
(24, 17, 'This week, we read the Scriptures in which Paul once again discussed the issue of false teachings from false teachers, but now more specifically on teachers who were promoting money for their selfish gain, corrupting many with the wrong concept of Biblical prosperity. Here, the concern is on how money and material supplies are made to be the most important benefit of salvation rather than being the by-product of salvation. Paul’s worries centred on putting money (or “gain”) first, and godliness as a method of getting gain. Paul used many words and phrases to describe such teachers, finally concluding that such prosperity teachers of errors are “men of corrupt minds, and destitute of the truth” (1 Tim. 6:5). This study is broken down into the following areas:', '2018-02-15 11:25:24'),
(25, 18, 'In our last study, we saw how Paul condemned false teachers who were using godliness as a means of gain, and thereby promoting money instead of the true doctrine of the Lord Jesus Christ. In these following verses, we see that the only great gain is godliness, the genuine kind of godliness which brings contentment to the heart of the believer. A big part of his argument is that “we brought nothing into this world, and it is certain we can carry nothing out” (1 Tim. 6:7). He is here emphasising the transitory nature of our lives through this world and why our understanding of prosperity should be premised on our destination and not on the journey. So while the people of the world may be covetous and always desiring temporal material things, we as Christians should focus on the reality of eternity with God. The focal points of our study are:', '2018-02-15 11:25:53'),
(26, 19, 'This week progressed on the issues of money and how to remain focussed on our destinations. We saw in the last study that keeping an eternal perspective and keeping godliness as our priority is a potent medicine to cure discontentment and dissatisfaction in life. While we know that our walk with Christ can be threatened by a number of internal and external factors, the desire for money and wealth may be the greatest threat of all. Paul showed us how the desire leads to a deception, which, in turn, eventually leads to destruction. The ordinate affection for money can be so disastrous and, if left unchecked may become an obsession that leads unto utter dead-end. In this study, the Holy Spirit shows us how this is a hidden trap of the enemy, with unseen consequences that finally bring pain and regret to those who refuse to take heed of the warning. This study focuses on:', '2018-02-15 11:26:18'),
(27, 20, 'In the last study, Paul had just spoken to Timothy concerning the dangers associated with being covetous and being a lover of money. In this continuing passage of the epistle, his first instruction was for Timothy to “flee these things.” He emphasised the seriousness of the need for a “man of God” to dissociate himself from the worldliness and covetousness of false teachers and those who listen to them. Not only was Timothy supposed to escape from the snare of money, but he was also instructed to actively pursue righteousness and godly virtues. In verse 12, the two exhortations are to “fight the good fight of faith” and to “lay hold on eternal life,” which means he must fight and persevere through all the challenges that come with the Christian faith, while keeping his eyes on eternity the whole time. There is much for us, the church, to benefit from this portion of the epistle, as it shows us the need to endure continually in the Christian race until we finally and successfully make it into the Promised Land. The focal points of the study are:', '2018-02-15 11:26:53'),
(28, 21, 'This study brings us into another dimension of how spiritual fathers must strongly charge, instruct, and mandate their sons unto godly path. Here we see how Paul charged Timothy before God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ to keep the commandments in strict compliance. True sons are not raised by advice but by God-inspired instructions. The young Timothy must maintain his integrity as a faithful witness of the Lord Jesus Christ, as there were pressures from both within and without the Ephesian church, which could have led to his crumbling. He said that Timothy must keep the commandment “without spot, unrebukable.” Paul used a number of strong points that will lead us into right leadership impetus to raise a generation of grace, excellence, and purpose. This study is just a piece, broken down step-by-step to give us some amazingly glorious reasons why we should be confident to keep God’s commandment without spot and unrebukable. \r\nThe focus is on how the knowledge of God’s glory keeps us strong under pressure.\r\n', '2018-02-15 11:27:23'),
(29, 22, 'After deep insight on the greatness of God, which provides a compelling basis for our ultimate consecration, Paul shifted the focus back to the issue of finances, but he was no longer speaking about those who love money and are covetous, but now addressing the concern of Christians who are already wealthy and have their lives needs met. Having lots of money usually brings pride, and this is the very first thing he warns against. We are not to trust in money, which is “uncertain,” but in God Himself who is the One who gives us everything. Although it is indeed the will of God for His people to prosper financially (3 John 1:2), this prosperity is based on being rich towards God, and rich in doing His will. Paul emphasised the need to be generous and giving, maintaining an attitude of using wealth to do good works. Paul also mentioned the “oppositions of science” in verse 20. This study is divided into the following segments:', '2018-02-15 11:27:55'),
(30, 23, 'In the introductory verses of his second letter to Timothy, Paul was thankful for Timothy’s life and for the faith that is in him—which was passed down from his grandmother to his mother and then to him. Paul also encouraged his son in the faith to “stir up the gift of God” which was in him, as he was going to need this for successful ministry, and for a victorious fighting of the good fight of faith. The pressures of the Christian walk can sometimes intimidate those who may not be naturally strong at heart, so Paul also reminded him that God has not given us a fearful or timid spirit, but His own Spirit of power, love, and soundness of mind. The overall theme of this introductory passage is that God has given us “unfeigned faith” and has gifted us His Spirit to serve Him without fear. We stand to gain great things from paying good attention to this study which focuses on:', '2018-02-15 11:28:26'),
(31, 24, 'After an inspiring challenge not to be defeated in fear, Paul called that this must mean we are unashamed of the Gospel of Christ and unashamed of the being the Lord’s prisoner. Paul was in prison at Rome under the custody of Caesar Nero at this time, from where he wrote the second letter to Timothy. But he never acknowledged himself to be Nero’s prisoner, but a prisoner of the Lord Jesus Christ. In every situation, we must never be ashamed of the Gospel, but confidently participate in any suffering that it may bring, even if it costs us our lives. The topics for discussions are:', '2018-02-15 11:28:51'),
(32, 25, 'Paul was in Roman custody awaiting trial when he penned the second epistle to Timothy. He said that the Gospel and his appointment as the Lord Jesus Christ’s ambassador was the reason he suffered “these things.” But just as he told Timothy in verse 8 not to be ashamed, he confidently celebrated his chain and explained the reason why—“For I know whom I have believed.” In this study, we explore again why we must entrust the Lord Jesus with our lives, knowing that we are permanently secured in Him. The focal points of this study are:', '2018-02-15 11:29:16'),
(33, 26, 'We all know how the Apostle Paul toiled and laboured in the Gospel from city to city through the vast expanse of the Roman Empire. Now, after many years of preaching the Good News of the Lord Jesus Christ and the kingdom of God, he was a prisoner of the Roman government, in custody awaiting trial for his role in the uproars and instability that his new “sect” called Christianity was causing throughout the empire. In this portion of his second letter to Timothy, Paul recounted his present plight, but with special focus on two kinds of persons and how they have treated him in his predicament. He said, first of all, that “All they which are in Asia be turned away from me,” and then specifically mentioned two people named Phygellus and Hermogenes. On the other hand, he spoke well of a man called Onesiphorus, and how he faithfully ministered to Paul in prison as much as he could. Paul also released a short prayer for him that he might obtain mercy of the Lord in the day when we all stand before the judgement seat of Christ. This study examines:', '2018-02-15 11:29:44'),
(34, 27, 'The summary of Paul’s heart-to-heart admonition to Timothy in Chapter 1 of this second epistle was aptly captured as, “Thou therefore, my son, be strong in the grace that is in Christ Jesus.”', '2018-02-15 11:30:55'),
(35, 27, 'Paul and Timothy had many challenges. Paul was imprisoned, many had abandoned him, and he was facing possible execution. Young brother Timothy had to deal with the general hostility against the Gospel message, false teachers that were causing problems for the congregation, plus his personal health issues. In the midst of all these problems and burdens, the exhortation from Paul was for Timothy to be strong, of course, not to be strong in his own strength, but rather in the grace that is in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus. Paul knew that it would be impossible for his “son” to carry the weight of the ministry on the foundation of personal effort. Grace, which can only be found in the Lord Jesus Christ, is the sure foundation that upholds and strengthens us through the numerous challenges that come with the Christian life. We can never exhaust the amount of things to be said when it comes to fully understanding what the grace of God actually is. The meaning of the song, “Grace alone, it is never powerless,” is so strong, as we explore this week’s study:', '2018-02-15 11:30:55'),
(36, 28, 'The mandate of the Lord Jesus to us is “Go ye therefore, and make disciples of all nations” (Matt 28:19). In our text today, Paul placed a similar mandate on Timothy. He was to teach (or make disciples) by committing the Word of God to “faithful men” who, in turn, will be able to teach others also. It should be noted that what Timothy was expected to transmit to others according to Paul were “the things that thou hast heard from me.” What are the deeper implications of that statement? We will find out.', '2018-02-15 11:31:40'),
(37, 28, 'Also, what qualifies someone as a “faithful man” and what does not? Finally, we shall explore what it takes to effectively transfer Biblical truth from one person to another. The subtopics and teachings for this study are:', '2018-02-15 11:31:40'),
(38, 29, 'Our passage today is about the principle of enduring pain and hard times, in order to reap the rewards later. In this study, Paul used three practical dimensions to illustrate what is required to make timeless impact in our generation. First is the soldier, who endures hardship and avoids distractions to please his commander and win the war. Then we have the athlete, who must exercise and compete lawfully before he can receive the crown. Afterwards a farmer, who must not only work on the land but also be very patient before he gets the fruit. These are all analogies of the Christian life. This study shows us clearly that we cannot reap the rewards without first going through the trials, hardships, and labour—the foundation for Christian success on a path of reasonable service. The breakdown of teachings are:', '2018-02-15 11:32:03'),
(39, 30, 'The recurring theme of Paul’s second epistle to Timothy is endurance for the Gospel’s sake. As we have previously mentioned, Paul was in custody of the Roman government awaiting execution, and this was the last of all his epistles. He spoke with deep convictions and passion of a labouring father who was at the end of his race. He continued to speak to encourage Timothy to remain steadfast through any adversity that may come with being a minister of the Gospel. He began his exhortation by reminding Timothy that the Lord whom we serve—the Lord Jesus Christ—became human like us (“the seed of David”), and after suffering and crucifixion, He was raised from the dead. Paul then continued by using his own example to encourage his young son in the faith, showing how he was regarded as a criminal that needed to be bound with chains—with the encouragement being that God’s Word remains unbound regardless of how much his enemies tried to stop his servants from spreading the Good News. He then reminded Timothy on the need to endure for their sake, before he finally closed with an interesting remark that shows us why we must follow the Lord Jesus Christ unto the very end. Our focal points for this study are:', '2018-02-15 11:32:29'),
(40, 31, 'The focus has shifted again to sound doctrine in this portion of the epistle. Paul began by instructing Timothy that he must see to it that Christians were not striving about words in an unbeneficial way. Timothy himself must “study” and rightly divide the Word to show himself approved unto God, while shunning profane and empty discussions that only further ungodliness. Of course, you cannot stop error if you have not fully learnt about the truth, sufficient to defend it. Paul mentioned two people—Hymenaeus and Philetus, who were spreading false doctrines and damaging people’s faith. But he concluded by asserting that the faith of God’s people stands on a sure foundation. The application of this passage to us has to do with how we properly learn and handle God’s Word. Many people like to argue and debate, not with the intention of edifying others, but to show off their supposed “knowledge.” God’s people must know and rightly divide His Word personally for themselves, through the help of His Spirit. We must avoid unprofitable arguments and be able to identify false teaching. This study is divided into the following segments:', '2018-02-15 11:32:55'),
(41, 32, 'This particular week’s study has strong prophetic meaning in TACEF, as the overwhelming covenant of a great house is anchored on this truth. In this study, Paul emphasised on two kinds of people, using an illustration of a great house which has both honourable vessels and dishonourable vessels. He had previously been talking to Timothy about false doctrines, and had concluded in verse 19 that everyone who names the name of Christ must depart from iniquity. So, in verse 21, he was only continuing the theme, mentioning the purging from falsehood and iniquity to become a vessel unto honour, which will make us become vessels of good use to the Master. Two basic directives are given in verse 22 to perfectly fulfil the requirements of being an honourable vessel: (a) flee from sin and (b) pursue godliness. We will carefully examine what God is telling us through these verses, and our focal points are:', '2018-02-15 11:33:32'),
(42, 33, 'As servants of the Lord, there will be times when He will bring us into contact with people who are doctrinally confused, and need to be corrected and helped onto the path of truth. This is the theme of what Paul was telling Timothy here. There are moments we shall meet people whose opinions can give us terrible headache. However, we are told that “foolish and unlearned questions” are to be avoided since they only stir up strife. The confused people who need help cannot be corrected in a spirit of strife and debate, but there are certain characteristics, which we must adopt to instruct them the correct way. Ultimately, the power to grant repentance and agreement with truth lies with God himself, though He uses our words as a mechanism to convict those who are in error. The breakdown of subtopics which we will examine includes:', '2018-02-15 11:33:57'),
(43, 34, 'Our passage today is an extremely important one for the church, and it needs proper examination and clarification. We are actually in the perilous time, which specifically mean the years leading to the Lord’s return to earth have drawn near. Reading from verses 2–4, one would think that the people being spoken of are completely ungodly people of the world, but Paul was also speaking of people who may be professing Christians, as we read in verse 5. They have a “form” of godliness, but do not truly belong to God. Some of them are also teachers of false doctrines that prey on the weak; and they continually study but never locate the truth (2 Tim. 3:6–7). In verses 8–9, Paul named two people who resisted Moses’ truth and compared them to the false Christian teachers who also resist God’s Biblical truth. There is much to glean from this study, and the focus are:', '2018-02-15 11:34:25'),
(44, 35, 'This portion of the epistle continues from our last study (2 Tim. 3:1–9). Paul had just described ungodly men who had a form of godliness but in actuality were false teachers in disguise. In the following verse, he was affirming his own genuineness which he said Timothy was already fully aware of (2 Tim. 3:10). What a transparent leader! While those who are genuinely godly will suffer persecution, the evil false teachers will only sink deeper into deception (2 Tim. 3:12–13). The exhortations in verses 14–15 show that Timothy had learnt from Paul (and possibly other people) and directly from the Scriptures. The overall theme and pivotal message for Timothy and all Christians are in verse 14 where Paul said he must “continue” in those things which he learnt no matter how much persecution he encountered for living godly in the Lord Jesus Christ or how many evil seducers promoted false teachings. We must remain consistent, pushing forward till we get to the very end of our earthly lives. The focal points of study are:', '2018-02-15 11:35:02'),
(45, 36, 'The prior verse connecting our text for today is verse 15, where Paul mentioned how Timothy had known the Holy Scriptures from childhood. Now, he affirmed the divine origin of Scripture, and continued by stating four basic benefits of God’s Word. As far as Christian service and ministry is concerned, one of the chief goals of the Scriptures is “that the man of God may be perfect, thoroughly furnished unto all good works” (2 Tim. 3:17). The main theme of this part of the epistle is the origin of the Bible and why we need it for a victorious life and ministry. The focus for the study are:', '2018-02-15 11:35:34'),
(46, 37, 'This portion of the epistle begins with another “charge” from Paul to Timothy in the sight of God and the Lord Jesus Christ, the third and final in both epistles (after 1 Tim. 5:21 and 1 Tim. 6:13). He had just assured Timothy that “All Scripture is given by inspiration of God,” and now, therefore, charged him to “preach the word” (2 Tim. 4:2). Since the Scriptures of God are needed for doctrine, reproof, correction, and education in righteousness, preaching the Word faithfully is the primary way to prepare believers before the Lord Jesus returns to “judge the quick and the dead” (2 Tim. 4:1). Though believers are saved from eternal damnation, we shall all still stand before the judgement seat of Christ to give account of our lives (2 Cor. 5:10). Paul signified that a time will come when professing Christians would not abide in sound doctrine (2 Tim.4:3–4) but follow the seducers (2 Tim. 3:13). Timothy, on the other hand, was to watch and remain steadfast, making “full proof” of his ministry (2 Tim. 4:5). The overall theme is twofold: (a) we are to preach the Word under all circumstances (2 Tim. 4:2, 5) and (b) we are to hear the Word and abide in sound doctrine (2 Tim. 4:5).', '2018-02-15 11:36:14'),
(47, 37, 'The subtopics of our study are:', '2018-02-15 11:36:14'),
(48, 38, 'At the time of writing the second epistle to Timothy, Paul was in Roman custody under the reign of Caesar Nero, a tyrant who hated Christianity with extreme passion and the message of the Lord Jesus Christ. After the critical instructions he had given, Paul was coming close to the end of his writing; he informed Timothy that he was coming close to the end of his life on earth as well. He used a language in verse 6 that made this clear to Timothy, as he was certain he would be executed by the tyrannical emperor of Rome, who saw Paul as an outlaw and criminal (2 Tim. 2:9). But the aged apostle was neither afraid nor sad; he knew he had done his job on earth and fulfilled his ministry and divine assignment (2 Tim. 4:7). He concluded with an emphatic reminder to all Christians that there is a sure “crown of righteousness” awaiting him in heaven; and all who love and anticipate the return of Christ will be partakers of heavenly crowns also (2 Tim. 4:8). The great theme of this portion of the epistle is that the Christian’s life and ministry is a marathon that we must faithfully run to the very end. There is no other way to obtain the crown which the Lord has kept in store for His people, except by labouring, serving, and finishing well. The subtopics of our study are:', '2018-02-15 11:36:56'),
(49, 39, 'These are Paul’s closing words to his son in the faith. Many things were happening here, from Paul mentioning that a trusted Christian named Demas had forsaken him and Alexander the coppersmith doing him much evil, to the aged apostle’s unquenchable desire to continue ministering the Gospel even while bound and facing execution (2 Tim. 4:11). At the time of writing, Paul had already gone through a preliminary hearing before the court (2 Tim. 4:16) and still hoped to serve the Lord with any amount of time he had left on earth. We saw here a man who was well prepared for life shocks and surprises. He remembered the value of his books and prepared for change in weather as a reasonable health-aware Christian when he demanded for his cloak against the cold of the summer season. He mentioned many names and a number of circumstances. We will examine this study by looking at the following subtopics:', '2018-02-15 11:37:31'),
(50, 40, 'Our one-year focus on the issues of repairing, revival and rebuilding will be better\r\nappreciated in context if weprayerfully study and reflect on how Israel becamerebuilt after a\r\nlong exile in Babylon as captured in the books of Ezra, Nehemiah, Haggai, and Zechariah. It is\r\na great lesson for our generation to understand how a nation transited from its backsliding\r\nstate in captivity of Babylon into a revived state to serve the Lord in spirit and in truth, in its\r\nown land.', '2018-11-02 11:49:54'),
(51, 40, 'For many years, Israel, as a nation has broken its covenant with God through\r\ncontinueddisobedience. They persisted in their sin even after many warnings came from\r\nmany prophets that the Lord raised to caution them. Unfortunately, the negative prophecy\r\ncaptured in our study text (Lev 26 vs 27-33) has now come to pass. The nation is now\r\nscattered and battered into slavery in the great city of Babylon. The armies of Babylon\r\nattacked the city of Israel. They destroyed the temple, broke down the walls of the city and\r\ntook many Israelites to Babylon as slaves.', '2018-11-02 11:49:54'),
(52, 40, 'This week\'s study explores Israel\'s journey into Babylon, as a way to explain when revival is\r\nneeded at a personal or group level, especially the moment we realise how far we have\r\nwalked away from God into a strange land (Babylon). A strange land is any place, space or\r\ncircumstance that is strange to our spiritual being. It is a place of worldliness, sin,\r\ncarelessness, backsliding and, of course, bondage, where wecan no longer fulfil our spiritual\r\nobligation to the Lord or keep our consecration.', '2018-11-02 11:49:54'),
(53, 40, 'This study, therefore, provides the necessarycontext, which led to Israel\'s exile into a strange\r\nland in the first place. It will also help us to understand the characteristics of a life that needs\r\nrevival and the key indicators that characterise a life that has walked into a strange land.', '2018-11-02 11:49:54'),
(54, 41, 'This week\'s study helps to capture the experience of the Israelites who were taken into\r\ncaptivity by the army of Babylon. It is a deep longing for God and the city of Jerusalem as\r\ncaptured in Psalm 137, which was written by one of the Jews who had been taken captive\r\ninBabylon. It is important to note here that David did not write all the book of Psalms. In fact,\r\nDavid only wrote about half of the Psalms—about 73 out of all 150. Psalms names more\r\ncontributors than any other book of the Bible. The book of Psalmsitself lists more than seven\r\nauthors, including five individuals and two families, who wrote psalms over the centuries.\r\nYou may have seen other names like Asaph andsons of Korah.', '2018-11-02 12:15:52'),
(55, 41, 'Psalm 137 is an expression of the inner yearning for God\'s city by one of the godly Israelites\r\nwho had been carried away with the majority of the population, just like Daniel and Ezekiel\r\nwere. The opening verse (“By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down...”) is in agreement\r\nwith verses from Ezekiel (1:1, 3:15) which showthat the captives had formed a Jewish\r\ncommunity that settled near one or more of Babylon\'s rivers, particularly the Chebar. It is\r\nfrom this place that the psalmist reflected on Jerusalem and the pleasant songs of the Lord\r\nthat they used to sing, which are now but a memory.', '2018-11-02 12:15:52'),
(56, 41, 'The importance of this psalm for us is that there should be a longing for God\'s kingdom in the\r\nhearts of His people even though weseem cut off or engrossed with the worldly demands of\r\nprofessional careersor ministerial lives. We must always have a longing for heaven, knowing\r\nthat this world is not our home (John 17:14, Phil. 3:20). We should desire both the spiritual\r\nkingdom at this present time, and also the physical kingdom of Christ in the near future.', '2018-11-02 12:15:52'),
(57, 42, 'This week\'sCstudy focuses on the fulfilment of prophecy according to God\'s timetable, as we\r\nfinally enter into the first verse of Ezra:“...that the word of the LORD by the mouth of Jeremiah\r\nmight be fulfilled” is a statement which shows us that God always brings His counsel to pass at\r\nthe appointed time. The Medians and Persians captured the powerful Babylon and thus\r\ngained full authority over the vast empire which the Babylonians had previously conquered.\r\nCyrus is the new king and he issued a decree to free the Jews within the first year of his reign.\r\nJeremiah had prophesied that seventy years would be accomplished before God would bring\r\nHis people back to their own land. That season had finally arrived. We do not know how many\r\nJews were conscious of the seventy-year prophetic timeline, but we know that Daniel was\r\none of those who were (Dan. 9:1-2). Inspired by Daniel\'s example, the main focus of this\r\nstudy will be how we as Christians should understand where we presently are in God\'s\r\nplanaccording to prophecy, and how those implications should affect our actions and\r\nlifestyle. Being in tune with Biblical prophecy is an important dimension that fans the flames\r\nof revival, re-alignment, and preparation against the time to come, both for the individual\r\nChristian and for the Church as the Bride of Christ.', '2018-11-02 12:28:50'),
(58, 44, 'These opening verses of Ezra serve as an explicit declaration of God\'s sovereign hand in the\r\nrealm of humankind. Cyrus\' ascension to power, his law to release all the Jews that were in\r\nthe captivity of Babylon, and the mandate upon him to see to the rebuilding of the temple at\r\nJerusalem, were all God\'s doing. It sounds so strange that an unbeliever king wouldrelease\r\nthe Jews, letting them go back to Jerusalem, and also instructingthem to build the temple in\r\nJerusalem. God is always God and this immediately shows us that we cannot have true\r\nrevival and spiritual rebuilding without God\'s direct involvement. He must take over the\r\nhearts of men and women in the high places in a manner that is beyond what anyone can do.\r\nThe focus for this study is on God\'s sovereignty, and the sub-sections include:', '2018-11-02 12:41:04'),
(59, 45, 'God had already accomplished the first leg of His plan for His people\'s restoration by raising\r\nup king Cyrus to power and putting it in his heart to free the Jews to rebuild the temple in\r\nJerusalem. The next part of the plan now requires this question: “Who is there among you of\r\nall his people? his God be with him, and let him go up to Jerusalem, which is in Judah, and\r\nbuild the house of the Lord God of Israel, (he is the God,) which is in Jerusalem.”\r\nWho is there among you of all His people? This tells us that though all of God\'s people were\r\navailable to participate in the revival, only a certain percentage would actually answer the\r\ncall. This reminds us of what Jesus said in Matthew 22:14—For many are called, but few are\r\nchosen. God\'s people today are facing this same situation. Though all Christians are called to\r\nspiritual revival, only few are stepping out to take the call seriously and respond\r\nwholeheartedly. It seems that the backslidden are not ready to return to Jerusalem, even as\r\nmany of the Jews in Babylon weren\'t ready to return, even Babylon has now been taking over\r\nby another country. It is a serious worry that many do not want to return home but prefer to\r\nbecome a second-level slave to another country that has taken over the country that\r\noriginally took them captive. What a calamity of double slavery! This week, we will study the\r\nfollowing:', '2018-11-02 12:58:37'),
(60, 46, 'When the time finally came for the few Jews who decided to depart Babylon to go rebuild\r\nthe temple in Jerusalem, God was not going to leave His people empty-handed. He is too\r\ngood to call a man into a mandate of revival and not make resources available. A popular\r\nsaying in TACEF is, “the vision will provoke provision”. Though the commandment to\r\nmaterially provide for the Jews came from Cyrus, and though the actual giving was done by\r\nother humans, it was no doubt all were orchestrated by God Himself. Each person today who\r\nmakes a decision to follow Christ has entered into a spiritual journey just like the Jews. And\r\njust as God made provisions available for the Jews, He will also make provisions available for\r\nus. He knows what we need both spiritually and materially to succeed in our call of revival.<br/>\r\nThe two main topics of this study are:', '2018-11-02 13:09:57'),
(61, 48, 'Verses 7-11 focuses on how Cyrus directed Mithredath the treasurer to bring out the articles of God\'s temple which Nebuchadnezzar had carried away to Babylon and placed in the temple of his gods. A man named Sheshbazzar, whom Cyrus had appointed as prince and governor of Judah, was put in charge of making sure the vessels arrived safely to Jerusalem from Babylon.The returning of these instruments to their proper place can be taken\r\nsymbolically to represent Christians who have backslidden and are now being restored by bringing back those spiritual and mental assets that have been previously wasted in sin and unrighteousness. The need to come back as a person and return all the treasures of the Lord are critical issues in the path of revival, hence this week\'s study will include:', '2018-11-02 13:34:21'),
(62, 49, 'This extensive portion of Scripture may seem unnecessary to the average reader, but we can\r\nbe sure that God has His reasons for whatsoever He chooses to include in His revealed Word.\r\nAfterall, all Scripture is profitable for doctrine, reproof, correction, and education in\r\nrighteousness (2Tim. 3:16). We can see from this list of returning exiles that God is keen on\r\ndetails concerning His people. When we ask for alist of converts, follow up schedules or the\r\nneed to keep fellowship attendance, you will realise that there is no one as keen about\r\nattention to details than our God. Unfortunately, in this study, we will see how some\r\n“Israelites” had lost record of their genealogy, and could not prove whether they were truly\r\nof Israel or not, much less be qualified to be priests, effectively shutting them out of the\r\npriesthood. This is a reminder to us that we must never lose our spiritual identity, because\r\nthere will be consequences that follow later on. This study today will be about how God is\r\nprecise and specific in dealing with His people, and how His people should operate with a\r\nsense of order, accountability and purpose in wholehearted return to the Lord. Topics\r\ninclude:', '2018-11-02 13:47:19'),
(63, 50, 'This portion of our study shows how the Jews first arrived in Jerusalem and what their\r\npriority was— the rebuilding of God\'s temple. The total number of this first group of people\r\nwho arrived under Zerubbabel was 49,897 (almost 50,000 persons). But it seems that the\r\nheads of the fathers were the ones highly concerned with making sure that there was enough\r\nmoney and material needed for the house. They gave whatever they could, offering it freely\r\ntowards the task at hand. This study will connect the attitude needed of people who will\r\nqualify to lead every move of revival today. Topics to discussare:', '2018-11-02 14:02:15'),
(64, 52, 'This study opens us to one of the most important principles of revival or how to live a revived life. It shows us the importance of the altar as a platform to kick-off the restoration of worship, which is the connecting point between man and God. A missing altar is an indication of a disconnection between heaven and the earth.<br/>\r\nThe altar is the first and most important place for regular sacrifice and worship. “The people assembled together as one in Jerusalem” (3:1) because worship had to be restored by first re-establishing the altar. There was unity and agreement amongst the individual Jews, and there are so much for us to learn. Topics for this week include:', '2018-11-02 14:27:47'),
(65, 53, 'In our last study, we saw that the Jews built the altar and reinstated the ceremonial worship\r\nof God in the seventh month of the year of their return to Jerusalem. This week\'s study will\r\nexplore how God\'s people finally laid the foundation of the temple. This was a major step in\r\nthe process of the assignment of restoration and revival that they came to do in their home\r\nland. Laying appropriate foundation in revival is a very critical step and the fact that as soon as\r\nthis was done, the priests and Levites were set in order to worship God in accordance with\r\nhow David had appointed them for the first temple (Ezra 3:10, 1Chron. Chapters 23 to 25),\r\neven when the full temple has not been built.', '2018-11-02 14:42:12'),
(66, 53, 'The climax of the temple\'s foundation being laid is seen in verses 11-13, as there were mixed\r\nemotions within the people. Those who were younger shouted for joy of seeing what they\r\nhad never seen before and gave praise unto the Lord, but the elders who had seen Solomon\'s\r\ntemple wept aloud when they saw the foundation of this new temple as lower in scale. We\r\nwill look at the reasons for this also. The subtopics of this study are:', '2018-11-02 14:42:12'),
(67, 54, 'After the foundation of the temple was laid, the strangers who dwelt in Judea heard about\r\nwhat the Jews were doing. These strangers were \'Samaritans\', i.e., these are half-casts who\r\nwere given birth to when the descendants of the people that were brought from\r\nMesopotamia intermarried with the Israelites after the Assyrians captured Israel. Of course,\r\nthey were not happy that the Jews had returned and may now be establishing permanent\r\nresidences. Though, their intent was evil, their first approach in attempting to destroy the\r\nrevival work of building the temple was to come as friends who wanted to help the Israelites\r\nin the rebuilding, with a claim that they worshipped the same God. This is a warning to\r\nChristians, as our enemies may come in different masks and disguises. Indeed, many\r\nchurches today have mixed the enemy\'s agenda with that of God, in a condemnable modern\r\nday Christianity when the church is not different from a club house, a political rally or a\r\nmagician circus. Thankfully, Zerubbabel and the elders rejected their offer of allegiance, and\r\ntook a stand to build God\'s temple alone—another strong message for Christians seeking\r\ntrue revival and the need to avoid any corruption or distraction.The topics to look at include:', '2018-11-02 14:56:12'),
(68, 56, 'In the last study, we saw how the Samaritans tried to partner with the Jews in rebuilding the\r\ntemple. Now, after their request has been denied, they show their true colours and their real\r\nintent, which is to foil the plans of the Jews and prevent the temple from being built. Verses\r\n4-5 saythat they “weakened their hands”, “troubled them in building”, and even “hired\r\ncounsellors against them.” These are the realities that every genuine move of God must face.\r\nThis week, we shall study how the enemy attempts to frustrate the move of God.The topics\r\ninclude:', '2018-12-03 18:55:54'),
(69, 57, 'This portion of the book of Ezra is parenthetical, that is, talking about a time period inserted\r\nwithin a different time period. The main narrative of chapter 4 is the building of the house of\r\nGod (the temple), but verses 6-23 are not talking about the temple; instead, they show how\r\nthe Samaritans not only resisted the Jews from building the temple during Cyrus\' reign, but\r\nalso how they resisted them from building Jerusalem as a city along with its walls during the\r\nreigns of Ahasuerus and Artaxerxes. One of the things wewill see in this study is that verses 7-\r\n23 are actually talking about the Jews who came back with Ezra during Artaxerxes\' reign as\r\nshown in Ezra chapter 7. This is why these parenthetical verses (6-23) only mention the city\r\nof Jerusalem with its walls, but no accusations against the temple, which had already been\r\ncompleted under Darius before this time.\r\nThe crucial element of this study today is how the Samaritans laid accusations against the\r\nJews and Jerusalem as a city, which caused the king to stop the building of the city. What does\r\nthis mean for God\'s people today? The topics for study include:', '2018-12-03 19:10:34'),
(70, 59, 'The Samaritans hired legal advisors against the Jews, among other tactics, and succeeded in\r\ncausing them to stop the building project of the temple (Ezra 4:5, 24). This week\'s study\r\nbegins in the second year of Darius, where we see God\'s prophets, Haggai and Zechariah,\r\nprophesying to the Jews, and directing them to rise up and resume building the temple until\r\nit is completed. They hearken unto them and the work is begun once again, but the\r\nopposition is ever-present as some of the Gentiles question the Jews about their\r\nauthorisation to continue the project, until the matter finally gets to Darius the king via a\r\nletter.', '2018-12-03 19:22:07'),
(71, 59, 'A subtle but important aspect of this passage is revealed in the book of Haggai chapter 1,\r\nwhere we see that the Jews had originally stopped building the temple for some personal\r\nreasons which were not connected to the Samaritans and legal advisors that played a\r\nsignificant role in the cessation. We will also examine this other subtle factor in this study.\r\nThe topics for this week are:', '2018-12-03 19:22:07'),
(72, 60, 'After the prophetic voices of Haggai and Zechariah woke up the Jews, they became\r\ndetermined to work and finish the temple. As we saw in the study of chapter 5, Tatnai the\r\ngovernor of the region questioned the Jews about the project until the matter reached\r\nDarius via a letter, in which Tatnai advised the king to check the records to see if Cyrus ever\r\nmade such a command to rebuild the Jerusalem temple (5:17). Our study text this week\r\nshows how an account of Cyrus\' edict is found, and how Darius subsequently sends a reply\r\nmessage to Tatnai, ordering that not only should he allow the Jews to build the temple, but\r\nany additional expenses they need for the temple and for the daily offerings should be given\r\nto them out of the royal treasury in Tatnai\'s jurisdiction. Darius also adds a strong warning of\r\ndestruction to anyone (including kings) who alters his commands or destroys the Jerusalem\r\ntemple (6:11-12). Tatnai has no choice but to speedily do as the king says, and the Jews\r\nFINALLY finish the temple with encouragement from Haggai and Zechariah. This sounds so\r\nunbelievable but a true reflection of how God works when we commit ourselves to the\r\nmandate of rebuilding and revival. God has a way of coming through in a measure that is\r\nbeyond our expectation. Clearly, when God\'s people wake up and become determined to do\r\nHis work, His Sovereign Hand will intervene to move heaven and earth to help them finish\r\nthe work. Determination precedes Divine Intervention. The subtopics to look at include:', '2018-12-03 19:37:15'),
(73, 61, 'This passage narrates the completion and also the dedication of the house of God. The\r\ntemple at Jerusalem was finally completed in the sixth year of Darius\' reign. The Israelites\r\noffered sacrifices to God at the dedication of the temple. They also kept the feast of Passover,\r\nand those who had been in the land before the exiles returned also partook in the feast. We\r\nwill see the conditions of “only those who had separated themselves from the filthy\r\npractices of the heathen [v. 21]” as God will never lower His standard of holiness. This\r\nportion of Ezra has a lot to teach God\'s people today.The topics of focus are:', '2018-12-03 19:50:39'),
(74, 63, 'Chapter 7 of Ezra begins with the phrase “Now after these things, in the reign of Artaxerxes\r\nking of Persia...” The setting here is about sixty years after the temple was completed under\r\nDarius\' reign, and it introduces the real man, Ezra. All the previous works that we have seen\r\nhave been carried out by Zerrubabel, Jeshua, Haggai and Zechariah. We are now formally\r\nintroduced to the man Ezra, who was a priest and a scribe in Babylon making a return to\r\nJerusalem after the temple has been built. He appears to be coming for the second phase of\r\nthe work after the temple has been completed.<br/>\r\nUnlike certain priests who could not trace their lineage in our previous study (2:59-63), Ezra\r\ncould prove through his genealogy that he was indeed a descendant of Aaron (7:1-5). He was\r\nthe man who built on the work of the temple to bring about true revival in the real sense of\r\nthe word and we shall understand this as we progress in this study. This study shows Ezra as a\r\nman of God indeed, who not only loved and practiced God\'s Word, but also had a great\r\nburden on his heart to go to Israel and teach God\'s people the way of the LORD (7:10). He\r\nmade a request of the king to allow him to return to the land of his ancestors, which the king\r\ngranted and also supported heavily through God\'s divine favour (7:6, 11-26). Ezra\'s zeal for\r\nJerusalem inspired many Jews to follow him out of Babylon and return to the holy land,\r\nshowing us that God can use an individual who has prepared his or her heart to bring mass\r\nrevival on a large scale. This study today emphasises the role of God\'s written Word in\r\nbringing revival in our postmodern era, with Ezra as a case study. The two subtopics are:', '2018-12-03 20:03:19'),
(75, 64, 'Chapter 8 of Ezra tells the story of how Ezra and his company gathered together for the four month\r\njourney from Babylon to Jerusalem. The passage for our study today is divided into\r\ntwo related parts. Verses 1-14 give the names of the heads of different families, and the\r\nnumbers of men that followed them on their journey. But there arose a problem in verse 15,\r\nnamely, that Ezra could not find any Levites among all those people. There were priests, but\r\nno Levites (that is, non-priests from the tribe of Levi); and Levites were needed to minister in\r\ndifferent roles in the temple as helpers to the priests in the temple\'s overall daily operations.\r\nIs it not often the problem these days? We may have ministers but there are no disciplers\r\nwho will manage the harvest when they arrive.', '2018-12-03 20:54:46'),
(76, 64, 'Ezra systematically solved the problem by sending eleven sensible men with his message\r\nunto a chief Levite named Iddo, who worked with Ezra\'s team to provide 258 Levites to go\r\nwith him to Jerusalem (v. 16-20). Though Ezra was a skilled scribe and priest, he knew that he\r\nneeded to surround himself with other necessary individuals if the revival was going to be a\r\nfull success. Revival starts with one person, but it never ends there. Other ministers are\r\nneeded for the work of God; as in Ezra\'s time, so also with us today. The topics we will look at\r\nfor this study include:', '2018-12-03 20:54:46'),
(77, 65, 'Ezra was well aware that the journey which they were about to undertake from Babylon to\r\nJerusalem was a dangerous and risky one. He did not pretend and underrate such a reality.\r\nThe fact that they were going to be travelling with many valuables only increased the threat,\r\nas robbers were known to lay in wait for vulnerable passers-by. He could not request armed\r\nescort from the king for protection, because he had already declared that God\'s good Hand\r\nwas upon those who seek Him, and it would have brought disrepute to the name of the\r\nLORD if he had turned around to ask for human protection after that statement he made to\r\nthe king. Now, Ezra must thread the spiritual path through a strong spiritual preparation\r\nbefore leaving the Ahava River in Babylon for this road trip to Jerusalem. He therefore\r\nproclaimed a fast for himself and his entourage (v. 21), humbling themselves before God to\r\nseek His face, His guidance, and His protection. So, they fasted and prayed, and God\r\nhearkened to their petition (v. 23).', '2018-12-03 21:11:07'),
(78, 65, 'Revival is not a one-day only affair, but an extended journey. It is a journey where there are\r\nspiritual enemies that also want to hinder us from completing that journey. There are many\r\nphysical and spiritual robbers waiting on our path and thus we must be fortified through\r\nFasting with prayer, as a strong tool for spiritual warfare in the ministry of revival. This will be\r\nthe main theme for this study.The topics are:', '2018-12-03 21:11:07'),
(79, 67, 'Not too long after Ezra and the second wave had arrived in Jerusalem, he was met with bad\r\nnews from some of the leaders of Israel. Many Israelites had intermarried with the Gentiles\r\nand also practiced their “abominations” (9:1), and to make the matter worse, it was the\r\nJewish leaders who were the ”leading” culprits in this transgression (9:2). God, through His\r\nLaw given to Moses, had forbidden Israelites from intermarrying with unconverted Gentiles\r\nbecause He knew they would influence His people to worship their idolatrous gods (Ex.\r\n34:11-16, Deut. 7:3-4). Ezra\'s response was first and foremost a heartfelt grief, as he tore his\r\ngarments in unbelief of what he was hearing, plucking out his hair before sitting down in deep\r\nastonishment of how a nation had receded in its service to God. But like a true agent of\r\nrevival, he could only remain inactive for a short time. By the evening sacrifice, he got on his\r\nknees and made a deep, heartfelt, remorseful confession of Israel\'s transgression to God.\r\nThough he was not guilty of this particular sin, he still identified himself as unworthy before\r\nGod, frequently using the terms “our” and “we” in his expression of the nation\'s error. This is\r\nwhat is called IDENTIFICATION PRAYER. You cannot be an agent of revival until you carry the\r\nburden of sin of others with high sense of involvement like the one Jesus did for us on the\r\ncross.', '2018-12-03 21:26:48'),
(80, 68, 'Ezra\'s great sorrow and remorseful intercession attracted many of the Israelites, as news\r\nmust have spread quickly about this skilled scribe who just returned from Babylon and is now\r\nweeping for Israel\'s sin in front of the temple. Men, women, and children assembled\r\nthemselves unto him, and the people also wept in acknowledgement of their sin (10:1). <b><i>This\r\nis the spirit of revival. It takes a man with the burden of sin to draw others unto genuine\r\nrepentance. It takes a man who feels the fire of God to shine the light of God on others. A\r\nman cannot give what he does not have!</i></b>', '2018-12-03 21:42:04'),
(81, 68, 'A man named Shechaniah took responsibility to speak for the congregation, and made the\r\nproposal to Ezra that they would make a covenant with God and put away all the pagan wives\r\nand children that were born of them (v. 2-4). The relevant parties agreed, and went through a\r\nthree-month process of evaluating the situation with each guilty Israelite, case by case (v. 16-\r\n17). Verse 18 reveals that some of the sons of Jeshua (the former high priest during\r\nZerubbabel\'s time who led the building of the temple) were found among the guilty,\r\nindicating that being a child of a minister does not automatically qualify for\r\ntransgenerational obedience except each member of the lineage consciously preserve the\r\nname of the Lord through genuine personal salvation.', '2018-12-03 21:42:04'),
(82, 68, 'We must mention here that God did not want Israel as a nation to become mixed and polluted\r\nwith the gods of the pagans, so the heathen wives had to be put away. This is a great principle\r\nthat is far beyond the marital application as used in this study because it is a pattern of God\'s\r\nexpectation on how we must do away with every connection with ungodliness, especially\r\nthose that are carried over, as soon as we become a born again Christian. This and many more\r\nwe shall explore in this study under the topics:', '2018-12-03 21:42:04'),
(83, 69, 'The Book of Nehemiah begins about 15 years after the book of Ezra ends, and about 100\r\nyears after the first captives returned to Jerusalem from Babylon after Cyrus\' decree. After\r\nsuch a lengthy period of time, Israel can claim that the temple has been rebuilt as a place of\r\nworship but the wall of Jerusalem was still in the same ruined condition from\r\nNebuchadnezzar\'s desolation of the city 150 years earlier. Even though a temple is rebuilt,\r\nthe city\'s wall and gates were still broken down. There seems to be a spiritual platform but\r\nothers things that secure a man\'s life appear broken and missing.', '2018-12-03 21:54:19'),
(84, 69, 'Nehemiah lived in Shushan the capital city of the Persians. He lived in the Citadel, which was\r\nthe fortified palace of the Persians. This was like living in the richest places in the land. From\r\nverse one, we know that Nehemiah was an important personality because he was living in\r\nthe king\'s palace, which is a validation of the fact that it is the nature of God to raise men and\r\nwomen to the place of prominence so as to use them for His purpose and glory.It could be\r\nsaid that Nehemiah was in Persia but his heart and interests were in Jerusalem. How do we\r\nassume this? When Nehemiah saw people who came from Jerusalem, he passionately asked\r\nabout the welfare of the city and the Jews (1:2). He was a busy man in the king\'s palace yet his\r\nheart still yearned for God\'s own city and His people. He was comfortable in the land of Persia\r\nbut still yearned for the land of Jerusalem. He was comfortable in the best places in life but his\r\nattachment to the land of his spiritual source was much more important to him.', '2018-12-03 21:54:19'),
(85, 69, 'The news that came from home was not pleasant to the ears of Nehemiah. The state of the\r\nnation was of utmost priority to him. As a Jew, he understood the implications of a city whose\r\nwalls were broken (See Prov. 25:28) The strength of a city was determined by how well fortified\r\nthe walls of that city were (like the walls of Jericho from Joshua 6). Like Jerusalem\r\nwith a temple but no wall, a life may be a temple of God but remains very exposed if it has no\r\nwall of financial, social, academic, career and life covering.', '2018-12-03 21:54:19'),
(86, 69, 'Nehemiah was heartbroken because his home country was vulnerable to attacks from\r\nenemy, invaders, wild animals, and any other form of aggression.\r\nThe topics for this opening study of Nehemiah will be:', '2018-12-03 21:54:19'),
(87, 71, 'Nehemiah was the king\'s cupbearer. He was a Jew by birth, but he was trained to learn and\r\nunderstand the lifestyle of the palace, reminiscent of the training Daniel and his friends\r\nreceived in Babylon (Dan. 1:3-5). The cupbearer was very close to the king for a number of\r\nreasons. including:', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(88, 71, '<ol>\r\n<li>The king “drank out of his hand”, so to speak.</li>', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(89, 71, '<li>He tasted what was good or bad for the king and had become acquainted with the\r\nking\'s preferences, so therefore was able to give recommendations to the wine\r\nmakers. He knew what was bad for the king and thus would never allow such to be\r\nbrought near the King. He did not need the King to tell him, he knew already.</li>', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(90, 71, '<li>He was like a friendly companion to the king, willing to lend a listening ear at all times\r\nand also give humble advice when appropriate.</li>', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(91, 71, '<li>He was a risk-taker who tasted the wine before the king drank it, in case an in-house\r\nenemy tried to poison the king. He was a man who would die for his king.</li></ol>', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(92, 71, 'The most critical aspect of Nehemiah\'s job was obviously that he was a risk-taker for the king.\r\nIf someone wanted to kill the king by poisoning, the cupbearer being the one who always\r\ntasted his drinks first would die instead. Like Nehemiah, how many of us today can take any\r\nrisk for our own King Jesus, who is the King of kings?', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(93, 71, 'The other part of this study focuses on how Nehemiah\'s training in the palace helped him\r\nbecome a leader in overseeing the efficient rebuilding of Jerusalem\'s wall. No education or\r\ntraining is ever wasted, and we should always look for opportunities to improve our\r\nknowledge base as we never know how God will use it in the future for His glory. The topics\r\nfor this study are:', '2018-12-04 07:07:00'),
(94, 72, 'Our passage today is an exposition into the spiritual preparation of Nehemiah in discharging\r\nthe mandate that came to him as a result of the message he had from his brethren who\r\nspoke to him about the broken walls and ruins in Jerusalem. We saw here how he went into\r\nfasting and prayer before God, as he prepared to make a request from Artaxerxes the king.\r\nNehemiah knew that revival cannot come unless one has first sought God\'s face and favour\r\nthrough serious fasting and prayer. It is not a mechanical work that responds to\r\nsophistication that is not birthed in deep intercession. This spiritual preparation is the\r\nfoundation which determines the height and steadfastness of the final completed building.\r\nNo revival work is greater than the quality of prayer preparation. The stronger and deeper\r\nthe foundation is, the stronger and higher the building can be constructed. Every lasting\r\nrevival throughout history, including through the church age, has been founded on deep\r\nspiritual preparation that originated in the hearts of men and women with a burden for\r\nGod\'s work and the welfare of humanity in general.', '2018-12-04 07:15:57'),
(95, 72, 'The focus of this study will be the indispensable role of spiritual preparation as we seek\r\nrevival and renewal both individually and corporately in our drive to repair the breach in our\r\nchurch and generation. Our study this week focuses on:', '2018-12-04 07:15:57'),
(96, 73, 'This portion of Nehemiah is where he makes his request known to the king. It begins with\r\ngiving us the precise month (Nisan), which is four months after the month Chislev when the\r\nnegative report first came to Nehemiah about the terrible state of Jerusalem (1:1). This\r\nshows that Nehemiah was praying, preparing, and seeking God\'s face for approximately four\r\nmonths until this particular day when he could no longer hide his concern for Jerusalem from\r\nthe king, and his sad countenance became visible to Artaxerxes. The king asked the reason\r\nfor the downcast look, and Nehemiah became afraid (v. 2). Some Bible scholars have said\r\nthat Nehemiah became afraid because in the ancient Persian culture it was an insult to the\r\nking for anyone to be sad in his presence, because the king was seen as such a wonderful\r\nperson that everyone should be happy when they saw him. So Artaxerxes noticing\r\nNehemiah\'s sad appearance had cause for concern for the Jew. But he took the risk and\r\nmentioned the reason, i.e., his hometown was in ruins. The king then asked him what he\r\nwanted. Nehemiah\'s intimate relationship with God is seen here as he made a quick silent\r\nprayer for God\'s favour before answering the king (v. 4-5).', '2018-12-04 07:26:06'),
(97, 73, 'As Nehemiah stated his request to the king, we can see that he had a clear vision of what he\r\nwanted to do at Jerusalem. There was no beating about the bush or indecision, just a simple\r\ngoal that he wanted to accomplish. This is a very crucial aspect of revival. We must be able to\r\ncommunicate our vision with clarity in ways that stimulate and provoke support and\r\ninterest. The topics for this study will be:', '2018-12-04 07:26:06'),
(98, 75, 'The Lord favoured Nehemiah and he got the approval and support of the king to start\r\nrebuilding the wall of Jerusalem. He left the glory and honour of the palace to a risky terrain\r\nthat was lower in value. He was willing to let go of his stature for the sake of preserving the\r\nkingdom and the welfare of the brethren who are in ridicule in Jerusalem. Here we see how\r\nhe arrived safely at Jerusalem, and for three days, he told none of the Jews he met what his\r\nplans were for the city. He initially kept it to himself for good reasons. There are many\r\nvaluable leadership lessons here. One of the clear reasons he did so was because he needed\r\ntime to do a feasibility study of the city, taking note of the damages and what amount of\r\nresources would precisely be needed for the work of rebuilding. He needed to translate the\r\nspiritual burden into clear easy-to-understand physical details. Vision operates well when\r\nthe leaders can articulate the details beyond just the spiritual of “God told me”. Excellence is\r\ntruly in the details and Verses 13-15 show us that he left no stone unturned, but made sure\r\nhe had a clear understanding of the current situation. He did not want anyone to interfere\r\nwith this crucial process. Verse 16 again shows that he did all the evaluation in the night to\r\navoid any distraction or call any unnecessary attention to himself. He effectively toured and\r\nexamined the city during the <b>night</b> as was mentioned in verses 12-13. Nehemiah finally\r\nbroke his silence in verses 17-18, revealing how both God and the king Artaxerxes had\r\nfavoured him, and had granted him permission to build the city. The people were in full\r\nagreement, and were encouraged to do the work. He heard from God, he got favour with\r\nmen, he made detailed evaluation and he communicated with precision in ways that drove\r\nthe desired actions.', '2018-12-04 13:07:44'),
(99, 75, 'The road to revival will require tact, wisdom, and paying close attention to details. It requires\r\neffective planning and counting the cost through intensive and intelligent analysis of issues.\r\nReal work of the kingdom is not for shallow thinkers or lazy executors, it is for a sound mind\r\nthat can think through end-to-end to deliver an outcome that glorifies the Lord. Our topics\r\nfor study are:', '2018-12-04 13:07:44'),
(100, 76, 'Nehemiah 2:16-18 showed us how he revealed the plan of rebuilding to the Jews and how\r\nhis effective planning and communication ensured acceptance and support for the project.\r\nNow, it was time to get the work done and we shall discover the secret of successful kingdom\r\nwork based on the approach of inclusion and involvement that Nehemiah deployed, which\r\nexplains how the work was completed in under two months (52 days!)\r\nHere we see Nehemiah\'s leadership skills on display. We observe how he assigned different\r\npeople to handle different parts of this huge project. He broke the task down into bits and\r\npieces. He simplified a complex task into manageable elements, while providing the\r\nnecessary oversight function that enabled the smooth running of the project as a whole. This\r\nchapter of Nehemiah proves that there is power in excellent leadership, those who can work\r\nwith others with clarity and the importance of having the right people to delegate to. The\r\ntask of revival is not a one-man job. It begins with the burden God places on one or two\r\npeople\'s hearts, but after a while it becomes a corporate affair. Everyone must have a sense\r\nof ownership.<br/>\r\nIt is a concern these days that certain people are overwhelmed because they have failed to\r\ndelegate responsibilities, either because they are afraid that the subordinates will make\r\nthem irrelevant or maybe because there are no quality sons or daughters who can be trusted\r\nwith the excellence of good delivery.\r\nIn this study, we will examine the importance of leadership and effective delegation. The\r\ntopics will be:', '2018-12-04 13:20:58'),
(101, 77, 'In the previous study, we saw how the work was divided among the people, and the building\r\nprocess carried on smoothly. The enemy knew it was time to strike. Sanballat, Tobiah and\r\nGeshem the Arabian who were previously mentioned in Nehemiah 2 are now being\r\nmentioned again. These men, after they heard of the Jews\' intention to rebuild the wall and\r\nthe ruined parts of Jerusalem, responded with mock and scorn.Nehemiah did not give them\r\na foothold; he told them plainly,“Ye have no portion, nor right, nor memorial, in Jerusalem.”\r\nHe took a strong stand and was determined to stop these people from disrupting what God\r\nwas about to do. There was no negotiation with the enemy!', '2018-12-04 13:40:02'),
(102, 77, 'Now in Chapter 4, Sanballat heard about the progress they were making and became more\r\nfurious. The Hebrew word here actually means “burning mad”. He came with his people to\r\nmock the Jews again like he did in 2:19, but now he realised that mockery and scornful\r\nremark will not stop the well determined builders from fulfilling the mandate of repairing, so\r\nthey switched tactics to now include intimidation and words of discouragement. When\r\nSatan sees that he cannot get us in one way, he will look for other avenues to try and stop the\r\nwork of God in our lives and ministry.', '2018-12-04 13:40:02'),
(103, 77, 'The topics for this week\'s study are:', '2018-12-04 13:40:02'),
(104, 79, '“Now it came to pass” is a powerful reassuring introduction into Nehemiah Chapter 6,\r\nwhich is a great point of fulfilment indicating the completion of the wall of Jerusalem. It did\r\nnot happen without one final attempt from the enemy. When Sanballat and his\r\ncompanions heard that the wall was almost finished (except for attaching gates to the\r\nspaces left open for them), they resorted to a quite pathetic tactic of pretending to seek\r\npeace and reconciliation with Nehemiah (6:1-2). For the enemies of Nehemiah and the\r\nwork of God, this was a \"now-or-never\" time. If they failed to do something immediately to\r\nstop the work, the walls will be completely finished.', '2018-12-04 19:13:18'),
(105, 79, 'They reached out to Nehemiah inviting him to the meeting, but changed tactic yet again\r\nafter it became clear that he would never come. The latest tactic was to claim that rumours\r\nwere spreading that Nehemiah was only building the wall because he wanted to rebel\r\nagainst Persia and become king of an independent Jewish State. They claimed that the\r\nrumours included him hiring prophets to preach about him in Jerusalem as the new king of\r\nJudea. Sanballat tried to use this to reason with Nehemiah that if this so-called rumour gets\r\nto the ears of Artaxerxes, it would mean trouble for him and the Jews. He therefore tried to\r\nuse this tactic to lure Nehemiah into agreeing to come to a meeting where they could talk\r\nand resolve the problem (v. 5-7). But Nehemiah knew it was all false, and, as usual, he\r\nprayed to God for strength (v. 8-9).', '2018-12-04 19:13:18'),
(106, 79, 'Sanballat and Tobiah hired other people to pretend to be prophets, who told Nehemiah lies\r\nto try to make him afraid. But by the grace of God he persevered, and the wall was finally\r\ncompleted in a total of 52 days. When God\'s hand is upon a project and we remain focused,\r\nthe enemy\'s attempts to stop the work will prove to be futile in the end, and it will be known\r\nthat we didn\'t do it with our own strength alone (v. 16). Let us know that the enemy can do\r\nanything and everything to frustrate every good thing that we are doing for God and we\r\nmust be aware of this.', '2018-12-04 19:13:18'),
(107, 79, 'The topics to look at in this study include:', '2018-12-04 19:13:41'),
(108, 81, 'Nehemiah and the Jews had gotten the victory over their enemies and triumphantly\r\ncompleted the protective wall to surround Jerusalem. However, the battle was far from over.\r\nThe walls and gates had to be regulated by responsible watchmen who took shifts to keep\r\nguard by watching out for invaders, intruders, and illegal persons. Christians must not go to\r\nsleep after a victory, but continue to watch and pray because the enemy is still alive and still\r\nseeks to do damage.', '2018-12-04 19:29:16'),
(109, 81, 'Nehemiah not only saw the need for watchmen, he also saw the necessity of appointing\r\nleaders who could carry the torch long after he returned to Persia according to the set time\r\nhe had promised the king. During the process of rebuilding the wall, he had seen the\r\npotential in two men, whom he gave the responsibility of leadership. How many fellowships\r\ncollapse as soon as someone leaves? Nehemiah knew he had to go back based on his promise\r\nto the king and thus had invested in high quality men who will sustain the work even after he\r\nhad left. It\'s always said that success without a successor is a failure. Who are you raising to\r\ntake over from you in every sphere of influence the Lord has put you in? <b>Leaders are not\r\nraised during executive choice retreat, they are raised over time and confirmed at a\r\nretreat.</b>', '2018-12-04 19:29:16'),
(110, 81, 'In addition, Nehemiah saw that the Jewish population was few and mostly poor, and many\r\nhouses destroyed by the Babylonians were still not rebuilt. God placed it in his heart to help\r\nthe people grow and prosper. True spiritual revival will not only build spiritual walls over lives,\r\nit progresses and increases. Revival is a lifter and a channel of enlargement. When the\r\npresence of God is activated in holiness in the place of revival, it comes with abundance and\r\ndivine prosperity. This is the reason why Nehemiah took a look at the old genealogical record\r\nwritten by the first Jews who returned with Zerubbabel. We shall see why he took note of the\r\ngenealogy, and why the people are the backbone of lasting revival.<br/>\r\nThe topics for study include:', '2018-12-04 19:29:16'),
(111, 82, 'Jerusalem\'s walls were now standing tall, watchmen were set in place, and the people had\r\npeace and joy. They observed Nehemiah and knew that God was with him, and that this 52-\r\nday success of building the wall despite their enemies\' opposition was nothing less than\r\nGod\'s Hand. These things made the people hungry to know the Lord better, and they\r\nthemselves requested that Ezra the scribe educate them in the word of the Lord (8:1). This is\r\nthe ultimate manifestation of true revival when people willingly seek for more of God. In this\r\nstudy, we see how Ezra\'s preaching got the people\'s attention, and they were in no hurry to\r\nleave (v. 3) and they waited patiently for Bible study for about 6 hours non-stop, from\r\nmorning till midday. This is a contrast to our modern time when many people will be\r\nchecking their watched repeatedly for a quick completion of the message. The key element\r\nin preaching God\'s Word is the Holy Spirit Himself. It was the Spirit that moved the people\'s\r\nhearts to seek the things of God, and it was the Spirit also speaking through Ezra. This is the\r\nessence of revival activated by the presence of the Holy Spirit.', '2018-12-04 19:40:08'),
(112, 82, 'A few verses in this chapter state that the people UNDERSTOOD the message of God\'s word\r\nthat was preached (v. 7, 8, 12). This understanding of what the Lord was saying made them\r\nshed tears of repentance and sorrow for their sins at first (v. 9), but the initial brokenness\r\nturned into joy because they understood that there was also forgiveness and blessing with\r\nGod (v. 12). Understanding God\'s message is what propels revival among the people. Even\r\nthe other priests and Levites gathered the next day to understand God\'s word better from\r\nEzra (v. 13). What a powerful revival that took place in Jerusalem! People wept, repented,\r\nand became obedient to God\'s Word. The word of God came alive! We clearly see from all\r\nthis that the Bible is an indispensable tool in bringing revival to the masses. Any revival that is\r\ncharacterised by only prayers, vigils, anointing service without a renewed passion and\r\nunderstanding of the word of God will not last. The topics for our study this week shall be:', '2018-12-04 19:40:08'),
(113, 83, 'These two chapters of Nehemiah are directly connected so we are putting them together. In\r\nthe last chapter we studied (ch. 8), the people had begun to return to the law of Moses,\r\nespecially after Ezra\'s powerful preaching. A new level of spiritual awakening and thirst for\r\nGod has commenced with great impact. Chapter 9 now opens with their expression of\r\nhumble repentance towards God. Their internal remorse for neglecting God\'s laws all these\r\nyears was now showing forth by external actions. Matthew 3:8 says that the genuinely\r\nrepentant sinner must,“Bring forth therefore fruits meet for repentance”. Verses 4-6\r\nmention the names of some Levites who admonished the people to rise and bless the Name\r\nof the LORD, before they led them into a long session of prayer of confession of Israel\'s sins\r\nboth past and present. This prayer takes up the rest of chapter 9 (from verses 7-37),\r\nrecounting from Abram\'s early beginnings before going into how Israel\'s history is filled with\r\ntheir disobedience to the Lord and His judgements and mercies towards them. The prayer\r\nconcludes with a petition for God\'s mercy concerning their present situation, including how\r\nthey were presently being ruled by the kingdom of Persia which was part of God\'s judgement\r\nfor all their sins (v. 32-37).<br/>\r\nAfter the solemn prayer, chapter 10 records how the people entered into a covenant with\r\nGod by oath, vowing to live by all His laws, which were handed to Moses. We could say they\r\nrenewed the old covenant and re-dedicated their lives to the LORD. There was a national\r\nremorse and repentance, followed by a national revival and transformation. As we drive\r\nrevival in our lives, church, we must understand how this must translate into our society or\r\nwhat is the essence of having churches at every corner and yet the nation remains\r\nunchanged in its governance, morality and lifestyle. We as a country and as individuals have\r\na lot to learn from these two chapters of God\'s word as we close our year-long exposition\r\ninto the books of Ezra and Nehemiah. The topics for discussion include:', '2018-12-04 19:49:45');
