INSERT INTO `teachings` (`teaching-id`, `point-id`, `row`, `date`) VALUES
(1, 1, 'During this period, the city of Ephesus was the fourth largest and was well known as a centre of trade, as well as diversity of cultures, art, and religion. The native Ephesians were strongly devoted to and worshipped the goddess Artemis (or Diana in Latin; e.g., Acts 19:27, 35). The magnificent temple of Artemis was included among the seven wonders of the world at that time. For this reason, many locals were enraged at Paul when he came into their city preaching the “one true God,” as a result of financial loss among the silversmiths who made idols. But other than the faithful followers of Diana, Ephesus was also filled with various spiritualists, including wizards, soothsayers, sorcerers, and astrologers. Some men and women from these groups might have believed the Gospel that Paul preached (Acts 19:18–19), but mixed the truth of God with their former religious practices. Such practice would naturally lead to false doctrines infiltrating the newly converted Ephesian church, with these false teachers combining the doctrines of Christ with their own doctrines thereby confusing and misleading the “young” church. For an average Yoruba, you can recall the concept of, “Igbagbo o ni ka ma s’oro,” meaning, “Christianity is not against traditional religion.” This error is something we must avoid, as we seek to offer reasonable service unto God.', '2018-02-17 17:57:44'),
(2, 1, 'In his epistle to the Ephesians, Paul strongly emphasised how Jesus is God the Son, and how He is above all principality and power and any name that is named (Eph. 1:21). He also stated blatantly that the Father was together with the Son in the creation of the universe (Eph. 3:9). The purpose of such statements was to let the believers fully understand that Jesus is not another “god,” or another school of thought, as many of these had begun to pollute the church. He encouraged them to not follow what the other Gentiles did, “in the vanity of their mind” (Eph. 4:17). We are called to put on the whole armour of God to successfully stand against the “wiles” (deceptions, falsehoods, trickery) of the devil (Eph. 6:11), which includes, among other things, false doctrines and philosophies from deceptive teachers.', '2018-02-17 17:57:44'),
(3, 1, 'Paul was not going to leave this church under heavy enemy attack; so when he had to continue his tour of the churches he made sure his trusted and faithful “son” remained with them as long as necessary. Can we be trusted to raise the standard of God, especially when others are not there with us?', '2018-02-17 17:57:44'),
(4, 2, 'Paul and Timothy’s relationship emphasised why we need people around us in our quest to serve God reasonably. Paul had a great team of fellow labourers and associates in the Gospel. One of his most cherished relationships was the one he had with Timothy (or Timotheos, meaning “dear to God”), the young disciple from Lystra. Timothy had earned himself a positive reputation among the congregation in Lystra and Iconium (Acts 16:2). He was also very young, possibly still in his teens when he met Paul, and the great apostle might have seen him as someone willing to humbly learn and be an apprentice. His mixed Jewish and Greek background was also appealing to Paul’s own background and personality. The combination of these factors led to an awesome relationship of love, respect, and trust, which ultimately became a kind of father-son experience, as Paul continually mentioned (1 Cor. 4:17, Phil. 2:22, 1 Tim. 1:2, 18, 2 Tim. 1:2).', '2018-02-17 17:57:44'),
(5, 2, 'Building strong relationships such as that of Timothy and Paul is necessary for many reasons in our service to the Lord. For example, Paul needed someone he could rely on to safeguard the Ephesian church from false teachers. Without a strong bond, communion, and understanding, he would be so unsure as to who was suitable for this particular job. Even though Timothy was very young and even shy, Paul knew he was strong in the Scriptures and in the Spirit (2 Tim. 1:6–7, 3:15); therefore, he was equipped to handle the task. In addition, Paul knew he did not have anybody else like Timothy who would genuinely care for the overall well-being of the churches (e.g., Phil. 2:20).', '2018-02-17 17:57:44'),
(6, 2, 'Timothy, on the other hand, needed a mentor like Paul. There was much to learn in Christ after salvation, and Paul became the spiritual “father” that Timothy never had (his natural father being a Greek). He was more than happy and willing to learn from and serve such a person who had been handpicked by the Lord Himself to be an ambassador of the Gospel to both the Jews and the Gentiles (Acts 9:15). No doubt, Timothy’s “reasonable service” to the Lord was greatly enhanced by his relationship and partnership with Paul. As a TACEFite, you need a discipler and a mentor who will help you maximise your potential in the path of reasonable service. Let us not be a lone ranger or a fatherless saint, struggling to grow alone or jumping from one spiritual covering to another. We need long-term submission to a leadership and discipleship programme to be able to come out great in the journey to the Promised Land.', '2018-02-17 17:57:44'),
(7, 3, 'After the introductory greeting, Paul shows that his young protégé (Timothy) had an obligation to make sure the church was guarded against teachers who were not conveying the wholesome doctrine of Christ, but misleading believers with their personal versions of truth. Paul understood the consequences of falsehoods being fed to the flock. Healthy meals lead to a healthy body; but the opposite is also true. Spiritually, holding false information in your heart and mind keeps one blinded from reality and can ultimately lead to spiritual death. This is one of the major reasons why false teaching is so dangerous—it leads to living incorrectly and ultimately to destruction (temporal or, if not corrected, eternal).', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(8, 3, 'God has appointed teachers in his church (Eph. 4:11–12) to educate his people about sin, judgement, salvation, redemption, His kingdom, the power of His Spirit, and other necessary realities. Unfortunately, as predicted by Paul in Acts 20:29–30, “grievous wolves” have found their ways into the congregation, with their personal agendas and false teachings. This has done great damage to the body of Christ worldwide.', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(9, 3, 'Today, we now have hyper-grace gospel that says, once-saved-ever-saved, which means sinners will go to heaven. They are turning the Bible upside down and taking the grace of God as a license to live their lives anyhow. We must avoid erroneous teachings such as this.', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(10, 4, 'Verse 4 of our study text speaks of fables, genealogies, and “questions.” What Paul was telling Timothy “to pay no attention to” in this verse is in reference to Jewish teachers of that time who had mixed the Law of Moses with their own vain traditions. Remember that this was the same era (first century A.D.) as the Pharisees, who the Lord Jesus had to correct on many occasions concerning the false teachings which they had intertwined into the God-given Mosaic Law (Matt. 15:7-9).', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(11, 4, 'The “fables” (Greek muthos = myth or fiction) refer to those teachings held by a good percentage of rabbis before and during the first century, which hijacked the Scriptures and twisted them into fairy tales. An example of this is the Book of Jubilees (written around 100 B.C.) which takes the historic account of events from Genesis and perverts them with untrue tales of mythology. Fable is also when a minister comes to the podium and relies on the latest movies he watched on African Magic which are based on mythology, tradition, and mysticism to preach. This is wrong! When did the altar become the platform for comedy, fantasy, and reinforcement of witchcraft? When did the altar become the opportunity to trigger fear in the hearts of people by emphasising the power of the devil through traditional African stories that de-emphasise the finished work of Calvary?', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(12, 4, 'Paul was letting Timothy see that the fables and endless genealogies will only produce speculations as to what is actually true and what is not. When it comes to foundational doctrines, it is not the will of God for His people to grope about in the dark and speculate about things. He gave the church the Holy Scriptures back then as He has delivered them to us now. “Thy word is a lamp unto my feet, and a light unto my path,” so said the psalmist (Ps. 119:105). It is by rightly dividing the word of truth (2 Tim. 2:15) that we can correctly hold fast to what is sound doctrine while disposing off the toxic teachings.', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(13, 5, 'Instead of entertaining the twisted interpretations of the law by the false teachers, Timothy was informed by Paul (1 Tim. 1:5) that the whole purpose of the law was to bring the disciple to the place of sincere, genuine love for God and man. The Lord Jesus has said, “If ye love me, keep my commandments” (John 14:15). The LORD also made the same direct connection between loving Him and keeping His commandments (Exod. 20:6). The Lord Jesus hang all the law on two commandments (Matt. 22:40), which are to love God wholly (Deut. 6:5) and to love neighbour as thyself (Lev. 19:18). Those who love God obey Him. In fact, those who claim to know God but refrain from keeping His commandments are liars (1 John 2:4).', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(14, 5, 'Paul emphasised that this charity can only come from a heart that is pure; and also from a good conscience and sincere faith. The word conscience is a very strong Greek word suneidesis, which means a co-perception (i.e., moral consciousness). The “co-” in the meaning of the word means that only two people are aware of your innermost thoughts—the two people are you and God. A good conscience means the person has made up his mind to think according to God’s will, as “he that is joined unto the Lord is one spirit” (1 Cor. 6:17). This conviction, along with a pure heart and sincere faith, is how a person attains the “end of the commandment”—love. And this is not the worldly kind of love, by the way, but the selfless, spiritual love that has the interest of the other person at heart—sacrificing one’s own comfort for the welfare of the other. This kind of love is what God wants us to have toward each other. May we get there in the Lord Jesus’ name. Amen.', '2018-02-17 18:03:40'),
(15, 6, 'The Jewish false teachers had obviously misapplied the Mosaic Law. One of the ways which they did this was by teaching that observing the Law (including the ceremonial rituals) was necessary for one’s salvation, even while acknowledging the redemptive work of Christ. An example is found in Acts 15, where some teachers were peddling the doctrine that unless believers were circumcised and kept the Law, they could not be saved (Acts 15:1, 5). However, they did not have the true revelation that “by the deeds of the Law shall no flesh be justified in [God’s] sight” (Rom. 3:20). Verse 9 of our study text shows us that the Law is not made for a “righteous man.” The righteous man in this sense is he who has come to faith in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus, the kind of faith that causes him to repent from sin—making up his mind to follow and obey the Lord. Such a person need not be told not to do the kinds of things listed in verses 9–10. He already knows and His new nature cannot operate in that domain again on a continued basis. In addition, the ceremonial rituals of the Law were for Israel under the old covenant, so it was a misapplication for these Pharisees to impose them on the church.  ', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(16, 6, 'So, what is the purpose of the Law for us?', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(17, 6, 'THE LAW CONVICTS MAN OF HIS SINFUL NATURE! ', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(18, 6, 'This is because God’s perfect nature and holiness is revealed in the Law, and mankind has fallen from perfection since Adam’s transgression in Eden. The average person has little idea of just how holy God is. In fact, some prophets of old were shocked and even terrified at the presence of God’s spotless perfection and holiness. God does not plainly reveal Himself to all mankind; otherwise, there would not be any need for faith. God wants us to love Him by choice, not out of fear. But He has revealed His holiness in the Law so that we can see that all have sinned and come short of His glory (Rom. 3:23). This conviction is what leads us to Christ, as we see how desperately we need Him. Nobody has ever kept God’s law of righteousness to perfection, but the Lord Jesus did—and now He is the only means by which sinful man can be redeemed. God’s Word says that the “law was our schoolmaster to bring us unto Christ, that we might be justified by faith” (Gal. 3:24).', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(19, 7, 'As used in verses 9 and 10 of our study text, the word translated as “sound” is the Greek hugiain? which literally means to be “healthy.” In other words, the spiritual health of the church is directly dependent on our observation of sound, healthy teaching and instruction. Therefore, “unsound” doctrine will also lead to an unhealthy and spiritually diseased church. As mentioned in the previous week, one of the greatest errors in doctrine in our generation is the belief and teaching of some that since Christ has fully paid the price for our sins, we are under “grace” and guaranteed a place in His kingdom regardless of how we live. This unhealthy doctrine belittles the necessity of obedience and holiness, and negates what the Lord said (Matt. 7:21). Because of such doctrine, many “Christians” come to Christ not for a real relationship and partnership, but just for what they can receive materially to live a “happy” life. No wonder the church today is so weak, and some misrepresents who God really is. Unwholesome doctrine produces anaemic and backsliding believers, but teaching the full Gospel in truth produces spiritually strong men and women of God.', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(20, 8, 'Paul in verse 11 says that the Law is in accordance with the Gospel. Moreover, he employs the word “glorious” in connection to the nature of the Gospel. He already stated in verse 8 that the Law is good, but now he is showing a transition from something that was “good” to something that is not just better, but “glorious.” Praise God! He further emphasised this in 2 Corinthians 3:7–18, where he indeed says that the Law was also glorious, but (in verse 10) that the glory of the Gospel “excels” (Greek huperball? = “surpass”). Hebrews 8:6 again shows that the new covenant is “better” than the former, and carries better promises. While the law works by punishment on what we fail to do, Grace works by enablement and ability to do God’s will by His spirit at work in us. Blessed be God, we belong to the grace and truth that came by the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(21, 9, 'In conclusion of this portion of his epistle to Timothy, Paul stated that the Gospel message was committed to his trust. This means that God did not just save him for [Paul’s] own personal benefit only, but was also entrusting the further spread of the salvation message to his care. We also, who have been saved by God through the Good News of His Son Jesus, are expected to communicate the same word of salvation to others.', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(22, 9, 'Properly using God’s Law of righteousness to explain to our fellow man why we have all fallen short of God’s glory is a good place to start. The good news can only be appreciated after the horror of the bad news has been realized. A person who knows he is a sinner under God’s judgement will flee quicker to Christ for refuge than a person who believes he is “good.” We are, therefore, under obligation to offer reasonable service to God by ministering the Gospel to our fellow man.', '2018-02-17 18:09:19'),
(23, 10, 'Apostle Paul would never have gone down in history today as one of the most important servants of God of all time, if not for the enabling mercy of the Lord. The word “enabled” in verse 12 is the Greek endunamoo which means “to empower,” and is derived from a well-known Greek word dunamis—endowment of power. Paul acknowledged he was once “a blasphemer” (1 Tim. 1:13). He admitted he was “a persecutor” recalling how he oppressed the believers, even consenting to the death of Stephen. But one thing about Paul is that he was zealous thinking what he was doing was the best way to serve the God of his father. But in spite of his zeal towards God, he was not yet “enabled” to believe in the Lord Jesus Christ, or see that the Law and the prophets whom he loved so much actually pointed to the Lord Jesus as Messiah. This was where the mercy of God had to step in. It took an explicit manifestation and proclamation of the Lord Himself (Acts 9:5) to turn his unbelief to saving faith. This is why we must continue to pray for the mercy of God who opens the eyes of sinners unto salvation—it is the foundation of a true encounter with the One true God, beyond the shackles of religion.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(24, 11, 'Paul spoke of the grace of God being “exceeding abundant” (1 Tim. 1:14). This phrase is translated from the word huperpleonaz?, which means to not only be abundant but superabundant, that is, far more than abundant. He was saying that he was so deep in unbelief and spiritual blindness, but God’s grace was more than sufficient to pull him out into deliverance and salvation. Many people, in times past and presently, have felt that they have gone too far (drowned) in sin and ungodliness, and that there is no way God could ever accept or forgive them after all they have done. Paul used his salvation experience to show such people that God’s grace in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus is far more than enough to not only forgive them, but also enable them to become powerful ministers of God. This is what he meant in verse 16 when he spoke of himself being a “pattern” [hupotup?sis = “a sketch for imitation”] that the Lord used to show His patience and superabundant grace upon sinners. This understanding must encourage our hearts as repairers of the breach, especially the knowledge that no one is too bad or too sinful to the point that he cannot be saved. The superabundant grace of God can save anyone—even the worst of sinners!', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(25, 12, 'It is a beautiful thing to know that the Lord Jesus Christ came into the world to save sinners. Paul most assuredly acknowledged this in verse 15, but also stated that he is “chief” among sinners. The word rendered as chief is the Greek protos which means foremost or first. Paul spoke with deep sense of gratitude of how he appreciated his salvation. We can tell from similar statements where he claimed to be “less than the least of all saints” (Eph. 3:8) or where he professed to be “the least of the apostles” (1 Cor. 15:9). These statements showed humility, mainly because he always remembered how he persecuted the precious believers of his Lord and Saviour, and, therefore, felt a sense of unworthiness. But this “chief” of sinners also became the chief of servants, as he himself testified in the verse that immediately followed. So even though he said he was the least of the apostles because of his crimes against the church, he also (truthfully) stated he laboured more abundantly than they did (1 Cor. 15:10). Paul’s life is a proof that our past is not a determinant of how far God can use us, if we choose the path of reasonable service.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(26, 13, 'Paul closed this portion of his first epistle to Timothy by expressing his gratitude to God for his generous grace and mercy in the gift of salvation, giving him all the glory and praise (1 Tim. 1:17).', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(27, 13, 'a)	God is the eternal king; we are his subjects.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(28, 13, 'b)	He is immortal; we are liable to physical death.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(29, 13, 'c)	He is invisible; we are in the visible realm.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(30, 13, 'd)	He is the God who alone possesses all wisdom; our own understanding is limited.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(31, 13, 'We all have to be extremely grateful that such a God would come down and save us. Thank God that “the Word was made flesh, and dwelt among us” (John 1:14, 1 Tim. 3:16). Thank God that He has made the Lord Jesus to be sin for us, who knew no sin; that we might be made the righteousness of God in Him (2 Cor. 5:21, Isaiah 53:6, 11). Thank God that we will not perish, but live eternally with Him in glory (John 3:16)—the way life was originally intended to be.', '2018-02-17 18:13:30'),
(32, 14, '“The prophecies which went before on thee” in Timothy (1 Tim. 1:18) may be directly connected to the earlier years of Timothy as a young disciple in Lystra and Iconium (Acts 16:2). There is reason to believe that there is a further connection with the “gift” which was in Timothy by the prophecies and laying on hands of the elders in those cities (1 Tim. 4:14). God must have begun to show those around Timothy that something was special about him and that he was set apart for a very special ministry. Clearly, the future of the young brother Timothy was birthed in the womb of prophecy. It is, therefore, not a surprise that Paul said to the church in Corinth, “desire earnestly to prophesy” (1 Cor. 14:39).', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(33, 14, 'We must also appreciate the higher dimension of the written Scriptural prophecies, which did not come by the will of the writers but by the activation and unveiling of God’s Spirit (2 Pet. 1:21). In addition, there is great importance in unwritten prophecies, which God gives to forewarn and prepare His people for a specific event. For example, in Acts 11:27-30, the Spirit revealed to Agabus that there would be a great famine throughout the world, and the prophecy came to pass during the reign of Claudius Caesar. Here, God used a prophecy through Agabus to inform His people in order to  prepare themselves against famine, just as how He revealed Pharaoh’s dream to Joseph for a similar reason (Gen. 41).', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(34, 14, 'In our walk with the Lord Jesus Christ through this present world, we must remain attentive to the voice of the Spirit (Rev. 2:29), as God still speaks through His people today. The gift of prophecy is a beneficial tool for the church to help navigate not only our personal lives, but also specific decisions concerning our works and ministries. The same Spirit of God in us will let us know who is actually speaking by the Spirit and who is a false prophet, because for every original prophecy, there are many fakes.', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(35, 14, 'In Timothy’s case, the prophecies that were spoken would have been a great source of encouragement during challenging times, as he would recall those things that were said and use them to his advantage. This is a strong advantage of prophecy: it strengthens us during trials and afflictions, helps us make wiser decisions and better choices. Paul said Timothy should use prophetic knowledge to “war a good warfare.”', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(36, 15, 'The next exhortation to Timothy is “holding faith” and “a good conscience.” The combination of these two virtues results in what is called integrity, which is also defined as moral soundness. It is a conviction of what is right, and the determination to follow and do what is right. A person may have faith, but lack “good conscience.” God’s Word says it is not enough to believe (even demons believe), but faith must be complemented by works (James 2:19-20). It is of no benefit to know the truth but not act in accordance. “Holding” in Greek means to hold, but more specifically to “possess”. We must possess faith and a good conscience. This means that regardless of the situation we find ourselves, we must continue to operate in faith—faith must become who we are at all times; we must possess faith and also be possessed by faith! A good conscience works together with faith to bring God’s approval, and the enemy will not be able to stand against our lives and ministry under these circumstances.', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(37, 16, 'In verse 19, Paul said that putting away faith and good conscience leads to shipwreck of faith - that is a journey that drowns in the middle of a great sea. ', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(38, 16, 'It is a painful experience to see many who started out believing in the Lord Jesus Christ, but down the road fall away for one reason or the other, thereby becoming casualties, that is, losing their faith. In the parable of the sower (Mark 4:14–20), a class of people put away faith when tribulation and persecution came (Mark 4:17) and those who yielded to the pressures of this world and deceitfulness of riches; and suffered a great loss of their seed sown. Only those who held faith and a good conscience (“good ground,” Mark 4:20) retained the word sown and reproduced fruits in life and ministry.', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(39, 17, 'In explaining issues of shipwreck or drowning of one’s faith, Paul named two of such persons (Hymenaeus and Alexander) who had not only caused a shipwreck of their faith, but had also become blasphemers. They went from being backsliders to becoming Christ’s enemies who opposed the faith. Hymenaeus is probably the same person mentioned in 2 Timothy 2:17–18, and Alexander is probably the coppersmith mentioned in 2 Timothy 4:14–15. These men were both known to blaspheme. In the first passage mentioned above, it was said that Hymenaeus had erred from the truth and even overthrew the faith of some by teaching that the resurrection and rapture had already passed. In the second passage, Paul said that Alexander did him much evil, and “greatly withstood our words.” This signifies that he was teaching things contrary to Paul’s words and doctrine.', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(40, 17, 'But what did Paul mean by saying he had delivered them unto Satan? Well, this same expression was  used by the apostle in 1 Corinthians 5:5, concerning the case of a fornicator. In this case, Paul said that the delivering unto Satan was for the purpose of “the destruction of the flesh that the spirit may be saved in the day of the Lord Jesus.” So he is most likely doing the same to Hymenaeus and Alexander for the same reason. The point is that Satan is the god of this world (2 Cor. 4:4)—the ungodly world is his domain. If a fellow Christian is in error, there is a step-by-step procedure to correct the problem according to the Lord Jesus in Matthew 18:15-17. If the erring Christian refuses to receive correction from you alone, then the matter should be presented before two or three witnesses; if he still refuses, then the matter should be presented before the church. If he refuses to hear the church, then he should be rejected and seen as a worldly unbeliever. Now Paul did not intend for the erring Christian to be lost forever, but that he should feel the pain of being excommunicated from the church so that he may return later in acknowledgment of his error (2 Thess. 3:14-15). This is what he means by “the destruction of the flesh that the spirit may be saved in the day of the Lord Jesus” (1 Cor. 5:5). Hymenaeus and Alexander would only be received back into the Ephesian church if they acknowledged their error and turned in repentance. This same principle still applies today. Blasphemy and teaching of false doctrines should not be overlooked in the church, but should be handled according to the Lord Jesus’ words (Matt. 18:15–17). Better to receive correction now and be saved later when the time comes to meet the Lord; than to continue in error and eventually hear him say “depart from me, ye workers of iniquity.”', '2018-02-17 18:20:43'),
(41, 18, 'In chapter 1 of First Timothy, Paul instructed Timothy what to do. But in chapter 2, Paul instructed all believers in the Ephesian church what to do. And what he urged them to do “first of all” is to pray. He emphasised on prayer as a priority above everything else. He specified four kinds of prayers, which are to be made for “all men.” This means that prayers must not become a selfish act of what the person who is praying can get, but how the prayer can be a benefit to all.', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(42, 18, 'The Christian life is dead without communication with God. Prayer takes priority since we are powerless without God and unable to do anything of eternal significance. We cannot activate our spiritual victory over Satan and his host without the supernatural assistance of God. Prayer introduces the help of God into the equation.', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(43, 18, 'Even though the Lord Jesus is God the Son, who became human, He still needed and maintained continual communion with God, the Father. He confessed, “The Son can do nothing of himself, but what he seeth the Father do . . .” (John 5:19). His whole life and ministry was marked by prayer. He prayed at His baptism which officially kicked off his public ministry (Luke 3:21–22). Sometimes He prayed all night before making critical decisions (Luke 6:12–13). He prayed before He ate (Luke 9:16, 22:19). The Lord Jesus prayed in connection with the simplest, commonest events of everyday life. Two of His own disciples did not even recognize Him after His resurrection, until they recognized the way He habitually prayed before breaking bread (Luke 24:30–31). He prayed before great temptations (Luke 22:40-43) and instructed His disciples to pray to avoid being tempted (Luke 20:40, Matt. 6:13). He interceded for Peter (Luke 22:31–32) and for all His disciples (John 17:11–20). He even interceded for the same people who condemned Him to death (Luke 23:34). His last words before death was a prayer (Luke 23:46), a fitting way to “end” a life marked by constant communion with God. Now, if the Lord Jesus the Master “could do nothing of Himself” but maintained communion with the Father, then it should be obvious that His servants need to do this even more! No wonder Paul exhorted that prayer should come “first of all” before any and everything else.', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(44, 19, 'In his letter to the Ephesians (6:18), Paul encouraged the believers to pray “always with all prayer and supplication in the Spirit . . .” This signifies that they are to offer up all kinds of different prayers to God to ensure that all kinds of needs are met. In his epistle to Timothy, he breaks this down into four specific dimensions, which are “supplications,” “prayers,” “intercessions,” and “thanksgiving.”', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(45, 19, 'a)	<b>Supplications.</b> Some Bible versions have this word translated as “entreaties” or “requests or petitions with all sense of humility”. These prayers originate from a deep sense of our own inability and God’s abundant sufficiency. They are heartfelt connections to the supply of God to meet needs that we may even find very hard to express in meaningful words. A passionate zeal and hunger fuels the act of supplication. Hannah’s prayer in Shiloh is an example of this heartfelt groaning approach to supplication. The prayer of supplication can sometimes lead us into fasting (Neh. 1:1-6). With supplications, we draw close to God and take the weight off our shoulders.', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(46, 19, 'b)	<b>Prayers</b>. Though this is a general term, but used here to refer to requests for regular everyday needs, in contrast to specific and special needs. For example, we may usually need wisdom, breakthrough, healing, or even food (as the Lord Jesus showed in Matt. 6:11).', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(47, 19, 'c)	<b>Intercessions.</b> To intercede means to plead or mediate on behalf of another person. Intercession involves various degrees of supplication. Intercession is not normally a one-off prayer. It requires persistence (Luke 11:5–8, 18:1–5). Intercessors stand in the gap on behalf of others and we see great examples in the lives of Abraham (Gen. 18:22–33), Elijah (1 Kings 18:41–46), Elisha (2 Kings 4: 32–36), the early church (Acts 12:1–18).', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(48, 19, 'd)	<b>Thanksgiving.</b> Some people tend to thank God only after He does something. But Psalm 100:4 says we are to enter His gates with thanksgiving. This means to thank God is proper even before presenting our petitions—thanking Him for what He has done already and also thanking Him in advance by faith. This is what the Lord Jesus did in John 11:41–44, when He raised Lazarus from the dead. He thanked God in advance, knowing that the prayer was already answered.', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(49, 20, 'Careful attention to the entire passage of our study this week will reveal that not only is it God’s will for every person to obtain salvation, but that with the believers’ prayers “we may lead a quiet and peaceable life in all godliness and honesty” (1 Tim. 2:2). Thus, Paul urged that supplications, prayers, intercessions, and thanksgiving should be made for “all men.” Then from verses 3–4, Paul explained that doing these things is good and acceptable in the sight of God our Saviour, who desires “all men” to be saved and come to the knowledge of the truth. The two Greek words translated as “all men” literally means all human beings. Paul then continued to emphasise that the only way human beings can be saved is through the Lord Jesus, the Mediator (1 Tim. 2:5–7). “Therefore”, he says, “I want men to PRAY everywhere” (v.8). He wants believers to make supplications, prayers, intercessions, and giving of thanks to God on behalf of all people in order to activate salvation of all men.  ', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(50, 21, 'When Paul said that supplications, prayers, intercessions, and thanksgiving be made for all men, he included rulers (“kings”) and those in authority (1 Tim. 2:2). It could have been strange he stated this, because this statement was made during the reign of Nero who was Caesar of the Roman Empire. Nero was a wicked ruler. Church history has it that Nero captured Christians and dipped them in oil before setting them on fire in his garden at night as a source of light. When the great fire of Rome broke out and burned for five days, Nero accused Christians and ordered that they be thrown to dogs, crucified, or burned. Yet, it was during his reign that Paul wrote Timothy and the church to pray for kings also.', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(51, 21, 'It seems that Paul was helping the church see that the means of peace would not come by a political revolt, but rather by intercessory prayer and supplication to the King of kings and Lord of lords who holds the hearts of men. As Christians, we are not called to criticise, condemn, or ridicule those in power but to use our power in the higher domain of grace to influence what we want to see. Paul said this is how the Christians would obtain a quiet and peaceable life (1 Tim. 2:2). The word “quiet” denotes we are not troubled from without, while “peaceable” infers we are not troubled from within. This is reminiscent of Jeremiah’s letter to the Israeli exiles in Babylon (Jer. 29), where God encouraged His people to seek the peace of Babylon through prayer, because in doing so, they would also obtain a quiet and peaceable life for themselves (Jer. 29:7).', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(52, 21, 'As God’s revival army called unto reasonable service, we must pray for rulers and those in authority, even if we find ourselves in challenging or anti-Christian lands such as some parts of Northern Nigeria. This is how we can live in peace regardless of the regime we are under. Moreover, we should intercede to God for the salvation of our rulers also, since they are humans and fall in the bracket of “all men.” We should also pray for God to equip them with the necessary virtues for proper leadership such as wisdom, honesty, courage, and a genuine desire to move the country and its people forward. Second Samuel 23:3 says, “He that ruleth over men must be just, ruling in the fear of God.”', '2018-02-17 18:28:09'),
(53, 22, 'The Holy Bible must be understood in context. We must understand the behind-the-scenes account that informed an action or a statement. These circumstances might differ by cities but the overarching theme of godliness is consistent as they all add up to godly order and divine instructions unto righteousness. This is the case of Paul’s specific message to Timothy on how to manage the situation in the Ephesian church because of the peculiarities of this unusual context, which we shall explore as follows:', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(54, 22, 'a)	<b>Ephesian goddess and cult of women:</b> The first-century Ephesus was known to be a sensual city that hundreds of thousands of people visited annually. Things like temple prostitution and other sensualities were included in the worship of the Ephesian goddess Diana (Greek Artemis). Ephesus, above all other places in the ancient world, celebrated women’s power, strength, beauty, and their ability to use their sexual prowess to manipulate and dominate men.<br/>\r\nEphesus was also a commercial centre with many wealthy people. Some women who had converted by coming to faith in Christ were apparently still dressing in a manner that was suggestive, provocative, and unnecessarily extravagant.<br/>\r\nActs 18:24 through Acts 20:1 shows us how Paul and Timothy spent three years in Ephesus, by far the longest time Paul spent in any single city during his three missionary journeys. Paul almost lost his life during a riot in the city because silversmiths who made little statues of the goddess Artemis were upset that Paul and Timothy were cutting into their business by winning converts to Christianity. Paul later wrote that he \"fought wild beasts at Ephesus (1 Cor. 15:32).\" Did he fight lions, tigers, and bears? No, the wild beasts were the people of Ephesus who were devoted to Artemis, \"The Queen of the Wild Beasts.\"<br/>\r\nAs Paul had anticipated, less than five years later, the Christians in Ephesus were in trouble. Some women, maybe even a single woman, most likely a new convert out of the Artemis cult, had begun to teach false truth in the assembly at Ephesus. Timothy was sent to Ephesus to help the church and give some correction. Timothy most likely sent Paul a letter from Ephesus, updating Paul on what was happening and asking questions about what to do and Paul’s response is a letter we now call First Timothy.\r\n', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(55, 22, 'b)	<b>Artemis female worshippers – dressing, gold, and braiding issues:</b> As we have learnt previously, the goddess Artemis was powerfully adored and worshipped because of its stunning beauty. It was known for power, beauty, and strength of women. This goddess was known to have elevated the position of a woman to a level that contradicted Biblical standard of submission, especially for converts who were just leaving Artemis for the true God. It was, therefore, easy to appreciate Paul’s specific instruction on how to manage women who were liberated and empowered to control men because of the spiritual influence they received from their worship of Artemis, in a manner similar to the worship of Aphrodite in Corinth—another church to which similar instruction was given.<br/>\r\nThe Ephesian women wore fancy hair braids and decorated themselves with jewellery and ornate clothes as they prayed to Artemis. History indicates that their locks of hairs carry their prayers; hence, this was an issue in the church as it negated the fundamental place of Christ, as the new converts found it difficult to differentiate between their new life and the old idol worship. In addition, while no sacrifices were done to Artemis, the women worshipped Artemis with their clothing, jewellery, and their words.<br/>\r\nThese broad contexts will be useful as we attempt to understand why Paul gave instructions on women silence and issues of jewellery in subsequent studies.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(56, 23, 'Evidently, God has made the man the leader of the human race. While the male is not necessarily superior to the female, as both are made in God’s image, the above mentioned Scripture specifies the special responsibility placed on the man. Just about every culture on every continent acknowledges the pre-eminence of the male, in spite of a few “feminist” groups that have been pushing for “equality.” There are even certain jobs that a woman is just simply not cut out to do mainly because of the strenuous nature of the work.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(57, 23, 'In the opening verse of our study, Paul says that men should pray everywhere, “lifting up holy hands, without wrath and doubting.” One good example of this similar lifting up of hands in prayer to God is found in 1 Kings 8:22–23. The temple had just been built, and all Israel was gathered together at the dedication of the house of God. As the leader of Israel, Solomon had the responsibility of being the one to lead in corporate prayer. In the Christian home today, God has also appointed men to be the leader and custodians of the spiritual welfare of the family. The spiritual state of a man, therefore, determines the state of a Christian home. A man who is in close relationship with God is in a good position to properly guide and direct his house. On the other hand, one who is unstable in his relationship with God will make many bad decisions that damage the well-being of the family. We can say that the man is also the spiritual breadwinner, who must spiritually watch over and pastor his home as a mini church for the Lord. God has made the man to be the foundation upon which the whole house is built. So while women and children play critical roles in the success of the family, the house is still sure to fall without a proper foundation.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(58, 23, 'For the success or failure of what becomes of a marriage, the Christian home and children are determined by the father, who is expected to raise holy hands as the spiritual breadwinner and hardworking hands as the physical breadwinner.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(59, 24, 'Now verses 9–10 show the right manner women ought to adorn themselves. The background study above has clarified why Paul gave this specific instruction.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(60, 24, 'Obviously, women come to the assembly of Christ in Ephesus similar to the way they used to go to the Temple of Artemis—dressed to kill, with braided hair, gold, pearls, and fine clothing. Paul is letting Timothy know that this mode of dressing, particularly in the city of Ephesus, is not conducive to the worship of Christ. What Christ desires is the beauty of heart, not the drawing of attention to oneself in public.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(61, 24, 'Historical sources indicate that in that era, women would braid their hair high atop their heads, having it intertwined with jewels, etc. It was a showcase—so elaborate as to be a sensation. One certainly may array herself with dignity, but to dress so as to flaunt the physical is not consistent with the will of Christ. This is not saying that women should not dress well and take good care of themselves, neither is it saying that braiding hair or wearing jewellery is forbidden by God. The braiding that Paul was speaking about here is what harlots in Ephesus do as acts of worship to Artemis. The spirit behind the words is that godly women should not emphasise these things, but instead set their focus on pleasing God inwardly and by good works outwardly. There must be a godly balance between inward and outward beauty. Dressing, hairdo, and any ornaments should be adorned with moderation in a manner acceptable to God, while the major focus of the woman should be fulfilling her God-given duties and responsibilities.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(62, 25, 'We will look at the divine order of sexes by looking at the key word used by Paul (1 Tim. 2:11–12, 1 Cor. 14: 34–35): \"Let the woman learn in silence with all subjection\" (1 Tim. 2:11).', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(63, 25, 'It is important to remember (as we have seen) that nowhere in Scripture does the Lord Jesus, Paul, or any other apostle restrict women in the assembly. This was very specific based on the unique situation in Ephesus as we have carefully described before. To appreciate this further, we may need to check other places where Paul himself spoke about women in the service of God. In Romans 16:1–2, Paul referred to a woman named Phoebe as a “succourer” and described her as “a servant of the church.” Paul greeted Priscilla, a helper in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus (Rom. 16:3). In the same letter to the Roman church, he also mentioned a woman named Junia (Rom. 16:7), whom he described as “fellowprisoners, who are of note among the apostles.” Also, we know that Joel’s prophecy that was fulfilled in Acts 2:17 was for sons and daughters.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(64, 25, 'Furthermore, the word translated silence is hesuchia (quietness). It is used in I Timothy 2:2 to describe what the character of every believer should be, both male and female. It never means \"don\'t speak,\" but addresses the character of humility. This was the light that an average Christian woman in Ephesus, coming out of a society saturated with the power, strength, abilities and even domination of women through the Artemis cult, needed to realise that she had a great deal to learn about Christ and His kingdom.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(65, 25, 'The word silence in this 1 Tim 2 (hesuchia) is used earlier in verse 2 of this chapter (hesuchion). But there it refers to the \"quiet\" life which all godly people should lead. This gives the tone and the background in which the word is used. It does not refer to absolute silence; it is more of a life that is untroubled and content. So the silence does not seem to be total. It is more like what we would call \"quietness.\" Clearly, this type of silence is not locking one’s mouth with a padlock but a state of mind that is willing to learn and subject to authority.', '2018-02-17 18:37:51'),
(66, 26, 'Right after we became born again in Christ, we were like spiritual new born babies—totally immature. From then on, we must grow slowly but surely, even as a new born baby would. Peter encouraged us, “desire the sincere milk of the word that ye may grow thereby” (1 Pet. 2:2). But spiritual maturity also takes time, effort, and discipline. There are no shortcuts, but we must exercise ourselves unto godliness (1 Tim. 4:7).', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(67, 26, 'This reminder is necessary for all Christians. However, the need for growth and maturity is more explicit for leaders in the body of the Lord Jesus Christ, because the leader is a figure who the other members may look up to and who can (positively or negatively) influence them. Let us look first of the qualities expected from the bishops, as listed in verses 2–7 of our text.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(68, 27, 'The word “bishop” is the Greek episkopos which means a superintendent, overseer, or officer in charge of the church. The Biblical requirements to fill this office are:', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(69, 27, 'a)	<b>Blameless.</b> This is a Greek word that means free of guilt, or irreproachable. He lives such a transparent life amongst all men that nobody can point an accusing finger at him. No one can accuse him of flirting with their daughter or tapping electrical power illegally.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(70, 27, 'b)	<b>Husband of one wife.</b> If he is married, he can only have one wife—not one wife physically and many “wives” on social media. You cannot be a leader and be lustful with impure thoughts.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(71, 27, 'c)	<b>Vigilant.</b> This means he is able to think clearly. He is alert in regard to the enemy (1 Pet. 5:8) and, therefore, able to make sound decisions.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(72, 27, 'd)	<b>Sober.</b> He is reasonably sound in mind, self-controlled, and not ruled by passions.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(73, 27, 'e)	<b>Of good behaviour.</b> He is orderly and well-mannered. He exhibits decorum and knows how to conduct himself publicly and privately. He is someone Yorubas will call, “omoluwabi,” people of good upbringing and disciplined character. His spirituality does not mean he will not respect, regard, or greet people of all classes. He is a responsible citizen who lives decently.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(74, 27, 'f)	<b>Given to hospitality.</b> This phrase literally means “generous towards guests, especially as an opportunity to use hospitality to reach out and share the love of Christ.” The Christian leader must know how to host new people and strangers. This means he must not be hostile or have tendencies to repeal people. We have no good testimony when people run away from us (see also Rom. 12:13, Heb. 13:2, and 1 Pet. 4:9).', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(75, 27, 'g)	<b>Apt to teach.</b> This same phrase is found in 2 Timothy 2:24, which refers to the capacity and depth of knowledge to instruct and deliver God’s Word. A Christian leader must know the Scripture well enough to teach sound doctrine and correct error with facts and not with emotions.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(76, 27, 'h)	<b>Not given to wine.</b> This speaks to excessive indulgence that takes over every decorum. Alchohol is a NO for a child of God. Its consumption is not just an issue for a Christian; it has been proven to be a trigger of many diseases.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(77, 27, 'i)	<b>Not a striker.</b> This word means to hit or strike. The Christian leader is never to physically strike a person under any circumstance. It is an error when a leader slaps someone and says it is done by the Spirit.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(78, 27, 'j)	<b>Patient.</b> This word means “mild.” The leader is to be kind to people in his dealings with them.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(79, 27, 'k)	<b>Not a brawler.</b> The Greek word used here is amacho which is the opposite of “macho” man. The leader does not have to prove his manhood by fighting or engaging in fruitless argument. When a leader begins to justify his position by saying, “I am older than you, I have been in the ministry before you were born,” you know such man is a brawler.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(80, 27, 'l)	<b>Not covetous.</b> Literally “not a lover of money.” First Timothy 6:10 tells us that the love of money is the root of all evil, and those who coveted after it have destroyed themselves. Matthew 6:24 also tells us, “Ye cannot serve God and mammon.” Never do anything in the kingdom for financial gain. Do not organise a vigil in the house of a rich man, so that he can sponsor your education or give you “prayer envelope.”', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(81, 27, 'm)	<b>Rules his own house or keeps his home with gravity.</b> Home testimony must validate ministry testimony. When we evaluate a man only by what we see on the pulpit, we diminish God’s priority where home is considered as the first church. If a man cannot meet the spiritual, emotional, parenting, relational, and social needs of a church of 4–6 people in his immediate family, then he is not qualified to be a leader of many. The only person who can help a man to be accountable on this godly demand is the wife, who can genuinely be truthful, least she exposes her husband to work outside divine boundaries. How terrible can we qualify a sister, who knows that her husband is not doing well at home and allow such to parade himself on the altar. Since no one can know the truth about the man except the wife, then she alone has the responsibility to help the husband not to overstep his boundary and expose her family to the wrath of a man who is a success outside but a failure on the inside. Inasmuch as a woman enjoys the aura of the husband on the altar, she must be careful not to turn the altar to an obituary for him. When you see a man live practically in unfaithfulness, deceit, bitterness, prayerlessness, and irresponsibility, and you do not raise a flag to the leaders or your mentors, to whom both of you have submitted under a form of authority, you are only ridiculing the privilege of divine placement.<br/>\r\nThe summary is that if a man cannot properly manage his own family, how then can he take care of the church of God? Included in this is that his children should appreciate and respect him as the head of the family and his children must be the standard of godly reference in character, behaviour, and excellence.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(82, 27, 'n)	<b>Not a novice.</b> This word literally means “a new convert.” Spiritual maturity and strength to lead takes time and experience. Paul also warned that a novice could become lifted up with pride and fall into the same sin that originally caused the devil to fall.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(83, 27, 'o)	<b>Good report.</b> Even non-Christians (“those that are without”) should be able to testify to the integrity of the church leader. This also keeps him from accusations and Satan’s traps and snares. We must be interested in what our colleagues at work, neighbours, flatmates, roommates, parents, supervisors, friends, and other associates say about us as a condition for effective leadership.', '2018-02-17 18:50:12'),
(84, 28, 'The next office Paul mentioned is that of a “deacon.” This word is the Greek diakoneo which means to “be an attendant” or “wait upon.” It is a word used to denote a simple servant. It is not as prestigious as the role of a bishop who is the overseer of the church, yet the requirements are high, as all Christians are servants, and the Lord Jesus Christ Himself is our ultimate example of servanthood (Matt. 20:26–28, John 13:14–15). For us as a fellowship, this must be the minimum qualification for anyone who is chosen to serve as a worker, even at a local fellowship or campus fellowship level.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(85, 28, 'But there is a special call, nevertheless, on the deacons to serve menially in hands-on roles. Two original deacons were Stephen and Philip, who later became great miracle-working evangelists. Requirements for the office of deacon include:', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(86, 28, 'a)	<b>Grave.</b> This word means to be honourable and respectable. It is reverent decorum, the quiet gravity, which never interferes with the innocent and childlike happiness.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(87, 28, 'b)	<b>Not double-tongued.</b> This word literally means to be forked-tongued in the sense of misleading people with words. The deacon cannot be a liar or speaker of contradictory tales.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(88, 28, 'c)	<b>Not given to much wine.</b> Same qualification required for the bishop as seen above.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(89, 28, 'd)	<b>Not greedy of filthy lucre.</b> This means not to be greedy of gain or profit from others. The deacon’s primary state of mind is to serve, and he knows his reward is sure to come later from God—directly or indirectly. ', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(90, 28, 'e)	<b>Holding the mystery of the faith in a pure conscience.</b> This is similar to Paul’s instruction to Timothy in 1 Timothy 1:19. But here he added “the mystery” of the faith. This means that the deacon should understand the deep things of the Christian faith and maintain integrity in his heart as a servant of the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(91, 28, 'f)	<b>Proven blameless.</b> The potential deacon must first be “proved” (“tested”), and if he is blameless, then he is qualified to take up the role. This explains why preliminary interviews and investigation are critical in choosing workers and executives.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(92, 28, 'g)	<b>Husband of one wife.</b> This is the same qualification needed for the bishops.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(93, 28, 'h)	<b>Rules own house well.</b> Again, this is also a prerequisite for the bishops.', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(94, 28, 'i)	<b>Faithful in all things.</b> A deacon, male or female, must be trustworthy (reliable) in fulfilling every task, even as Phoebe was trusted by Paul to successfully deliver the epistle to the church in Rome from Cenchrea (a port of Corinth).', '2018-02-17 18:55:24'),
(95, 29, 'To conduct ourselves properly in the house of God, we must understand that the church is the pillar and ground of the truth, hence we cannot misbehave or do things anyhow. As it is often said, when the purpose of a thing is not known, abuse is inevitable. And to understand why the church is the pillar and ground of the truth, we must understand the mystery of godliness.', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(96, 29, 'The word mystery is a good translation of the Greek must?rion which means a “secret.” The true godliness, as revealed in the Person of the Lord Jesus Christ, was not always known through ancient history, though God had left clues through His prophets. In Ephesians 3:3–5, Paul said that this “mystery of Christ” was not made known unto the sons of men in other ages. In 1 Peter 1:10–11, the apostle Peter showed us that the prophets of old had some insights into this mystery, how Christ was to suffer (e.g., Isa. 53) and the glory that should follow (e.g., Dan. 7:13–14).', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(97, 29, 'Paul breaks this revealed mystery of Christ down into six parts:', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(98, 29, 'a)	<b>Manifest in the flesh.</b> The Incarnation is one of the most unbelievable events in human history. We know from Scripture that the Eternal Creator exists as one God yet three distinct Persons: God the Father, God the Son, and God the Holy Spirit. The Son is also called the Word (1 John 5:7). The Word became a human being like us (John 1:1, 14).', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(99, 29, 'b)	<b>Justified in the Spirit.</b> God was manifested in the flesh, but He (the Lord Jesus) was justified in the Spirit. One of the biggest rivalries in the New Testament is between the flesh and the Spirit. Paul, therefore, commanded that we must remain in the Spirit so as not to fulfil the lust of the flesh (Gal. 5:16).', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(100, 29, 'c)	<b>Seen of angels.</b> The whole life of the Lord Jesus was witnessed and surrounded by angelic personnel. An angel announced His conception to Mary (Luke 1:35), angels ministered to Him after His temptations in the wilderness (Matt. 4:11), and an angel strengthened Him during His agony before going to the cross (Luke 22:42–43).', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(101, 29, 'd)	<b>Preached to the gentiles.</b> The Good News of the death, burial, and resurrection of the Lord Jesus Christ was not limited to the people of Israel. It was revealed “to the Jew first” and to the Greek (Rom. 1:16).', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(102, 29, 'e)	<b>Believed on in the world.</b> The reality of this mystery is that it became a believable story in every language, culture, and tongue all over the world.', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(103, 29, 'f)	<b>Received up unto glory.</b> The Lord Jesus Christ physically ascended into heaven after fulfilling his assignment on earth. His being received into glory makes the mystery more elevated for us that in due time, we shall be partakers of the same glory.', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(104, 30, 'In verse 15 of our text, Paul affirmed that the church of the Lord Jesus Christ is the pillar and ground of truth—the Biblical definition of a church or its extension in a fellowship. Understanding the mystery of godliness, as outlined above, helps us see why this is so. There is only one truth in regard to the reality of who God is, as the Lord Jesus said of Himself, “I am the truth” (John 14:6) and “No man comes unto the Father but by me.” This Scriptural passage leaves no room for any other belief system. He made this clear when He sent His disciples to go into the world and preach the Gospel to every creature: “He that believeth and is baptized shall be saved; but he that believeth not shall be damned” (i.e., judged and sentenced, Mark 16:16).', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(105, 30, 'The words “ground” and “pillar” indicate the sense of a foundation and support for a building. So the members of the Lord Jesus Christ’s church [Greek ekklesia = called-out ones] support and hold up the Truth for the world to see. We are to uphold the standard of God everywhere, even as we maintain our foundation on this ground of truth. You can appreciate why TACEFites pray to be pillars in the great house!', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(106, 31, 'Since we are the pillars in the Lord Jesus Christ, it is very important to know how we ought to behave and comport ourselves as members of His household. Our attitude, disposition, and activities in the church and fellowship must be right and bring glory to God. This involves things way we dress, hairstyle, and personal grooming, to name a few. It also involves things like keeping our children under control in the church, being punctual at service, and engaging in positive, edifying conversations that encourage love and promote unity. It speaks to how orderly, decently, nicely, and respectfully we treat every opportunity to fellowship together as brethren. You cannot lounge into a fellowship meeting as if it is another sitting room conversation time, or be chewing gums or just stroll in carelessly without any sense of realisation that you are on a holy ground. If we truly respect the gathering of the brethren as a ground of truth, we cannot allow the devil to turn us into a fellowship gossip, killer-dresser, politician, or favour seekers whose allegiance is for motives that is not about glorifying the Lord Jesus. We are to respect ourselves as well as others.', '2018-02-17 19:41:21'),
(107, 32, 'God revealed many things to the apostles concerning how the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ would spread and how this present age would finally end. One of the things that have been revealed is that there will be a “departure” from the faith in the latter times. If you take a few minutes to look at 2 Thessalonians 2:1–3, you will find that not only will this departure happen in the last days, but it is a precursor to the rise of the Antichrist, the “man of sin.” Paul stated there will be a “falling away” and this phrase is the Greek apostasia which means ‘a defection from truth’, and is where we get our English word apostasy. But it will be more than just a defection from truth, but people who once professed Christianity will turn against the Lord Jesus Christ and proactively instigate others to rebel also. This last statement is what the Greek word aphistemi means (translated as “depart from”) which Paul used in verse 1 of our study text. Many will not only depart from the truth, but will incite others also to forsake their faith, as similarly prophesied by Apostle Peter (2 Pet. 2:1-2).', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(108, 32, 'Peter explained that these betrayers shall bring in “damnable heresies,” while Paul said they will “speak lies in hypocrisy.” Paul also said that their conscience is seared with a hot iron, which in the original language literally means that they will be insensitive (i.e., have no feelings or conscience towards sin, truth, righteousness). One is left to wonder what will make a former follower of the Lord Jesus Christ not only lose his faith but also actively damage the faith of others.', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(109, 32, 'There are already many individuals, groups, and religious organizations today who have taken the Bible and twisted it to bring in “damnable heresies.” Indeed, many young Christians are departing from the faith and encouraging others to do the same, choosing perverted belief systems over the Gospel they once happily received. There is a particularly growing “grace movement” today (in clusters and on some campuses), who are bringing back the “once saved, always saved” message, with an erroneous doctrine that a Christian can fornicate because the death of the Lord Jesus took care of everything in advance. Their Gospel speaks to licentiousness and indulgence.', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(110, 32, 'This is the last days when the love of many will wax cold and, therefore; those of us living in times like this must stand fast and take firm hold of the truth. God’s Word says, “let him that thinketh he standeth take heed lest he fall” (1 Cor. 10:12).', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(111, 32, 'In describing the conditions of the end-time, the Lord Jesus said many false prophets shall rise and deceive many, and that love will grow cold in many because of abounding iniquity. Then he added these words: “But he that shall endure unto the end, the same shall be saved” (Matt. 24:11–13). May the Lord help us to endure in righteousness.', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(112, 33, 'Paul said that the end-time defectors from truth will give heed to “seducing spirits” and doctrines of demons. We must know and understand that we are in warfare—spiritual warfare. Our real enemies are not flesh and blood, but principalities, rulers of the darkness of this world, and spiritual wickedness in high places (Eph. 6:12). And the first piece of armoury mentioned, which we are to use is the truth (Eph. 6:14). This makes perfect sense if we consider what a “seducing” spirit is. The word in the original Greek is planos which means “misleading” or “deceptive.” So the number one attribute of these spirits is their capacity to mislead; their primary objective is to deceive or lead astray. We also know that their aim through deception is to steal, kill, and destroy (John 10:10). Satan, their leader, is the well-known Deceiver (Rev. 12:9). He was the one who deceived Eve and brought chaos upon man (2 Cor. 11:3). He is a liar and the father of lies (John 8:44). So Paul correctly stated the belt of truth as the first armour we are to use in warfare against the wickedness of the enemy.', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(113, 33, 'These same deceptive spirits are responsible for demonic doctrines. Lucifer, Satan, or the Devil—is the first person to ever peddle a false doctrine on earth. God taught Adam, who in turn taught Eve, that they were free to eat from any tree of the Garden—except for one particular tree of knowledge of good and evil, which was in the middle of the Garden. God also forewarned them about the consequences of disobedience. God’s Word is truth, as always. But the devil possessed a serpent and twisted God’s truth to teach Eve a false doctrine—a doctrine of demons—or rather, of the chief demon himself.', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(114, 33, 'The damage that falsehood causes cannot be overemphasised, especially in light of the eternal destiny of men and women. Living a lie surely damages a person in this present life, but those damages are little in comparison to hell. There is a Creator and He has told us the truth. We know some minor doctrinal errors may not cause a person to lose his place in God’s kingdom. But the “doctrines of devils” will surely cause those who give heed to them to end up on the wrong side of eternity.', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(115, 34, 'According to Paul’s prophecy, the false teachers are hypocrites whose consciences have been damaged to the point where they are not even convicted about their words and deeds anymore. Their hearts are far away from God but they make up self-righteous doctrines, similar to the hypocritical Pharisees (Matt. 15:7–9). One of their doctrines exaggerated outward piety by forbidding people to marry and teaching them to abstain from certain foods. But Paul stressed that these things are appointed by God to be received thankfully by those who know the truth. Marriage is an institution ordained by God from the very beginning (Gen. 2:22–24).', '2018-02-17 19:47:03'),
(116, 35, 'For a person to seriously dedicate himself to something, he must have a solid reason to do so. No sane person would invest huge amount of his time, energy, and resources into something in which he sees no value. For example, a medical student who spends as much as eight to ten years in the medical school, studying very hard the whole time, does so because he knows his efforts are not in vain, which gives him motivation to keep going as he keeps his eyes on the prize. The athlete will also train hard for long hours each day and eat proper diet, all the time thinking about the gold medal he will receive if he is diligent enough.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(117, 35, 'The Christian walk is comparable to this. Paul said that the secular athlete goes through all the trouble of disciplining himself only to obtain a “corruptible” crown (1 Cor. 9:24–27). But the life that the Lord Jesus has called us unto brings an “incorruptible” crown. So Paul kept his body under and brought it into subjection; otherwise, he would lose the eternal, “incorruptible” prize and ended up being a castaway.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(118, 35, 'Our journey to heaven requires a walk of godliness—a consistent walk to become like God. Of course, we may miss our steps here and there, at different times, hence a need to exercise and discipline ourselves, until it becomes a way of life. A marathon race runner can run for one hour, nonstop without feeling anything afterwards. However, if someone who has not had any form of exercise in the last six months tries to do only 30 minutes of jogging around, he will be forced to spend the next one week nursing muscle wound and body pains because he has not exercised himself on a consistent basis. However, if he continues to discipline himself on a consistent basis with similar exercise, his muscles and body system will become adjusted to this new life. This is the same reality for us as Christians. <b>We only become what we consistently exercise ourselves unto.</b> If we exercise our tongue to always say the truth, it will just become naturally difficult for any form of lies to come out of our mouth. If we discipline our mind to always meditate on the Scripture on a consistent basis, it will be difficult for a lustful thought to find a space to grow, and if we are consistent in praying daily for definite period of time or time of the day, we will get to a point that it becomes our normal way of life – without any stress or being bored. A man of God said, <b>\"Prayer starts as a duty, becomes a discipline, then becomes a delight\" (Olubi Johnson).</b>', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(119, 36, 'Like every athlete have so many things they have to do on a consistent basis to become a world-class gold medallist, so also must every child of God commit himself to the regular routine and lifestyle of discipline to become the best in the schemes of God. We must have regular spiritual exercises in godliness to build our spiritual immunity and strengthen our spiritual muscles to stand firm. Below are some fundamental spiritual building blocks that we must exercise ourselves unto.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(120, 36, 'a)	<b>Bible study.</b> The Bible is God’s revelation of Himself to mankind. It contains the will of God for His people. Studying God’s Word with an obedient heart is the beginning of being in agreement with His will. His word pushes us towards godliness by “sanctifying” us (John 17:17). Needless to say, it is impossible for a Christian to grow without ingesting God’s Word (1 Pet. 2:2).', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(121, 36, 'b)	<b>Prayer.</b> Communication with God is done through prayer. We hear from God mainly through the Bible, and we talk to God in prayer. Paul said we should pray with all kinds of prayer and supplication in the Spirit (Eph. 6:18). Moreover, the Bible teaches that we can pray in tongues, pray with singing, and even pray with unutterable groanings through the Spirit. Prayer should not just be a fellowship affair or special vigils. It must be a daily exercise to build our spiritual stamina, sufficient to withstand the reality of the daily temptations.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(122, 36, 'c)	<b>Meditation.</b> Deep thinking in the Word of God is called meditation. We have to ask ourselves how God’s Word and Biblical truths apply to our practical lives. First Timothy 4:15 says, “Meditate upon these things; give thyself wholly to them.” This is how we are transformed by the renewing of our minds (Rom. 12:2). After Moses died and Joshua was about to lead Israel into possessing the Promised Land, God’s main instruction to Joshua was not to carnally prepare for war by sharpening swords or attending to other tasks. His main instruction was for Joshua to meditate in the Word of God day and night (Josh. 1:8). Nobody can go far in godly discipline without meditating on God’s Word continually and applying those thoughts to every area of life.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(123, 36, 'd)	<b>Fasting.</b> Abstinence from food and refusing to fulfil any ungodly desire of the flesh are the essential practices of fasting. Both forms of fasting are needed to break the power of the flesh over us and to be grounded in the things of the Spirit. This is similar to an athlete denying himself of fatty, sugary, and high-calorie foods; opting instead to exercise discipline and do what is more beneficial for his body. The Lord Jesus has said that some kinds of demons cannot be cast out except by the combination of “prayer and fasting” (Mark 9:29). He also said that those who fast unto the Father will be rewarded openly (Matt 6:18). Spiritual maturity is attained quicker as we learn and apply the principle of fasting.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(124, 36, 'e)	<b>Preaching the Gospel.</b> Every person that has been saved by the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ has a responsibility to communicate that same life-saving message to others. Even if a person has been saved for several years, every time he preaches the Gospel to others he is reminded that he is only saved by the grace of God through the finished work of the Lord Jesus Christ. His personal sanctification and growing godliness over the years are a by-product of his salvation and God’s training. This helps him to see his dependency on God’s grace and, therefore, draws him even closer to God. Preaching the Gospel not only save the hearer but also strengthens godliness in the preacher by drawing him closer to God.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(125, 36, 'f)	<b>Christian fellowship.</b> No Christian is an island. God’s Word shows us that the members of Christ’s body need one another (1 Cor. 12:21). We are not to forsake the assembly of one another, but we are to exhort and encourage one another (Heb. 10:25). As we exhort one another, we grow our spiritual muscles, just as iron sharpens iron, according to Proverbs 27:17. No single Christian has all the gifts of the Spirit, but God has distributed them among the members of the body. We must minister our gifts to one another and increase in strength thereby.', '2018-02-17 20:17:17'),
(126, 37, 'We will start our study from the last verse of our text because of its importance in the whole passage. In verse 16, Paul said to Timothy, “Take heed unto thyself, and unto the doctrine.” To break it up properly, he was saying: (a) take heed to thyself and (b) take heed to the doctrine.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(127, 37, 'This is the basic twofold summary of ministry. First, we take heed to ourselves, representing our personal walk with Christ. From there, we take heed to the doctrine, representing our work for Christ. Our walk with Christ is the necessary basis and foundation for our work for Christ. In other words, a great ministry is dependent on a great relationship with God. As we grow and become more filled with Christ, the joyous reflection of our ministry spills over to the people we encounter, and this is what ministry is about. Ministry is not activities, but the outpour of the life of God in us. If we do not have consistent relationship with the Lord where He pours Himself into us, we have no ministry, no matter how recognised or popular we are as a title carrier. This same principle is found in Acts 20:28, where Paul told the Ephesian elders, “Take heed therefore unto yourselves, and to all the flock…” They were to ensure they were in good standing with God (their walk), and then translate this to shepherd the flock (their work).', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(128, 37, 'It is when we first take heed to our personal relationship and communion with the Lord that He imparts into our spirit what we need to take heed to our ministry. Anybody who claims to serve the Lord Jesus Christ but does not have a good relationship with Him is not serving Christ but themselves, possibly for money, fame, or some other selfish motive. “All seek their own, not the things which are Jesus Christ’s” is the reason Paul gave for his confidence in sending Timothy alone to the Philippians (Phil. 2:19-21). He knew that Timothy’s walk was genuinely developed to support his work. As a people called unto reasonable service, we must understand that it is completely unreasonable to work for God without a walk with Him. It is like a driver leading people through a road he does not know at all.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(129, 38, 'One of Timothy’s challenges as a servant of God was that he was very young and shy. He is like that brother who will see people misbehaving in the fellowship and would not have the boldness to correct and put everyone under the weight of God’s grace. He is that executive or subgroup leader who allows error, indolence, or unseriousness, among other things, to persist because he lacks the ability to take charge and correct with divine influence. Timothy type of leaders cannot confront issues. They always push things under the carpet until they degenerate to points of utter mess. They always shy away into their shell when leadership actions are much needed to put things in order with all sense of gravity. They will see other members or even leaders who come late to fellowship without reason or those who indulge in bad attitude and they will rather be silent or even withdraw from any frontal engagement. They are good at reaction and not at action. They will watch symptoms grow into full-blown spiritual disease that can destroy people’s lives and even weaken the standard of God in a fellowship. We see similar behaviour among couples, parent-to-children, partners, and even friends, when we shy away instead of acting responsibly.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(130, 38, 'Oftentimes, the timidity of these types of people may be out of perceived self-gap or thinking less of themselves just like Timothy who thought his age was his limitation. We see instances where these kinds of leaders feel insufficient or incapacitated because they think those who they should lead or correct are more experienced, more learned, richer, or even more exposed than them. They forget that by virtue of being a spiritual leader in a position as a fellowship or subgroup leader, they are by grace higher in placement than any other human basis for classification.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(131, 38, '<b>The fundamental principle here is that when you are called a leader, you must act as one. </b> When God trusts you to lead His people, rise beyond how you see yourself and enter into the consciousness of how God sees you as the “one in charge,” not by age, race, pace, place, or ace, but by grace. May we not continue in the excuses of “God knows that I am weak in this area or that area” to the point that our natural limitations diminish the work of God in our hands.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(132, 38, 'This also speaks to the need for conscious character modification, so that we correct our personality gaps and be able to fit into the role that God has called us unto. For example, If we know we are bad in relationship or courtesy (e.g., we do not know how to greet, say thank you for gifts we have received, or we do not smile at people), then we must not spiritualise these as a generational curse or an uncorrectable flaw inherited from our upbringing. We must consciously correct these now before they discredit our ministry or diminish our ability to be an example of the believers who have been called unto reasonable service. Let us be careful that our personal character or weaknesses do not cut others off from the best of God that our ministry is meant to deliver.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(133, 39, 'Not only did Paul exhort Timothy to ignore any negative remarks concerning his limitations or perceived gaps, he confidently instructed him to stand out as an example for all the believers, both the despisers of his youth and those who hear him (1 Tim. 4:16).', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(134, 39, 'Paul gave Timothy six dimensions in which he was to be a model for others to see and follow. These things apply to all Christians today and we should continually strive to grow in them.', '2018-02-17 20:34:50'),
(135, 39, 'a)	<b>In word.</b> This refers to our choice of words when we speak. James Chapter 3 warns us that the tongue is a very dangerous entity, which has the ability to defile the whole body (James 3:6). But “if any man offend not in word, the same is a perfect man, and able also to bridle the whole body” (James 3:2). God’s Word says that no corrupt communication should proceed out of our mouths, but only beneficial words that minister grace to the hearers (Eph. 4:29). This means there is no room for filthy talk, lying, gossip, dirty jokes, words of threat or revenge, murmuring, and so on. But instead, our words should show others grace, through encouragement, appreciation, proper correction, sympathy, personal testimony, Biblical warning, and helpful advice.', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(136, 39, 'b)	<b>In conversation.</b> This word does not mean communication, but is an Old English word translated from the Greek anastroph? which means “behaviour” or “conduct.” Our lifestyle involves conversation, which should show that Christ lives in us. We should reflect integrity, honesty, how we spend our time and money, our priorities, personal appearance, and how we treat others, just to mention a few.', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(137, 39, 'c)	<b>In charity.</b> This is the literal Greek agap? love. Biblical love is sacrificial and caring. It seeks the highest good of the other person. This is the true kind of love that the Holy Spirit in us helps us grow into continually. God’s Word expounds on what love is (1 Cor. 13, especially vv. 4–8). In reality, all other Christian virtues are dependent on love. This is because God Himself is love (1 John 4:8), and the two supreme commandments are to love God and to love humanity (Matt. 22:37–40).', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(138, 39, 'd)	<b>In spirit.</b> This means that our innermost being must reflect Christ. The invisible man of the heart reflects our spiritual fervency and how our spirit draws from the life and nature of God on a consistent basis.', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(139, 39, 'e)	<b>In faith.</b> This is not only the saving faith that brings us to Christ, but also the faith that believes God at all times. When others see our faith in a specific situation and God’s positive response, they are encouraged that truly “with God all things are possible” (Mark 10:27).', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(140, 39, 'f)	<b>In purity.</b> Purity here is the Greek word that means “chastity”, i.e. sexual purity. We live in a time that is pervaded with sensuality, and this easily leads to fornication, adultery, pornography, and other forms of lasciviousness. Now you don’t even have to buy the DVDs or books because an ordinary message received via WhatsApp can be one that defiles. Already remember that our Lord Jesus said to us that when we look at a woman’s body and lusting after her in our hearts, we are already in sin without even committing the physical act (Matt 5:28). ', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(141, 39, '<h3>Week 12 ends here and Week 13 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(142, 40, 'Even after we have discovered our gift and calling, it will still take a lot of spiritual, mental, and physical effort to fulfil our God-given ministry. This does not happen automatically. That is why Paul continually gave Timothy certain phrases, which all carried a sense of urgency: “command and teach” (1 Tim. 4:11), “be thou an example” (1 Tim. 4:12), “give attendance” (1 Tim. 4:13), “neglect not” (1 Tim. 4:14), “meditate upon” (1 Tim. 4:15), and “take heed” (1 Tim. 4:16).', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(143, 40, 'If Timothy should ignore any one of these directives, he would lose momentum and suffer losses in his life and ministry. We must not dismiss these things as rhetorics. They are the foundational truth for reasonable service that is sustainable and heaven-rewarding. Just as Timothy did at Ephesus, God’s people today must be diligent in all areas of life and service. Paul said, “[I]n doing this thou shalt both save thyself, and them that hear thee” (1 Tim. 4:16).', '2018-02-17 20:38:28'),
(144, 41, 'If we love our brothers and sisters in Christ, we will understand a need to correct them if we see them heading in the wrong direction. The Bible teaches that the wages of sin is death and we know that no one will get away with sin no matter how early or how long he has been saved. If sin in a person’s life is never corrected, he might rationalise that sin, get hardened, and die in that state. According to God’s Word, we understand that even a believer who errs can be in danger of the eternal judgement of God (Matt. 7:21).', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(145, 41, 'With the foregoing, we can see the reasons why the ministry of correction is needed in the church. If our children were playing on a dangerous road without our knowledge, and another adult sees them in the path of danger but just shakes his head without correcting them, we will be angry if we find out that the person just allowed our children to continue playing on that dangerous road. If a Christian cares about the welfare of the brethren, then he will not allow them to continue on the dangerous path of sin and iniquity. This attitude of genuine love for others must be the foundation of every act of correction. When this is missing, it becomes more of a vendetta or ridicule to those concerned.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(146, 42, 'In some cases, a Christian might really desire to help and correct a brother in error, but chooses not to for one reason or the other. These reasons that prevent the person from helping his fellow believer are what we call the hindrances to correction. A number of things can be the reason behind this, but we have narrowed them down to the three biggest hindrances.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(147, 42, 'a)	<b>Fear of the person to be corrected.</b> Some people will see a believer living in sin, but choose to just mind their own businesses because of fear. They are afraid of how the person might react if they point out their error to them. This is understandable nevertheless not a good excuse to allow someone to continue walking down a destructive path. The best way to remove the barrier of fear and go ahead to correct the person is by fearing God alone, and not man. We must realise that God will hold us accountable if we see someone heading for trouble and do not help such. In Acts 20:26–27, Paul said that he has warned the Ephesian elders and declared all the counsel of God unto them, so he was, therefore, free from being guilty of the blood of any who chose to operate outside the counsel of God.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(148, 42, 'b)	<b>Misapplication of Matthew 7:1.</b> This verse says, “Judge not, that ye be not judged.” Some Christians have taken this to mean that we should not correct anybody at all, as correction is misinterpreted as judgement. It wrongly assumes that we should close our eyes when we see our brethren fall into error. To accurately understand what the Lord was saying in this verse, we must read it further to verse 5 so as to understand the context. He was obviously saying that we cannot point out the speck in our brother’s eye when we have a plank in our own eye, that is, we are being hypocrites by pointing out someone else’s sin whereas our own sins are way greater. Hence, if we are living right with God, we have the grace to help the brethren because we can give what we have.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(149, 42, 'c)	<b>Awareness of personal sins.</b> An honest Christian will find it impossible to correct someone else if he himself has not cleaned up his own life, as the Lord Jesus has exhorted us in the verse studied above. Paul said those who are “spiritual” (i.e., spiritually mature) are the ones qualified to correct someone that is in error, but they should also take heed lest they also be tempted (Gal. 6:1). As humans, we all are prone to sin; but the seriousness of salvation should motivate us to keep our lives clean and help our brothers and sisters when necessary.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(150, 43, 'The issue of correcting one another is quite delicate and, therefore, should be approached with caution. Spiritual and physical preparations are required when we correct, so that the intention of God is not defeated due to our personal bias, uncleared mind and sentiment. We must first ask ourselves some questions to help us verify that we are suitable to correct another person. The major questions to ask are listed as follows:', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(151, 43, 'a)	Is my life an example?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(152, 43, 'b)	Have I prayed sincerely enough for this person with a conviction that it is time to engage?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(153, 43, 'c)	Do I have a form of relationship with this individual to be corrected?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(154, 43, 'd)	Do I have the fact or am I walking on rumours or hearsay?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(155, 43, 'e)	Do I have the right motive, a genuine and sincere concern to help and not ridicule?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(156, 43, 'f)	Do I have the right words?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(157, 43, 'g)	Am I emotionally prepared for surprises in case of rejection, denial or even attack?', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(158, 43, 'Once these questions have been carefully considered, then we can now follow through to confront the individual.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(159, 44, 'The body of Christ is a single family. We are members of the household of God and thus must have good relationships with one another. However, we must respect boundaries. Relationship with the opposite sex must be well spelt out and with clear boundaries. We can all genuinely relate by learning, praying, fellowshipping, evangelising together. We must, however, avoid sending signals and messages that mislead members of the opposite sex to be emotionally attached to us. As a reasonable child of God, we must avoid terms of endearment (e.g., “my dear,” “my darling”, “sweetie”, “honey”) when engaging with the opposite sex that you are not married to. It can create unpleasant tension and unfavourable atmosphere that can breed ungodliness and lack of decorum in the house of God. We must also be careful of unholy bodily contact that can provoke sensual feelings.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(160, 44, 'Just as Apostle Paul admonished us, the younger men should be looked at as our brethren, because that is the relationship between us in the Lord Jesus Christ, while the older women should be as our mothers, and the younger ones as sisters “with all purity.” The word “purity” like we saw in the last study (the same word Paul used to exhort Timothy in 4:12), is a Greek word that means “chastity” or sexual purity. Do not abuse any sister or brother emotionally or sensually.', '2018-02-19 12:12:01'),
(161, 45, 'It is a natural rule and basic law of human dignity that an individual who works is deserves a reward. This may seem like common human knowledge, but the truth is that its origin is not human but divine. The first worker that ever lived was God Himself. In Genesis 1, we have the account of God’s work of creation, day by day, step by step. In Genesis 2:2, we see that He finished all His work, and “rested” (i.e., ceased from working) on the seventh day. In Genesis 1:31, the account tells us, “God saw everything that he had made, and, behold, it was very good.” The reward, which God the Creator gets for His work, is the sense of pleasure and fulfilment from His creatures on earth and the accompanying Glory from all His handiwork. Revelation 4:11 says “Thou art worthy, O Lord, to receive glory and honour and power: for thou hast created all things, and for thy pleasure they are and were created.”', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(162, 45, 'The importance of this can be seen even through verse 18 of our study, “Thou shalt not muzzle the ox that treadeth out the corn,” then it will not be right for a Christian employer to owe his staff (for no reason) or for the organised church group to owe a full-time ministry worker for 3–6 months of unpaid salaries and allowances! It is unbiblical and sacrilegious! In the original text recorded in Deuteronomy 25:4, the Scripture says, “Thou shalt not muzzle the ox when he treadeth out the corn.” This was a literal instruction to Moses, that the Israelites should allow the oxen (farm animal) to eat grass or grain as they worked in the field, and not shut their mouths with a muzzle, a device that covers an animal\'s snout. This is the Scripture Paul used in our study text, making a comparison of the ox with a Christian worker in God’s field (see Matt. 9:37–38 and John 4:35–36) and the need they must be compensated as they work on the field.', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(163, 45, 'He further expounded this principle (1 Cor. 9:7–10). He asked, “Doth God take care of oxen” (1 Cor. 9:9). Is God overly concerned about lower animals that are not created in His image? His point is that the principle of not muzzling the ox was ultimately intended by God to be for His servants in ministry (1 Cor. 9:10).', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(164, 45, 'Even secular workers earn their wages. How much more should those who labour in the saving Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ get paid for what they do?', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(165, 46, 'Certainly, not every role in the church requires a monetary compensation, but it is definitely God’s will that the labourers in His field are compensated accordingly. Of course, it is beyond financial reward when we go further to understand Paul’s use of the concept of “double honour.” The word “honour” in our text (1 Tim. 5:17) is the Greek tim? which literally means “money paid,” and it also symbolically means “dignity or esteem.” It means to reward a person financially and reverentially (with dignity and respect). The word “double” is the Greek diplous which means “twofold.” ', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(166, 46, 'So “double honour” literally means to reward a person with twofold financial compensation and also twofold esteem/respect. The next verse (1 Tim. 5:18) connects by showing that the ox should not be muzzled and that the labourer is worthy of his “reward” [Greek misthos= “pay for service”], so we know that Paul is talking primarily about financial compensation with human dignity when he speaks of double “honour.” ', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(167, 46, 'However, this consideration for double honour comes with its responsibilities. You cannot claim to be a full-time minister and yet spend all week watching African Magic and football on television, with no spiritual investment of at least one-two hours of prayers for your members on daily basis and still expect any form of double honour. You do not deserve it. You cannot claim to be a full-time minister with no full-time prayer life or full-time Bible study that is complemented by excellent evangelism, visitation, and counselling. Can you imagine a full-time minister who has not even preached to a single soul around the location where his church is for 6-months and yet claims to be compensated with “double honour”? If you spend most of your time visiting the house of the rich people to gain their favour and be politically aligned while you forget the poor, the aged, and widows in your visitation schedule, then the honour is not deserved.', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(168, 46, 'If we explore the meaning of those who deserve the double honour, we see that Paul uses the exact same word presbyteros (as used in Titus 1:5). So a good place to start would be to look at what qualifications were communicated to Titus. In verse 6, Paul said about the elders: “if any be blameless, the husband of one wife, having faithful children not accused of riot or unruly.” These are the same kinds of things required for the bishops and deacons (1 Tim. 3:1–13, Titus 1:7-10). So this is the very first requirement for “double honour.” ', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(169, 46, 'Beyond this, in verse 17 of our text, Paul says they must “rule well,” and those who must be held in highest regard are “they who labour in the word and doctrine.” The word “labour” is the Greek kopiao which means “to work hard.” To work hard in God’s Word and doctrine is to first of all tirelessly strive to get clear understanding of the Scriptures through diligent study, prayer, and meditation. Men who deserve double honour are not preachers whose members are sleeping because the message lacks power and depth. Men who labour in doctrine prepare before they mount the podium and do not go there to teach about the story of tortoise that they watched on television. They are loaded with the right words and accurate in speaking the truth with boldness and sure impact. When sinners listen to them, they repent and when believers hear them, they renew their consecration. It is exciting when you see ministers who study (not just read) the entire Bible every year, which is also complemented with contemporary books to enhance the impact of their ministry. Ministry is “labour” according to our text and it is not a place for lazy people who failed out of other areas of life and think that it is the easy path to earn a living. No way!', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(170, 46, 'No wonder, Paul wrote about his pursuit in ministry, “I laboured more abundantly than they all” (1 Cor. 15:9–10).', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(171, 46, 'We must also appreciate the deeper dimension of the double honour in our text to mean that those who serve God faithfully by labouring in word and doctrine, will be worthy of honour (a) In this world, and (b) In the world to come—this is the ultimate double honour! The Lord Jesus told His apostles that they will not only be abundantly blessed in this world, but would also “sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel” in the world to come (Matt. 19:27–29).', '2018-02-19 12:20:04'),
(172, 47, 'When a church leader sins and does not repent but continues therein (e.g., in adultery, inappropriate use of church funds), the matter may eventually come out publicly even to the knowledge of the unbelieving secular world. This concern does not only damage the confidence and morale of the church or congregation, but the unsaved, who may have been thinking about turning to the Lord Jesus Christ, could also get discouraged and change their minds. It is, therefore, essential that church leadership should be kept godly and held accountable at all times.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(173, 47, 'Since some elders were already living in sin  in the Ephesian church, it was necessary for Paul to first remedy the existing problem, before talking about proper steps to take in selecting future leaders, so that only godly men were put into office and the chances of future scandals in leadership could be greatly reduced.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(174, 47, 'Paul said in verse 19 that any elder who is accused of any wrong should not be disciplined, unless at least two witnesses could testify and confirm the accusation. The process is to allow for transparency and fair hearing. This principle is derived from the Law of Moses (Deut. 19:15). We are aware of the satanic tactic of some people who may actually hate the minister for their own selfish reasons and thus arrange false witnesses to wrongfully accuse him and tarnish his reputation. The same situation happened to the Lord Jesus (Matt. 26:59–60). But Moses gave the solution (Deut. 19:16–20). The church council must follow what is written in verse 18, which is to “make diligent inquisition” concerning the claims of the witnesses and find the underlying cause of the matter. This is how to determine whether the accused leader is indeed guilty. As a church and fellowship, anything that is not based on proper evidence and proof should be dismissed, and no place must be allowed for rumour, hearsay, and gossip. Discernment of the spirit is very critical here when engaging the accused and the accuser. We have seen instances where there is no evidence, yet the Holy Spirit spoke expressly of a leader’s secret sins.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(175, 48, 'Those who are found guilty should be rebuked for everybody to see (1 Tim. 5:20). If a leader or an executive sins but the matter is kept secret for relevant reasons, the issue always boomerangs when such leaks out and becomes known among the congregation. It often breeds distrust in the church members towards their leaders. The process of public rebuke, however, does not mean we have to be too detailed in explaining what has happened, but to establish that something was done wrong by someone, who has been corrected and being helped to regain his spiritual momentum.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(176, 48, 'Public rebuke is a principle that Paul had to exercise in correcting Peter in the presence of all (Gal. 2:11–14). There are two major reasons why public rebuke is necessary: ', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(177, 48, 'a)	When a sinful leader is openly rebuked, it clears God’s name from toleration of evil. A Biblical account for this is when God exposed David for his sin of adultery and murder so that all Israel and even the Gentiles knew that God does not tolerate sin (2 Sam. 12:12).', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(178, 48, 'b)	Public rebuke causes others to become fearful of sinning (Deut. 19:20, 1 Tim. 5:20). If people know that church discipline will be administered without respect of persons, they will be fearful of becoming the object of such rebuke and will avoid sin.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(179, 48, 'A fellowship loses its leadership grip, gravity, and goodwill when it fails to correct sins at all levels and when it is perceived that there is unfairness and preferential treatment.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(180, 49, 'In verse 21, Paul strongly charged Timothy (before God, the Lord Jesus, and the “elect” angels) that he should observe and implement his detailed instruction on transparent leadership correction without any form of partiality. It is very unrighteous when a man of high esteem is not properly rebuked but another less influential leader is thoroughly punished. The gathering of the children of God must not become a place of selective judgment with a sense of “untouchableness.” It is nothing but an act of injustice that can incur the wrath of God. Partiality is something that God warned Israel against and He Himself is not a “respecter of persons” (Lev. 19:15, Rom. 2:11).', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(181, 49, 'Indirect Biblical indications show Timothy had a tendency to be shy and timid. This may be the reason Paul charged him “before God” to execute justice without preference for personalities. As we have learnt in the previous weeks, we must not allow our personality deficiency or weakness to diminish the influence of our ministry. Shyness must not lead to a situation where partiality breeds because the leader is naturally shy and cannot face the high and mighty but can vent his anger on the lower class. In such case, Paul challenged Timothy to fear God and nobody else, regardless of how powerful or highly ranked the leader might be in age, class, experience, and wealth. It must never be said that he was unfair in judgement because he was of the same tribe as the accused or he was living free in the accused boy’s quarters. It becomes an error when an executive member of a fellowship fails to make right judgement on a matter because the parents of the affected individual are the ones paying his school fees.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(182, 50, 'Paul progressed further to give a future way to resolve the problems of wrong leadership practice. He instructed that to reduce the chances of any leader bringing ridicule to the name of the Lord through a scandalous living, Timothy must understand what to look out for before making selections. In verse 22, he charged Timothy to “lay hands suddenly on no man” that he must not hastily approve or ordain anyone into an office or else he will become “partaker of other men’s sins” having appointed unqualified people who ridicule the name of the Lord.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(183, 50, 'Can you imagine how terrible it is to become a partaker of another man’s sins by not being properly led when we approve the selection of executives for local or campus fellowships? According to this study, we share in the heaven’s blame and punishment for every error committed as a result of wrongly approving the “unqualified” for leadership. May the Lord have mercy on us in the Lord Jesus’ name. Amen.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(184, 50, 'Would-be leaders must first be proven worthy of the position before appointment. We must not be in haste to fill executive position, especially when we are not fully persuaded. The consequences of putting an unqualified individual who will bring shame to the name of the Lord far outweigh a situation where there are no confirmed executives.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(185, 50, 'In the same vein, Paul called for continuous monitoring and supervision. He explained why we must carefully observe the lives of potential candidates for church leadership. In verses 24–25, he noted that some men’s sins are public knowledge and church members already know these kinds of people, while the sins of some are not immediately known but show forth in due time. The idea is that a leader must be elected only after long-term observation of their lives and personalities, since some people’s true nature might not be accurately determined immediately. We must be careful in choosing our leaders since much is expected of them as far as both service and personal integrity are concerned.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(186, 51, 'Christians, particularly leaders, are privileged custodians or stewards of God’s resources. One of the resources in our care is our physical body. We are called to glorify God in our body” (1st Cor. 6:20). It is a wrong leadership lifestyle to continue to labour without careful awareness of the state of our bodies (this is not an obsession with our bodies). In verse 23 of this text, Paul urged Timothy to use a little wine for an apparent stomach ailment that he had. Note that Paul said, “a little” wine, whose intent is purely for medicinal purpose. Be aware that this is not a free pass for a Christian to consume alcohol, as some have twisted the Bible for their selfish interest. Paul was directing the young minister, Timothy, to manage his personal health through a harmless, acceptable method. Why will a Christian minister continue a retinue of repeated period of ministrations when his body signals are not favourable? Why will a brother who has been diagnosed of high cholesterol continue to eat all kinds of fatty food in the name of spirituality? Maintaining undisciplined eating habits is foolishness. The sister who knows that she is susceptible to asthma when exposed to cold, then throws caution to the wind because she was on village evangelism, and exposes her body to cold is similarly being unwise because she could have planned to travel with a protective blanket.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(187, 51, 'The teaching on accountable healthy behaviour does not mean that we are discouraged from exercising faith to be healed, but that observing basic healthy living with right hygienic behaviours and proper rest can prevent many health challenges.', '2018-02-19 12:26:35'),
(188, 52, 'The word which is translated as “servants” in verse 1 is a Greek word doulos that means either voluntary or involuntary engagement to serve. Slavery was rampant in Paul’s time (1st century A.D.), but, of course, many servants worked for their masters voluntarily. Since we are in the 21st century and slavery is not as common as it used to be, our focus shall be on voluntary servanthood or voluntary employment, which is the second meaning of the word as used by Paul in our text.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(189, 52, 'The phrase “under the yoke” (1 Tim. 6:1) signifies immediately that servants are under obligation to fulfil their responsibilities. Like a yoke ties an animal, so also does our work ties us to certain expectation and targets that must be delivered. An employer of labour is not a Father Christmas who dashes out salary every month even when employees are contributing nothing to what is coming in as income. The truth is this: either we are at home with no job and be free of any yoke, or we submit under a yoke to perform. Therefore, as a Christian employee in government or private businesses, we must have a sense of performance, <b>where we feel fulfilled each month that we have genuinely worked to earn our monthly take-home pay or bonuses.</b>', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(190, 52, 'Our Christian values must come to bear in our attitude to work. Whatever is required of us as a Christian worker cannot be neglected or ignored. God expects us to be fully accountable of our duties, tasks, chores, errands, and any other assignment. Irresponsibility will not only incur the displeasure (and rebuke) of our secular boss, but our true Boss in heaven will not be pleased either. It is completely wrong when a Christian is underperforming or is a latecomer. It is a discredit to the name of the Lord when Christians are known as slothful, laid-back, and unable to meet target that is transparently set for all and sundry. How do we explain it when the students of a Christian teacher are the ones who are not passing their examinations? Or how do we glorify God when Christians cannot patronise another Christian furniture maker because the last chair that was made did not last one week? Of course, we did not complain but carry the frustration.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(191, 52, 'The Bible’s standard for work according to our text is that we should count our masters “worthy of all honour.” This is in reference to an employer who is not a Christian, and possibly cruel and harsh towards us. We know this because of the contrast he makes with “believing masters” in the next verse. It is very common in many parts of the world, Nigeria included, for secular bosses to belittle and mistreat their workers. Paul said we should not hate them for this, but instead esteem them worthy of our respect. The primary reason for this, as explained by Paul, is “that the name of God and his doctrine be not blasphemed.” This is a big responsibility for us! His point is that if an unbeliever mistreats his Christian servant or worker and the Christian responds with a negative humanistic attitude, the unbelieving boss will begin to say things like “Is this the kind of thing you Christians do?”', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(192, 52, 'We carry the testimony of the Lord Jesus in our workplace and it must never be said that our lives or even work ethics contradict or oppose the excellence of the Lord Jesus. God’s Word shows us that we must not grumble but we should do our work heartily as if we were doing it unto God, and not unto man (Col. 3:22–23).', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(193, 52, 'In the second verse of our text, the right attitude towards bosses who are Christians is also dealt with. First, we are warned that we should not secretly despise our Christian employers in our heart. Yes, they are wealthy. Yes, they are blessed. Yes, they are our bosses and may even order us around. But yes, they are also our brethren who have been tasked as business leaders and not as a non-profit charity. We must not take our work for granted because we are Christians working with another Christian. We must always be the ones who come early, work late, go the extra mile, create new improvement ideas, and expand the opportunities because we must recognise that this is not about the employer but the fact that we are part of God’s project that our employer–Christian is privileged to pilot for the Lord.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(194, 52, 'It is painful these days that Christian businesses that have more Christian staff tend to collapse faster because of the I-don’t-care attitude that we set, which unfortunately gives the nonbeliever workers a cue on how to work. When unbeliever workers see that those who should be the employers’ “spiritual family” are not creative, innovative, and excellent, they will reduce their energy levels and follow the flow of laziness, tardiness, and anything-goes.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(195, 53, 'It is clear that God has blessed many of his children financially and materially to lead businesses as owners and employers of labour, with a number of servants or employees working under them. It is needful for such Christians to also know how to properly relate to and treat their workers. First of all, in Colossians 4:1, Paul speaking to believing masters, said that they should give adequate salary to their employees, as they also have a Master in heaven who will reward everybody according to his works (Matt. 16:27). This foundation agrees with our previous study on good compensation for every worker. We must never exploit our Christian employees by paying them peanuts, when our profit can adequately match what other related businesses are paying. Besides salary and other statutory payment, Paul also said that masters should treat their servants well and not threaten them (Eph. 6:9), as God Himself is their Master and does not regard our status in His fair justice. There is no partiality or respect of persons, as all Christians (great or small) are servants in God’s eyes.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(196, 53, 'In addition, we must respect all the welfare schemes or pecks that are generally given to workers of their levels of experience and certificates and not use spirituality to cheat them for any reason. If they are entitled to a leave, please allow them and do not emotionally blackmail them with words that provoke slavery and not the love of Christ.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(197, 54, 'The truth is that we must sincerely face the reality of our circumstance and the state or stage we are when we met the Lord. Some people are from very privileged homes, some came from the middle class, while others rose from abject poverty. The problems of someone who was born and raised in the lower class will not automatically disappear when he gives his life to Christ. If the person is already in his 40s or 50s, he must be sincere to the fundamental reality whilst also trusting God for help through remedial efforts like adult school, home learning, and other means. If such are already married with children, there is very minimal encouragement that can make such to become a graduate banker in five years, not even at a time when companies want under-25 recruits. It becomes an issue when such persons expect their fortune to change as soon as they come into the knowledge of the Lord Jesus Christ. God is not a magician and thus it is very unreasonable not to accept our reality, especially those that are carried into the Lord Jesus Christ because of our past.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(198, 54, 'We know it is a blessing to be able to work in any capacity and be paid, even if the salary is just enough to put food on our tables. We should never look down on roles such as a house help, gateman, car washman, newspaper vendors, recharge card vendors, okada rider, shoe cobbler, driver, and other artisans’ work when we do not have required qualifications (educational, age, or experience) for our much-desired roles. These are not demeaning in any way but a realistic posture, which if we are faithful and diligent can become a platform that can bring such people before kings and princes. However, the first rule is to gladly accept our situations and never live in self-pity as unfortunate folks.', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(199, 54, 'The Good News of eternal life in God’s kingdom brings hope to the believer no matter the situation. God said He has chosen the lowly of this world, because they are rich in faith and love for Him (James 2:5). Therefore, any Christian who finds himself in challenging circumstances should remember that he is ultimately not a servant of man, but of God—and his eternal reward is waiting for him when he hears the Lord say, “Well done, thou good and faithful servant” (Matt 25:21).', '2018-02-19 12:33:17'),
(200, 55, 'In verse 5 of our text, Paul said that these false teachers were “supposing that gain is godliness,” that is, they presumed that the purpose of godliness is to ultimately get gain. Their message is as simple as, “accepting Jesus means you can become a multimillionaire.” They saw money as the chief goal and outward piety as only a means to an end. It is painful that this is what the many years of inaccurate propensity message is creating in our nation today. Unfortunately, this kind of gospel shifts people’s minds into quick business wins and shady deals, in a quest to become rich and in actual reality, despising God in their hearts, with their shameless love of money.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(201, 55, 'The Lord Jesus has taught us that we must not lay up treasures for ourselves on the earth, but rather in heaven, because where a man’s treasure is, that’s where his heart will be also (Matt. 6:19–21). Paul affirmed when he said that we should set our affection on things above and not on things on the earth (Col. 3:2). Many false teachers are not as concerned with holiness and matters of eternity, as they are with laying up treasures on the earth.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(202, 55, 'This in no way suggests that wealth is wrong or bad, but it must never become our focus or obsession. It is a virus of the mind if we think that our being a Christian is the guaranteed ticket to quick money.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(203, 55, 'The error and folly of putting money first is illustrated in the parable of the rich fool, which we read in Luke 12:15–21. According to Matthew 6:33, the proper order is to seek first the things of God’s kingdom and His righteousness, then God Himself will prosper us materially in addition, and according to His own timetable and in the best ways He believes He can meet our needs (and not covetous wants). This is the same reality that even as God feeds the birds and clothes the lilies, He knows exactly what we need. So any teacher who uses godliness as a means to gain, or who puts financial prosperity at the forefront of his doctrine, is in great error and is not sent by God. For we “cannot serve God and mammon” (Luke 16:13).', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(204, 56, 'In this study text, Paul pointed out those false teachers have certain characteristics about their personalities and, therefore, can easily be identified by those who are indeed rooted in the truth. God’s Word says that by their fruits we shall know them (Matt. 7:20). Paul noted three primary observations about false teachers—their contents, their conducts, and their values.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(205, 56, 'a)	<b>Their content.</b> The first way to identify these kinds of false teachers is by the content of what they teach. In verse 3, Paul begins with “If any man teach otherwise,” showing that the first thing to look out for is any teaching whose content is contrary to what is taught by Paul and the apostles. Paul said that if any person, even an angel from heaven, preaches any other gospel than that which they have preached, that person should be accursed (Gal. 1:8–9)! Strong words! In verse 3 of our text, he said that these teachers do not consent to “wholesome words.” They will rather pick a little here and there and take off areas on consecration, will of God, heavenly prosperity, ethical living. Their most important message is, “Give X and you will have Y” and not on “giving your heart.”', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(206, 56, 'b)	<b>Their conduct.</b> We see the nature of their personalities, attitude, and conduct, from verse 4. The hallmark of false teachers, especially those whose primary objective is to get gain, is their pride and show-off. They are mentally puffed up and use all means to show their flamboyant lives. You can immediately see their excesses. You see them lie on television stations that millions of people attend their programmes when the hall or place of meeting can only accommodate tens of thousands of people – their conducts are completely out of the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(207, 56, 'c)	<b>Their values.</b> They can also be known by what they value above everything else. A true man of God puts the Lord above everything and every person. He knows he is nothing without the Lord Jesus Christ and His sacrificial work of atonement. If God blesses him with financial abundance, he is thankful, enjoys it with moderation, and uses it to propel the cause of Lord Jesus Christ on the earth. A false teacher, on the other hand, values money and fame above everything. He loves to have a following of “disciples,” and the truth of God is of secondary importance. In his mind, godliness is only a means to get gain, which is his true aim, but covers it up with twisted applications of the Bible. His messages are fine-tuned to be very appealing to his audience as people like him are “lovers of pleasure more than lovers of God” (2 Tim. 3:4).', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(208, 57, 'The doctrines of false teachers can be quite appealing, especially if there are promises of material prosperity. Can you imagine when you are told that you can become a millionaire in 7 days! Paul instructed Timothy, “From such withdraw thyself” (1 Tim. 6:5b). There is no way out but to withdraw—complete separation from anyone whose influence can shift your focus away from the Lord Jesus Christ unto worldly possession.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(209, 57, 'One of the biggest dangers of this inaccurate doctrine of prosperity is that it promises that God will bless us with financial wealth now in this present world, without even emphasising any need for obedience and holiness. It is absolutely true that many passages of the Scripture show us that God promises to bless us financially, but every single one of those passages are based on the condition of loving and obeying God, both in the Old and New Testaments.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(210, 57, 'Beloved, let us avoid messages of unbalanced prosperity preaching because they will push us unto godlessness, ambitious living, unethical standards, and I-must-have-it-by-all-means lifestyle.', '2018-02-19 16:03:54'),
(211, 58, 'In our world today, possession and acquisition are the hallmark of who is who. The more you have, the more you are known and respected; hence, everyone is in a rat race of covetousness, struggling not to be beaten by the next man. Our understanding of life and contentment is a perpetual drive to possess more things or achieve exclusive advantages over others. This may include things like a university degree, high-paying job, big house, successful marriage, large business, nice cars, foreign visas, and so on. We spend our lives chasing material things as if they are what will define tomorrow. In the process, some have even used God’s Word as a means to get wealth and only see the church as a business. Others will go to any length to achieve success, including seeking the help of occultists and ritualists. Some do not even mind to kill the next man in their quest to get their desired status. It is a race that is never satisfying. They are just never content and are always striving for more wealth and possessions.', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(212, 58, 'However, the Bible has the ultimate answer to surviving this pressure and living our lives worthy of our destination and not be carried away by the distractions of the journey. The logic here is about priority—which is more important? Short-term benefit here or long-term benefit there? Contentment only comes from having the priority of godliness, not gain, and the perspective of the eternal, not the temporal. Godliness becomes a great gain that brings contentment because godly people have the inner peace of knowing that they are right with God and whether they have a little or a lot, whether they live or die, they belong to the Lord’s family now and forever. Their priority is godliness—to live a life pleasing to God, and their perspective is grounded on eternity. No wonder Paul could say, “I have learnt, in whatsoever state I am, therewith to be content” (Phil. 4:11).', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(213, 59, 'This automatically leads us into the next segment—the issue of the rat race that is so prevalent in this world, and how this has worn out many to the point of extinction and utter frustration. You see a man, who is obsessed with outdoing his fellow man in a never-ending competition for who is more “blessed” and prosperous. He is, therefore, looking for what more to do that will reduce his fellow competitors in a never-ending cycle of trying to prove a point. This is essentially what the rat race is. It demands that an individual works tirelessly and continually for money and material things, with little attention paid to the deeper issues of life. Some call it “keeping up with the Joneses,” that is, using every effort to make sure you are in the in-crowd, the “happening” people, you have the latest phones, the latest fashion trend, up-to-date with the best malls and outlets, and the list goes on. We then live our lives according to the popular quote, “We spend money that we do not have, on things we do not need, to create impressions that won\'t last on people who do not even care about us.” We borrow to get the latest dress. We borrow our friend’s shoes to an event. We steal from the office to have an upgraded car. We send our children to schools with rates that are equal to our cumulative six months salary and get all possible loans to live in areas where our salaries cannot afford. How long can we live in this self-imposed rat race in a quest to want to be like our friends, neighbours, or family members? Some do not even have shame—they can borrow from their spiritual sons, they can go down to the lowest level to borrow from the unbelievers! How ridiculous is this “fake” lifestyle!', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(214, 59, 'But what is the end result of all these? Paul reminded us that “we brought nothing into this world, and it is certain we can carry nothing out” (1 Tim. 6:7). Our Lord Jesus has been a little more explicit saying, “For what shall it profit a man, if he shall gain the whole world, and lose his own soul? Or what shall a man give in exchange for his soul?” (Mark 8:36–37). Even if we “hustle” till we accumulate all the wealth in the world, what do we gain ultimately if we “lose our soul,” that is, be rejected by God in the end and cast into the flames of destruction (Matt. 10:28, 13:30, 18:8, 25:41; Rev. 20:15)? Or what shall a man give in exchange for his soul? That is, what amount of money can you pay God to redeem your soul and let you into His kingdom? ', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(215, 59, 'We brought nothing into this world and can carry nothing out, so there is no point focusing all our attention on short-term materialism, and eventually miss God’s everlasting kingdom. We must move out of the rat race to the right race by refocusing our attention from the temporal accumulation of wealth to the eternal kingdom of God. This is a part of being transformed by the renewing of our mind and ceasing from being conformed to this world (Rom. 12:2). Just as we invest our mind, time, energy, and resources in the rat race, we also have to invest much more in the right race of God’s kingdom.', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(216, 60, 'After showing us why we should be content in godliness by freedom from materialism, Paul concluded that “having food and raiment let us be therewith content” (1 Tim. 6:8). He practically simplified life’s demands down to the necessities. The crisis we face in life is essentially because we are looking for wants (every desire of our heart) rather than needs (what we need to survive now). Economics show that human wants are insatiable; therefore, we must learn to be satisfied and content even if we only have the basic necessities of life in this world. God’s Word, says that our conduct and lifestyle should be without covetousness (longing for material wealth), but we should be content with whatever God gives us (Heb. 13:5). The Lord Jesus also told us  that our heavenly Father already knows what we have need of, even before we ask Him (Matt. 6:8). On top of this, God has also promised to supply those needs according to His riches in the Lord Jesus (Phil. 4:19). So why worry or anxious about being taken care of, when our top priority must be seeking God’s kingdom and its righteousness, and the food and raiment will be added unto us, even as He feeds the birds and clothes the lilies (Matt. 6:25-33).', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(217, 61, 'The two words are synonymous but not necessarily the same. The worldly view of “happiness” is based on the goodness of our circumstances. If we are in decent health, have a good source of income, good family, and friends, then we are happy. But if the circumstances change for the worse, then we sink into sadness, sorrow, and despair.', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(218, 61, 'The Biblical view of “joy,” on the other hand, is quite different. Biblical joy does not come from having money or material possessions, but rather from a deep knowledge of who God is, and the redemption which He has provided for His people. God’s Word lets us know that all things work together for the good of those who love God (Rom. 8:28), so any circumstances we find ourselves in is ultimately just a piece of the bigger picture. A person who is filled with the joy of the Lord does not get depressed or become hopeless even if he loses his material possessions. It takes a fullness of joy (Ps. 16:11) to remain happy and cheerful in the Lord Jesus Christ regardless of one’s circumstances. And this fullness is only found in one place: by continually abiding in His presence. This is why Paul, while he was in Roman custody as a prisoner, wrote to the Philippian church, “Rejoice in the Lord always, and again I say, Rejoice” (Phil. 4:4). “Always” means in any situation you find yourself: rich or poor, healthy or sick, married or alone, free or in prison, among other situations. This cannot come by riches or by the world’s standards, but only by abiding in the glorious presence of God. This kind of joy becomes our strength at all times—in season and out of season. Are we happy or full of joy?', '2018-02-19 16:10:41'),
(219, 62, 'A careful observation of the entire study text reveals a 3-part process of the effects of money on the unsuspecting victim. It first begins with a desire and demand for money, then a deception and delusion, which finally ends with destruction and despair. We shall explore each stage as explained in our text.', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(220, 62, 'a)	<b>The desire.</b> Paul pointed out first a desire for money in the heart of the individual, which is the origin of the problem (1 Tim. 6:9–10). “They that will be rich”—the word translated as will is the Greek boulomai which means to will, want, or desire. The more accurate translation is, “They that desire to be rich.” In verse 10, he mentioned “The love of money”—this phrase is from the Greek philarguria which literally means love of silver [or, money]. It is also called “avarice”, which is a strong and insatiable desire for riches. The Scripture says, “He that loveth silver shall not be satisfied with silver; nor he that loveth abundance with increase: this is also vanity” (Eccl. 5:10). This is a key verse. God shows us that the love of money just leads to a desire for even more money, because there is never any true contentment or satisfaction. The verse concludes with “this is also vanity,” since it all adds up to nothing in the end. Zero plus Zero plus Zero is always Zero. Someone might say “Well, if I could only have ‘X’ amount, then I’ll be OK.” But that is what many in the past have said, and never dealt with the real problem, until they got what they wanted and raised the new expectation that, of course, will continue to be raced to no end.', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(221, 62, 'b)	<b>The deception.</b> Paul mentioned that those who desire to be rich “fall into temptation and a snare” (1 Tim. 6:9). He added that “they have erred from the faith” (1 Tim. 6:10). The Greek words used in these two phrases are reminiscent of an animal that has wandered and lost his way. Then there is a pit covered with grass and sticks which the animal thought is solid ground until it eventually falls into it. This is what the desire for riches does to a person—it keeps him deluded from reality. It makes him believe he is safe and secure, walking on solid ground, until the reality dawns on him. The Lord Jesus has spoken of “the deceitfulness of riches” (Mark 4:19). <br/>\r\nVerse 9 also says that they fall into many “foolish and hurtful lusts.” This is another form of deception and trickery that an abundance of wealth can bring. Someone with limited finances cannot do too much and does not even think about certain things because he just cannot afford them. But a person that has money to spend freely is more prone to wander in his mind and begin to think about some things he ought not. He can easily afford an expensive hotel and seduce women with his riches. He can bribe his way out of any situation. He can throw extravagant parties just to flaunt and be loved by people.', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(222, 62, 'c)	<b>The destruction.</b> The same way in which the wages of sin is death is the desire and love of money will end in destruction both in this world and in the world to come. In verse 9, Paul used the word “drown,” which indicates a total submerging, like someone who sinks in an ocean and has no way to swim out. They that desire to be rich fall into temptations, snares, as well as foolish and hurtful lusts, which finally submerge them into destruction. The words “destruction” and “perdition” in the original Greek both mean ruin, and it could be physical, spiritual, or eternal. <br/>\r\nWhen a man cannot control his appetite for worldly taste and is caught with the bug on seeking for money, the spirit of destruction will make such individual to go any length in a quest to satisfy the destructive desire.<br/>\r\nIn verse 10, Paul said they have “pierced themselves through with many sorrows.” The word sorrows is a Greek word that means grief or despair, which is the end result of putting confidence in money instead of God. Men who are caught in the rat race for financial possession live their days in deep pain and continued sorrows, which, unfortunately, culminate in eternal damnation.\r\n', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(223, 63, '“The love of money is the root of all evil” is a Scriptural verse that is often misunderstood. First, notice that the Scriptures do not say that money is the root but the love of money. So it is not money itself that is the problem, but philarguria, the love of money—the strong desire, thirst, and appetite for riches, which is also called avarice or sometimes covetousness.', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(224, 63, 'Next, how is it the root of all evil? First, let us check the original rendering of the phrase in Greek, “the love of money is a root of all kinds of evil.” This means that the love of money is a root sin from which many other sins flow and grow. If someone is covetous and wants money by all means, then he can go the extra mile to commit another sin (lie, deceive, or even kill). In essence, a singular desire as a root of evil can lead to multiple fruits of sins.', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(225, 63, 'It may interest us if we check this root against each of the Ten Commandments to establish that truly, when covetous or love of money is a root sin in our lives, it can lead to many unpleasant fruits of sins.', '2018-02-19 16:18:47'),
(226, 63, '•	First Commandment: “Thou shall have no other gods before me.” The Lord Jesus has said that we cannot serve God and mammon (Matt. 6:24). Either money is our god, or God is our God. If someone continues to love money, then he has failed the first commandment because you cannot serve God and money.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(227, 63, '•	Second Commandment: “Thou shall not make for thyself any graven image,” that is, any idol. Colossians 3:5 says that the love of money (covetousness) is idolatry. Money can become a god that people worship and its imagery becomes what we seek after.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(228, 63, '•	Third Commandment: “Thou shall not take the name of the Lord thy God in vain.” How many people have cursed and misused God’s name when they have lost a lot of money? How many people have lied with God’s name to make money?', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(229, 63, '•	Fourth Commandment: “Keep the sabbath day holy.” Many are too busy pursuing riches and can never set aside one day each week for the Lord.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(230, 63, '•	Fifth Commandment: “Honour thy father and mother.” Many have disregarded their parents in their quest to make money and many have cut off from their parents because of their passionate desire to make money.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(231, 63, '•	Sixth Commandment: “Thou shall not kill.” We all know that many murders have occurred due to insatiable desire for money. Ritualism for money is one of the worst disasters in our time.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(232, 63, '•	Seventh Commandment: “Thou shall not commit adultery.” Women often seduce other women’s husbands  because of money.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(233, 63, '•	Eighth Commandment: “Thou shall not steal.” This one speaks for itself. ', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(234, 63, '•	Ninth Commandment: “Thou shall not bear false witness.” Many Christians lie to make money! Many use birth certificate and even with sworn affidavits that is not their true date of birth.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(235, 63, '•	Tenth Commandment: “Thou shall not covet.” The love of money and covetousness go hand in hand. They are twins from the same source.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(236, 64, 'As we have seen, it is love for money that is the source of the problem, and not money itself. Money in reality is just a tool that can be used to get some works done. Just as we need a shovel to dig, a broom to sweep, or a saw to cut wood, we also need some things and use money to get the job done. As Christians, we are stewards of God’s property; whatever we possess ultimately belongs to the Master. God evaluates our hearts to see if we are at the point where we are strong enough to handle money without falling into the temptations that accompanies it. Christian ministry definitely requires money. The Lord Jesus, being the Owner of the silver and the gold (Hag. 2:8), had the ability to have money readily available whenever He needed it (see Matt. 17:27). We know that Paul had a business (Acts 18:3) and used the money to support his ministry (Acts 20:33–34). At other times he asked the church to contribute and help one another financially (e.g., 2 Cor. 8:14-15).', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(237, 64, 'Today, many have unfortunately used the Lord’s name to make merchandise of their congregation; and they will be rewarded according to their works. But the true ministry of the Gospel does indeed need funding, especially in the missions field where unreached people groups desperately need freedom from spiritual bondage. God disperses the necessary funds as He sees fit through any means He chooses, and expects His servants to use the money accordingly. This does not mean we cannot enjoy what He gives us (1 Tim. 6:17), but we must remember who the money belongs to and what it is actually for. We are only a privileged treasurer of God’s resources and God Himself decide how, when and for what purpose our money must be used for.', '2018-02-19 16:22:17'),
(238, 65, 'To victoriously fight the good fight of faith, we must first realise God has not called us to a 100-metre sprint, but to a long marathon that involves obedience in the same direction and on a consistent basis. To guarantee success, we must make sure that we run in the right direction or we will never get to the right destination. In other words, there are two different directions and each leads to two different destinations. The first direction is worldliness, which leads to destruction while the second direction is godliness, which leads to eternal life. Paul, in verse 11, instructed the believers to “flee these things.” What things? The things he had just mentioned to Timothy include the desire to be rich and the love of money, together with the associated foolish and hurtful lusts, which are a summary of what worldliness is (1 Tim. 6:9–10). Paul instructed the believers to flee from following this direction and follow the second direction—which is godliness that leads to eternal life.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(239, 65, 'In verse 11, he said we should “follow after,” which is derived from the Greek word diõkõ that literally means “to pursue.” This is a very strong word that carries the tone of energetically going after something or someone. So he told Timothy (and the rest of the believers) to aggressively and passionately pursue the things he listed next in the same verse, which are the means of laying hold on eternal life. This instruction is a reminder to us of what the Lord Jesus has said about how the kingdom of God “suffereth violence, and the violent takes it by force” (Matt. 11:12), or in Luke 13:24 where he tells us to “strive” to enter in because many will seek to enter in but will not be able. The word he used, which is translated as “strive”, is the Greek agonizomai, which literally means “to struggle, compete, contend, or endeavour.” So we are being continually admonished to pursue the things that will lead us unto eternal life in the kingdom of God with a lot of energy, zeal, and passion. ', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(240, 65, 'Paul listed six things we should aggressively follow:', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(241, 65, 'a)	<b>Righteousness.</b> this is the Greek word dikaiosune which means both the imputed righteousness of Christ and also practical rightness in character or act. It means that a person is not only justified through Christ, but that he also chooses to do what is right. So we are called to consciously and deliberately live right.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(242, 65, 'b)	<b>Godliness.</b> this is the Greek word eusebeia which means piety, reverence, or obedience towards God. It flows out of a sense of awe and wonder at God’s personality, which, in turn, connects to worship and living our lives in God’s way out of godly fear. ', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(243, 65, 'c)	<b>Faith.</b> this is the Greek word pistis which means a persuasion or conviction about the truthfulness of God. It means both the faith in Christ for salvation as well as faith for the battles and challenges of life. Paul knew that Timothy, and we today also, would need faith to continually be triumphant in our Christian journey.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(244, 65, 'd)	<b>Love.</b> the agap? love means benevolent and sacrificial. A Christian cannot successfully move in the direction that is pleasing to God without love. A major part of fighting the good fight of faith is being committed to letting go of the best in us for the good of others.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(245, 65, 'e)	<b>Patience.</b> the word here is hupomon?, which is not just patience in the ordinary sense, but a “cheerful and hopeful endurance.” This word represents a calm delight even through trials and tribulations. It looks to God’s promises and knows that the good fight is already won. ', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(246, 65, 'f)	<b>Meekness.</b> Paul uses a Greek word praot?s that means gentleness and humility. The natural man cannot submit himself to the Lordship of Christ without humility. The good Christian fight cannot be fought in pride, because God will sometimes allow situations to come our way that will require great humility.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(247, 66, 'It has been almost 2,000 years that the faithful believers have continued fighting the good fight, at the same time taking the Gospel to the uttermost parts of the earth just as the Lord Jesus has commanded. In his short epistle, the apostle Jude (the Lord Jesus’ brother) said we should “earnestly contend for the faith . . .” (Jude 1:3). This means to strive to uphold the truth about the Lord Jesus in the face of lies, deceptions, and various forms of falsehood. Apart from Christians individually fighting the good fight on a personal level, contending for the faith also means to defend sound doctrine and correct the errors of false teachers.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(248, 66, 'Through the centuries of the church age, many heresies and doctrines that oppose the faith have reared their ugly heads, and sometimes it took individual believers to defend and stand for the truth. In our modern times, the Christian faith has seen many opposing belief systems try and sometimes succeed in drawing away people who once professed faith in Christ. Besides the contrary religions, we live in the era prophesied in Daniel 12:4 called ‘the time of the end’ when “knowledge shall increase.” New so-called “knowledge” of the world is coming, particularly the OSAS messages (once saved, always saved). Be warned with this new knowledge that is part of the manifestations of the evils of the last days.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(249, 67, 'The end result of fleeing worldliness, pursuing godliness, and fighting the good fight of faith is that we are literally admitted into the heavenly place that God has prepared for those who love Him (John 14:2–3, 1 Cor. 2:9). A Christian must always keep an eye on the end, living this present life with an eternal perspective. Paul said if our hope in Christ is for only this present life, then we are of all men most miserable (1 Cor. 15:19). So the exhortation to Timothy was to “lay hold on eternal life” (1 Tim. 6:12). We are to lay hold just as a stamp must remain stuck to a letter to ensure that both get to the destination. Any moment that the stamp detaches, the letter becomes an ordinary paper with no ability to get to its destination.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(250, 67, 'We must never be distracted by the glitz and glamour of this world. We must not be tempted to veer off the path that God originally placed in front of us. Laying hold on eternal life involves not turning to the right hand or to the left, maintaining our focus on eternity—our heavenly home.', '2018-02-19 16:30:30'),
(252, 68, 'In our Christian walk, we are aware of the many pressures from the devil and his demonic host, and even humans with intent to destroy our Christian profession. This was the reality of the young minister Timothy at Ephesus. The city itself was a nest of devils, and many of its citizens were against the preaching of the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ (Acts 19:23-28, 34). In addition to this, we see from earlier study the vileness of some false teachers who were being used by seducing spirits to propagate various doctrines of demons. Young Timothy had a sizeable amount of pressure upon him that could have easily made a person reconsider their commitment to the Lord Jesus Christ. He could have fallen into the category of the second kind of people that the Lord Jesus spoke about in the parable of the sower, who at first received the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ gladly, but later fell away after persecution and tribulation arose (Mark 4:16-17). Paul, who was full of the wisdom of God, understood the realistic nature of this danger and, therefore, wrote strong words to Timothy to keep his integrity intact irrespective of the circumstances. Sometimes we need strong words to face strong hardship and true leaders must not shy away from this. The focus of his admonition to Timothy was God Himself; he highlighted certain attributes of the Creator to remind Timothy (and us) of who the Person is that we serve and why we should never back down in light of this reality.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(253, 68, 'a)	<b>Consciousness of God’s presence. To kick off the engagement, Paul clar</b>ified the context of the discussion to be “in the sight of God” (1 Tim. 6:13). He seemed to say that everything done in heaven and on earth is clearly seen by the watchful eyes of God. He is omnipresent and omniscient, and “neither is there any creature that is not manifest in his sight, but all things are naked and opened unto the eyes of him with whom we have to do” (Heb. 4:13). A person who is aware of God’s omnipresence and omniscience can stand confidently because he knows that he is not alone and thus we must live our Christian lives “in the sight of God”—with a full-time awareness of His presence.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(254, 68, 'b)	<b>God owns our life.</b> Paul said that God “quickeneth [i.e., gives life to] all things.” He was saying to him that the power to give life and to resurrect the dead belong solely to God (John 11:25). Paul was essentially showing Timothy and all Christians that even if we are faced with the threat of death, God is the one who quickens all things. We have a sure promise of the resurrection and eternal life, so we can stand with integrity, when threatened, and not soften or water down our witness of the truth.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(255, 68, 'c)	<b>Christ is coming back.</b> Paul says we must continue to keep this demanding strong commandment without spot, “until the appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ” (1 Tim. 6:14). A Christian is motivated to live a life of integrity if he is certain that the Lord Jesus is coming back one day. Without any sense of deep expectation of His coming, the tendency is for the Christian to become complacent and eventually crumble when faced with pressure. The Lord Jesus has raised this question, “Nevertheless when the Son of man cometh, shall he find faith on the earth?” (Luke 18:8).', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(256, 68, 'd)	<b>The only blessed and most Potentate.</b> The remembrance of the Lord Jesus Christ’s return led Paul into a deep praise of God’s ultimate supremacy above all things and this sufficiently guarantees us safety. When the text reads that God is the only Potentate. “Only” is the Greek mono which means sole or singular—there is no other. “Potentate” is the word dynastes which means a ruler; and not just a ruler, but derived from a root word that means this particular Ruler can do whatever he wants to do. This means that as we submit to preserving God’s commandment, we are on the side of a God who is ultimately in control of all things.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(257, 68, 'e)	<b>The King of kings and Lord of lords.</b> The words “King” and “Lord” in the original language both mean a person who is sovereign or supreme over a realm. All authority in heaven and on earth belongs to Him (Matt. 28:18). With the understanding of the God that we serve, we can confidently stand fast in the integrity of our witness even in the face of death, knowing who is really in charge.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(258, 68, 'f)	<b>The Only Everlasting.</b> The God of the Bible is the One “who only hath immortality” (1 Tim. 6:16). The same word mono is used, meaning “only, sole or singular.” The word immortality is the Greek athanasia which means “deathless”, but when used in reference to God carries the sense of God’s eternal being—he is the only being that is “from everlasting” (Ps. 90:2, Mic. 5:2). This means that he has no beginning. He is uncreated Creator. It is a little easier for our finite minds to understand immortality or eternal life in the future sense, but a little more challenging to understand how God can just exist from eternity past. Some have said that God’s eternal nature, unlike a straight line, which has point A and point B, is more like a circle that has no beginning or ending. His Hebrew name Yahweh literally means “self-existent,” meaning that He is not a created entity and He is totally independent in His existence from everlasting to everlasting.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(259, 68, 'g)	<b>Glory that is concealed.</b> In conclusion, Paul gave some insightful revelation about God and His Glory. He dwells in the light which no man can approach (1 Tim. 6:16). Not only does God dwell in light, God Himself is light (1 John 1:5). This shows the exclusive nature of God and how we must be serious in how we deal with Him with our whole lives. We can truly trust Him with our yesterday, today, and tomorrow, for He alone is omnipotent, omnipresent, and omniscient.', '2018-02-19 16:40:47'),
(260, 69, 'This study pushes a clear frontier on our expected attitude to money when we are privileged of the Lord to have it. In TACEF, we always believe that we are a “privileged treasurer” of the Lord’s resources. The Lord owns whatever we are individually opportuned to have and we are just His treasurer. He has the 100% right to demand for His resource anytime and for any purpose He intends it to be used for. If we wrongly assume that we own it, then we can spend it anyhow to satisfy our desire or to join the rat race of trying to be like our friends and neighbours. When the purpose of money in our custody is not known, abuse is inevitable and it is very terrible to abuse the opportunity to be God’s treasurer.', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(261, 69, 'Therefore, it is important that we have the right attitude towards money. In this study, the first attitude is that those who have money should not be “high-minded.” This is a Greek word that means “lofty in mind” or arrogant. God is warning us that we should not think that “my power and the might of mine hand hath gotten me this wealth” (Deut. 8:17). The reality is that a man can receive nothing, except it is given him from heaven (John 3:27).', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(262, 69, 'Secondly, we are admonished not to put confidence in riches, because they are “uncertain.” This means that money can come and money can go. Job had it all, but then he lost it all in one day. The richest men of yesterday are paupers today and those who were known as multimillionaires few years back are struggling to survive today.', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(263, 69, 'It is with this mind-set that we should manage whatever God has placed in our treasures (Luke 12:21), that is, being “rich in good works.” If we understand the purpose of what the Lord has placed in our care, we shall gladly yield ourselves to help others and to further the progress of the Gospel and kingdom by His leading and guidance. The phrase “ready to distribute” is a Greek word that means the person is liberal and good at giving. This means that we must not be stingy or tight-fisted. However, this does not mean we throw money on every request that comes our way. In the same manner that a treasurer can only dip his hand and spend at the command of the treasure owner, we must be subjected to the specific instruction of the owner of the treasure on how to distribute, to whom to distribute, for what purpose, and at what time. God will never lead you to distribute into initiatives that will not promote His name or ventures that are borne out of greed or covetousness. Be advised that it is not all welfare demands that must be served if you are truly led of the Lord. The leading of the Holy Spirit is very central to the process of meeting the needs of others. In Acts 11:27–30, we see how Prophet Agabus discerned an imminent need for welfare through a prophecy on the coming famine in Jerusalem. The church readily responds to similar revelation and divine prompting.', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(264, 70, 'The term “laying up in store” (1 Tim. 6:19) is similar to how we save our money in banks or our valuables in a safe today. But Paul said we should lay in store a good foundation “against the time to come.” There is a time coming. And every person will give account of himself before God, and receive the rewards for the things he has done in this present time, as many Biblical passages testify. This verse means that instead of measuring our wealth by how much we have in our bank account, we should rather store up credit with the bank of heaven. Whatever amount of money that God gives us now is to be invested wisely in the things of the kingdom. There is a process to dispense money and in TACEF, we have advised six steps on how individual finances is managed to ensure that it is justifiably distributed. The procedural rule constitutes tithe/offering, family upkeep, savings, support for parents, welfare for brethren, gifts to household of faith, and support for the poor. (Details of these are in the TACEF financial guidelines.) This stepwise approach does not remove the possibility of God overriding our thoughts with specific leading by His spirit with total conviction and confirmation. We have seen instances when God asked people to close their bank accounts to meet a need of a particular programme and God Himself compensated back. Avoid doing what God has not led you to do when it comes to freewill or sacrificial giving.', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(265, 71, 'The concluding parts of Paul’s first epistle to Timothy include instructions for him to guard and watch. He is not only to avoid profane and useless discussions, but oppositions of science as well. The word “science” here is the Greek gnosis which means “knowledge”. ', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(266, 71, 'The “opposition of knowledge” was also a prophecy that is for our 21st century. Scientific knowledge has tremendously increased (Dan. 12:4) over the last few decades, and it has got to the extent that it opposes God and His truth. Though the denial of God’s existence is nothing new (Ps. 14:1), modern science has caused numerous people in our day to err by teaching irrational doctrines like the Big Bang and evolution. These teachings oppose everything that Christianity and the Bible stand for. They are seductive because the “experts” that teach them profess to have deeper knowledge of the created world; unfortunately, some Christians have been tempted and seduced.', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(267, 71, 'The Word of the Lord has always been ahead of science because many Biblical facts that science previously opposed are now found to be true. Some of them are listed below:', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(268, 71, '<img src=\"Pictures/bibleStudy1.jpg\" alt=\"Tacef Study\"/>', '2018-02-19 16:47:08'),
(269, 72, 'In the opening verse of this epistle, Paul gave us some insight into the path of transgenerational greatness that defined young Timothy’s life. Timothy’s grandmother Lois, as well as his mother Eunice, both had faith and taught Timothy the Scriptures. They must have invested heavily in young Timothy early in life and thus provide the foundation for what he would become in the scheme of heaven. Of course, issues of parental foundation matters and parents (spiritual and physical) must not miss the opportunity to provide the right head start for their children on the path of greatness in God.', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(270, 72, 'However, the great faith of Lois and Eunice could not save Timothy. Our parents or grandparents’ faith cannot save us. We cannot say “My father is the bishop,” or “I was baptised when I  I was a child.” The only way a human being obtains the promise of life in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus is by “unfeigned faith.” That word “unfeigned” is a Greek word anupokritos which means genuine, sincere, not pretending. In other words, this person actually believes the things that are written about the Lord Jesus Christ. Of course, there is no doubt that Christian parents can teach and influence us, just as Timothy’s did, but neither is there any doubt that the salvation of the Lord Jesus Christ is on an individual basis through unfeigned faith.', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(271, 72, 'In this regard, as parents, we should always pray for the salvation of our kids and do our God-given part to teach them the truth about God, life, death, the world, and eternity. TACEF Seed of purpose guideline actually provides indicative years (under 8) when the salvation of a child must be confirmed and they must immediately start seeking the gift of the Holy Spirit before the age of 12. In Genesis 18:19, we saw how God was positive that Abraham would lead his children in the way of the Lord. Our times are even tough, with many forces and ideologies that compete for our children’s minds. Our job is to use the power of the Word to protect them as God gives us wisdom. We are also instructed to “[t]rain up a child in the way that he should go: and when he is old, he will not depart from it” (Prov. 22:6). It has been said repeatedly that even if a child rebels, as long as the foundational training in God’s Word has been instilled from childhood, there is a very high certainty that he will trace his path back to God.', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(272, 73, 'Every born-again believer, who has been saved through unfeigned faith, has also been baptized by the Holy Spirit into the Body of the Lord Jesus Christ (1 Cor. 12:13). As the Spirit made His way into our hearts, He also imparted one or more divine gifts into each believer. Paul in verse 6 of our text reminded Timothy to stir up the gift of God which he received by laying on of Paul’s hands. The words “stir up” are from the Greek word anazopureo, which actually means to rekindle. Paul told Timothy to rekindle the divine gift that was residing in him. Young Tim had already faced many challenges in ministry and as a Christian in general, which could have begun to douse the once brightly burning flame in his heart. God’s Word tells us to “[q]uench not the Spirit” (1 Thess. 5:19). The word “quench” here is the Greek sbennumi, which literally means “to extinguish,” like when a fire is put out. This means that it is possible for us to let the intensity of the Holy Spirit diminish in us, possibly through ignorance, through the daily demands of the carnal world we live in, or through “grieving” the Holy Spirit (Eph. 4:30) by disobedience. Whatever the case, Paul’s reminder (for Timothy and us) was to reactivate any gifts that the Spirit has deposited in us which we have allowed to fade for one reason or the other. It is a concern that many who used to operate the gift of prophecy or even word of knowledge cannot remember the last time these gifts found expression; it is like they have become “rusted” with time due to being unused or unrefined for a long period.', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(273, 73, 'As we reignite them, let us be fervent in making good use of what the Master has given us, making a difference in our world and expanding His kingdom on earth, then He will pour more of His gifts into our lives.', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(274, 74, 'After Paul reminded Timothy to stir up the gift of God, he immediately followed it with “For God has not given us the spirit of fear.” The word “fear” is the Greek deilia which means timidity. It is allowing ourselves to become intimidated by a person, a situation, circumstances, and so forth. Many are intimated by examination, boss at work, or even ordinary wall gecko! Fear is the opposite of faith and it comes to challenge the basis of our belief in God. Faith does not \"overcome\" fear; it actually takes it away completely. It is like Light and darkness, faith and fear cannot occupy the same space at the same time; there will be either one or the other. Faith is a choice of our will, as is fear. It is said by Bible students that there are 365 “Fear nots” in the Bible—one “Fear not” for every day of the year! Amazing!', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(275, 74, 'In the following text, we see that instead of the spirit of fear, God has given us His own Spirit of power, and love, and a sound mind. The “power” is the dunamis of God, the ability which is above our own ability. “Love” is the agape sacrificial benevolent love, that has the welfare of our neighbour at heart, and which we must continue to grow in. “A sound mind” is sophronismos which is self-control or “disciplined thinking.” It is thinking and acting according to the truth of God’s Word, not according to frail emotions such as the fear of the world.', '2018-02-19 16:54:12'),
(276, 75, 'Before the Lord Jesus went to the cross, while He was preaching and teaching, He already made it clear that those who follow Him will face rejection, persecution, and affliction. He plainly says, “Ye shall be hated of all men for my name’s sake; but he that endures to the end shall be saved” (Matt 10:22). In other verses around this passage, He has spoken of His followers being as sheep in the midst of wolves. He has warned them about the threat of local authorities and the possibility of being betrayed by their own family members.', '2018-02-19 17:00:35'),
(277, 75, 'The Lord Jesus has told us that the world will hate us because it hates Him (John 15:18–20). There is no hatred or persecution that we can suffer in this world that the Lord Jesus Himself did not suffer while He was on earth. It may come in a different form, but He has experienced it also. Not only was Timothy to be unashamed, he was to be a partaker of the afflictions that come with professing and representing the Lord Jesus Christ. Throughout the history of the church, the Lord’s people have seen diverse kinds of persecutions, torments, and afflictions. Up till today in some parts of the world such as China, India, and many Muslim nations including Northern Nigeria, Christians are still being physically persecuted and many have to either flee or resort to “underground church.” For the rest of us, the persecution may not necessarily be physical, but more on an emotional and psychological level. A Christian might be belittled, ridiculed, and intimidated at home, at work, in school, among friends, or even in the community because of his faith.', '2018-02-19 17:00:35'),
(278, 75, 'Our ultimate secret of success through all this is also found in verse 8 of the text. The Lord Jesus says we are to do it “according to the power of God.” This means that a Christian cannot live victoriously in this hateful world in his own strength. It is only God’s own power through the Holy Spirit that enables us to endure any afflictions or hardships that may come our way. No wonder the Lord Jesus called the Holy Spirit the Comforter (John 14:26). That is a Greek word parakl?tos which means an ‘intercessor’ but also a ‘consoler’, i.e. someone who gives emotional strength. This is how we are fortified, and how we can go through the afflictions of the gospel of Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-19 17:00:35'),
(279, 76, 'Although our salvation was given us in the Lord Jesus Christ before the world began, He still had to come physically in the flesh at a time appointed by God the Father, to accomplish the actual task necessary for the redemption of His people. This is what Paul was talking about (2 Tim. 1:10). The Lord Jesus came in the flesh and “abolished” death, purchasing life and immortality on behalf of His elect. Paul further said that this Good News has been committed to him to be a preacher, an apostle, and a teacher (2 Tim. 1:11). But Paul was not alone in this appointment, we have also being saved by the appearing of the Lord Jesus Christ, and we have been appointed to serve Him in one office, capacity, or the other.', '2018-02-19 17:00:35'),
(280, 76, 'Many New Testament passages (e.g., Rom. 12:4-8) show us that the different members of the Lord Jesus Christ’s body are indeed appointed to serve in whatever gift and office we have been called to. God did not choose us in the Lord Jesus Christ just to inherit eternal life, but also to represent Him now in this present world. The Lord Jesus has said, “My meat is to do the will of him that sent me, and to finish his work” (John 4:34). The Lord Jesus was willing to work for and glorify God the Father on earth, even if the work included dying on a Roman cross. Paul was willing to work for and glorify the Lord on earth, even if it included dying at the hands of a Roman emperor. We also should be willing to work for God and glorify Him on earth (1 Cor. 10:31), even if it means persecution and death. Even if we do not die physically, we should die to the flesh (Gal. 5:24) and serve the Lord faithfully without fear. ', '2018-02-19 17:00:35'),
(281, 77, 'Paul had so much assurance of his source. He actually knew whom he had believed. The word he used here is eido, which means knowledge by seeing, which gives clarity, assurance, and certainty that is beyond the ordinary. He wrote authoritatively without any confusion: “I know whom I have believed.” No ambiguity or doubt, he was very assured and supernaturally confident of the basis of his faith.', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(282, 77, 'Beloved, only when we can say we know whom we have believed we are on the right footing of a faith that can stand the test of time. The saving faith is not based on wishful thinking or calculated guessing, but by a knowledge of the Lord Jesus Christ that God Himself unveiled to us (Matt. 11:27). It is not sufficient to be excited at the aura of the church and the faith-boosting miraculous without coming to one’s own conclusions about God. This comes only by revelation. Job reached that moment and could emphatically say, “I know that my redeemer liveth” (Job 19:25), in the midst of all his anguish and pain. The word he used there is the Hebrew yâda which means “to know or ascertain by seeing.” This was before God spoke audibly to him (Job 38:1). Job had never seen a vision of God literally before this (Job 42:5), but he had seen God by revelation and was fully convinced of his standpoint with Him. Wow!', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(283, 77, 'Job could go through all he endured and still serve God in the midst of it all, because he knew his Redeemer, just as Paul did. God’s people today also need a clear revelational knowledge of the Saviour, as this is how we will serve Him faithfully in the midst of any trial.', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(284, 78, 'Not only did Paul know whom he had believed, he was also persuaded [Greek peitho = “convinced”] that the Lord Jesus was able to keep [phulasso = “preserve”] what he had committed unto Him against the day to come. “Committed” is the word paratheke which means deposited or entrusted. ', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(285, 78, 'So what had Paul entrusted to the Lord Jesus Christ? The answer is his life—both now in this world and in the coming day. He was convinced that the Lord Jesus is fully capable of preserving him unto eternal life. This is similar to what we see in 1 Peter 1:5, where Peter said that we are “kept” by the power of God through faith unto salvation, ready to be revealed in the last time. That word “kept” in the original language means guard or protect, similar to what Paul said. It means that God preserves and keeps us in the Lord Jesus Christ, as we live our lives through this world unto the end of the journey. He will not let us go or fall by the wayside, because He has chosen us for Himself. The Lord Jesus says that He has given us eternal life, that we will never perish, and that nobody can pluck us out of His hand (John 10:28). Paul had full expectation of God keeping His promise. What a sure word!', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(286, 78, 'We also can trust God with our today and our tomorrow. We can confidently entrust our lives to the Lord Jesus Christ as Saviour and Preserver, just as we would entrust our money in a certified bank. No sensible person would give his money to a suspicious character in an uncompleted bungalow with a bank’s name written poorly on a signboard. But we can put our money in a real bank with all confidence, knowing that we will not be disappointed when we go to make a withdrawal. The Lord Jesus is so sure compared with the most verified banks because they can go down or distress. In the same parallel, we should wholeheartedly give our lives to the Lord Jesus Christ, entrusting Him with our all, being assured that He will sufficiently preserve us as the “apple of His eyes.” ', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(287, 79, 'Not only does the Lord Jesus have a responsibility to keep what we have entrusted to Him, but we also have a responsibility to keep what He has entrusted to us. It is a mutual deal here as we can see in verses 13 and 14. The first instruction is, “Hold fast the form of sound words which thou has heard…” In verse 14, Paul also said that we should keep “that good thing” which has been committed unto us, through the Holy Ghost who dwells in us. The “good thing” which the Lord has deposited and entrusted to us are twofold: (a) His Word and (b) His life.', '2018-02-19 17:04:49'),
(288, 80, 'As long as we remain in these mortal bodies, the possibility to fail or sin remains present, but we are called to strive against sin (Heb. 12:4). The Lord Jesus has said, “The spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak” (Matt. 26:41). Therefore, we should not be surprised when a person, Christian or non-Christian, lets us down when we need them the most. We must prepare ourselves emotionally to reduce the impact of the pain of human disappointment, because our Christian journey is a long one and we cannot afford to become bitter or resentful.', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(289, 80, 'The Apostle Paul was in a situation where he needed all the help he could get. Unfortunately, the people he had expected to come to his help turned out to be not so faithful after all. Asia Minor was a region where Paul worked hard. Its chief city was Ephesus, leading other notable cities of the “seven churches” including Philadelphia, Laodicea, Smyrna, Sardis, Thyatira, and Pergamum. The church of the Colossians was also right next door. After all that Paul had done for these people, it must have been quite painful for him to say, “all they which are in Asia be turned away from me.” Remember that Paul had, by the grace of God, ministered to all people from all walks of life, including people in authority and positions of power, who could have used their position with the Roman government to come to his assistance, especially because he was also a Roman, who should naturally enjoy certain privileges as a man with dual citizenship. They were in a position to help, but drew back either out of embarrassment or fear, not wanting to be openly known as associates of Paul, the outlaw. No wonder Paul appealed to Timothy not to be ashamed of his bonds (2 Tim. 1:8), and applauded Onesiphorus for not being ashamed of his chains (2 Tim. 1:16). Many of his supposed brethren had abandoned him, especially those who could have made a difference, fearing the “afflictions of the Gospel.” This reminds of many notable Jews who believed in the Lord Jesus, but only secretly with no open association because they were more concerned with maintaining their reputation (Luke 23:50–52, John 3:1–2, 12:42, 19:38).', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(290, 80, 'Of all those who turned their backs on Paul, he picked out two people—Phygellus and Hermogenes by name, for some particular reason. They were probably mentioned because they were the least expected by Paul to disappoint him. They most likely were notable men who were in significant positions of influence and could have assisted Paul in one way or the other. It is interesting that none of their names are mentioned anywhere else in the Bible. As far as history is concerned, what they will always be remembered for is that they were the two people who failed to come to the aid of one of the Lord’s greatest ambassadors of all time.', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(291, 81, 'Though many deserted Paul, one exceptional character stood out. His name was Onesiphorus. Who knows what he had to go through in order to visit and minister to the ageing apostle in his Roman cell (or dungeon). He first of all had to diligently seek Paul out (1 Tim. 1:17). There also had to be an official procedure and questioning which a person had to go through before being allowed to visit prisoners, especially an internationally known figure like Paul. He must have been so guarded like Nelson Mandela was in a place where no one could easily access, not even journalists or government officials. This man took the pain and a huge risk to be identified with a notorious ringleader of the Christian sect (Acts 24:5), especially seeing that Nero was in power at that time. Nero was a most brutal enemy of the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ and remained the biggest antagonist for his hatred and persecution of Christians. But Onesipherous’ love and genuine concern for Paul outweighed any opposing threats that stood in his way. From the moment he found Paul, and saw his deplorable condition, he did not minister to him just once, but he kept coming back “oft.” This word, “oft” is the Greek pollakis which means “many times” or “frequently.” He knew that Paul needed refreshing. The word “refreshed” is the Greek anapsucho which means “relieve.” – when someone’s presence re-energises, renews, and reignites someone’s passion, there can never be a better person to have around. We also do know that there are certain people who come around only to throw pity party, blame game, and make you feel bad and worse off. Imagine there could have been some other brethren who come around to tell Paul that he was not smart or diplomatic enough. May the good Lord surround us with refreshing people at critical moments in our lives, in the Lord Jesus’ name. Amen.', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(292, 81, 'We know that Apostle Paul had been through a whole lot, including beatings, imprisonments, stoning, shipwrecks, long journeys, robbery, and lack of good nutrition (2 Cor. 11:23-28). It must have taken a toll on his body. Onesiphorus knew he could not ignore Paul’s present difficulty, even if others did; neither was he ashamed of his chains nor afraid of what his continual association might cost him. Note that this was Paul’s second time in Roman custody, not under Claudius Caesar like before, but now under Nero—the demonic god-king. It was not the same situation in Acts 28:16–31, when he was placed under house arrest. This was a worst time and yet he was blessed to have a right man for his worst season.', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(293, 81, 'Like Onesiphorus, God has placed a mandate on us today to support one another even in the direst of times. We must stand together, in the sun and in the rain. We must sustain the bond of the Lord Jesus Christ and weather every challenge together, either as a couple, friends, colleagues, and genuine brethren who truly share the love of the Lord Jesus Christ. May the good Lord help us to be willing to uphold and support one another even when it may be costly, at the risk of everything that is important to us.', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(294, 81, '<h3>Week 28 ends here and Week 29 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(295, 82, 'There is no good thing a person does that goes unnoticed by the Lord. Paul prayed to God for special mercy on Onesiphorus and the members of his household (2 Tim. 1:16, 18). This was a great man whose act of goodness to God’s servant provoked transgenerational blessings on his household. Of course, the answer to this prayer is sure, according to the words of the Lord Jesus Himself. In Matt 5:7, the Lord Jesus has said, “Blessed are the merciful, for they shall obtain mercy.” It was not a common prayer that Paul prayed; he prayed from the depth of his heart!', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(296, 82, 'As Christians, we must remember our Lord’s admonition: “whosoever shall give you a cup of water to drink in my name, because you belong to Christ, verily I say unto you, he shall not lose his reward” (Mark 9:41). Hebrews 6:10 repeats a similar truth. Our labour of love, which we show by ministering to His saints, cannot be forgotten by God. We also understand that we do not only get a reward now in this life, but even in the world to come. If we check again verse 18 of our text, Paul’s second prayer for mercy was that the Lord should grant it unto him “in that day.” The Bible shows us that even among the Christians who are saved, we shall still stand before the judgement seat of the Lord Christ and each person will be rewarded according to what deeds he has done in this present time (see Luke 19:16–19, Rom. 14:10–12, 1 Cor. 3:12-15, 2 Cor. 5:10). This is “that day” that Paul was referring to—he was connecting Onesipherous into a timeless dimension of mercy!', '2018-02-19 17:12:54'),
(297, 83, 'We are the product of God’s grace. Everything about our journey with God is summarised by the five-letter word in its wholesome essence. We are nobody outside the grace of God! We understand what God’s Word says, “For by grace are ye saved through faith; and that not of yourselves: it is the gift of God: Not of works, lest any man should boast” (Eph. 2:8–9). This immediately tells us, like many other New Testament passages also affirm that we are not saved by our good deeds. Rather, we are saved by the grace of God, through faith, that is, the grace of God gives us the faith needed to accept the Lord Jesus Christ and be saved. That is why He said it is the gift of God. The word “gift” is the Greek doron which literally means “a present.” Salvation is a gift or present from God, which God in His own sovereign freewill chose to give to His people. After Paul had preached the Gospel to the people of Antioch Pisidia, God’s Word says, “as many as were ordained to eternal life believed” (Acts 13:48). Not everybody believed, only those who were ordained to eternal life. The word “ordained” is the Greek tasso which means “to assign to a certain position or lot.” In other words, it was pure grace to believe in the Lord Jesus Christ unto life eternal. Of a truth as the Lord Jesus has said that no man can come to Him except it were given by God the Father (John 6:65).', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(298, 83, 'Grace also comes with instructions of what we must do. We understand that we are saved by grace not by works (Eph. 2:8–9) and that “we are his workmanship, created in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus unto good works, which God has before ordained that we should walk in them” (Eph. 2:10). In other words, we are saved by God’s grace and not by works, but that same grace of God empowers us to do good works, which is one reason He “created” us in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus, in the first place. Therefore, obeying His commandments is necessary, but our obedience flows from His grace and not from carnal effort. Just as Paul said that he was who he was by the grace of God (1 Cor. 15:10). And this grace empowered and enabled him to do what he did in the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(299, 83, 'The grace of God is not a pass for people to live any type of life by reasoning that the Lord Jesus Christ has paid it all. Be aware of the demonic teaching today on hyper-grace and the erroneous doctrine of OSAS (once saved always saved). Do not be carried away when these teachers quote so many Scriptures with many Greek analogies that are contrary to the simplicity of the Lord Jesus Christ. This is the same issue that Jude was talking about in his short epistle, when he raised a red flag that many were “turning the grace of our God into lasciviousness”; they thought they could use the Good News of the Lord Jesus Christ’s grace as a reason to live sinful lives, but in the process they were really “denying the only Lord God, and our Lord Jesus Christ” (Jude 1:4). Paul showed us that justification through the Lord Jesus Christ does not make us free to sin, since the Lord Jesus Christ is not the minister of sin (Gal. 2:17). Paul showed us how he himself was “crucified” with the Lord Jesus Christ, who was the one who lived in him and through him (Gal. 2:20). Paul topped it up by saying, “I do not frustrate the grace of God: for if righteousness come by the law, then Christ is dead in vain” (Gal. 2:21). So he was not saved by works; nevertheless, he himself (the old man) was crucified, and the Lord Jesus Christ, the Righteous One lived through him. This is what Grace does for the believer and not a license to live with a mind-set that every yesterday, today, and tomorrow’s sins have been forgiven and thus can live anyhow. The grace of God does not only bring salvation, but by God’s grace, we ought to deny ungodliness and worldly lusts and live soberly, righteously, and godly in this present world.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(300, 83, 'This is how Timothy needed to be strong in the grace, which is in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus, who enables us to live successfully and acceptably unto God. Without God’s grace there is no salvation and without salvation, we cannot be useful to God. Grace is the ultimate enabler of reasonable service.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(301, 84, 'Timothy was a young man who was brought up by his mother and grandmother who taught him the Scriptures of God (2 Tim. 1:5, 3:15). He indeed had a great foundation but oftentimes it becomes clear that as we journey along the way, we need more strength at all times to face the demands of each phase of our lives. Blessed be God for the success of a man’s life on campus  but as he transits into marriage, there is a need for another strengthening to fortify one’s path in God.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(302, 84, 'We need strength in the present world for life and ministry after we are saved by the grace of God through the Lord Jesus Christ. One major way we derive this is from the grace that God has given us to understand and apply His Word in our daily lives. God knew that Joshua would need strength to fulfil his mission and ministry after Moses died. His most important instruction to Joshua was: “This book of the law shall not depart out of thy mouth; but thou shalt meditate therein day and night, that thou mayest observe to do according to all that is written therein: for then thou shalt make thy way prosperous, and thou shalt have good success” (Josh. 1:8). This is one of the most fundamental and extremely critical means by which we derive the strength we need to carry out our assignment and expand God’s kingdom on earth.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(303, 84, 'Timothy needed this since childhood (2 Tim. 3:15) and continued to need it throughout his work in the Gospel mission. Our quest for God’s strength in our race must be continuous and progressive. We need the inner strength to face the reality of the demand of the world we are sent to and to maintain our spiritual momentum at all times.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(304, 84, '<h3>Week 30 ends here and Week 31 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(305, 85, 'Paul was a servant of the Lord Jesus Christ who had been through his share of ups and downs in this life. The Lord Jesus said that this would be so (Acts 9:16). His service to God was one that brought all kinds of tribulation and challenges for him, as shown in a summary of his suffering (2 Cor. 11:23–29). As if this was not enough, God allowed him to live with a “thorn in the flesh” (2 Cor. 12:7). Many have speculated about what this “thorn in the flesh” was. Maybe it was a kind of physical ailment, or it could have been something else entirely. Whatever it was, he asked the Lord on three different occasions to relieve him of this problem (2 Cor. 12:8). God’s profound reply was, “My grace is sufficient for thee: for my strength is made perfect in weakness” (2 Cor. 12:9). Paul understood this statement and, therefore, concluded by saying, “when I am weak, then am I strong” (2 Cor. 12:10). It is reminiscent of the Scripture that says, “let the weak say, I am strong” (Joel 3:10).', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(306, 85, 'God’s grace is always ever sufficient for us. None of us has ever gone through anything close to what Paul had to endure. Human being can only take so much pain to a degree. But God’s grace gives us sufficient strength to go through anything. At the beginning of that same epistle (2 Cor 1:8-9), Paul said that they were pressed out of measure, above strength, insomuch that they despaired even of life. “Above strength” means they did not even have the energy to handle the pressure anymore: so they “despaired even of life,” that is, they were ready to quit and die. But they did not quit for one single reason: they stopped trusting in themselves and looked to God who is the raiser of the dead (2 Cor. 1:9). This is the meaning of “my grace is sufficient for you” and “my strength is made perfect in weakness.” This is exactly what Timothy needed for his own tribulations, as Paul could speak from experience when he said, “My son, be strong in the grace that is in Christ Jesus” (2 Tim. 2:1).  ', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(307, 85, 'In our Christian journey of reasonable service, we might be faced with many challenges and obstacles, and sometimes not even know what else to do to move forward. But if we stop looking to our own strength and begin to look up to God for His grace, then we will see that truly His grace is indeed more than enough to get us through. His strength is perfected in our weakness, so we ourselves cannot take the glory or credit, but must confess that if not for the Lord, we never would have made it just like the popular song says.', '2018-02-19 17:21:22'),
(308, 86, 'Now that we have received God’s Word, a responsibility has been placed on us to communicate that same truth to others also. The word “commit” in our text is the Greek paratithemi which means ‘to deposit something as a trust or for protection’. It means you place the thing (God’s Word) into the hands (or heart) of another person with expectation of the receiver doing the right thing with it. This should be the basic benchmark of what discipleship should be. It is, of course, not just inviting people to a church or fellowship to count as statistics but to labour in ways that can deposit all the investments of the Lord Jesus Christ in someone’s life, that is, investment of the word, spirit, discipline, fruits of the Spirit, good works, eternity, heavenly consciousness, and so forth.', '2018-02-19 17:26:31'),
(309, 86, 'The discipleship and the continued passing of the Gospel truth is similar to a relay race, where one runner hands the baton to another, who, in turn, hands it to another, until the race is finally completed. Paul was in a Roman cell facing execution (2 Tim. 4:6–7) and was handing the baton to Timothy, who was mandated to hand it to others. The faithfulness of such men down the historical timeline is the reason we are here today with God’s Word readily available for our use and benefit. However, we have not been given the baton to hold and keep to ourselves, but must pass it down to our fellow men and women. We must also pass it in the same manner as it was given to us. We cannot reduce the size of the baton to make the process of exchange faster. We cannot watch the baton reduce to the size of an ordinary pin because we are now in the technology “instant noodle” generation of unbaked Christians, who are products of spiritual kwashiorkor (overeaten of Christian messages that are based on a single truth, such as material prosperity, hypergrace or demonology). We cannot reduce the essence of the baton because it is now an “old baton” that does not look like our desired modernity. We are called to handle the baton in the size and shape as it was handed down to us—we are not to compromise the standard of God or blend it to serve the worldly pressures of our time. We must consciously entrust the Gospel message and doctrine to others: leaders must transfer to people they disciple, excos to next generation of excos, husbands to their wives and children, and every Christian in general to whomever God connects us with. This is how we preserve the legacy of the body of the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-19 17:26:31'),
(310, 86, '<h3>Week 32 ends here and Week 33 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-19 17:26:31'),
(311, 87, 'The demand for effective baton exchange was also specific. The mandate has to be given to people who met certain criteria. It is not an all-comers affair. The word “able” as used by Paul in our text is the Greek hikanos which means “COMPETENT.” An effective baton handler, whose aim is to make people disciples for the Lord Jesus Christ, must be competent. He must be adequate for the purpose, well equipped, sufficiently qualified, capable, and efficient. We can only give what we have in abundance. Men who are great baton exchangers are well trained to exchange batons under any circumstances—whether it is 100m or 400m race—they are well groomed, hence they can pass the baton well.', '2018-02-19 17:26:31'),
(312, 87, 'This is one of the reasons Paul told Timothy, “Study to shew thyself approved unto God, a workman that needeth not be ashamed, rightly dividing the word of truth” (2 Tim. 2:15). To be genuinely competent, able, and qualified to impart and commit Biblical truth to others, we have to be  “faithful” men and women. We must be well grounded and with solid foundation. We must also prepare for every opportunity and platform that God provides to pass on the baton. For us, every opportunity to preach, teach, share Bible study outline, facilitate a seminar, coordinate a programme, plan an outreach, lead a prayer, share announcements, and so forth is another opportunity to pass the baton of excellence, where someone can look up to that simple task and be inspired to raise the game in their little corner because a path of excellence has been deposited, albeit unconsciously. TACEF is praying for high-quality brothers and sisters, who are so well prepared for every opportunity given to them to provoke godly revival, hunger for God, and an accompanying passion for excellence by reasons of how the assignment has been done for the Lord. We are tired of men who weaken standards and use divine platforms unprepared and with no sense of “What will I use this short moment to deposit in my hearers and observers?”', '2018-02-19 17:26:31'),
(313, 87, 'This competence dimension must also be completed with faithfulness as advocated by Paul. This twin dimension makes reasonable service last a lifetime of impact. The word “faithful” is the Greek pistos which means “trustworthy.” It means that the person is loyal, reliable, dependable, and can be counted on. Someone whom you know will faithfully adhere to the standards required of the platform and will not weaken the opportunity by virtue of unpreparedness or lack of divine inspiration. Faithful men rely on God in prayers and pray through to be sufficiently enabled to occupy the offices they have been called unto.', '2018-02-19 17:26:31'),
(314, 88, 'The phrase “endure hardship” is a Greek word kakopatheo which means to “undergo hardship.” It means that we withstand difficult situations and challenges while looking towards the positive outcome of our determination. The main point that describes a good soldier is that he does not entangle himself with the affairs of this life. The word “entangle” is the Greek empleko which means to “entwine or get involved with.” A soldier at war has no choice but to remain focused on the mission and the reality of his extreme life-or-death conditions. Even when the soldiers are not presently engaged in battle with the enemy but camping out, there is still no time to waste with matters that do not concern the war. He cannot, for example, consider looking for a woman and starting a family. That would only be a major distraction that could end up costing lives. His only concern is the present war and the best strategies for winning battles.', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(315, 88, 'For a Christian, the “affairs of this life” which Paul stated can be compared with the “cares of this world” which the Lord Jesus mentioned (Mark 4:19). In that parable of the sower, the person who received seed among thorns “entangled” himself with those affairs of life, which choked him and rendered him ineffective and unfruitful. We as Christians living in this world cannot afford to get ourselves mixed up in all the things the unsaved are involved in. Most television shows are just distractions and waste of precious time. Many festivals and ceremonies are just unnecessary and may not even concern us, so we do not have to attend all of them. Many associations we try to belong to or activities we do for relevance only waste our precious times and reduce the time we have to focus on what is important. Can you imagine a father who spend all his weekend attending to events and activities, and cannot spare one hour to check his children’s book. What a parent living in delusion of entanglement that is out of purpose! We must remember that we are engaged in warfare against Satan and his demonic host. We cannot afford the entanglements of the ungodly world, but should keep our lives as simple as possible, similar to the good soldier at war whose aim is to please Him who has chosen him to be a soldier. God’s Word warns us against loving this world and getting entwined with the lusts of the flesh, the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life (1 John 2:15–17). A good soldier at war will do the will of his commander, and “he that doeth the will of God abideth for ever” (1 John 2:17). Not only do we win the battles of life if we remain focused, but we also have the eternal reward promised to those who obey the Commander-in-Chief, Jesus Christ, our Lord.', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(316, 89, 'The next analogy is the athlete. The term “strive for masteries” (2 Tim. 2:5) is the Greek athle? which literally means to “contend in the competitive games.” It is from this Greek word we derive our English words ‘athletics’ and ‘athlete’. But the verse says that if a man contends in the competitive games, it is not possible for him to receive the crown of victory unless he competes lawfully. The word “lawfully” is the Greek nomimos which means “according to the rules.” So the athlete must do two major things if he desires to obtain the crown: (a) He must prepare his body and contend, and (b) He must compete according to the rules.', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(317, 89, 'Preparing his body involves real hardship and discipline. To be a reasonable competitor who stands a chance of winning, he cannot prepare by doing a little jogging every other day in his neighbourhood. He must instead discipline his body properly through rigorous exercises that will get his muscles fit for endurance, along with abstinence from foods and drinks that are too fatty or sugary. For us as Christians, this means that we must exercise spiritual discipline through activities like diligent Bible study, prayer, and deep meditation. We must also fast like the athlete by abstaining not only from too much food, but also from sin and ungodliness. We cannot clog our spiritual system with weights that reduce our ability to run the race with grace.', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(318, 89, 'In addition, the athlete cannot be crowned unless he strives lawfully, that is, according to the established rules. Disobeying the rules in any sporting competition gets us penalised, in accordance to the degree of the violation. We also as Christians must compete according to the rules of God’s Word, as disobeying God’s Word means we are penalised and cut off  from receiving God’s blessing (see Col. 3:25, Deut. 28:15). For example, we cannot be dishonest in business dealings and expect God to bless our business. We cannot cheat on our spouse and expect our marriage to be blessed. We cannot come to minister unprepared and expect God to be happy with us. We cannot spend our tithe and expect the windows of heaven to open for us. We cannot be lazy at work and expect God to grant our request for promotions—see what happens to those who have been diligent, even though they are unbelievers. God is not partial and He does not reward slothful behaviours. We cannot seek for long life and fail in basic hygienic and healthy living. We cannot treat our parents anyhow and expect our own children to treat us like a king or queen; there are rules to every game (parenting, business, ministry, service, employment, discipleship etc.). The bottom line is that we must play by the rules—God’s rules!', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(319, 89, 'To obtain the crown, we must learn every rule that governs getting the right result and commit to the path of consistent discipline, enduring the rigours of self-denial, sacrifice, and strict self-restraint.', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(320, 89, '<h3>Week 34 ends here and Week 35 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(321, 90, 'Verse 6 of our text speaks of the “husbandman.” This is an Old English word derived from the Greek georgos, which means a farmer. First of all, Paul said that the farmer must labour. The word “labour” here is the Greek kopiao which does not just mean to work, but to “work hard and feel fatigue.” It means that the farmer works to the point of physical exhaustion. He works himself, in season and out of season until breaking point. During this time, there was no farming machinery as we have today, hence the farmer had to labour to get the ground tilled, prepare the land, sow his seeds, manage the weeds, ensure consistent watering, and so forth. After this, a different kind of work comes next—which is the work of exercising great patience while the crops grow. God’s Word exhorts us to be patient in our waiting on the Lord’s return (James 5:7). He compared our needed patience to that of the farmer who has no choice but to wait for the early and latter rain, before the precious fruit finally comes. So the Christian has to not only sow good seeds through practical righteousness, since a man reaps whatever he sows (Gal. 6:7), but he must also learn to be patient in receiving the fruit of his labour now in this time, and finally, when the Lord returns. Similarly, a farmer gets surprises with unfortunate events such as farm fire, pest infection, and farm destruction by animals; a Christian who suffers unfavourable, unexpected events in this world for doing what is right must still continue to sow his good seeds and not get discouraged (1 Pet. 2:19-20). God’s Word says, “Let us not be weary in well doing, for in due season we shall reap if we faint not” (Gal. 6:9). Patience through the waiting period when our seed appears buried in the soil is very critical because we know that the seed is not buried but planted and at the right time, it will yield its fruit.', '2018-02-19 17:32:48'),
(322, 91, 'One of our greatest sources of encouragement is the suffering and ultimate victory of the Lord Jesus Himself. Paul told us to remember that the Lord Jesus Christ was human, a literal descendant of David. The other apostles, such as Peter and John, walked with Him when he was on the earth, so they knew this very well. But Paul and Timothy (and we also) never saw the Lord Jesus suffer and die. So Paul was reminding Timothy and all other Christians that the Lord Jesus was indeed a flesh-and-blood human being who physically suffered and was crucified on a cross. But He triumphed over death and the grave by His physical resurrection from the dead. The Lord Jesus Himself foretold His disciples about His coming ordeal and final victory. God’s Word tells us to consider that the Lord Jesus was sinless yet He endured suffering at the hands of sinners and we, therefore, should not get tired physically or mentally through our own trials which may sometimes seem unfair (Heb. 12:3). In addition, we also have the promise from God of the resurrection and glorification of our own bodies, the Lord Jesus Himself being the model or prototype and first begotten from the dead (Col. 1:18, Rev. 1:5).', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(323, 91, 'A curious statement that Paul made additionally was that he called this “my” Gospel. Why the personalisation? Well, the Gospel obviously does not “belong” to Paul, though it was revealed to him directly (Gal. 1:11–12). But the bigger point is that the Gospel personally saved him, who was once the “chief of sinners” (1 Tim 1:15–16). If we as Christians want to successfully endure through the hardships and get to the end of the marathon, we must be like Paul and get to a point where the reality is so personal that we consider the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ as “our Gospel.” This degree of making it very personal draws for us strength even when we seem lonely in our journey.', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(324, 92, 'In verse 9 of our text, Paul used the same word he used in verse 3, when he told Timothy to “endure hardship.” Here, he said I “suffer trouble” [Greek kakopatheo], which he used to show Timothy that we all are in the same boat of enduring hardship for the Gospel’s sake. The word “evildoer” is a Greek word kakourgos which means a wrongdoer, but more specifically, a “criminal.” Paul was suffering trouble and enduring hardship as a common criminal would, even being bound with chains. Our Christian lives will sometimes bring trouble, which may not be any fault of ours. In these cases, we must take courage from Paul’s example and from the statement he made next: “The Word of God is not bound” (2 Tim. 2:9).', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(325, 92, 'Even though the minister was bound with chains, it was not possible for the spread of God’s Word to cease. No form of suffering should reduce the efficacy of our ministry. No lack of job should take away our prayer life. No bodily ailment should stop us from getting God’s Word out through other media and channels. Delayed admission to higher institutions must not take our eyes off the mandate of discipling young ones in our local fellowships. Our everyday challenge must not diminish, reduce, or take off the ministry of the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ in our lives. We must not let God’s Word be bound by our circumstances. On the contrary, Paul’s bonds and imprisonment only gave other brethren more boldness to speak even more fearlessly (Phil. 1:12–14), such that more doors were open when he was physically bound. What a life!', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(326, 92, 'We must all endure the hardship of the Gospel together and never let our personal circumstances bound the Word of God and the spread of His kingdom.', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(327, 93, 'From verses 11 to 13 of our text, we find Paul delving into a deeper truth that must be the ultimate guiding light for us as pilgrims of greatness unto reasonable service. We shall explore each sentence.', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(328, 93, 'a)	<b>“For if we be dead with him, we shall also live with him.”</b> To be dead with Christ means to be crucified with Him. It means to be crucified to the flesh and crucified to the world. God’s Word says, “they that are Christ’s have crucified the flesh with the affections and lusts” (Gal. 5:24). The Lord Jesus was a flesh-and-blood human, made in the likeness of sinful flesh (Rom. 8:3), and was tempted in all points as we are, yet without sin (Heb. 4:15). He had to crucify the flesh, and He now asks us to take up our cross and do the same (Luke 9:23), to live in holiness and righteousness before Him, all the days of our lives (Luke 1:75). ', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(329, 93, 'b)	<b>Being dead with him also requires us to be dead to the world, and the world dead to us.</b> God’s Word says, “God forbid that I should glory, save in the cross of our Lord Jesus Christ; by whom the world is crucified unto me, and I unto the world” (Gal. 6:14). This does not mean that we become useless or ineffective in the world, but is rather speaking about what John said that we must crucify the lust of the flesh along with the lust of the eyes and the “pride of life” (1 John 2:15–17). Being dead with the Lord Jesus Christ means being dead to the ungodliness that this world is filled up with, which is not of the Father. ', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(330, 93, 'c)	<b>“If we suffer, we shall also reign with him.”</b> The Lord Jesus suffered so much even before His arrest and eventual crucifixion, including being rejected by His own brothers and His own townspeople (Matt. 13:55–58, John 1:11, 7:5). A Christian today must be willing to identify with the sufferings of the Lord Jesus Christ, if we want to also reign with Him. No amount of rejection or persecution should stop us from enduring hardship now to obtain the crown later. Sacrificial obedience leads to victory, which begins now in this present time and flows on into eternity.', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(331, 93, 'd)	<b>“If we deny him, he also will deny us.”</b> The Lord Jesus Himself clearly made this statement (Matt. 10:33). To deny the Lord Jesus is the opposite of confessing Him, especially when under pressure or threatened with death for our faith. Sometimes, we deny the Lord Jesus Christ to avoid being ridiculed by our friends and neighbours—we hide our relationship with the Lord Jesus. If the Lord Jesus means all to you, then you must take pride in that relationship and be willing to live without being ashamed. If He openly died for us on the cross, why should we want to secretly serve the Lord Jesus where no one will know that we belong to Him? The Lord Jesus cannot be a spare tyre in the journey of our lives, He is either the most important or He is not there at all. If our lives were worth the trouble He went through, why should we avoid being identified with the blessings that comes with this shame of identification?', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(332, 93, 'e)	<b>“If we believe not, yet he abideth faithful: he cannot deny himself.”</b> If we believe not, that is, if we fall into unbelief, backsliding, and sin, God will remain faithful and cannot deny Himself. He remains God no matter the situation. Our challenges do not limit Him from being God. The fact that our desired miracles have not come does not change His nature as a caring and good Father. His personality is never defined by the situations we have found ourselves or will ever go through. This statement also captures the consistency of God\'s character. Even when we are weak, in the face of trials, testing, tribulations that we pass through, we can be sure of the fact that : God is faithful, and He cannot deny Himself. He will somehow sort us out unto His own honour.', '2018-02-19 17:42:20'),
(333, 94, 'To know a counterfeit, you must first possess good knowledge of the genuine. A fake or counterfeit Naira note, handbag, designer’s shirt, or almost anything else, can only be identified as fake if the observer already knows what the real one looks like in detail. If we do not know the original so well, there is no way we will be able to compare and spot the errors. The same applies to God’s Word. The only way a Christian can spot false teachers and false teachings is by being conversant with the Bible and knowing what God has said. We have the anointing of His Spirit to guide us into all truth (John 16:13), and our job is to cooperate with Him by doing what Paul instructs Timothy to do in verse 15 of our text.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(334, 94, 'We cannot offer reasonable service without being able to rightly divide the Word of Truth. To divide the words means we know the boundaries of application of every Word of God and can properly situate and divide what is old truth (Old Testament) that are not applicable in the New Testament and the Old Testament instructions that remain relevant even in the New Testament. Can you imagine when someone builds a revelation around Moses removing his shoes by Mount Sinai as basis for people not to wear their shoes, or someone arguing that tithe was only mentioned in the Old Testament and thus not applicable in the New Testament, or a prophet who curses on slightest provocation on an excuse that Elisha cursed some little kids? These three types of errors require a proper “division” of the Word of God. Hence, Paul advised that first of all, the word “study” is a Greek word spoudazo which means to be diligent, earnest, or zealous. It means to have a sense of urgency and passion for in-depth analysis. It is not studying by face value but being diligent at mastery of the Word of God with good understanding of application and relevance. So we must be passionate and desirous to show (i.e., “present”) ourselves approved unto God. We ultimately want to know God’s mind as revealed in His Word and, therefore, must be zealous and diligent to obtain His approval. The phrase “rightly dividing” is the Greek word orthotomeo which literally means “to make a straight cut or path,” so that a traveller, for example, may go directly to his destination. God’s Word is both simple and complex (but not complicated) and, therefore, should be easy to dissect for the honest reader. We should be able to go directly from point A to point B, by “comparing spiritual things with spiritual” (1 Cor. 2:13), that is, we weigh different passages of Scripture with each other to come to the right conclusions. A good user of the Word of God is a man or woman who knows how to make “a straight cut” of the word by pushing through a single line of Biblical message woven around the title and supported by other references, and not a preacher who is here, there, and everywhere and at the end of the day has gone nowhere. It is frustrating to listeners when they ask themselves after a massage, “What was this preacher saying” because he used so many applications that cannot be linked back to the theme or title.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(335, 94, 'It is so sad today to see  preachers making  blunders on the podium because they have not prepared in the place of studying God’s Word. They asked you to go to a verse, which is completely unrelated to what they are talking about, not out of genuine mistake, but out of lack of thorough preparation. No wonder the Bible says we must study so that we are not ashamed. It is a shameful misplacement of grace for a man to be called to minister and such has not spent hours of studying and meditation to zealously grasp the depth of truth behind the message. Please do not be like those unserious leaders who prepare their message in the vehicle few minutes before their ministration or those who fail to prayerfully digest and decode the “rhema” before they speak on behalf of a God that they have not stayed long with in the place of prayers. Of course, God can change our message on the road, even though we have well prepared but this must not turn us to lazy ministers of God’s Word.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(336, 94, 'Inappropriate preparation in the place of studying God’s Word leads to inappropriate impact in the lives of the listeners. In the same vein, wrong teaching leads to wrong thinking and wrong living, which neither glorifies God nor advances the course of the Gospel.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(337, 95, 'Our study text (2 Tim. 2:14, 16–18) shows us some particular dangers that can arise from getting into arguments with people who do not know God or understand His Word. We who know Him and have been taught by His Spirit are to take heed of Paul’s warnings. Verse 14 says we should “strive not about words to no profit, but to the subverting of the hearers.” There is a double loss or danger here for the believer who gets into debates with others.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(338, 95, 'a)	<b>Ultimately “to no profit.”</b> It is a huge waste of precious time and energy to go back-and-forth with a person or persons who have already made up their mind to believe what they have chosen to believe. Many people have heard false doctrines that were extremely appealing to them, and you cannot change their minds no matter how much you point to Scriptures that speak against what they have accepted as truth. The right thing to do is intercede to God on their behalf with expectation that He will open their eyes. It has been proven from the testimonies of many Muslims or even Jehovah’s Witnesses who met the Lord Jesus that argument do not change people, it is rather better to pray for those individuals for the light of God to illuminate their eyes with the truth.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(339, 95, 'b)	<b>“Subverts” the hearers.<b> The hearers could be fellow Christians who are newly converted and not strongly rooted yet, or other bystanders who are just listening to the debate. Arguing about God’s Word with a contrary person will only bring confusion to the ears and minds of the hearers, which ends up subverting them. The word “subverting” is the Greek word katastrophe which literally means an overturning or catastrophe like an earthquake or any natural disaster! It may even put a new believer into a state where he is not sure whether to believe the Bible anymore.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(340, 95, 'The next verse stresses that the words of such people “will eat as doth a canker” (2 Tim. 2:17). This phrase in the Greek language means that their words will “spread like gangrene or cancer.” Gangrene is dead tissue in a portion of the skin due to infection or cessation of blood supply. It continues to spread on its own if left untreated. Paul was showing how false teachings, which may be appealing to the flesh, could easily spread quickly and become a form of destructive, dangerous cancer. In this text, Paul named two people: Philetus, who is not mentioned anywhere else in the Bible, and Hymenaeus, who was spoken of in the first epistle to Timothy and already identified by Paul as a blasphemer (1 Tim. 1:20). Paul said that they erred from the truth, that is, they have gone away from the Lord (2 Tim. 2:17). They were probably spreading many erroneous doctrines, but one in particular was the false teaching that the resurrection had already happened. They were saying that rapture had already taken place and there was no reason to look forward to another. Of course, a teaching like this will make Christians live a careless life with no hope of something worth living for in holiness and in honour.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(341, 95, '<h3>Week 37 ends here and Week 38 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(342, 96, 'In the midst of all the confusion and contradictory teachings in our world today, there are still people who belong to the Lord in the midst of all deceptions and will continue to abide in the truth. Verse 19 of our text says that regardless of what anybody teaches or believes, the foundation of God remains steadfast. A “seal” is the Greek word sphragis which means “an official stamp.” This seal or official stamp was used in Paul’s time to verify the authenticity of the origin of a letter sent from an important individual, like a king or governor. Many impostors wrote letters using the names of important and well-known individuals, and many fake “Gospels” and “epistles” were written by fraudsters who used some of the apostles’ names, with the intent of spreading false teaching as apostolic truth. But a seal, especially from a king or governor, was imitation-proof and a letter sealed with such a stamp ensured the recipient that this document actually came from the said authority.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(343, 96, 'God also uses seals, as seen in Rev 5:1. And verse 19 of our text mentions two identifying marks of the seal of God’s sure foundation: (a) “The Lord knoweth them that are his”: This is the ultimate seal that separates His own from the impostors. This is because salvation originates from God Himself, and He knows the fake from original (b) “Let every one that nameth the name of Christ depart from iniquity”: People who belong to the Lord are proven and confirmed by their lifestyle, which is to depart from iniquity. People who live in iniquity are a fraud. They have no logo or image or the seal of the Lord and are therefore counterfeits.', '2018-02-19 20:13:38'),
(344, 97, 'Paul, in verse 20, used a simple depiction to portray two different situations in which two people can come into agreement with. The first observation from the text is that there is “a great house.” The vessels of silver and gold in such a house are used for honourable purposes such as a banquet with important guests. The wooden and earthen vessels are far less honourable and may be used for keeping less important things and for less important occasions—plus they are easily broken and easily replaced.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(345, 97, 'When entering a home, a vase of flowers greets you at the door. It is set there to bring colour and honour to the house. In the kitchen, however, a completely opposite vessel stores the trash. It is of value, but in a different manner. In the same vein, a cup can be used at a dinner and a variant of it can be used in a toilet—same cup but different purposes. One unto honour and the other unto dishonour.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(346, 97, 'The great house represents the kingdom of God while the vessels describe the different types of people in God\'s kingdom. The word honour is also translated as noble, which can be used to describe rank or title; but in this instance, it is more appropriately used to describe an exalted moral or excellent character. The word dishonour can be translated as ignoble, a word that simply means inferior, base, or of low character. So, one example describes a person of maturity, the other describes a person of less development. It is clear enough to say that each of us have a role to play in what we become in the great house. The degree to which we commit ourselves to the path of reasonable service will determine how far the law of greatness will find expression in our lives and this will determine the level of honour or dishonour that our lives will enjoy. Hence, Paul’s position that we just “purge” ourselves because the Master only uses honourable vessels.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(347, 97, 'This verse also speaks of the choice we must make to become a person of value with God. Honour is available, and so is dishonour. Same for light and darkness, right and wrong, love and hatred, humility and pride, wisdom and folly, kindness and wickedness, positive and negative, and so forth. In other words, two powers co-exist and are readily accessible to man, and we have the willpower to choose the right path by the process of purging ourselves.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(348, 98, 'There is no doubt that man is responsible for his own choices and decisions. Righteousness leads to honour with God while unrighteousness leads to dishonour and destruction. So, Paul, in verse 21 of our text, said, “If a man therefore purge himself.” This means that the responsibility lies with us. If we want to be vessels unto honour, we must purge ourselves from iniquity, which those who name the name of the Lord Jesus Christ must depart from.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(349, 98, 'If we purge ourselves, we will be “sanctified,” That is a Greek word hagiazo which means to be purified, and it is twofold. First, we are sanctified by the sacrifice of the Lord Jesus Christ (1 Cor. 1:30, Heb. 10:10). However, we need practical and continuous sanctification by cooperating with the Holy Spirit to work in us the process of purification, as we crucify the flesh (1 Thess. 4:3–7, 1 Pet. 1:2). This is the only way for a Christian to be a vessel meet for the Master’s use. A dirty spoon or plate previously used by someone else will be unacceptable, unless it is first washed and cleansed. Or how many of us will not make effort to cleanse ourselves every morning, even when we have had a most thorough bath the previous night? So is it also with God. He will not use us if we do not continually cleanse ourselves from all filthiness of the flesh and spirit (2 Cor. 7:1). Our reasonable service totally depends on this because God has already done His part by sending His Son Jesus, and putting His Spirit within us. It is now our responsibility to purge ourselves if we want to be greatly used by the Lord.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(350, 99, 'The major way in which we cooperate with the Holy Spirit in the process of sanctification involves two dimensions: We must consciously flee from sin and we must also pursue godliness. Fleeing from them is the first step to our preparation for the Master’s use.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(351, 99, 'The “lusts” which we are told to flee from is the Greek epithumia which can be a general desire or longing, but more specifically for something forbidden. They also pertain more to the younger adults than the elderly. This lust includes all forms of immoralities such as pornography, flirting on social media, and masturbation, among others.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(352, 99, 'In addition, we must actively follow righteousness, faith, charity, and peace, which can be grouped together under the umbrella of godliness. The word “follow” is the Greek diõkõ which means to pursue something or someone. It means going after something vigorously, and is the same word used (to mean, “persecute”) in many places in the New Testament. This, therefore, underscores the fervency, energy, and passion with which we must run after the things of God. Following godliness cannot be passive, but requires our zealous pursuit of God’s will with a determination to obey. The Lord Jesus has said, “Blessed are they that hunger and thirst after righteousness, for they shall be filled” (Matt. 5:6). We must be hungry and thirsty for righteousness to be filled with it. We must be determined to press on towards the ultimate in godliness.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(353, 99, 'Also, Paul said we are to pursue godliness “with them that call on the Lord out of a pure heart.” This means we are to pursue this endeavour with other Christians who are already moving in that direction, whose hearts and motives are pure before God. This speaks of the right kind of people whose lives can provoke us on the journey, as we are to provoke one another unto love and to good works (Heb. 10:24). Proverbs 27:17 also tells us that iron sharpens iron, so those who are seeking the same pursuit of godliness will naturally encourage and strengthen one another. It will be a disaster when we surround ourselves with people who do not have the same spiritual pursuit as ours. It is a misadventure if our best friend today is not our prayer partner or spiritual catalyst. When a firebrand Christian has unbelievers or cold Christians as best friends, he must be sure that their influence will one day weaken his pursuit of God. They will complain that we are becoming too “churchy” and of course, the weight of the temptation can push some back. Let us be careful of who we associate with because they determine how far we can go in God.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(354, 99, 'As we diligently depart from sin and go after godliness, we will become sanctified vessels of honour, and be ready to be used by the Lord as He sees fit. A vessel that is already clean is presently meet for the use of the owner because it has undergone the process of being washed and cleansed. If we are still harbouring sin, it will be difficult to be used by the Lord to minister to others. May we purge ourselves from these, and be vessels who will offer reasonable service to our Lord and Saviour.', '2018-02-19 20:22:04'),
(355, 100, 'Some issues concerning doctrine and theology are not worth getting involved in, if the other person is just determined to argue and debate. Paul said we should avoid “foolish and unlearned questions” (2 Tim. 2:23). The phrase in the original language is “stupid and ignorant disputes.” It represents a situation where the person is ill-informed and negatively poised about the topic, similar to those who desire “to be teachers of the law; understanding neither what they say, nor whereof they affirm” (1 Tim. 1:7). Paul said we should avoid these kinds of people since they already believe they are right and are willing to get into heated debates to prove their position. Can you imagine spending three days arguing with a man who believes there is no hell when that time could have been used to pray for the same person for divine revelation? When we spend so much effort on proving our points, as if God cannot on His own accord open their eyes, we mistakenly engender strifes. “Engender” here is the Greek gennao which means to procreate or beget, like a parent giving birth to a child. So foolish and unlearned questions will most likely give birth to “strifes” [mache = battle or controversy]. The next verse tells us that the servant of the Lord must not strive. A man of God must never be caught in the provocation that hot debate can trigger. It diminishes the goodness of the Good News we are trying to justify, as if God Himself is not sufficient to justify the truth.', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(356, 100, 'However, certain people genuinely need to be properly informed—especially those who are obviously confused and require clarification without any intent to engender debate. This is why subsequent verses use words like “apt to teach” and “instructing.” It says we should teach and instruct “those that oppose themselves.” What kinds of people are those? The phrase in the original Greek means people who debate with their own selves; probably from listening to many different doctrines and cannot come to a certain conclusion about what is actually true. They end up favouring a particular doctrine above the others but remain deluded, spiritually and mentally being held captive in Satan’s snare. It is the will of God for us to gently guide such people to the truth, as He has revealed in His Word. ', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(357, 100, 'This responsibility requires us to be “apt to teach.” The word “apt” speaks to a state of readiness in meeting demands of some special situation or emergency. It is as if we have the right tool for the right hour and not searching for Scripture when needed most. The sense of urgency of this Word can be understood better in its military application as \"apt for war\" (2 Kings 24:16). A man or woman who wants to stay long in the act of reasonable service must be well preloaded with appropriate Scripture for every situation. This speaks to being consistent in our personal study altar which equips us to meet all emergency ministry need in the use of the Word to instruct, guide, and correct errors.', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(358, 100, 'Like Boys Scout motto, always “be prepared”!', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(359, 101, 'For us to even have a chance at successfully bringing those who oppose themselves to the acknowledging and accepting of the truth, following are few character traits which Paul said we must adopt and exercise:', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(360, 101, 'a)	<b>Non-quarrelsome.</b> The first thing we are to remember is that the servant of the Lord must not strive (2 Tim. 2:24). The word “strive” is the Greek machomai which means to war or “quarrel.” It means we must not have a mind that is over-determined to prove its point even if it leads into physical exchange of blows. This is not the method of the Spirit in our endeavour to correct the confused person. Paul continually warned Timothy in both epistles to avoid quarrels and debates because he knew they would not help anybody. In fact in, he said striving about words is not only unprofitable but also subverts the hearers (2 Tim. 2:14), leaving them in a worse state than they previously were. ', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(361, 101, 'b)	<b>Gentle.</b> Paul then said that the servant of the Lord must be “gentle” unto all men. This is a Greek word epios which means “mild” or “kind.” It means that God’s servant is not harsh in his treatment of others, especially those who need guidance into God’s truth. If we are not gentle when we minister to others, how do they believe the genuine simplicity of the Lord Jesus? We must remember we are trying to help another human being, not a show off of knowledge or status.', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(362, 101, 'c)	<b>Patient.</b> this is a Greek word anexikakos that means “enduring of ill” or “forbearing.” When a servant of the Lord is in the process of correcting another person, he may begin to get annoyed or find fault. We must take it patiently, forbearing and enduring the unfriendliness, as long as we still see there is hope to win the person and they have not rejected us or our assistance with clear hostility. We must be patient for as long as necessary, because our desire is to see the person freed from the deception of the devil and embrace the truth of God.', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(363, 102, 'After we have played our part and done everything we are meant to do, Paul said that “if God peradventure will give them repentance to the acknowledging of the truth” (2 Tim. 2:25). This tells us that God is the One who has the final say as to whether a person’s eyes will be opened to see and accept His truth or not. The word “peradventure” in the original language is mepote which means “perhaps,” indicating that the event may take place or it may not. “Give” is didomi and literally means “give.” So God may give repentance and acceptance of truth, or He may withhold it for reasons He knows best. It is sad to assume the role of the assistant Holy Spirit who can change a person and thus dissipate so much energy in the flesh as a way to correct or lead someone to the way of the Lord.', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(364, 102, 'God is the only One who grants repentance, which will thereby help the individuals to “recover themselves” out of Satan’s snare. To recover self in the original Greek is the word ananepho and it means to “regain one’s senses.” The devil’s “snare” is a Greek word pagis which means a trap, a trick or a strategy. All these opine that Satan previously had the person’s senses in captivity through his tricks and deceptive strategies. No wonder the Lord Jesus said “ye shall know the truth, and the truth shall make you free” (John 8:32). It is acknowledging the truth that sets a person free from the mental captivity of Satan, who is the father of lies (John 8:44).', '2018-02-19 20:33:38'),
(365, 103, 'Paul, first of all, told Timothy to “know” that perilous times shall come, and though the evils which he listed have been around for most of human history, they are going to become intensified in the last days. The word “perilous” is the Greek chalepos which means “dangerous,” “violent,” or “fierce,” also used to describe the two demon-possessed men in Matthew 8:28, the only other place in the New Testament where the word is used. The Lord Jesus speaking about the end-times has said, “And because iniquity shall abound, the love of many shall wax cold” (Matt. 24:12). The origin of the problem which we see in verses 2–4 of our text is misdirected love. The beginning of the list says that men shall be “lovers of their own selves,” and the end of the list says that they shall be “lovers of pleasures more than lovers of God.” Their love will become misdirected, inverted, or turned upside down. They are lovers of their own selves but do not love their neighbour, and lovers of pleasures but do not love God—a subverting of the two greatest commandments. All the other vices flow from this, including the second one listed as “covetous,” which is the Greek philarguros that means “lover of money.” Love of self and love of pleasures inevitably leads to love of money, because it can buy all the pleasures that the self desires—and is the root of all kinds of evil (1 Tim. 6:10), as our list shows. Some of the other words listed are not so easy to understand, but the clear meaning of the more difficult ones listed are as follows:', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(366, 103, 'a)	<b>Without natural affection.</b> This is a Greek word astorgos which literally means hard-hearted. It means the person is insensitive to other people, especially his own family members. A man who does not care about other people’s pain.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(367, 103, 'b)	<b>Trucebreakers.</b> This is the word aspondos and it represents a person who does not want peace. These people never seek forgiveness when they do wrong and never forgive if someone do them wrong.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(368, 103, 'c)	<b>Incontinent.</b> This is the word akrates which means “without self-control.” The person’s love for self and pleasure causes him to be undisciplined and inconsiderate of others. He just behaves anyhow he pleases at any given time.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(369, 103, 'd)	<b>Heady.</b> This is the word propetes which means a person who arrogantly jumps to conclusions without even having the facts of the matter. He is someone who is selfishly concerned about doing things his own way to get what he wants.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(370, 103, 'There have been people like these since the early years after the Fall of Man (Gen. 3), beginning with Cain, which was why God destroyed the world with the flood after seeing man’s wickedness on earth (Gen. 6:5–8), but only spared Noah and his family. However, the Lord Jesus hinted that in the end-times the people of the world will be “as the days of Noah” (Matt. 24:37–39). He was primarily talking about the nonchalant attitude of “eating and drinking,” but the other things he said previously in that chapter tells us that the wickedness of man will also be similar to how it was in Noah’s day before the flood.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(371, 104, 'If we continue reading our text from verse 4 to verse 5, we can see that Paul was still talking about the same kinds of people in verse 5. They are in the same group. They have a form of godliness but deny the power thereof. That word “form” in the Greek is morphosis, which means an “appearance” or “resemblance”, and it is also where we get our English word ‘morph’, which means to change in form or appearance. To keep it simple, these people have a resemblance of Christianity, but it is a counterfeit that does not agree with the power and truth of the Lord Jesus Christ. They look like original from afar, but when you draw closer, you will see that they are fake products—they are counterfeits! They can speak like Christians or even dress like one, but their innermost lives are full of deadly poison of evils and all forms of immoralities.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(372, 104, 'Paul indicated to Timothy already that this would happen: “Now the Spirit speaketh expressly, that in the latter times some shall depart from the faith, giving heed to seducing spirits and doctrines of devils” (1 Tim. 4:1). These people have departed from the faith because they deny its power, and end up having a “form” of godliness—which is a mixture of Biblical truth with their true nature of wickedness and selfishness. They are not born-again by the Spirit (John 3:5), but only practice empty religion. Paul told us to “turn away” from such.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(373, 104, 'It is interesting that the kind of wickedness we find in our text is very similar to what Paul also mentioned in Romans 1:28–32. Just like the people of the ungodly world, false Christians do not like to retain God in their knowledge (Rom. 1:28), so He gave them over to a reprobate mind, as Paul also showed in verse 8 of our text.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(374, 104, 'They have an outward form of religion but no inward union with the Lord Jesus Christ. They appear in sheep’s clothing of fake humility, dull looks, sisterly or brotherly but the lives they live in secret is a complete negation of the truth of the Lord Jesus Christ. How do we explain a sister who comes as a hard-line Christian with no earring or basic cosmetics in the choir but d just had an abortion during the weekend or a brother who lifts up holy hands in the fellowship and yet has secret association with a cult? These are the dangers of the last days!', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(375, 105, 'Verse 6 of our text tells us that among the counterfeit Christians who have a form of godliness are false teachers who particularly prey on carnal women. Today, many leaders of false Christianity know how to take advantage of weak people with emotional and spiritual needs. We have seen how many ministers abused women sexually, financially, and emotionally because of their simple nature. Most times, as Satan did with Eve, they target women because they are the weaker vessel (1 Pet. 3:7), and are usually more vulnerable than men. Generally, women follow their feelings, while men follow facts. But there is a warning here for all of us, male or female. These men are false teachers who continually seek wisdom but never come to the truth about the Lord Jesus Christ or Biblical reality (2 Tim. 3:7). They, nevertheless, succeed in “creeping into houses” (2 Tim. 3:6) and draw carnal followers away into their congregation. Creeping to houses in our modern days include the digital opportunities they have to bring their heresies to us via our television or mobile phones. It is sad these days when you see pastors step on women or touch certain parts of their bodies in the name of deliverance. May the Lord save His church!', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(376, 105, 'These same “seducers” deceive others and continue to be deceived themselves, as Paul spoke of (1 Tim. 3:13). There are many false versions of Christianity today, whose leaders mix the Bible truth with other “revelations.” They claim to be very “spiritual” with the highest revelation of divine truth. God’s genuine people must turn away from these cults. Their messages are often appealing and arouse spiritual curiosity, which many people naïvely fall prey to. Be careful each time a so-called pastor is stepping out of the Bible boundaries in their type of unbiblical prayers, use of prayer objects (e.g., egg, soap, powder), use of names other than the name of the Lord Jesus, and unnecessary closeness and engagement of one’s body during their so-called deliverance sessions.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(377, 106, 'The truth always wins in the end. After the smoke clears and the dust settles, after the war is over, the truth remains standing while everything else perishes. Verse 8 of our text speaks of two men, Jannes and Jambres. These men were Egyptian magicians who challenged Moses in Pharaoh’s court not long before Israel’s eventual exodus out of Egypt. Their names are not mentioned in the book of Exodus or anywhere else in the Bible, but Paul could have gotten the information from some ancient Jewish writings which Timothy was also familiar with. Do not be deceived to accept someone as a man of God because people are falling under the anointing or because miracles are happening. Magicians are different from God-ordained miracle workers. These men, such as the magicians, imitated God’s miracles which He did through Moses, but only succeeded in doing so for a short while. All power ultimately comes from God.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(378, 106, 'Paul said that the way these men challenged Moses is similar to how false teachers “resist the truth.” They have confidence in their own “truth” and dare to challenge God’s supreme truth about His Son Jesus Christ and the doctrine of His apostles. He also said that they are men of corrupt minds and reprobate concerning the faith. The word “reprobate” in the original Greek is adokimos and it means “unapproved and rejected.” It means they have been tested and found to be impostors, who cannot be useful in any way.', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(379, 106, 'Verse 9 tells us that “they shall proceed no further.” This, however, does not mean that false teachers ceased from peddling false religion in Paul’s day. We know this because he said their folly shall be manifest unto all men. There will always be counterfeit religion until its folly is made manifest when the Lord Jesus descends from the sky and manifest unto all men (Matt. 24:30, Rev. 1:7). Even as Jannes and Jambres were only allowed by God to be imitative impostors for a short season, so will untrue religion be shown to be folly very soon. As the magicians were brought to the point where they had no other option but to confess that “This is the finger of God,” so will every knee bow and every tongue confess one day that “Jesus Christ is Lord,” to the glory of God the Father (Phil. 2:11).', '2018-02-19 20:41:56'),
(380, 107, 'In contrast to those who only had a form of godliness, Paul was a genuine minister of the Lord Jesus Christ and his transparency was well known to his son in the faith. The phrase he used in verse 10, “fully known” is the Greek parakoloutheo which means “to follow near.” Timothy, being Paul’s travel companion, had firsthand experience of the kind of man the apostle was. He did not need anybody to tell him whether Paul was genuine or not because he was a personal witness. The church today needs more leaders of genuine integrity who can live out their lives fearlessly before others, even becoming mentors, role models, and godly examples for fellow Christians. Paul’s life was transparently influential, as his followers could see through him and they were assured that he lived what he preached. What kind of leader are you? Can an ordinary member come to stay with your family for one week and will it be possible for the members to learn godliness, family values, discipleship, excellence, and Kingdom lifestyle? It is painful that many have been turned away from the Lord Jesus Christ when they see transparently into the lives of many Christians!', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(381, 107, 'Timothy was very conversant with Paul’s lifestyle and knew that his doctrine was not erroneous; he observed his mode of living, saw the intent of his heart, witnessed powerful manifestations of his faith, experienced his forbearance, benefitted from his selfless love, and derived encouragement from his patient endurance in trials.', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(382, 107, 'In verse 11, Paul mentioned the persecutions and afflictions he endured. The apostle suffered much in many cities, but he specifically mentioned Antioch (of Pisidia), Iconium, and Lystra—because Timothy was from Lystra and was fully aware when Paul originally brought the Gospel of the Lord Jesus Christ to these three neighbouring cities. We can read about his persecution in Antioch in Acts 13:50, where the envious Jews stirred up people to cause problems and eventually expelled Paul and Barnabas out of their city. So they left and came to Iconium, where both Jews and Gentiles along with their rulers plotted to stone them to death (Acts 14:5–6). But they found out about the conspiracy and fled to Lystra. But the Jews from Antioch and Iconium followed them there and corrupted the people’s minds to stone Paul, then dragged him out of the city after they believed he was dead (Acts 14:19–20). But Paul somehow was still alive and got up again, then continued to preach the Gospel in those same cities even after all this (Acts 14:21-22)! True leadership is a living testimony that followers can touch, feel, and experience—not just a story!', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(383, 107, 'The young Timothy knew Paul’s heart and labour firsthand. That is why Paul was able to write to him and say, “Thou hast fully known my. . .” He knew how Paul worked with passion, commitment, excellence, going the extra mile, zeal, and so forth. What are people learning from our leadership style? Does it inspire or depress people. It becomes depressing when we have a leader who sits on our life and cannot align with our higher aspiration for spiritual, career, marital, or financial growth. It is demoralising when we have a leader who is careless, has I-don’t-care-attitude, lacks discipline, and has relational weakness, poor parenting disposition, bad planning, poor financial management, careless speaking, negative mind-set, poor self-development, and unclear life goals. The followers have two options: reduce to the leader’s level or leave for somewhere else.', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(384, 107, 'For Paul, Timothy saw his genuineness and was greatly influenced by the great apostle. Christian leaders today can learn a few things from this again and again. We must not be hypocrites, but our lives must preach to others and inspire those who look unto us. We must preach and teach the Word faithfully, but people know that actions speak louder than words, so we must practice what we preach and be godly examples for others to follow. The emerging generation are looking for role models (who are living proofs of the Bible) to follow. Today, if our life does not prove the love, excellence, knowledge, glory, lifting, principles, and possibilities of the Lord Jesus Christ, we do not deserve to be followed by others, because leaders must lead with a life that leads in key qualities, which is the ultimate attraction for this emerging generation. May our lives be a magnet that attracts men to the Lord Jesus Christ and not repel them away, in the Lord Jesus’ name. Amen.', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(385, 108, 'Paul was a genuine Christian, as Timothy testified, who endured much persecution. He also mentioned in verse 12 that “All who will live godly in the Lord Jesus Christ Jesus shall suffer persecution.” Persecution comes in different degrees that can range from mocking and rejection to physical violence and death. The worst kind of persecution most of us will face these days is more emotional than physical, and can happen in our workplace, school, neighbourhood, and everywhere else. But many Christians today have to escape death frequently, especially in Muslim countries (including Northern Nigeria) and communist nations like China. Those who are still alive today can say with Paul, “Out of them all the Lord delivered me” (2 Tim. 3:11).', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(386, 108, 'Persecution is part of the package whichever form it comes; therefore, we must pray for one another, that the Lord keep us courageous in any situation we find ourselves. We must never deny our faith, but remain genuine followers of the Lord Jesus Christ till the very end.', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(387, 108, 'On the opposite end of the spectrum from those who live godly in Christ are those “Christians” who only have a form of godliness, but deny the power thereof. Paul called them evil men and seducers (2 Tim. 3:13). The word “seducers” is the Greek go?s, which means an “impostor,” someone who makes deceitful pretences. He is essentially an actor showing himself to be someone he is really not. We have explained this in our last study like all the actors we see on stage who may act the role of a pastor today and the same actor can act the role of a herbalist in another movie tomorrow. He only becomes a versatile actor by the ability to act different roles – from a madman to a rich man in different movies. Each movie or situation demands different characters that are changing depending on the script. These kinds of “changing actors” in spiritual lifestyle will grow worse in their deception of others and in their own delusions. Stop being an actor in your spiritual journey who acts spiritual when on campus and acts carnal when far away from the brethren!', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(388, 109, 'In verses 14–15 of our text, we find out certain things which Timothy learnt and different sources from which he learnt them. “Knowing of whom thou hast learned them” signifies that we should be sure of where we are learning our Biblical revelations. We cannot buy a new car from a second-hand market and expect it will not knock sooner than expected. Know your source and be sure of its quality!', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(389, 109, 'Verse 15 reveals the other source of Timothy’s education: “From a child thou hast known the holy Scriptures, which are able to make thee wise unto salvation through faith which is in Christ Jesus.” Timothy might have studied the Scriptures on his own, but more likely was guided from an early age by his mother and grandmother (2 Tim. 1:5). Learning from God through His Word and through his people (Paul, Lois, Eunice) is the foundation upon which Paul said Timothy was “assured” of the things which he learnt. This is what Christians should do today also. Our primary source is the Bible, and our secondary source is genuine men and women of God who have many years of reasonable service under their belt.', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(390, 109, 'Paul said that Timothy should “continue” in the things which he learned. That word “continue” is the Greek meno and it means to stay, abide, or remain. It carries a sense of someone or something being consistent. It is the same word that the Lord Jesus used repeatedly in John 15:4, when He was emphasising our need to abide in Him. As we abide, growth comes because the abiding branches of the vine in John 15:4 will grow and then bear fruit, as they remain connected to their source. Spiritual growth and maturity must be our aim.', '2018-02-19 21:00:01'),
(391, 110, 'First, we need to understand what Paul meant when he said “Scripture,” which is the original Greek word graph? and it means “holy writing.” Sometimes it refers to the entire Old Testament (e.g., Luke 24:45, John 10:35). It may also refer to a passage or portion of the Old Testament (Luke 4:21). But it equally refers to the New Testament (1 Tim. 5:18) where Paul quoted Luke 10:7 as a Scripture. And Peter acknowledged Paul’s writings as a Scripture (2 Pet. 3:16). ', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(392, 110, 'Throughout history, many wrote documents and claimed they came from God, but the Holy Spirit has separated the counterfeit for us and faithfully preserved His Word. The 39 books of the Old Testament have been the Jewish canon since the centuries before Christ, and the Lord Jesus also used the same Old Testament, which we have today. The New Testament was written by the apostles of the Lord Jesus Christ, and again, the Holy Spirit has thankfully separated the counterfeit writings of false apostles from the authentic 27 “books.” We have 66 books altogether in the Bible.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(393, 110, 'The phrase “given by inspiration of God” is two Greek words combined together: Theos, which is God, and pneo, which means “breathe out.” The two words as used together is Theopneustos and literally means “breathed out by God.” Paul was telling Timothy and all Christians that the Word of God carries the breath of God. Even though the words of Scripture were penned by human hands, they were under the total control and influence of breath or spirit of God. Peter said that “holy men of God spoke as they were moved by the Holy Spirit” (2 Pet. 1:20–21). Beloved, we can be confident that the Bible is not the words of men, but God through His Spirit is the true Author. If the Creator of the earth and the heavens is a God of truth, then we can trust Him. “The Scriptures are as reliable as God is,” a man of God once said.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(394, 111, 'After affirming the divine origin of Scripture, Paul then gave us four benefits of applying the Bible to our lives:', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(395, 111, 'a)	<b>For doctrine.</b> God’s Words are profitable for doctrine (or teaching). Sound doctrine comes from God, while false doctrine comes from seducing spirits and devils. God is the Source of truth (Ps. 119:160), while the devil is the father of lies (John 8:44). We need doctrinal truths to answer the many questions concerning human existence. Who is the Creator? What is our purpose on this planet? Why so much pain and suffering? What lies after death? Who determines what is right and what is wrong? Many other questions are answered in the Bible through God’s eternal wisdom, including those which have to do with our practical daily lives: How should I treat other people? How should I relate concerning money? How should we raise children? How should we relate with unbelievers? To simplify it, <b>the Bible is the manufacturer’s manual for proper operation of the created product.</b> The doctrines and teachings found therein are for our good; and we will be wise to apply them to our daily lives.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(396, 111, 'b)	<b>For reproof.</b> The word here is the Greek elegchos which means “conviction.” The Bible convicts us and points out our sin. It is like a great floodlight that shines into a dark place to reveal and make manifest everything that is present, whether good or bad. The Bible reveals to us what is really in our heart, which the natural man (“the flesh”) tries to rationalise away, make excuses for, or even explicitly deny. The Bible is also to be used by the minister to lovingly reprove other believers when they are in error.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(397, 111, 'c)	<b>For correction.</b> The word used here is epanorthosis which literally means “straightening up again” or “correction.”  While reproof points out the sin, the Bible also gives us methods and measures by which we correct our thinking, and thus our actions and our lives. It straightens us up again if we begin to drift away from truth or from righteousness.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(398, 111, 'd)	<b>For instruction in righteousness.</b> The word “instruction” which Paul used here is the Greek paideia and it means “education” or “training.” It carries the sense of how parents would train their children so they can grow to become the kind of people they want them to be. God also educates and trains us through His Word so that we can live righteous lives that are pleasing and acceptable to Him. His ultimate standard for righteousness has been revealed in His Son Jesus our Saviour, who was made to be sin for us, that we might be made the righteousness of God in Him (2 Cor. 5:21).', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(399, 112, 'The perfection of the man of God is directly connected with him being “thoroughly furnished unto all good works.” The phrase “thoroughly furnished” is a Greek word exartizo which means to be “fully equipped.” It means something or someone has been enabled to meet all demands—excellent for all assignments. It means we are all-rounder and not cakes that areunturned like Ephraim (Hosea 7:8). This word was used to depict a ship that had previously been ill-equipped for travelling, but because its owner had decked it out with new equipment and gear, the ship had become thoroughly furnished to sail anywhere in the world. This boat has been fully supplied, completely equipped, or thoroughly furnished. Another illustration for this is a soldier at war. In the modern era, depending on his role, he would need to be furnished and equipped with weapons like an assault rifle, ammunition belt, hand grenade, emergency pistol, and dagger for close combat. But we get a spiritual parallel from the ancient Roman soldier, who was thoroughly furnished with the whole armour of God, as Paul illustrated (Eph. 6:10–18). Each item listed is very essential to the soldier’s victory, and each soldier’s victory is very essential to that of the whole army. “Thoroughly furnished” here thus means that every part of this army’s life is protected and no part is exposed to attack.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(400, 112, 'Bring both together, we can infer that being “thoroughly furnished” is to have it all complete in one such that we can exhibit the lives of the Lord Jesus Christ with utmost excellence at 100% mark in all facets of our lives. We can be wonderful children to our parents, gracious student at school, diligent workers at work,  excellent friend in our network, inspiring sibling to our family, excellent project planner for ministry works, prudent financial manager, benevolent giver, time maximiser, and a lifetime enhancers to all those who we mentor, among others. We can become the best in all sphere of life as the breath of the living Word takes His place in our lives unto perfection.', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(401, 112, 'The mandate of reasonable service requires a life that is all-round in grace. If the soldier is not equipped with the shield of faith before engaging the enemy, he has no way to defend himself from flying arrows and may not last long in battle before he is struck dead, even though he has other armour. If he does have everything except the sword of the Spirit, which is God’s Word, then he cannot attack the adversary but will continually be on the defensive, and no battle can be won with such imbalance. The breastplate guards the Christian’s heart from love waxing cold due to abounding iniquity in the ungodly world. The helmet protects the mind from false doctrines and deceptive spirits. The sandals preserve the soldier’s feet from becoming sore during battle, so he remains strong to continue taking the Gospel of peace wherever his feet lead him. Even a seemingly insignificant equipment such as the belt of truth is extremely important since it holds the soldier’s garments together and enables him to freely use the other weapons with agility. Everything must all come together for us to be reasonable vessels in the hands of God because a 0.01% exposure can mess up the whole!', '2018-02-20 11:06:18'),
(402, 113, 'In today’s Christianity, many pastors and ministers indeed preach God’s Word, but not with the right attitude or motive. Some preach sermons that appeal to the carnal desires of their congregation, to keep them coming back and bringing more tithes and offerings. Some establish churches nationwide and only preach with a desire to be famous and well-known. Others are actually in the ministry because they did not get admission on time or other areas of life did not work for them. Others preach for other reasons which do not agree with Scriptural truth. But Paul, in this passage, gave us the most important reason why we should preach God’s Word, \"Jesus is coming back soon to judge the earth, and the Scriptures have been given by God to prepare us through sound doctrine, reproof, correction, and education in righteousness.\" So a preacher must preach with a consciousness of the Lord Jesus Christ’s return. He must impart this same awareness to his audience and show them why it is necessary not just to hear the Word, but also to practically apply it to their daily lives. God’s Word says we must be doers of the Word, and not hearers only; otherwise we are only deceiving ourselves (James 1:22).', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(403, 113, 'Verse 1 of our text says that the Lord Jesus Christ shall judge “the quick and the dead.” The word “quick” is an Old English terminology derived from the Greek \"zao\" which means “alive” or “living.” Those who are alive at the Lord Jesus Christ’s return will be judged, as well as those who are dead by His return. At the rapture, those who are in the Lord Jesus Christ, both living and dead (1 Thess. 4:16–17), will be taken up with Him to receive rewards according to how they have served Him on earth (1 Cor. 3:11–15, 2 Cor. 5:10, Rev. 11:15–18), and after this they will be invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb (Rev. 19:7–9). Those who are not in the Lord Jesus Christ will also be judged at His return. After the marriage supper of the righteous, the Lord and His heavenly army will return to judge those who were left behind on earth (Luke 17:26–30, Rev. 19:11–21). Finally, all the unrighteous, including those who were already dead before the Lord Jesus Christ’s return, will be eternally condemned at the second resurrection (Rev. 20:11–15).', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(404, 113, 'Those of us today who profess to belong to the Lord Jesus Christ must be very careful. This is because the Lord Jesus has said not everyone who calls Him Lord will enter His kingdom (see Matt. 7:21–23). Many will be convinced that they belong to the Lord Jesus Christ, but will be rejected when He returns, just as we read in the parable of the ten virgins (Matt. 25:1–13). All the virgins were waiting for the return of the Bridegroom, which is symbolic for Christians waiting for the Lord Jesus Christ. The five wise ones prepared themselves properly, but the foolish ones were unprepared. At the Lord’s return, those who were ready were received into the marriage, and “the door was shut” (Matt. 25:10). The other virgins prayed to be allowed in, but were denied (Matt. 25:11–13). After the rapture, those Christians who believed that they were all right with the Lord but in reality were unprepared, will be left behind with the unbelievers (Matt. 24:40–42). This is why Paul’s exhortation to Timothy was very critical. We are to preach the Word because the Scriptures are given to prepare us for the Lord Jesus Christ, through sound doctrine, reproof, correction, and instruction in righteousness.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(405, 113, 'We can safely say that one of the most important reasonable services is to preach with a consciousness of the Lord Jesus Christ’s return: to prepare us for the marriage of the Lamb and our eternal cohabitation with the Lord.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(406, 114, 'Many admonitions to Timothy in this portion of the epistle emphasise his need to be consistent in reasonable service and in the fulfilling of his ministry. First, Paul said he must be “instant in season, out of season.” What could this possibly mean? The word “instant” is a Greek word \"ephistemi\" which literally means to “stand upon.” It means to take a firm stand or remain in position, a term borrowed from the military that meant to stay at one’s post. So Paul was charging Timothy (and us) to remain steadfast in our position in the Lord Jesus Christ, to stand firm in our office and in our calling. He also said that this should be done “in season and out of season,” which in Greek root means \"in good times and in bad times.\" As Christians, we are to stand firm in our calling, whether in good times or in bad times, when it is convenient and when it is inconvenient, when there is peace and when there is persecution or tribulation. We are to stay at our post and remain consistent under all circumstances without compromise. Whether things work the way we desire or not, we are under a mandate to stand at our duty post for the Lord.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(407, 114, 'In addition, we must reprove, rebuke, and exhort others with all long-suffering and doctrine. This can only be done properly using God’s written Word. Any preaching that does not help people to build the consciousness of the Lord Jesus Christ\'s return through rebuke or correction is nothing but a comedy show. We must use God’s Word not to entertain or excite but to drive in godliness through reporting, rebuking, and exhortation. This must, however, be built on doctrine and it requires consistency over a long period (long-suffering), as we patiently watch the word grow in the lives of our listeners.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(408, 114, 'In verse 5, Paul also said, “watch thou in all things.” The word “watch” is the Greek nepho and it means to remain sober and careful, to be vigilant and discreet. The enemy attempts to knock us off from our mission on earth, so we must be cautious and not let him succeed in destroying our witness and our ministry. Then Paul said, “endure afflictions,” which is the same as kakopatheo “endure hardship” (2 Tim. 2:3) and “suffer trouble” (2 Tim. 2:9). It means we must continue to persevere through any trials or challenging times. Our service to the Lord must not be hindered due to external difficulties, but we must remain faithful in all things. The next exhortation is to “do the work of an evangelist,” derived from the Greek word euaggelistes which literally means “a preacher of the Good News, that is, the Gospel.” The work of an evangelist is to preach the Gospel to everyone. This could be individual persons or a gathering of people. The historical truth of the Lord Jesus’ death, burial, and resurrection (1 Cor. 15:3–4) must be communicated to others, as this is the power of God unto salvation to those who will believe (Rom. 1:16). Every Christian is an evangelist to one degree or another, though some have been specifically called to that office on a large scale (Eph. 4:11). Finally, Paul said to Timothy and all Christians: “make full proof of thy ministry” (2 Tim. 4:5). The phrase “full proof” is a Greek word plerophoreo which means “to carry out fully” or “accomplish entirely.” It means that we must see to it that we fulfil and thoroughly complete the assignment which God has given us to do for Him on earth. We are called for 100% delivery of the reason why God created and redeemed us.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(409, 114, 'We must endeavour to use everything He has made available to us to continue pressing forward in the successful completion of our calling.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(410, 115, 'We are under obligation to preach the Word, but it is equally important that we hear the Word. In verses 3–4, Paul guaranteed that there would be times when professing Christians will not endure sound doctrine. That word “endure” is the Greek anechomai and it means, “to put up with.” He is saying that many believers will be tired or fed up with the basic truths of the Bible, maybe due to boredom of hearing the same things over and over, or a desire to hear some new exciting stuff.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(411, 115, 'So “after their own lusts shall they heap to themselves teachers, having itching ears”. They will begin to lust (desire) for a “higher” or more exciting spiritual revelation, but instead of seeking God’s face, they will go after teachers who impart something different that arouses curiosity and are completely the opposite of what the Lord Jesus is and represents. This inevitably turns them away from the truth and deludes them into believing fables [mythos = “fiction,” “myth”] (2 Tim. 4:4). The absolute necessity of abiding in Biblical truth cannot be overstated. Many seducing spirits use human vessels to spread doctrines of demons. If we are not careful, we will find ourselves allowing and indulging in such doctrines and erroneous beliefs. One of the most popular of these today is once-saved-always-saved, which argues that a Christian cannot backslide and we do not need to confess our sins and that once we have made a sinner’s prayer, we are completely free to live anyhow!', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(412, 115, 'The Lord Jesus has said that He is the vine, and we are the branches (John 15). The branches must remain connected and abide in the vine to be of any use in fruit bearing, since all the nourishment comes from the roots and stem of the main tree (John 15:5). But those who do not remain in the Lord Jesus Christ will be cast out as branches; and a branch separated from the main tree cannot bear fruit, but withers away. The Lord Jesus says that they will not be good for anything else but to be burnt in the fire (John 15:6). This is the grave danger of “having itching ears” and departing from the truth of the Lord Jesus Christ. Paul already warned Timothy that some would depart from the faith in the latter times (1 Tim. 4:1). It is a bad prophecy that must not find fulfilment in our lives. ', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(413, 115, 'Let us not fall victim to many seducers who teach spirituality that is inconsistent with what God has revealed to us in the Bible. May we abide in truth and remain steadfast in preaching that same truth to others, in the Lord Jesus’ name. Amen.', '2018-02-20 11:11:46'),
(414, 116, 'Before a person can give his all, and invest his life into a particular endeavour, he must first be fully persuaded that the cause is worth sacrificing his entire future for, before he can commit to it wholeheartedly. We cannot effectively fight the good fight, keep the faith, and finish our course to the very end, if we do not first make up our minds to give our all to the Lord Jesus Christ. Giving our all to Christ is an offering. It is an offering from the day you accepted Him as Lord, until the day your soul leaves your body to go on to be with Him (2 Cor. 5:8). Paul said, “I am now ready to be offered.” He was approaching the end of his earthly life. The word “offered” is a Greek word spendo which literally means “to pour out as a drink offering.” Paul was saying, as his death was drawing closer, his soul (or his spirit) was prepared to be poured out as a drink offering, to be received into the bosom of the Lord Jesus Christ. Throughout the Law of Moses, a drink offering usually accompanied the meal offering and animal sacrifices, as a complete gesture of giving back to God everything that was already rightfully His to begin with (see Num. 15:7, 1 Chron. 29:13–14). Our lives do not actually belong to us, but was originally given to us by God (Acts 17:25). Paul had full understanding of this and, therefore, saw his impending execution for the Gospel’s sake as only pouring out the life back to the original Owner and Giver.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(415, 116, 'He signified, “the time of my departure is at hand” (2 Tim. 4:6). From Paul’s words, we can note that death is not a cessation of existence, but a departure of the spirit (the real person) from the body. Death has never been the end of the person’s existence, but only the person’s eventual departure from his earthly body. Paul said that he had a desire to depart and to be with the Lord Jesus Christ, which is far better (Phil. 1:23). And now the time of that departure was finally at hand. It is time to close the chapter of a gracious life that was spent for the course of eternity.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(416, 116, 'But Paul’s whole life since his salvation (Acts 9) had been an offering poured out unto God. TACEF\'s annual theme focus for 2017 plainly states that we should offer ourselves as living sacrifices, holy and acceptable unto God, which is our reasonable service (Rom. 12:1). This is what it means to give our life to Christ. A Christian’s time, money, energy, and resources must be dedicated to the risen Saviour, in humble service and joyful obedience. It is only as we offer our lives in service unto Him now in this present time, that we can pour it out at the very end as a drink offering which the Lord will receive into His heavenly presence. May we live a life that is worthy to be poured as a drink offering for the Lord. As every one of us desires drink with good taste, so will the Lord only be pleased with lives whose drink offering is sweet unto the Lord.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(417, 117, 'Paul gave us three areas that a Christian who desires to finish well must experience. These experiences involve courage, consistency, and the crown.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(418, 117, 'a)	<b>Courage in service.</b> The first dimension in service which the Christian must experience is courage, as Paul said, “I have fought a good fight.” The Apostle Paul was a very courageous man. Catching a glimpse of the Lord Jesus in glory gave him all the boldness and motivation he needed to take the Gospel into the most dangerous regions of the earth at a total risk to his life. Reading from Acts 13 to 28 and observing his epistles, we see Paul’s fearlessness in the face of danger, adversity, and death. He knew that the One who had called him to preach the Gospel to the nations was Supreme over all, and that his own life was in the hands of the Supreme God. He was too sure of His source that nothing hindered him from going far in his conviction and calling. No wonder, he advised Timothy and all Christians to “war a good warfare” (1 Tim. 1:18), “fight the good fight of faith” (1 Tim. 6:12), and be “good soldiers of Jesus Christ” (2 Tim. 2:3). This is the only life that we have and it is only worth any value if it is lived for the Owner. This requires courage, and without courage we will not be able to experience the second dimension—consistency.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(419, 117, 'b)	<b>Consistency.</b> Paul said, “I have kept the faith” and “I have finished my course.” These are marks of a consistent individual. The word “kept” is the Greek tereo which means to “guard.” It means to be faithful in retaining and maintaining the principles of the faith of the Lord Jesus Christ and living a lifestyle that reflects that faith. It is a life that is on fire for God on campus and still maintains same consecration when going home on holiday, even when there is no one to encourage or look up to. It is a life that is on fire as a single sister, whose passion for God does not die like a malfunctioning battery in marriage. Consistency is a pursuit of God that stands the test of time, location, or situation.<br/>\r\nPaul said he had finished his “course,” that word in the original Greek is dromos which literally means a “race.” The Christian race is not a 100-metre sprint, but a stretched out marathon. A marathon is a long race that requires the runner to cleverly pace himself to remain consistent and never run out of energy until he reaches the finish line. Starting well is comparatively easy, but finishing well is a different kind of challenge. For example, it is easy to begin a weight reduction programme with so much energy on Days 1–15 with consistent dieting and rigorous exercise, which, unfortunately, dies off in the second month as if one never started at all, when the temptations of mouth-watering food comes. Many never complete the program. <br/>\r\nIt is also easy to get married after a most exciting courtship, but more challenging to continue through the personality incompatibilities that may be discovered during the course of the marriage. Many marriages end in painful divorce. But Christians are called to persevere and remain consistent until we finish our course. We must stand true to our calling, marriage, academic pursuit, career, and commitments. Being saved is only the beginning; we still have to go through the difficulties of this world, defeat temptations, and deal with trials and even persecution. The Lord Jesus has said that “strait is the gate, and narrow is the way, which leadeth unto life” (Matt. 7:14). So we first enter through the gate, but must also travel the path to the end. This requires consistency, and our faithfulness in being consistent leads to the third dimension of experience.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(420, 117, 'c)	<b>Crown.</b> The Christian’s courage and consistency will eventually lead to the Christian’s crown. Paul said, “Henceforth there is laid up for me a crown of righteousness” (2 Tim. 4:8). This may be a literal crown, or it may be a figurative term representing honour and dignity, or it may be both, since the Greek word permits it. “Crown” is the word stephanos, which means a chaplet or wreath, which was a circular band adorned with flowers and ornaments that the winner of the Ancient Greek Olympic received.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(421, 117, 'But Paul also mentioned that all those who love and anticipate the Lord’s return to earth will also receive crowns (2 Tim. 4:8). This means that although all true Christians will be saved, not all will have crowns reserved for them by the Lord. It is like a prize-giving day—everyone graduates but only few get special prizes for leading in various subjects (see also 1 Cor. 3:10-15).', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(422, 118, 'The foundation of salvation is the Lord Jesus Christ, but we can build a number of different works upon that foundation, which Paul represented as gold, silver, precious stones, wood, hay, or stubble (1 Cor. 3:12). Paul further said that there are rewards for those whose works abide (1 Cor. 3:14), but those whose works are burnt will lose their reward, though they themselves shall still be saved (1 Cor. 3:15). With this understanding, we can see also that there are five different kinds of crowns mentioned in the New Testament, and Christians will be rewarded accordingly. While the attributes of these crowns may apply to all believers to a certain degree, the crowns remain special epitomes in various archetypes as explored below:', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(423, 118, 'a)	<b>Crown of rejoicing.</b> Paul mentioned a “crown of rejoicing” (1 Thess. 2:19). Although, as we said already, all the attributes of these crowns apply across the board, yet each crown that carries each attribute represents a hallmark or height of that particular attribute. There is nothing but joy in God’s kingdom, but this special crown of rejoicing, signifying a “fullness of joy” (Ps. 16:11). This crown is only reserved for those who have won many souls for the Lord Jesus Christ, because we are told about how joy erupts in heaven over one single sinner that repents (Luke 15:7).', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(424, 118, 'b)	<b>Crown of righteousness.</b> This is the crown which Paul spoke of in our text (2 Tim. 4:8). Righteousness is twofold: First, we are declared righteous and justified by the Lord Jesus, and His own righteousness is imputed unto us (2 Cor. 5:21). Secondly, God also requires practical righteousness from His people in our daily lives (Luke 1:75, 1 John 3:7). Though all are declared righteous by faith in the Lord Jesus Christ, this special crown is reserved for those Christians who have laboured and toiled in practical righteousness in their lives and service unto God.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(425, 118, 'c)	<b>Crown of glory.</b> We read about this crown (1 Pet. 5:4), which is reserved only for genuinely labouring church leaders, as Peter indicated (1 Pet. 5:1–3). These are the leaders who rule well, and labour in the word and doctrine, as Paul mentioned to Timothy (1 Tim. 5:17).', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(426, 118, 'd)	<b>Imperishable crown.</b> Paul mentioned a crown that is “incorruptible” (1 Cor. 9:24-25). That word in the Greek is aphthartos, which means undecaying or imperishable. Those who contend for earthly prizes are rewarded with corruptible crowns, which are temporary and will eventually perish. But the Christian’s crown which he receives from the Lord, depending on his life and service, will last forever without decaying or decomposing. The Lord Jesus warned us not to focus on storing up earthly treasures because they are corruptible (Matt. 6:19), and Peter spoke of an incorruptible inheritance which has been reserved in heaven for God’s faithful people (1 Pet. 1:3–4). Since Paul used the analogy of a dedicated runner who disciplines himself to obtain the prize, this incorruptible crown thus is for any Christian who exercises discipline and self-denial from things that hinder him from fully pleasing God.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(427, 118, 'e)	<b>Crown of life.</b> This crown is spoken about in James 1:12 and Revelation 2:10. In both verses, the situation has to do with Christians being “tried,” which is synonymous with undergoing temptations and tribulations. In Revelation 2:10 in particular, the Lord Jesus says “be thou faithful unto death, and I will give thee a crown of life.” There are clear indications that the church in Smyrna was undergoing serious persecution, even to the point of believers being killed (Rev. 2:8–10). The Lord Jesus assured them that he “was dead, and is alive” (Rev. 2:8). The crown of life, therefore, points to those who were martyred and suffered premature death for their faith in the Lord Jesus Christ. All that are in the Lord Jesus Christ certainly have eternal life, but special honour will be granted to His martyrs.', '2018-02-20 16:08:43'),
(428, 119, 'A number of people forsook Paul when he became a prisoner of the Roman government, especially during his second incarceration under Nero’s reign. The first striking observation in our text is verse 10: “Demas hath forsaken me, having loved this present world.” This is worth mentioning by Paul because he once recognised Demas as his “fellow labourer” (Philem. 1:24), mentioning his name alongside people like Mark and Luke (Col. 4:14). In other words, Demas was a trusted Christian who had worked together with Paul in the ministry, and thus it is a most shocking reality that a man who was a shoulder to lean on forsook him at a most critical time in his life. Like every genuine father, he was disappointed that the once faithful man had now chosen to abandon him. The former companion had now forsaken him, and the former lover of Christ had now loved this present world.', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(429, 119, 'But the issue was even more complex. Not only did people forsook Paul but they also departed from the faith and turned to be his enemies. He spoke of a man called Alexander, a coppersmith, who did him “much” evil, and greatly withstood the Word of God (2 Tim. 4:14–15). We have every indication to believe that this is the same Alexander in Acts 19:33 and 1 Timothy 1:20. In Acts 19:23–34, there was a riot at Ephesus caused by silversmiths who made shrines for the goddess Diana. Alexander was the man in verse 33 who acted as a mediator between the believers and the rioting Ephesian silversmiths, since he was also a coppersmith. Also, the first epistle was written to Timothy after Paul left him at Ephesus to put the church in order (1 Tim. 1:3), and Alexander is said to have put away his faith (1 Tim. 1:19-20). No doubt, this was the same Alexander who did Paul some kind of evil and became an opponent of the Gospel. Another big disappointment for Paul.', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(430, 119, 'As if this was not enough, verse 16 of our text shows that at Paul’s first hearing in court, no Christians at Rome identified with him or spoke up for him. Paul was pained but he was never offended. He felt the disappointment but it was clear from the text that he lived beyond his pains. This was why Paul prayed that their forsaking of him should not be laid to their charge. <b>He forgave them prayerfully.</b> He did not pray that they fall down and die, but he stood as their advocate, asking the Lord not to count it against them. What a man Paul was! May God help us not to become defiled with bitterness, offence, and malice.  <b>A man\'s betterment can be destroyed by bitterness.</b>', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(431, 119, 'As bad as Paul’s predicament was with his trusted people abandoning him, one Person, our Lord Jesus Christ never left his side. The Lord Jesus has said to His disciples, “I am with you alway, even unto the end of the world” (Matt. 28:20). God’s people can always rely on this promise. In Hebrews 13:5–6, the writer repeated the Lord Jesus’ promise by combining two passages from the Old Testament (Josh. 1:5, Ps. 118:6). Paul had this concrete assurance—the reason why he could speak the way he did (2 Tim. 4:17–18). Paul confidently concluded that the Lord will “preserve me unto his heavenly kingdom.”', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(432, 119, 'As God’s servants, our lives are in His hands and He knows the exact date and by what means He will call us home. We must serve Him without fear of man, which Proverbs 29:25 says brings a snare. Many forsook Paul but the Saviour never did.', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(433, 119, 'We may be forsaken by man, but we will never be forsaken by the Lord Jesus Christ. It is safe to prepare our hearts for a time when our best friends, most intimate family members, closest spiritual networks, prayer partners, and those we have laboured on turned their backs against us. It is better to  prepare in advance and forgive ahead of time. The meaning of the word \"forgive\" is actually \"before give,\" meaning before an offense is committed against us, we should let it go in advance. It is a future preparation, as it will necessarily happen just as the Lord Jesus had already told us, \"for it must needs be that offences come” (Matt. 18:7). Beloved, consciously insulate your minds from the shocks and surprises of life because the best of men will always be men!', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(434, 119, '<h3>Week 47 ends here and Week 48 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-20 16:17:31'),
(435, 120, 'In verse 11 of our text, Paul instructed Timothy to take Mark and bring him along when coming to visit, because he was seen as beneficial for the ministry. This was towards the end of Paul’s life, but ironically, Mark was someone Paul had rejected from working with him in ministry as a companion on his first missionary tour with Barnabas (Acts 13:2–5). We have the account that he forsook Paul and Barnabas in Pamphylia probably at a time when ministerial demands were high (Acts 15:38). It was because of him that Paul separated from Barnabas and took Silas instead for his second missionary tour (Acts 15:40).', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(436, 120, 'Though Paul once rejected Mark, he was now telling Timothy that the man was profitable for the ministry. We cannot know what happened between them from the time of Paul’s second missionary tour till this present time of his incarceration in Rome, but we know that Paul had granted him a second chance—the ultimate of a father\'s heart. All of us have a lesson to learn from this. We should not give up on people too easily, but remember that we are all human and can make mistakes. The members of Christ’s body need one another (1 Cor. 12:21–22), and the Lord Jesus Himself emphasised reconciliation (Matt. 6:14, 18:15). However, we must also be interested in knowing why Paul said he was now beneficial. He was formerly said to be inefficient for service but now very beneficial. Something must have changed! It must be that Mark had worked on himself. He had proved himself again and convinced Paul that he had gotten better. He must be a man who did not take offense when a leader corrected him. He must be a man who accepted his fault and committed to win back lost confidence. He was a man who took his past mistakes seriously and consciously made amends to a point that he became a choice vessel of huge beneficial value. <b>What is our attitude when chastised? Do we get better or bitter or even grow blisters?</b> Do we avoid, ignore, disregard, and cut off from our own \"Paul,\" who had previously rejected us because of a past disappointment? Let us endeavour to win back every relationship and trust that we have once betrayed, and we can become another beneficial vessel.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(437, 120, 'Let us not give up on our misbehaving or low-performing children, lose hope on our spouse, or even give up on our failing business partner. Something beneficial can still come out of them.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(438, 120, 'As reasonable stewards, let us not allow the mistakes of the past to keep brethren separated, but let us operate in the spirit of winback, self-improvement, rebuilding broken confidence, and complete reconciliation, as this is well pleasing to our Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(439, 121, 'Paul was close to the end of his time on earth. However, he did not make excuses for himself by saying things like, “Let me relax a little, after all, I’ve worked so hard all these years,” or “Somebody else can continue preaching the Gospel, I’ve done my fair share.” No! Instead, aged and incarcerated, he was still consumed with thoughts of the ministry and preaching the Word! This was an old man who was arrested and facing execution, yet he said he needed Mark to assist him with some aspects of his ministry, maybe writing his letters like Tertius once did (Rom. 16:22) or being the mailman who delivers them to the churches like Phebe (Rom. 16:1–2). He was not done serving! If Paul was not locked up, no doubt he would still be out and about serving the Lord Jesus Christ. In verse 17, we see that Paul continued to preach both by his letters and to those who were around him near the Roman palace and dungeon.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(440, 121, 'Not only was Paul still fully concerned with ministry, he continued to read books and develop his knowledge as well. In verse 13, he requested for Timothy to bring his cloak when he would come, probably because the winter season was approaching (2 Tim. 4:21). But even more importantly, he asked the young minister to bring his books, and especially the parchments (2 Tim. 4:13). A “parchment” is the Greek word membrana which is a written scroll made from sheepskin. The material was more valuable than the regular papyrus sheets, and it was clear in the text that Paul put so much value on this as an eternal asset.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(441, 121, 'Paul had been preaching the Gospel for about thirty years or more, he had seen visions of the Lord Jesus Christ, written the majority of the New Testament, and was in a Roman cell facing death penalty, yet he asked Timothy to bring him books! The Roman dungeon could not quench his thirst for deeper knowledge in the things of God.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(442, 121, 'This shows us that no matter how far we have come in our understanding of the Lord, we must continue to seek more revelation and wisdom, both from the Bible and from certified servants of God from past and present. Paul himself once instructed Timothy to “give attendance to reading” (1 Tim. 4:13). A worthy Christian must develop a reading culture, build own spiritual library, and keep journals of our earthly progress in the Lord Jesus Christ for our future reference, and for the benefit of others who will come after us. The same applies to our career—let us never become outdated in our profession. Let us always seek for current learning, research, innovations, and progress in our chosen specialisation through regular exposure to knowledge via books, certification, conferences and strategic membership of world-class organisations within our knowledge domain. Let us not become a dull axe! Build a library and become a man of books!', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(443, 121, 'As a Christian, when last did you read a Christian literature? When was the last time you finished reading the Bible back to back, even in your more than 10 years Christian journey? ', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(444, 121, '<h3>Week 48 ends here and Week 49 continues below</h3>', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(445, 122, 'This last segment of our study will look at the associates whom Paul mentioned in the text. Besides Demas and Alexander, he mentioned fifteen different people whom he had come to know and build relationships with over the years of his ministry. He was obviously not a loner, but rather was committed to the cause of the Lord Jesus Christ with many others he considered fellow-labourers. Paul had good relationship with these people and was very aware of every individual’s situation. His letter showed the depth of the intimate relationship he had and how he consciously managed them with utmost sense of respect and warmth of the Lord Jesus Christ. Let us explore these individuals mentioned in this closing part of the letter to Timothy.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(446, 122, 'Luke is well-known and a beloved physician (Col. 4:14) who Paul also mentioned in Philemon 24. We recall we have studied his two letters: Luke and Acts of the Apostle. We have already talked about Mark earlier in the study. Tychicus was sent by Paul to Ephesus (2 Tim. 4:12) to deliver the epistle to the Ephesians (Eph. 6:21–22), and it was he who also delivered the epistle to the Colossians (Col. 4:7–8). He is also mentioned in Acts 20:4 and Titus 3:12. Carpus is not mentioned anywhere else in the New Testament, but Paul left his cloak (or special cloth) with him at Troas (2 Tim. 4:13). He must be a trusted man who was not a waster and who would not use other people’s things in his custody. He would not borrow Paul\'s cloak in his absence or kept it where it would be spoilt. Aquila and Prisca (or Priscilla) were a married couple who were strongly associated with Paul. They are first mentioned in Acts 18:1–3, where we learn that they were fellow tentmakers just as Paul was (see also Acts 18:18, 26, Rom. 16:3, 1 Cor. 16:19). Onesiphorus and his household were mentioned earlier by Paul and we have studied about him (2 Tim 1:16–18). He frequently visited and ministered to Paul in prison and at Ephesus. ', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(447, 122, 'Paul also had progressive network of high-ranking people as inner caucus friends. We recall that we have spoken extensively about improvement relationships in previous TACEF Bible studies, as a call to build value-adding network of quality people who can help us improve our capacity and competence without compromising our faith. Erastus was one of such (2 Tim. 4:20, Rom. 16:23). He was a chamberlain or a treasurer of the city of Cenchreae in Corinth, from whence the epistle to the Romans was written (Rom. 16:23). This may or may not be the same Erastus who ministered to Paul along with Timothy (Acts 19:22). We can note  that the Ethiopian eunuch in Acts was also a finance minister of his country. These were high-quality men who added value to Paul\'s mandate, hence the special recognition he had for them. Let us never feel intimidated and avoid our old friends or even brethren who have moved to higher position relative to where you are at the moment. Let us never cut off from people because their spiritual, academic, social, marital, and financial credentials have increased beyond what we used to know. We may just be the reason why the Lord lifted them up, for their story to inspire us to move up. So why run away from them?', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(448, 122, 'Next, Paul talked about Trophimus who was sick in Miletum. He was the Ephesian who was with Paul in Jerusalem (Acts 21:29), and is also mentioned in Acts 20:4. At this point, Paul genuinely mentioned his poor state of health and why he had to let him stay back in Miletum (2 Tim. 4:20). Paul was a careful leader who did not allow spirituality to blind his eyes from being genuinely concerned about people\'s health to the point that he advised Trophimus to stay back and not continue the ministry journey with him. Many get stupidly spiritual and fail to know when they need to stay back in their own Miletum to properly take care of their state of health. Many know that they are in a poor state of health and yet continue to carry the burden of the ministry—nothing but complete act of foolishness! We must not be a leader who uses words to intimidate folks when they genuinely express their state of health. It will be wrong for a leader to tell his follower, \"You don\'t have faith,\" when an individual, who has been nursing a critical medical condition for a few days humbly and genuinely requests to be excused from a long-fasting period. Of course, this does not mean that brethren should now focus on their sickness and lose sight of the power of God to heal or use this as an excuse to forget their altar of personal relationship with God. There is a balance here and we must be sure that we are true to God at all times and, at the same time, sensitive to the warnings from our physical bodies.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(449, 122, 'A Christian walking on the path of reasonable service must keep, nurture, and develop quality relationships and networks that foster peace, excellence, self-development, and mutual commitment to others. A Christian who does not have good relationship with his neighbours, colleagues at work, brethren in the fellowship, and siblings—whether they are born again or not—is losing out in the place of meaningful transfer of mutually beneficial value.', '2018-02-20 16:23:26'),
(450, 122, 'Just like Paul, Christians will be able to face life’s winter better if they are part of a body of committed believers, who uphold one another in the great cause of God’s kingdom. As the saying goes, “No man is an island.” The members of Christ’s body need one another for optimum functioning and effectiveness in reasonable service (1 Cor. 12:21).', '2018-02-20 16:23:44'),
(451, 123, 'To start this study, it will be important to understand what Babylon means as it relates to the\r\ndemands of revival in our time. The name Babylon was introduced to us in Genesis as\r\n“Babel”, from the root word \"babilu\" (the gate of god). It was the ancient city founded by\r\nNimrod, where human beings decided to make a name for themselves in defiance of the\r\nword of God with a building that was meant to riseas tall as the heaven. This is as recorded in\r\nGenesis 11 vs 8-9', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(452, 123, 'Further in the Old Testament, we see how Babylon evolved again to become an empire that\r\ndestroys Jerusalem, burns the temple and takes the people of God into exile. It was a mighty\r\nempire that ruled the known world of its time and imposed a worldview upon all of the\r\npeople that it conquered. Babylon was a brutal and proud city, thought to reign forever. The\r\npopular \"Hanging Gardens\" of Babylon, regarded as one of the seven wonders of the ancient\r\nworld, was located in this city. The engineering exploit remains world-class, with\r\nNebuchadnezzar\'s palace considered to be the most magnificent building ever erected on\r\nearth.', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(453, 123, 'Babylon was indeed a great city that influenced popular culture. It brought ungodliness and\r\ndefilement to the nations it governed. It was a negative influence that takes a man into\r\nbondage, plunders purpose and negatively influenced lives. It also enforced its own identity\r\non anyone it came in to contact with. You will remember how the names of Daniel and the\r\nthree Hebrew men were changed and named after the gods of Babylon.\r\nIn essence, wecan see Babylon as a place of corruption, loss of identity, desecration and total\r\nbacksliding into the abysmal worldliness.', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(454, 123, 'While Babylon was a city In the Old Testament, we saw another dimension of Babylon in the\r\nBook of Revelation, where it was seen as a spirit, a whore and a beast that almost swallowed\r\nthe bride; but in the end, she was judged, despoiled and thrown down. (Rev 17: 3-6). The\r\nwhore of Babylon was seen as a spirit of seductive culture, actively engaged in the deception\r\nand destruction of God\'s people. Its drive was to desecrate God\'s temple, hold God\'s people\r\nin total captivity and block them from going to their spiritual source (Jerusalem). It is\r\nthisspirit of anti-revival that steals identity in Christ, promotes immorality, activates\r\ndeception and fortifies self to operate against the purpose of God.\r\nThe call of revival must be seen as a mandate to rescue lives from the power and spirit of\r\nBabylon. It is not child\'s play. It is a serious demand of laying hold on God to break the yoke of\r\na spirit that changes destinies of nations.\r\n<h3>Week 1 ends here and week 2 starts below</h3>', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(455, 124, 'Sin is the starting point of a man\'s journey into the captivity of Babylon. Sin takes a man away\r\nfrom God into a strange land. Sin takes a man on a wrong path that is far away from the best\r\nof God. Sin is a destiny destroyer; sin takes a man into the land of strange happenings.', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(456, 124, 'God warned Israel repeatedly that disobedience would bring many negative consequences,\r\nof which the ultimate would be the desolation of the land by their enemies, and also their\r\nexile to foreign nations (Lev. 26:31-33, Deut. 28:36). God warned them that they will be taken\r\naway into a strange land if they fail to repent. Unfortunately, Israel\'s apostasy started right\r\nthere in the wilderness before they had even entered the Promised Land (Ex. 32:1-6) and\r\ncontinued until the Babylonians invaded the land.', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(457, 124, 'Thecapture by the Babyloniansdid not happen all at once, but gradually, step by step. During\r\nthe time of Nebuchadnezzar, Jehoiakim, the king of Judah becamesubject to him.', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(458, 124, 'Daniel and his friends were among these first Jews who were taken captive to Babylon (Dan.\r\n1:1-7). Then came the second wave when Jehoiakim\'s son ,Jehoiachin became king of Judah\r\nand a possible rebellion caused the Babylonians to besiege Jerusalem again. This time, more\r\nwere taken away—Jehoiachin the king, along with the queen, their princes, and many nobles\r\nand dignitaries of Judah into Babylonian captivity(2 Kings 24:8-17). Ezekiel, who was a priest,\r\nwas also taken captive during this time (Ezekiel 1:1-3). Then the third and final captivity was\r\nthe time when Nebuchadnezzar appointed Zedekiah to run the affairs of Judah, and he was\r\nking for almost nine years before rebelling against Nebuchadnezzar\'s authority for two years.\r\nThis would be the last rebellion as Nebuchadnezzar must have had enough—he did not only\r\ntake people captive, he killed the king\'s sons and many other people, plucked out the king\'s\r\neyes, burnt the temple of the Lord, burnt the king\'s house and the houses of Jerusalem,\r\nbroke down the walls of Jerusalem all around, and took the remainder of the temple\'s\r\nprecious vessels away to Babylon (2 Kings 24:17-20, 25:1-21).', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(459, 124, 'The devil always comeslike Nebuchadnezzar in a step-by-step manner until he comes for the\r\nfinal onslaught as the one who comes to steal, kill and destroy (John 10:10).The devil is\r\nmercilessly consistent!', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(460, 124, 'Judah\'s step-by-step degeneration canbe likened to how some of God\'s people today slowly\r\nbut surely backslide into ungodliness. James the apostle says it well: “but every man is\r\ntempted, when he is drawn away of his own lust, and enticed. Then when lust has conceived,\r\nit brings forth sin; and sin, when it is finished, brings forth death” (James 1:14-15). A\r\ndiscerning Christian will not tolerate any appearance of evil and neither pretend with any\r\nform of secret sins. Be truthful to yourself and know how to shout to the Lord for help when\r\nyou observe that the weight of temptation is becomingunbearable.', '2018-11-02 12:10:26'),
(461, 125, 'The author of Psalm 137 was physically present in Babylon. However, his spirit was\r\nsomewhere else, namely, Jerusalem—God\'s chosen city (Deut. 12:5-14, 1Kings 9:1-3, 1Kings\r\n11:13). There was not much he could do to change the geographic location of his body, but\r\nthat did not stop his heart and mind from being in the right place. This reminds us of Daniel,\r\nwho also was physically present in Babylon, but his heart was truly in Jerusalem. He made a\r\nhabit of praying to God towards the open window in his room which faced the direction of\r\nJerusalem (Dan. 6:10). And when he prayed earnestly for God\'s mercy upon the captives, he\r\nmade sure to include Jerusalem in his petitions (9:16-19).', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(462, 125, 'This is a picture for God\'s people today. Though we live and function in the present\r\nBabylonian world system, our hearts and minds ought to be in God\'s kingdom. Many\r\nChristians today are modern professionals and withsecular jobs come daily demands, which\r\nmust be complied with. The secret, however, is to represent God\'s kingdom (Righteousness,\r\nPeace, and Joy in the Holy Spirit [Rom. 14:17]) in meeting the demands of the secular world.\r\nThis is exactlywhat Daniel did, and it helpedhim succeed in both realms. One of the first\r\nthings that Daniel did on arrival to Babylon was to settle it in his heart that he would not\r\ncompromise God\'s righteous standards by “defiling himself” with the alluring temptations of\r\nhis new secular location (Dan. 1:8). God honoured this crucial decision by remaining faithful\r\nto Daniel throughout his life in Babylon, and Daniel never stopped living for God in the midst\r\nof the Babylonians. He excelled so notably that even his worldly enemies knew they could\r\nnot find fault with him (6:3-4). <b>The secret is clear—in Babylon physically but connected to\r\nJerusalem spiritually.</b>', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(463, 125, 'A close observation of the rest of Daniel\'s life teaches us how to operate in a Babylonian\r\nworld system in a way that honours God, while keeping our hearts and minds on the kingdom\r\nat all times. The pressures, demands, and temptations of this present world must not\r\ndisconnect you from “Jerusalem”. Let it not be said that the Babylon of the academic world\r\nhas turned you into examination cheats or the pressure to get a job has made you change\r\nyour date of birth or deceitfully use fake certificates.', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(464, 126, 'The first teaching showed us how wecan keep our hearts in Jerusalem while living in Babylon,\r\nwith Daniel as a mini case-study. Unfortunately, however, many of the captive Jews lost focus\r\nof Jerusalem and became indulgent in the Babylonian way of life. They became settled and\r\nsatisfied, losing any real interest in God\'s kingdom in the process. As we progress into this\r\nstudy of Ezra, you will realise that when an opportunity was given for all the children of Israel\r\nto return to Jerusalem by a good king named Cyrus, only few were willing to return to\r\nJerusalem. Many remained in Babylon, being unwilling to leave their possessions. They had\r\nbecome obsessedby their possessions, and basically enslaved by the lifestyle of Babylon. The\r\nspiritual hunger and zeal was gone. This is the same reality formany Christians today who\r\nhave fallen victim to thesame danger. Such Christians have become complacent with no\r\nsense of genuine longing and desire for the return of the Lord Jesus Christ.', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(465, 126, 'Let us explore what Jerusalem meant to the writer of Psalm 137. Jerusalem represented\r\nworship, covenant, the temple, sacrifice for remission of sins, and an intimate relationship\r\nwith God. For the New Testament believer, however, the proximity of the Jerusalem temple\r\nhas been brought closer by God regardless of our physical location. The individual Christian\r\ntoday is the temple (see John 2:18-22, 1Cor. 3:16-17, 1Cor. 6:19, 2Cor. 6:16). This man\'s\r\nloyalty to Jerusalem was so deep that he swore to his own hurt (Psalm 15 vs 4). This man has\r\nmade a vow to remember Jerusalem, even in exile.', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(466, 126, 'Even when the unbelievers who took them captive asked him to make a mockery of\r\nJerusalem, he refused by saying, “How shall we sing the Lord\'s song in a foreign land?”.\r\nThough things had become bad for him, he will not stand to see the name of the Lord put to\r\nridicule. The fact that things had Cnot worked out does not mean that he will throw caution\r\nto the wind. Though their conquerors wanted them to sing for their own amusement, he\r\nknew the boundaries and would not allow his bad circumstances to corrupt the legacy of the\r\nkingdom. He knew very well that the songs of God\'s people were not for show or\r\nperformances; they camefrom a relationship with God.', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(467, 126, 'He will not turn the altar of the Lord to a place of shame where worldly songs and comedy is\r\nplayed for fun. No, he will not, he has made a vow! His sense of consecration was not a mere\r\none. He has vowed to an eternal consecration when he said, “If I forget you, O Jerusalem, Let\r\nmy right hand forget its skill! If I do not remember you, let my tongue cling to the roof of my\r\nmouth”. He has vowed that he would never forget God\'s holy city. He consecrated that it will\r\nbe better for him to lose his skills and talents that the world desire than lose his place in the\r\nbook of life. What a commitment needed to survive the pressures of our time.', '2018-11-02 12:20:32'),
(468, 127, 'Before the proclamation of Cyrus to free the Jews actually took place, God had already\r\nforetold the event almost 70 years earlier through Jeremiah (Jer. 25:11-13, 29:10), and even\r\nmentioned Cyrus by name almost 150 years before he was born, through the prophet Isaiah\r\n(Isa. 44:28, 45:1). Our God is Jehovah ever-accurate! Jeremiah\'s prophecies were\r\n“understood by books” as Daniel studied these Scriptures (Dan. 9:2). As soon as he saw what\r\nhadbeen written concerning the situation, his attitude changed in Daniel 9 vs 3, “So I turned\r\nto the Lord God and pleaded with him in prayer and petition, in fasting, and in sackcloth and\r\nashes”.', '2018-11-02 12:33:15'),
(469, 127, 'There are many great promises and prophetic words hanging over the lives of every\r\nChristian, particularly anyone who belongs to the mandate of a great house. However, God\'s ability to bring it to pass is dependent on our ability to know, believe and activate by praying.\r\nDaniel did not take this revelatoryinsight for granted, he went into prayers and fasting. He complemented this with humility of heart as represented by sackcloth and ashes. The fact that you have a promise from God does not mean it will come to pass, except you connect to it with the right attitude—prayerful heart, deep consecration in fasting and humility of heart\r\nto birth that which God has effected in the spiritual realm.', '2018-11-02 12:33:15'),
(470, 127, 'How about us today? Do weknow where we are in the prophetic timeline for the church and\r\nfor our individual lives? Do we know what events to watchoutfor leading up to the Lord\'s\r\nreturn? Matthew chapter 24, for example, gives us a good picture of what to take note of, and\r\nJesus said weshould use these markers to discern the proximity of His second coming (verses\r\n32-33). Everything that God has said, will come to pass. We are admonished to “Study [be\r\ndiligent] to show thyself approved unto God, a workman that need not be ashamed, rightly\r\ndividing the word of truth” (2Tim 2:15). This is what Daniel did, and we would be wise to do\r\nthe same.', '2018-11-02 12:33:15'),
(471, 128, 'As we look for revival and a move of God in the earth, being conscious of the Biblical\r\nprophecy will push our hearts and minds to dig deeper into the things of the Spirit. It will\r\nrecondition our minds and make us more heaven-conscious. Understanding that the Lord is\r\non His way, and understanding the seasons, will position the Church to better prepare herself\r\nto meet the Bridegroom.', '2018-11-02 12:33:15'),
(472, 128, 'In the parable of the ten virgins (Matt. 25), five were said to be wise and five were said to be\r\nfoolish. The virgins are comparable to the church today since they were all waiting for the\r\nsame Master/Bridegroom. The wise ones prepared against the time to come by taking extra\r\noil in vessels with their lamps, but the foolish ones did not realisethe importance of thinking\r\nahead and therefore were ill-prepared with no oil reserves. When their lamps were\r\nextinguished, they made a last minute dashto go and acquire more oil. But while they were\r\ngone, verse 10 says that the Bridegroom came, and “they that were ready” went in with Him\r\nto the marriage, and the door was shut. Readiness that is based on a clear understanding of\r\nthe scheme of the spirit is very critical in activating a move of revival in our generation.', '2018-11-02 12:33:15'),
(473, 128, 'We must adopt the mentality of the wise virgins who peeped into the future and begun to\r\nprepare themselves while there was still time. Taking Bible prophecy seriouslike Daniel did\r\nwill ignite revival in Christ\'s church, and keep us on our toes as we joyfully anticipate our\r\nMaster\'s return while paying attention to the signs.In the same vein, we must understand\r\nGod\'s timing for our life per time. It is an issue to be in the past tense when God is already in\r\nthe present tense over our career, ministry, finance etc.', '2018-11-02 12:33:15'),
(474, 129, 'According to archaeological documents, Cyrus II (the Biblical Cyrus) becamea local king over Persia but was under Babylonian and Median authority. Cyrus was both a highly skilled diplomat and soldier, and was also determined to remove Persia from under the yoke of any superior authority. He began to conquer surrounding regions little by little, and his army eventually captured Babylon (the capital of the Babylonian empire). Cyrus would come to be known as “Cyrus the Great”, and his empire stretched wide to become the largest empire that the world had yet seen up to that point.', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(475, 129, 'In His foreknowledge, God had already revealed to Isaiah the prophet that a great king would rise to world power, about 150 years before he was born, who would also liberate the Jewish people and facilitate the building of the Jerusalem temple (Isa. 44:28, 45:1-4, 45:13). He specifically mentioned Cyrus by name and called him His “anointed”, the only non-Israelite king in the Bible to be so-called by God. In Ezra 1:2, Cyrus himself acknowledged that God had chosen him and raised him to world dominance, saying <i>“Yahweh God of heaven has given me all the kingdoms of the earth”.</i>', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(476, 129, 'The way God used Cyrus to bring revival to the Jewish people shows us that God can raise up\r\nanybody (even non-Christians) and use them as a part of His ultimate plan to bring revival to\r\nhis Church today. We should not put God in a box or limit His wisdom and ability to use\r\nunexpected pieces of the puzzle for salvation and restoration.', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(477, 130, '<i>“...the LORD stirred up the spirit of Cyrus king of Persia...” (Ezra 1:1)</i>', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(478, 130, 'When the fullness of the appointed time came, God moved the king\'s heart to begin to make\r\nthe decree that would allow God\'s people to return to the Promised Land. This is in\r\nagreement with Proverbs 21:1—“The king\'s heart is in the hand of the LORD, as the rivers of\r\nwater, he turneth it whithersoever he will.” And God turned Cyrus\' heart not only to let the\r\nJews go free, but to “build him a house at Jerusalem, which is in Judah” (Ezra 1:2). Later on\r\nwhen Ezra and the second wave of returning exiles were about to leave Babylon for\r\nJerusalem, God again stirred up the heart of a Persian king, this time king Artaxerxes, to\r\nprovide everything they would need for their journey and for service in the temple (Ezra 7:1,\r\n7, 11-20). 7:27 says “Blessed be the LORD God of our fathers, who has put such a thing as this\r\nin the king\'s heart, to beautify the house of the LORD which is in Jerusalem”.', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(479, 130, 'God is in the business of touching the hearts of secular rulers and bringing His people into\r\nfavour with them. A few other Biblical examples include Nebuchadnezzar\'s goodness\r\ntowards Jeremiah (Jer. 39:11-14), Ashpenaz and Melzar\'s favour towards Daniel and his\r\nfriends (Daniel 1:3, 9-16), and the goodness of Achish the Philistine, king of Gath, towards\r\nDavid (1Sam. 27:1-6). Sometimes the people of the world are even able to tell that webelong\r\nto God, and can see His hand on us, like how Egyptian officials could see that God was with\r\nJoseph (Gen. 39:1-6, 19-23). Part of our progress in this present world system may include\r\nGod stirring up the hearts of people we least expected to favour us, working all things\r\ntogether for our good in the process (Rom. 8:28). The Lord can use your promotion\r\ncommittee, boss, unbeliever friends, gateman and many other groups of unbelievers to\r\nachieve His purpose. We know very well that God works in our lives through different\r\nchannels to fulfil His will and purpose.', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(480, 131, 'We have seen so far in this study that God is indeed sovereign, and He is the One who is fully\r\ncapable of inspiring kings to act according to His will for the benefit of His people. With this\r\nunderstanding, Christians nevertheless still have a role to play in bringing God\'s full counsel\r\nto pass. Besides living in obedience to His commandments, we must also intercede for all\r\nleaders that weare subject to, accordingly to 1Tim. 2:1-2, which says—', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(481, 131, '<i>“I exhort therefore, that, first of all, supplications, prayers, intercessions, and giving of\r\nthanks, be made for all men, for kings, and for all that are in authority; that we may lead a\r\nquiet and peaceable life in all godliness and honesty.”</i>', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(482, 131, 'This was Paul writing to Timothy during the reign of Nero, Caesar of the Roman empire, who\r\nheavily persecuted Christians. The instruction to pray for kings and those in authority shows\r\nthat God\'s ears are open and attentive, and He wouldnot demand of us to pray such prayers\r\nif He was not willing to move the hearts of those kings in some way that would either protect\r\nus from some danger or positively bless us. Our prayers may even be one of the reasons why\r\nGod would bring salvation through faith in Christ to some of our secular leaders. Whichever\r\nthe case may be, there is no doubt that God wants us to pray for our civil rulers, and that\r\nthese prayers play a significant role in bringing blessing to the Church. As we follow this\r\ninstruction, weshould expect to see more people in government becoming active Christians\r\nand/or enacting policies that will favour God\'s people. There can be spiritual revival and\r\nrenewal if God\'s people will earnestly seek His face in prayer.', '2018-11-02 12:50:19'),
(483, 132, '<i>“Who is there among you of all his people?” (Ezra 1:3)</i>', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(484, 132, 'Our Lord Jesus is calling all His people unto full repentance and revival as we see in His\r\nmessage to the seven churches (Rev. Chapters 2 & 3). Unfortunately, this call is only being\r\nanswered by the lesser percentage of Christians. In Matthew 22:1-14, we encounter Jesus\r\nparable about a King who organiseda wedding feast for his Son, and sent out invitations to\r\nmany guests to come and be partakers of the festivities. “Again, he sent forth other servants,\r\nsaying, Tell them which are bidden [invited], behold, I have prepared my dinner: my oxen and\r\nmy fatlings are killed, and all things are ready—come unto the marriage” (v. 4). For us, this is a\r\ncall to a spiritual feast with the Son, even as Jesus Himself said in Rev. 3:20 to the Laodicean\r\nchurch: “Behold, I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears my voice, and opens the door,\r\nI will come in to him, and will dine with him, and he with me”.', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(485, 132, 'Instead of us seeing great enthusiasm and a joyful response to this wonderful invitation, we\r\nsee in verse 5: “But they made light of it, and went their ways, one to his farm, another to his\r\nmerchandise.” In a similar parable in Luke, weread the following response of those who were\r\ninvited to the feast: “And they all with one consent began to make excuses. The first said unto\r\nhim, I have bought a piece of ground, and I must needs go and see it: I pray thee, have me\r\nexcused. And another said, I have bought five yoke of oxen, and I go to prove them: I pray\r\nthee, have me excused. And another said, I have married a wife, and therefore I cannot\r\ncome” (Luke 14:18-20). The responses of these invitees from Matthew and Luke show us one\r\nof the great hindrances to supernatural experience. God calls His people to something\r\nhigher, but His people are overly preoccupied with the cares of this world and indulge in\r\nexcuses (Mark 4:18-19).', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(486, 132, 'Continuing with the passage in Matthew, the King says “The wedding is ready, but they which\r\nwere invited were not worthy” (22:8). So he sends his servants into the streets to callas many\r\npeople as they can find, “both bad and good”, and the wedding was furnished with guests (v.\r\n9-10). The fact that both bad and good were called into the wedding testifies that God is\r\ninviting “whosoever will” to “take the water of life freely” (Rev. 22:17). The ending part of the\r\ninvitation in Matthew 22 shows us a critical necessity to enter fully into God\'s banquet. In\r\nverses 11-13 wesee a man who had entered into the wedding but did not have on a wedding\r\ngarment. This wedding garment is the fine linen which represents the righteousness of saints\r\n(Rev. 19:7-9), symbolic of both Jesus blood that washes all our sins (Rev. 1:5), and the Holy\r\nSpirit who empowers God\'s people to obey Him (Acts 5:32). You can “come as you are” but\r\nyou cannot “remain as you are”! This is one of the errors today that require the intervention\r\nof a move of revival, where the church has become an air-conditioner for sinners, making it\r\ncomfortable for sinners to enjoy the church with no salvation or discipleship. The full\r\ncompletion of revival must result in transformed hearts that have received the wedding\r\ngarment which Jesus freely offers us. Refusal to accept His garment, i.e., refusal to put on the\r\nrobe of righteousness (Isaiah 61:10), will lead to eternal rejection by the King (Matt. 22:13).\r\nSo “who is there among you of all his people?” Will we be the Jews who chose to return to\r\nJerusalem and partake of God\'s spiritual rebuilding, or are we comfortable where we have\r\nsettled? Will we be the invitees who made excuses due to worldliness, or will we come into\r\nthe King\'s wedding? Will webe the man whom God can trust to step out as a true intercessor\r\nfor revival or will you rather enjoy the nice ambience of that new place of worship that is\r\nclose to you at the risk of many dying souls in your local church, where your light is much\r\nneeded to catalyse revival?', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(487, 133, 'Ezra 1:5 says the main tribes that returned were of Judah, Benjamin, and Levi, and\r\nreasonably so, since these were the main tribes in the Southern Kingdom of Judah before the\r\ncaptivity. They were included among those whose hearts had been “raised” by God. That\r\nword “raised” is the same Hebrew word ûr which is translated as “stirred up” in Ezra 1:1 when\r\nspeaking of how God stirred up the spirit of Cyrus the king. Ûr literally means to wake or rouse\r\nup. So most of the Jews in Babylon could have returned, but for some reason a remnant was\r\naroused in spirit by God.', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(488, 133, 'So what differentiates those who were willing to go back home and the higher percentage\r\nwho chose to stay behind? It is very likely that those who offered to go back had for a while\r\nbeen longing for their homeland, like the writer of Psalm 137. They also could have remained\r\nconscious of God\'s covenant and blessings attached to their Promised Land. Or, like Daniel,\r\nthey had read the prophecies of Jeremiah that God would restore them to peace and\r\nprosperity in Judah after seventy years were accomplished in Babylon. We know that many\r\nJews became prosperous in Babylon while many were hired into governmental positions, yet\r\nwe saw how they were willing to let go of these privileges and their hard-earned labour of\r\nmany years to return to the city of the Lord. Since they had spent seventy years in Babylon,\r\nwereckon that a generation would have also emergedwho had never seen Jerusalem before.\r\nGod will use various methods to motivate us into doing His work, especially when many\r\naround us have failed to respond to the call. “Then rose up the chief of the fathers...” (Ezra\r\n1:5). It is our responsibility to rise up, like the chief of the fathers. If we do not rise up, the\r\ntemple will never get built. Jesus said, “My Father works now, and I work” (John 5:17). God\r\nwill do His part, and we also must do our part, if we desire to see the work of genuine revival\r\naccomplished in our time.', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(489, 133, 'The way God will stir one person\'s heart would not necessarily be the same method He uses\r\nto stir that of another, because He knows weare different and He knows what will push us out\r\nof our comfort zones. We then have the choice to make whether we will rise up and fulfil our\r\ncalling or not.', '2018-11-02 13:02:23'),
(490, 134, 'God had promised the Jews long ago that He would bring them back from captivity and\r\nrestore their welfare and prosperity (Jer. 29:10-11, Deut. 30:1-9). However, this was of\r\nsecondary importance in God\'s plan for His people. Their material well-being was going to be\r\na by-product of what was of primary importance to God—their spiritual well-being. This is\r\nevidenced by the fact that Cyrus\' decree to release them was fundamentally based on their\r\nrebuilding of the temple in Jerusalem [“..he has charged me to build him a house at\r\nJerusalem” (1:2), “..and build the house of the LORD…which is in Jerusalem” (1:3), “…for the\r\nhouse of God that is in Jerusalem” (1:4), “…to go up to build the house of the LORD which is in\r\nJerusalem” (1:5)]. The building of the temple was the primary goal, and the provisions which\r\nwere given to the Jews were firstly to ensure that the goal was accomplished. This\r\nunderstanding is the reason why we always emphasise in TACEF ministry that “every life\r\nlifting wereceive in career and business is primarily for the enlargement of the kingdom”.', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(491, 134, 'As Christians, weare in a spiritual walk with Christ—a journey. Our primary assignment is the\r\nwelfare of God\'s temple. Now it is not the temple in Jerusalem, but the temple of our hearts\r\nand minds where God has now taken up residence within us (2Cor. 6:16, John 4:20-24).', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(492, 134, 'Since God is more concerned with our spiritual well-being before anything else, He has made\r\nspiritual provisions for His people to see that we succeed in our journey and that the temple\r\nof the inner-man gets rebuilt. But the temple of our hearts and minds do not get rebuilt\r\novernight. The point when we wereborn again and gave our lives to Christ was only the\r\nbeginning of the journey, and the re-building is an on-going process called sanctification. The\r\nprovisions which God the Father has made for us in this regard include:', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(493, 134, '<li>The sacrificial blood of His Son Jesus, which cleanses us from sin and grants us access into covenant relationship with God (1John 1:7, Matt. 26:28).</li>', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(494, 134, '<li>The Holy Spirit, who helps us to obey Him, and guides us into all truth (Acts 5:32,\r\nJohn 16:13).</li>', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(495, 134, '<li>The Bible, which is the divine revelation of God\'s mind, counsel, direction, and will\r\nfor His people (2Tim. 3:16, 2Pet. 1:21).</li>', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(496, 134, '<li>The tool of Prayer, by which wecommunicate freely with God, expressing to Him our\r\nneeds, emotions, thanksgiving, and intercession for our fellow man (1Tim. 2:1, Luke\r\n18:1).</li>', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(497, 134, '<li>Faith, without which spiritual access is impossible (\r\nHeb. 3:19), but with which all\r\nthings are possible (Mark 9:23).</li>', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(498, 134, 'In other words, His divine power has given unto us all things that pertain to life and godliness\r\n(2Pet. 1:3). He knows weneed these provisions and therefore has made them available to us,\r\nbecause our spiritual success is of primary significance to our Father who loves us dearly. For\r\ngodliness is profitable unto all things, having promise of the life that now is, and of that which\r\nis to come (1Tim. 4:8).', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(499, 135, 'There is some uncertainty among a few theologians as to whether the people who gave\r\nmaterial items to the returning Jews were Babylonians or fellowJews. But verse 6 says “all\r\nthose who were around them...”. This positively suggests that it was the Babylonians who\r\nhelped them with the goods, since the Jews would have been the minority and the Gentiles\r\nthe majority. It also would not be the first time that God\'s sovereign handmade Israel\'s\r\ncaptors release valuables to them on their departure from bondage. In Exodus, which we\r\nstudied two years ago, we saw how God made the Egyptians give His people material goods,\r\nincluding gold and silver, as He would later do with the Babylonians (Exodus 3:21-22, 12:35-\r\n36). All this agrees with what God said through Isaiah: “you shall eat the riches of the\r\nGentiles” (Isa. 61:6).', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(500, 135, 'As wejust saw in the first teaching of this study, the first and foremost reason for the material\r\nprovisions was to ensure that the temple of God in Jerusalem got rebuilt, and that the\r\njourney which the Jews had to undertake to get there would be a successful one. In essence,\r\nthe primary reason was (and still is) spiritual. But, of course, God also knows that His people\r\nhave to take care of their bodily needs as well. The Jews had to eat, change their garments,\r\nuse soap and other hygiene products, etc. And as He provided for them, He will also provide\r\nfor us today. He knows we need finances both to take care of our physical needs and to\r\nhelpHis church accomplish many assignments in the expansion of His kingdom on earth.', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(501, 135, 'God is fully aware of our material needs, but the last thing He wants is for us to be worried\r\nabout such things. Jesus said, “Your heavenly Father knows that you have need of all these\r\nthings” (Matt. 6:32). Then He gives us the KEY to everything in the next verse: “But seek first\r\nthe kingdom of God and His righteousness, and all these things shall be ADDED unto you (v.\r\n33). As long as the Jews were seeking first to build the temple of God, their material\r\nnecessities were added unto them.', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(502, 135, 'In addition, our individual ministries, and the ministry of the church as a corporate body, will\r\nneed funds to get certain things done in order to reach the world for Christ and disciple those\r\nwho have been converted. These are significant components of revival. When we combine\r\ngenuine faith with genuine works, like James admonished, then shall we begin to see the\r\nHoly Spirit move powerfully wherever our ministry takes us. The promise from heaven is:\r\n“My God shall supply all your needs according to his riches in glory by Christ Jesus” (Phil.\r\n4:19). If we seek the kingdom first, no devil on earth will be able to stop that promise from\r\nbeing fulfilled in the lives and ministries of God\'s people.', '2018-11-02 13:23:04'),
(503, 136, 'Verse 7 above states that Nebuchadnezzar had put God\'s vessels into the heathen temple of\r\nhis own gods, which wealso find recorded in 2Chron. 36:7 and Dan. 1:2. As if this was not bad\r\nenough, Daniel chapter 5 records how Nebuchadnezzar\'s descendant Belshazzar threw a\r\nparty, and used those vessels of the Almighty God to drink wine with his wives, concubines,\r\nand princes. As they mocked and disrespected the God of Israel, they also praised the images\r\nof their own gods (v. 4). It is notable that God\'s vessels had been in the temple of the\r\nBabylonian gods for decades, and it wasthis deeply perverted act by Belshazzar that\r\nprovoked divine judgement on the Babylonians which led to the take-over by a name\r\nkingdom, the Medes and Persians (v. 22-31).', '2018-11-02 13:39:45'),
(504, 136, 'There is spiritual application to this reality. Every backslider has not only taken themselves\r\ninto Babylon, they have also taken all the treasures of God like gift of the spirit, fruit of the\r\nspirit, encounters, revelations etc. in the same manner as Nebuchadnezzar put God\'s vessel\r\nin the temple of heathen gods.', '2018-11-02 13:39:45'),
(505, 136, 'True revival begins when we not only return, but make effort to restore every wasted hour, resource and investment of God. It is a proven fact that when a Christian backslides and returns to the Lord, the risk to go back is high. Why? The treasures are still in the world. It is only when a man returns to the Lord and reactivate sall those spiritual investments as soon as he returns that he gains stability. For example, if a man used to pray for two hours before backsliding, the only way to survive the return to the Lord is to maintain the same level or the return becomes sporadic and inconsistent.', '2018-11-02 13:39:45'),
(506, 137, 'It was time to bring back the articles of worship to Jerusalem where they belonged, after\r\nbeing in a Babylonian temple for almost seventy years. Revival takes off when we realise that\r\nwe have neglected the fundamental instruments of worship, then we begin to bring them\r\nback as we repent and re-commit our hearts and minds towards serving God. It is interesting\r\nthat the author of Hebrews says that the earthly articles for the temple were only a shadow\r\nof the heavenly things (Heb. 8:5). For God\'s people today under the new covenant in Christ,\r\nthis means that the focus has shifted from the earthly to the heavenly, and that\'s where we\r\nshould set our affection (Col. 3:1-2). It is also interesting to note that of all the articles which\r\nwere brought back to the temple in Jerusalem, nothing is said about the golden lampstand,\r\nthe table for show bread, the golden altar for incense, and the most important article of them\r\nall—the Ark of the Covenant. The Ark was specifically where God\'s Presence dwelt upon the\r\nmercy seat between the two cherubim (Ex. 25:22, Num. 7:89). In as much as they returned, it\r\nappears that important parts of their legacy with God cannot be found again. This is the\r\ndisaster of backsliding. In as much as God will have mercy, forgive and accept us back unto\r\nHimself, there are certain things that a life cannot get back after returning to Christ, hence a\r\nneed to remain with the Lord at all times. It can be likened to a man who is bruised. Of course\r\nit will heal but the scar tends to remain forever. If a woman goes into fornication and a child is\r\nborn out of wedlock, such will remain forever until another comes to accept the woman as\r\nshe is, even though on God\'s side, she is forgiven and heaven-bound.', '2018-11-02 13:39:45'),
(507, 138, 'Ezra 2:1 ends with the phrase “...everyone to his own city.” These were Jews that were leaving\r\none city (Babylon) and relocating to another (their different cities in Judah). They were leaving the ambience of a sophisticated city lifestyle in Babylon to the ruins of their old cities\r\nthat had been laid to waste for decades. Jerusalem was now old school and not a desired place to be, yet they have made up their mind to leave the enjoyment of Babylon to stay in the place where the temple of God is, even when it means they will lose all. Please note that on their return, they did not congregate together in the centre of the city.<br/>\r\nThe scripture says, everyone went into their specific city. They came back to find their specific\r\nplace of assignment. They understood that for every location in the scheme of God, there is an allocation of divine responsibility to be discovered. They did not clutter in the central city\r\nwhere everything may look safer and a little better, they were willing to take a step further\r\ninto their local areas of assignment even when it was lower in sophistication and honour than\r\nwhere they were coming from. It is similar to someone who wants to serve at a central choir at the convention and find sit difficult to be an active and faithful disciple-maker at the local fellowship. The children of Israel were clear about their decision— they have not left the comfort of Babylon to seek any pleasure in Jerusalem. They knew their own local place and\r\nthey went there as their place of primary assignment, whether it was an unknown village or a town that had become rubble.', '2018-11-02 13:50:54'),
(508, 138, '“Every one to his own city” also shows us that not all persons are called to the same area. For\r\nexample in 1Cor 12 we see a picture of Christians as being members of Christ\'s Body. The\r\nhand has its role to play, which is different from the role of the foot. The eyes have their job to\r\ndo, but not the same office as the ears. God is not only calling us out of modern Babylon, He is\r\ncalling everyone to his own city—his own service for the kingdom and his location in the\r\nbroader body of Christ. Revival involves making the conscious decision to begin to move out\r\nand to move fully into our area of calling.', '2018-11-02 13:50:54'),
(509, 139, '<i>“Now these are the people of the province who came back from the captivity”... </i>This is how the passage begins before going into the details of those who returned from Babylon in the first wave. Some may wonder if these names, families, numbers, cities, etc really needed to be stated particularly. But we know from Scripture that God does take note of the specifics, e.g. Psalm 147:4—\"He counts the number of the stars, He calls them all by their names”. God\r\nis a God of details and anyone who wants to make great value in kingdom service must be a master in this area. When you are asked about the number of converts at your last December retreat, you cannot remember, let alone recall the total number of active fellowships under your watch? It will be a bigger shame if we go further and ask about details of the individual fellowship members or where the fellowship properties are kept. You serve a God who cares about the details of the people He leads, even down to our physical body—“the very hairs of your head are all numbered” (Matt. 10:30).', '2018-11-02 13:53:35'),
(510, 140, 'Scanning through the list in Ezra 2, we notice that there is order and sequence in the presentation. Verses 2-35 give us the numbers of people who returned to various towns in Judah (“everyone to his own city” 2:1). Verses 36-39 give us the numbers and families of\r\npriests who returned. 40-42 give us the numbers and families of Levites, that is, descendants of the tribe of Levi who were not priests, including singers and gatekeepers. 43-54 give us the\r\nchildren of the Nethinim (i.e., temple servants), 55-57 give us the children of Solomon\'s servants, and verse 58 is the total number of both groups.', '2018-11-02 13:53:35'),
(511, 140, 'From verses 59-63, a very significant problem arises. In verses 59-60, there were 652 people\r\nwho had left certain towns of Babylon with the Jews, but these people could not prove from\r\nthe recorded genealogy that they were indeed descendants of Israel. To further complicate\r\nmatters, verses 61-63 state that there were some others who were supposedly children of\r\npriests, but they also could not find their births listed in the record of genealogy. [Only\r\ndescendants of Aaron could qualify as priests (Ex. 28:1, Lev. 21:1, Num. 16:39-40)]. Because\r\nof their lost identity, the governor excluded these people from serving as priests. They\r\nbecame cut off and cast away because their memorial with God has been deleted with time\r\nand they have no mention or memorial in the scheme of God. May we not lose our identities\r\nin Jesus name.', '2018-11-02 13:53:35'),
(512, 141, 'From the reading of the text, it is quite obvious that the Jews who returned had a businesslike\r\nmentality towards their divine assignment of restoring the temple. There was no looking\r\nfor old friends or any sight-seeing. No pity party of any kind. There was no distraction. They\r\nhad a clear focus on the goal that needed to be accomplished. When a person understands\r\nhe is on the Lord\'s assignment, there is a sense of urgency that usually accompanies that\r\nunderstanding. Such a man does not get confused with multiple assignments that come on\r\nhis way. He knows the single most important assignment and will not succumb to the\r\npressure of accepting other tasks that will become a distraction or waste of time. Why do you\r\naccept a role that God has not called you to? Why do you fear what men would say at the\r\ndetriment of laying hold on the most important assignment that the Lord has given you?<br/>\r\nOnce we realise that this is God\'s business (Luke 2:49), our chief focus will be to see the task\r\nto completion, and this will be a fuel-source that keeps us going until the mission is\r\nfulfilled—“My food is to do the will of Him that sent me, and to finish His work” (John 4:34). Finishing His work will require full attention on our part, because there is an enemy called Satan who desires the exact opposite for us. He is called the tempter (Matt. 4:3), and he uses temptations of roles of honour and recognition as a major tactic to distract us from finishing God\'s work.', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(513, 141, 'These gracious men were ready for business, after being so long in Babylon. They did not come to seek any other assignment. It is the mandate of revival or nothing else and they were too convinced to be distracted.', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(514, 142, '<i>“...Offered freely for the house of God, to set it up in its place” (2:68).</i><br/>\r\nThe heads of the Jewish fathers were not only ready for business, they were also willing to\r\nsacrifice whatever was necessary to see that the temple got rebuilt. They offered freely for the house of God, why?“to set it up in its place.”We understand the building of the temple is\r\nthe building of lives because the Bible makes it clear that we are now the temple of the living\r\nGod— the house in which God resides. Like the Jews, our biggest assignment is the business\r\nof building the temple of the Lord in the hearts and lives of men. The mandate of raising a\r\nrevival army is a conscious effort to invest and deposit in a life through discipleship until such\r\nbecomesa living temple of God. The measure of our success is how many lives did we make a living temple of God in our ministry.', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(515, 142, 'In addition to their focus to freely offer gifts for the building, they also “set it up in its place.”\r\nWhen building lives for the Lord, we must complement it by understanding the need to set\r\nthem in the right place. They must be established and grounded on specific foundational\r\ntruth and with a clear idea of their position and placement in God. We cannot raise men and\r\nwomen who do not understand their placement in divine purpose; we cannot raise those\r\nwho are tossed to and fro with no sense of their place in divine purpose. Every discipleship\r\npractice that sustains a revival move is hinged on setting people up in their functional and\r\nspiritual place in God. Everyone raised in this vision of revival must be fortified to become\r\npillars carrying the weight of revival in all our local churches.', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(516, 143, 'Verse 69 of our text says <i>“they gave according to their ability unto the treasure of the work.”</i><br/>\r\nIt further shows how they gave gold, silver, and garments for priests. They gave as generously as they possibly could, demonstrating the value they placed on the work of God\'s kingdom.<br/>\r\nGod had made provisions available to them when they were leaving Babylon (Ezra 1:5-6), and now they were making provisions available for God. They did not deny God all the provisions\r\nHe graciously made available. They gave and went beyond measures. David knew this. In 1Chron. chapters 28 & 29, we see how David, Solomon, and the Israelites made great provision in preparation for the construction of the first temple. David in 29:14-16 says in his prayer to God:', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(517, 143, '<i>14 But who am I, and what is my people, that we should be able to offer so willingly after this sort? for all things come of thee, and of thine own have we given thee.15 For we are strangers before thee, and sojourners, as were all our fathers: our days on the earth are as a shadow, and there is none abiding.16 O Lord our God, all this store that we have prepared to build thee a house for thine holy name cometh of thine hand, and is all thine own.</i>', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(518, 143, 'He understood that whatever they had offered freely for the temple belonged to the Lord to\r\nstart with, and it was God who had prospered them. Paul, in his instruction to the church,\r\nencouraged them to give offerings according to how God had prospered them (1Cor. 16:1-2).\r\nBut incredibly, there were some Christians (in Macedonia specifically) who were willing to\r\ngive even beyond their ability (2Cor. 8:3). We must give our time, physical strength, mental\r\nabilities, money, and other resources towards the cause of Christ. How many of us today are\r\nwilling to go that far for the Lord? Epaphras gave himself for a great cause. Paul spoke of his\r\nzeal again to the Colossian church, “For I bear him record, that he has a great zeal for you, and\r\nthem that are in Laodicea, and them in Hierapolis” (Col. 4:12-13). His contribution to the\r\nspread of the Gospel cannot be precisely measured, but from Paul\'s words we know he gave\r\nhis all, and even beyond. When there is genuine zeal for the Lord, revival does happen.', '2018-11-02 14:18:55'),
(519, 144, 'When the time came for them to come together, they all left their various towns to gather for\r\na specific purpose. Remember that after they arrived in Judea from Babylon, the different\r\nfamilies went to their different towns in Judea (Ezra 2:1, 70), which represents how we must\r\ndeepen the work of revival at our local fellowships, while also being available when we are\r\nneeded to gather as a central or zonal spiritual family.Clearly, the different families did not\r\nhave different agendas. They knew the fundamental reason why God used Cyrus to release\r\nthem to their own land; that reason being to “build the house of the LORD God of\r\nIsrael...which is in Jerusalem” (Ezra 1:3). This was the main agenda. So all of God\'s people\r\nwere united in purpose. They were galvanised around the common purpose. No man had any\r\nsecret agenda. No one was seeking position or desire to amass wealth, title or recognition.', '2018-11-02 14:31:39'),
(520, 144, 'This was also the case with the first century disciples of Christ after His death, resurrection,\r\nand ascension back to heaven. “And when the day of Pentecost was fully come, they were all\r\nwith one accord in one place” (Acts 2:1). The total number of disciples at that time was about one hundred and twenty (Acts 1:15). “They were all with one accord in one place”, which coincidentally, like the Jews in Ezra 3:1, was a place in Jerusalem. Jesus had instructed them\r\nbefore His departure to “tarry in the city of Jerusalem, until you are endued with power from on high” (Luke 24:49, Acts 1:4). If we want to see true revival, there must be unity. Sis X cannot\r\nbe holding a grudge against Bro Y and subgroup A cannot hold itself back because subgroup B\r\nmade them do more work than they had planned at a previous event. We should always be “endeavouring to keep the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace” because “there is one\r\nBody, and one Spirit...” (Eph. 4:3-4). Jesus said the world will know we are His disciples only\r\nwhen they see the love we have for one another (John 13:35).', '2018-11-02 14:31:39'),
(521, 145, 'The returning Jews knew that it would take them a significant amount of time to get the\r\ntemple rebuilt. However, this did not stop them from reinstating the worship of the God of\r\nIsrael. They understood that as long as they could set up the most essential element required\r\nfor worship, i.e. the sacrificial altar, then the journey couldbegin. No excuse will hold them\r\nback from starting something.', '2018-11-02 14:31:39'),
(522, 145, 'The ancient patriarchs always built altars as a point of connection and communion with God.\r\nNoah, after coming off the Arkafter the Flood, built an altar unto the Lord (Gen.\r\n8:20).Abraham built at least four different altars at different locations (Gen. 12:7, 8, 13:18,\r\n22:9). Same for Isaac (Gen. 26:25), Jacob (33:20, 35:1-3), Moses (Ex. 17:15, 24:4), Joshua\r\n(Josh. 8:30), Gideon (Judges 6:24), Manoah, the father of Samson (Judges 13:19-20), and\r\nElijah (1Kings 18:30-32).', '2018-11-02 14:31:39'),
(523, 145, 'Now let us analyse how the altar was built. Ezra 3:3 says “they built the altar on its\r\nfoundation” (\'bases\' KJV). The underlined word in the original Hebrew is mekonah; it means a\r\npedestal or spot or a fixed resting-place. It basically means a foundation that is prepared to\r\nhold up something else. The Jews could have reared up the altar anywhere at the temple site,\r\nbut they located the true foundation of the altar and re-built upon it. This is an important\r\nlesson for us. 1Cor. 3:11 says “For no other foundation can anyone lay than that which is laid\r\ndown, which is Jesus Christ.” Jesus Himself is our foundation. If we try to build apart from\r\nHim, we are wasting our time. Building on Him also means building according to His Word,\r\nupon the right Biblical foundations. We cannot approach God just anyhow we think, just as\r\nthe Jews could not build the altar on just any spot. Even Moses, before he built the\r\ntabernacle, was admonished by God to make sure he constructed everything according to\r\nthe pattern that was shown to him (Ex. 25:40, Heb. 8:5). So our attitude towards God when\r\nseeking revival and restoration must be based on His terms, not ours. We must construct our\r\naltars based on Biblical principles only. Notice that Ezra 3:3 says the Jews were afraid of the\r\nstrangers that had settled around them, but they nevertheless did what they had to do. We\r\nmust not let the fear of man bring a snare (Prov. 29:25), which has caused many to\r\ncompromise on their walk with Christ. We must build according to how the Lord shows us\r\nregardless of how others may look at us or the threat that this may bring.', '2018-11-02 14:31:39'),
(524, 146, 'The quality of a building is easily determined by the foundation. The deeper and more\r\nqualitative a foundation, the better the stability and the height of a building. The foundation\r\nof a 20-storey building can never be the same as a bungalow. The purpose and intent of each\r\nbuilding inform the nature of its foundation. In the same way, the quality of the foundation\r\nwe lay will determine the stability and height to which the temple of the Lord that we are\r\nbuilding in the hearts of men will go. Revival process requires building solid foundations that\r\nstand the test of time. These solid foundations are built on undiluted discipleship, prayers\r\nand qualitative ministry of the word and not on excitement, fun or a miracle galore show that\r\ncannot provide the right footing or establishment in the principles of Christ.', '2018-11-02 14:47:40'),
(525, 146, '2Tim. 2:19 describes the nature of the foundation of the Lord as that which stands sure. It\r\nstands the test of time and is unchangeable by time or season. It is not adjustable to\r\nindividual nuances or tastes. It cannot be bent to suit our desires and interests. The Bible\r\nfurther describes that the seal of this foundation is,“the Lord knows them that are His, and,\r\nLet everyone that names the name of Christ depart from iniquity.” There is a direct\r\nconnection between the spiritual foundation of revival and a conscious departure from\r\niniquity. The ultimate seal of the foundation of revival is that <b>EVERYONE THAT NAMES THE NAME OF CHRIST MUST DEPART FROM INIQUITY.</b> Any pursuit of revival that permits\r\nindulgence in open or secret sin is an error. Any lifestyle of iniquity weakens the foundation of\r\nrevival and makes the house collapse with the consequence of death to everyone associated\r\nwith it. It is like the backsliding Samson whose eyes have been plucked away, but who chose\r\nto die by making the house collapse on himself and killing thousands that he could have\r\nactually saved. This is what sin does to the foundation of revival. It destroys the life of the\r\nrevival agent or leader and the implications spread to the point of destroying the faith of\r\nmany. The true move of revival collapses and the move of God dies as soon as sin is\r\npermitted. When we permit pleasure, indulge in anythinggoes activities or de-emphasise\r\nthe walk of holiness, weweaken the work of revival to the root and make the labours of many\r\nyears fall into rubble.', '2018-11-02 14:47:40'),
(526, 146, 'This reality is also evident from Jesus parable about the two builders (Matt. 7:24-27). The\r\nfoundation is what holds everything else up, and Jesus connects this with obeying His words.\r\nOne man built a solid foundation upon a rock. In the parallel account in Luke, it says he\r\n“dugdeep” (Luke 6:48) before laying his foundation. Revival will require us to dig deep our\r\nown foundation. It cannot be shallow or ephemeral. We cannot afford to be like the second\r\nbuilder, who without a foundation built his house upon the sand. Later, when the rain of life\r\ndescended, and the floods came, and the winds blew, and beat upon that house, it fell and\r\ncrumbled horrifically. Without a foundation based on the solid rock of God\'s Word,\r\nconsistent discipleship and a walk of holiness, there cannot be any lasting revival. When\r\ntemptations, trials, persecutions, and other challenges come, only lives who are rooted and\r\nfirmly established on the foundation of truth will stand sure.\r\n<h3>Week 15 ends here and week 16 starts below</h3>', '2018-11-02 14:47:40'),
(527, 147, 'The event of making the foundation for the temple had a dual experience – a mixture of the\r\nloud weeping from the old people and the shouts of excitement from the young. As we saw in\r\nthe scripture, the elders were weeping because they had seen the first temple—the better\r\ntemple that was destroyed when Nebuchadnezzar moved them to Babylon. This was the\r\ntemple that David carefully prepared for and Solomon actually built. Modern estimates\r\nindicate that the temple was built with materials worth $5-8 billion (over 2 trillion naira!).\r\nClearly for the elders, the new foundation being laid looked pale in comparison to\r\nSolomon\'s, which was later a question posed by God Himself through the prophet Haggai\r\n(Hag. 2:3).', '2018-11-02 14:47:40'),
(528, 147, 'The young men had only heard stories about the glory of Solomon\'s first temple but never\r\nsaw it. They shouted for joy because they were excited to be partakers of history, as this\r\nevent marked a renewal and rededication of Israel to God. This is the only one they had ever\r\nseen and anyone could identify with the excitement of young people when seeing\r\nsomething new. They have no sense of history, hence their sense of judgement and\r\nappreciation is limited. They judge by what they see now. They respondto the pulse of the\r\nmoment. As far as they are concerned, the fellowship must modernise to the prevailing\r\ntrends. They want some shouts and liveliness. This is what they see in every other fellowship\r\nthey go and often take this as the standard because they did not know where the mandate\r\nwas coming from. However, it is important to recognise that the making of a true revival is a\r\nmix of the cry of the old with the energy of the new. In a true revival, there must always be\r\nthe “elders” who know the past and who can always communicate the burden in genuine\r\ncries so that there is no sense of “we have arrived” or distraction or any form of change of\r\nfocus. They always come with emotions to capture the depth of the labour of yesterdays and\r\nwhy the core of the work must always be preserved and undiluted. When a revival move\r\nloses its sense of history, it cannot attain its purpose for the future. If no one is there to tell us\r\nabout the earlier years of TACEF—the birthing, the fasting, the sacrifice, the pains and the\r\npassion, we may lose our sense of identity, calling and pursuit. It is important to note here\r\nthat the voice of the elders always comes across as a cry because emotion is involved. They\r\nsaw it before and they cannot afford to see it reduce in size and in value. They live on the\r\nborders of outburst and inner expression, which are oftentimes not understood by the\r\nyoung ones. This cry of the “elders” can therefore be confusing to the younger ones,\r\nespecially when they are expressed in form of a sharp rebuke, correction or an emotional\r\noutburst. To the young ones, their natural reaction oftentimes is—“what more do they want\r\nus to do that wehave not done” or “we are also doing our best—so what?”', '2018-11-02 14:47:40'),
(529, 147, 'In the same vein, the innocent energy and the exuberance of the young men are definitely\r\nneeded as raw materials to activate and sustain the work. A work that cannot be transferred\r\nto the next generation is not worth the labour. The young ones come with new ideas of\r\nmodernity and sophistication in their quest to make the work more attuned to the time they\r\nlive in. They will want modern musical instruments, fun-filled activities mixed with\r\nspirituality, novel use of the media, contemporary messages that fuse spiritual life and\r\ncareer demands etc. These are useful to consider but must not contradict the spirit of the\r\nvision. For example, if the modern times we live in make it feel that it is “cool” to use online\r\nchannels to raise money for the work of God through crowdfunding, we need the cries of the\r\nelders to provide the check-and-balance and remind us of how God met and supplied all the\r\nneeds of the vision at various stages without human help. If it is now the norm for a\r\ncomedian to mount the podium in churches, the cries of the elders must always remind us\r\nthat TACEF, like the nation of Israel, is not like other nations and as such this can never be\r\npermitted no matter what. It is very important that elders must let their cries be heard\r\nespecially on matters of God\'s leading per time, God\'s sovereign ability to provide, and the\r\nimportance of keeping to the orders of core discipleship no matter the pressures of\r\nsophistication. This must, however, be done in love and understanding, with utmost sense of\r\na genuine caring heart.', '2018-11-02 14:47:40'),
(530, 148, 'Verse 1 of our study says the adversaries “heard” that the Jews were building the temple of\r\nGod. The loud shouts of joy and weeping from the Jews after they had laid the foundation\r\nwas heard from afar off (Ezra 3:13). So, these people came to investigate the rumours that\r\nhad spread, with a malicious intent in their hearts. In the same vein, the enemies of Christ are\r\nalso usually waiting for the latest news about God\'s people. They also understand that the\r\nbest time to come is not when the full building is ready, it is actually when the foundation is\r\nbeing laid. The enemy knows how to attack early, not waiting for the finished building. They\r\nwant to attack the divine assignment as early as possible in order to make sure the project\r\nnever gets completed. That\'s also why the devil attacks children and youths even before they\r\nbecome adults, as he tries to get them early. It is not uncommon to hear that cults are now in\r\nsecondary schools, even some primary schools. The devil is seeking for foundations to\r\ncollapse early. He is now very impatient as he sees that his time is coming to an end with the\r\nsecond coming of Jesus. He wants to take as many as possible to hell.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(531, 148, 'In Jesus parable in Luke 14:28-30, we saw that the devil\'s plan was to make a mockery of us,\r\nsaying “this man began to build, and was not able to finish.” We must expect our adversary\r\nthe devil (1Pet. 5:8) to walk around like a roaring lion, seeking whom he may devour. Once he\r\nhears and sees that you are building lives for God in a local fellowship or have started a work\r\nof discipleship on a campus, he comes to strike, even at the foundation stage. The devil will\r\ndeploy all tactics to distract us and weaken our hands. He will use temptations of the flesh,\r\npersecution from people, financial challenges, and any other ploy to prevent you from\r\nfollowing Christ fully. But the good news is that even as the enemy pays attention to our lives\r\nand what we are doing in Christ, so also does the Omnipresent God whom we serve pay\r\nattention. He has promised that He will never leave us nor forsake us even as His spirit dwells\r\nin us. We must not succumb to any pressure from the opposing forces, rather we should trust\r\nthat the same God who gave us the grace to lay the foundation and begin building will also\r\nsee to it that we finish the work.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(532, 149, 'The Samaritans sought to do some kind of damage to the Jews\' plans forrebuilding. But they\r\ndid not come against them with direct violence, instead, they used a half-truth to try and\r\nentice their way into building together with the Jews as friends. They said “we seek your God\r\nas ye do, and we do sacrifice unto Him since the days of Esar-haddon king of Assur, who\r\nbrought us here.” This was a half-truth because the Samaritans partially worshipped Yahweh\r\nGod of Israel, but simultaneously also worshipped the Mesopotamian gods. For emphasis,\r\nSamaritans were a mixed-race (half-cast), the descendants of the Mesopotamians who had\r\nintermarried with Israelites. They worshipped Yahweh God of Israel and also worshipped the\r\ngods of their ancestors (2Kings 17:41). So, when they told Zerubbabel that they served the\r\nsame God as the Jews, it was indeed a lie. This is actually reminiscent of the encounter of\r\nJesus and the Samaritan woman in John 4:9, when she said, “the Jews have no dealings with\r\nthe Samaritans”.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(533, 149, 'This is the language of the enemy in his attempt to make us backslide. They always come to\r\nsay they are also born-again Christians, tongue-talking and Bible-quoting, yet they keep\r\nboyfriends, lie, steal, indulge in betting etc. This “it-doesn\'t-matter” wave of error is based\r\non this reality and we must be careful not to be carried away.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(534, 149, 'Today, the church has mixed it up with“seeker-friendly” compromises. Entertainment is now\r\na big factor, as some churches even rely on comedy shows to attract people to church. The\r\nstandards of God have been lowered. People can even dress any way they like(sometimes\r\nprovocatively) and are allowed to mount the podium half-naked. Secular music has infiltrated\r\nsome churches. And so the list goes on. This practice of mixing original with fake is called\r\nsyncretism and was described by Paul as “has a form of godliness but denies the power\r\nthereof” (2Tim. 3:5).', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(535, 149, 'The modern churches who mix God\'s Word with secular worldliness are playing with fire.\r\nEven James 4:4 warns us that friendship with the world is enmity against God. We must not\r\nallow the counterfeit of modern day Samaritans to corrupt the true worship of God.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(536, 150, 'Zerubbabel, Jeshua, and the elders of Israel responded to the Samaritans with a firm NO,\r\nwhen they requested permission to help build the temple of God. They said,“Ye have nothing\r\nto do with us to build a house unto our God, but we ourselves together will build unto Yahweh\r\nGod of Israel”.They were very firm and definite. There was no negotiation or seeking for a\r\nmiddle point. They stood their ground. They knew who they were and would not yield to any\r\npretence of false Christianity to blend and mix up.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(537, 150, 'As a ministry called unto revival, we cannot mix our calling with the errors of time in an\r\nattempt to be politically correct. If you are a TACEFite in your local church and there is a\r\nmixture of the doctrine of Christ and heresy, you must stand for God and be firm and let your\r\nminister know about your position without being disrespectful. If your minister is using egg to\r\ndo the anointing service, be the only one that will not go out. Don\'t be deceived when they\r\nask you to do a special bath by the river or all forms of errors that are not compatible with the\r\nNew Testament realities of what Jesus completed on the cross. Be firm in your ability to\r\ndefend the truth of Christ, while still maintaining excellent human relationships. Do not\r\nbecome a spiritual politician who wants to be right with every man and yet be wrong with\r\nGod.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(538, 150, 'Like Zerubbabel, we must be on guard against such fakes and say a big NO when they or their followers request to build God\'s kingdom with us.', '2018-11-02 15:00:40'),
(539, 151, 'The phrase \'weakened their hands\' is a Hebrew figure of speech which means to discourage\r\nor frustrate. The Samaritans were using various means to discourage the Jews from carrying\r\non with the project. Satan uses different life circumstances to discourage us from marching\r\nforward in our walk with Christ. This is especiallypeculiar to anyone who has a special\r\nassignment and mandate to do for the Lord. These frustrations emerge in the form of\r\nseemingly unsolvable financial crises, and the enemy throws doubts into our minds about\r\nGod\'s promises to provide for us, and some even begin to consider looking to alternative\r\nungodly means. Sickness strikes some Christians unexpectedly, and lack of medical or\r\nsupernatural cure is used by the enemy to make us feel discouraged, shaking the faith of\r\nsome. Parents see their children going down the wrong path in life and cannot control or\r\nchange them even after many prayers. Seeds of uncertainty are then sown and this beginsto\r\ntake rootin the minds of these Christian parents. Other sources the devil uses to discourage\r\nGod\'s people include lack of academic success, looking for a husband/wife for years without\r\nresults, no fruit of the womb after marriage, continued unemployment, and other such\r\nbecause of pressure from the people, he compromised on God\'s Word (1Sam. 15). After\r\nfailed attempts at trying to explain himself to Samuel, he finally confessed,“I feared the\r\npeople, and obeyed their voice” (15:24).', '2018-12-03 19:02:31'),
(540, 152, 'Many of us fear what will become of our career, our future or even our children, and this is\r\nforcing us in to doing things that are ungodly. How do you explain a Christian parent who\r\nplacedtheir child in a special centre because they do not want them to fail or a TACEFite who\r\naccepts a huge responsibility in the church, when God is not leading him because he is afraid\r\nthat the benefits of support he receives from the church will stop? Be aware that the devil\r\nwill not sit back and let revival happen without challenging it. He will use any means\r\nnecessary, including using human vessels to make us afraid of doing what God wants. The\r\nremedy, like Jesus said, is to fear the Almighty God instead, and not mortal man. This is the\r\nsame advice wefind in Isaiah 8:12-13 –“...neither fear ye their fear, nor be afraid. Sanctify the\r\nLORD of hosts Himself, and let Him be your fear, and let Him be your dread”.', '2018-12-03 19:02:31'),
(541, 153, 'Ezra 4:5 shows that an additional strategy of the Samaritans was to hire counsellors (legal\r\nadvisors) against the Jews to frustrate their plans. The amazing part is that this happened “all\r\nthe days of Cyrus king of Persia.” In verse 3, when Zerubbabel and the elders said NO to the\r\nSamaritans, they made sure to remind them that they had authorisation from Cyrus (“as\r\nking Cyrus, the king of Persia has commanded us”). But the Samaritans somehow succeeded\r\ninspite of the fact that it was Cyrus himself whogave the commandment to build the temple,\r\nand the Jews ceased from building the temple because of their enemies (Ezra 4:24). So you\r\nmay ask, where was Cyrus, whom God had charged to build the temple (Ezra 1:1-3)? How\r\ncould he allow the Samaritans to force the Jews to stop the work? Perhaps his mind was\r\noccupiedwith concerns of governing his vast empire and dealing with problems from\r\ndifferent regions?', '2018-12-03 19:02:31'),
(542, 153, 'Cyrus actually died and he never completed the temple which God put in his heart to release\r\nthe children of Israel to build and the temple did not get rebuilt until the reign of Darius\r\nabout fifteen years later. What is the lesson here? Well, the Jews could have placed more\r\nconfidence in Cyrus than they placed inGod Himself! They over-emphasised his authority,\r\ninstead of depending on God\'s authority as supreme above all. It is therefore no surprise, as\r\nwe see, that Cyrus let them down and disappointed them. The Almighty God will share His\r\nglory with no-one (Isa. 42:8), especially when He sees His people putting more confidence in\r\nthat person instead of in Him. The Jews should have read Psalm 118:8-9, which says “It is\r\nbetter to trust in the LORD than to put confidence in man. It is better to trust in the LORD\r\nthan to put confidence in princes”. Or Psalm 60:11 which says “Give us help from trouble,\r\nfor vain is the help of man”.<br/>\r\n', '2018-12-03 19:02:31'),
(543, 153, 'It is true that God will use people to help us, but we must NEVER place so much confidence\r\non people instead of depending on God above all else. God can use anyone to help us in the\r\npursuit of revival but be careful that they do not become more important in your life than\r\nGod. People who have been a blessing to you can turn their backs on you and be absent\r\nwhen they are needed most because God will never allow any man to share in His glory. If you\r\nhave a type of Cyrus as an uncle who promised you an education to university level, be\r\ncareful not to make a “god” out of him because the building of our lives (both spiritually and\r\nmaterially) may become delayed for several years like the building of the Jewish temple.\r\nMany sisters are finding it difficult to break off from their old unbeliever boyfriends, who has\r\nbecome a mini god in their lives because he is the one helping to pay school fees. When a man\r\ngoes into ministry because someone promised to be a major sower, it will only take a few\r\ndays before the person realises that we must never rely on men for our material/financial\r\nadvancement in this world. God will use people to help us, but we must look to Him directly\r\nand place Him above any human. Revival will progress greatly without delay when we shift\r\nour expectations from human sources and authorities, to God\'s Omnipotent authority and\r\ncapacity to supply all our needs.', '2018-12-03 19:02:31'),
(544, 154, 'As mentioned in the introduction to study, Ezra 4:7-23 is dealing with the Jews who came\r\nback to Jerusalem with Ezra as described in chapter 7. In Ezra 4:6, weare not given the details\r\nof the letter written against the Jews during the reign of Ahasuerus. But we are given the\r\ncontents of the letter written to Artaxerxes who ruled after him. Verse 12 clearly shows us\r\nthat they were addressing the Jews who came from Artaxerxes in Mesopotamia and had\r\ntravelledto Jerusalem. This is exactly what happened in Ezra 7, which tells the story of the\r\nsecond wave of returning exiles. Yes, after the first return—another set of people returned.', '2018-12-03 19:13:54'),
(545, 154, 'Verses 11-16 give the exact content of the letter. The accusation is that if Artaxerxes allows\r\nthe Jews to rebuild and restore Jerusalem, they will go back to their old ways of rebelling\r\nagainst emperors, and the king will lose revenue, as these Jews have shown in the past that\r\nthey do not like to pay taxes (“toll, tribute, and custom”). They encourage the king to check\r\nthe historicalrecords and read about Jerusalem and their rebellious tendency, which was\r\nwhat, according to the accusers, caused the city to be destroyed. This is the ministry of the\r\ndevil, who is the accuser of the brethren in an attempt to bring to remembrance our past\r\nbefore the Lord. We must always assure ourselves with Isa 43 vs 25, “I, even I, am he that\r\nblotteth out thy transgressions for mine own sake, and will not remember thy sins”.', '2018-12-03 19:13:54'),
(546, 154, 'Verses 17-22 show the king\'s reply. He checked the historical records and found that\r\nJerusalem indeed had been a rebellious province, and likely saw that it was destroyed by\r\nNebuchadnezzar for that particular reason of its kings\' rebellions (2Kings 24). So, after\r\nreceiving the information concerning Jerusalem\'s past, Artaxerxes ordered that the Jews\r\nwho had returned with Ezra should cease from restoring the city (v. 21). But, he adds this\r\nstatement—“until another commandment shall be given from me”. In other words, he still\r\nconsidered allowing Jerusalem to be rebuilt sometime in the future, which is exactly what he\r\ndid thirteen years later in the twentieth year of his reign, when he permitted Nehemiah to go\r\nand rebuild Jerusalem (Neh. 2). But then, his present commandment was to stop the work,\r\nand the Samaritans quickly used that authority to force the Jews to cease (Ezra 4:23).', '2018-12-03 19:13:54'),
(547, 154, 'Verse 24 then picks up from where verse 5 left off, i.e., that the Samaritans stopped\r\nZerubbabel from completing the house of God (the temple), during Cyrus\' reign, unto the\r\nsecond year of Darius.', '2018-12-03 19:13:54'),
(548, 155, 'The way in which the Jews\' adversaries accused them before the king is reminiscent of how\r\nour adversary the devil (1Pet. 5:8) accuses us before the King of kings, that is, God (Rev.\r\n12:10). He reminds God about our sins which we have committed, just like the Samaritans\r\nreminded Artaxerxes about Jerusalem\'s past sins and rebellions. But the good news is that\r\nwe as Christians have \'overcome our accuser through the cleansing blood of the Lamb, and\r\nby the word of our testimony\' (Rev. 12:11). We are washed from our sins in the Lamb\'s blood\r\n(Rev. 1:5, 1John 1:7, Matt. 26:28), and, therefore, the Father accepts us in Christ the Beloved\r\n(Eph. 1:6-7).', '2018-12-03 19:13:54'),
(549, 155, 'Armed with this knowledge of our victory through Christ, we can confidently continue to\r\nbuild God\'s kingdom even when the adversary tries to stop us from doing so. Paul the\r\napostle, even after his enemies sent him into Roman detention (Acts 21:27-36), did not allow\r\nthat to stop him from continuing to spread the Gospel. He was eventually incarcerated by the\r\nRomans, first under house arrest, then, later in a real prison. During these times, he wrote\r\nnd five epistles altogether— Ephesians, Colossians, Philippians, Philemon, and 2 Timothy. His\r\nenemies had limited him physically, but the work of God\'s kingdom continued through his\r\nwritings. These epistles, written under conditions of imprisonment, impacted the first\r\ncentury saints and continue to impact people all over the world today. The other apostles,\r\neven after being beaten and threatened by their enemies, still continued preaching Christ\r\njoyfully under a hostile environment (Acts 5:40-42). This shows us that no matter how much\r\nthe enemy tries to make us cease from doing God\'s work, we must never succumb. We must\r\nbuild ourselves spiritually, and build God\'s kingdom by preaching and teaching Christ\r\nwherever we find ourselves on assignment. We have already overcome the accuser through\r\nJesus sacrificial blood, so we can be sure that God will back us in serving Him and carrying out\r\nHis will in our practical day-to-day lives.', '2018-12-03 19:13:54'),
(550, 156, 'After a long break of about 15 years without any action concerning the building of the\r\ntemple, God sends two prophets to urge His people to get back to work. Some Christians\r\nbegin a journey of rebuilding their lives to Christ, but they then allow the enemy to cause\r\nthem to cease halfway through the process. Some remain in spiritual hibernation for a long\r\ntime, like the Jews with the temple in Jerusalem. Some even get distracted on the assignment\r\nof revival with so many life issues. When this happens, God is always magnanimous to send a\r\nprompt, a check and a reminder, which may come through prophetic voices with an intent to\r\njolt us back into consciousness of His work and the mandate hanging over our lives. <b>This is\r\nalso how we know a real prophet from a fake, because real ones focus our attention back on\r\nthe things of God and the assignment He has for our lives and not self-serving seers whose\r\ndesire is to exploit, deceive and abuse.</b>', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(551, 156, 'While we must be careful about false prophets, the role of God\'s real prophets cannot be\r\noverstated, especially when it comes to directing mankind towards repentance, revival, and\r\nrestoration. Notable prophets who brought mass revival include people like Elijah (1Kings\r\n18:20-40) and Jonah who brought revival to the Assyrian people of Nineveh (Jonah chapter\r\n3).', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(552, 156, 'In our present age of the New Covenant, God has preserved the prophetic role (Rom. 12:6,\r\n1Cor. 12:10, 28), and appointed prophets for different reasons that benefit His people.\r\nEphesians 4:11-12 shows that a prophet may be instrumental for “the perfecting of the\r\nsaints, for the work of the ministry, for the edifying of the body of Christ.” Prophets do not just\r\nclaim to know your future (though God may reveal to some), but more importantly they are\r\npeople who activate a consciousness of God within others, especially in a generation that has\r\nbecome cut off from God because of its sins and worldliness. Prophets also bring God\'s\r\ncounsel for specific seasons and circumstances. This is what Haggai and Zechariah did. But\r\nthey took it one step further, not only speaking forth God\'s words, but standing side-by-side\r\nwith God\'s people in revival and restoration (Ezra 5:2). Their prophetic intercession paid off,\r\nas the temple finally got completed, because the Jews builded and <b><i> “prospered through the\r\nprophesying of Haggai the prophet and Zechariah the son of Iddo. And they builded, and\r\nfinished it...” (Ezra 6:14).</i></b> The prophets reached the consciences of the people and provoked\r\na divine work in the hearts of men.', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(553, 156, 'The genuine prophets whom God has appointed among His people today seem to be few. But\r\nthis agrees with history, as God usually raises only a few men and women from among the\r\npeople to speak His revealed Word for different circumstances and scenarios. But His spoken\r\nWord and Instruction through these particular people usually becomes a catalyst that drives\r\nrevival and repentance in the hearts of the listening audience. The prophetic voice is\r\ntherefore a necessary element that God uses today in the process of revival as a way to bring\r\nthe hearts, minds, and attention of His people fully back to Himself. <b>“He that hath an ear, let\r\nhim hear what the Spirit saith unto the churches” (Rev. 2:7).</b>', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(554, 156, '<h1>Week 22 ends here and week 23 starts below</h1>', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(555, 157, 'It is true that the work was stopped through the hiring of legal advisors against the Jews which\r\ncaused them to cease building the temple during the reign of Cyrus (Ezra 4:5, 24). But in the\r\nopening chapter of Haggai\'s book, we find that there was an additional reason for the\r\ncessation which is not mentioned in Ezra. According to Haggai 1, the people had actually lost\r\ninterest in finishing the house of God, and began to focus more on their own houses. They\r\nmust have given up easily after the Samaritans challenged them, which explains why they did\r\nnot immediately protest the matter to Cyrus the king, who was the supreme ruler and had\r\nbeen charged by God to build the temple. The Jews gave up with little fight, because they had\r\ngreater concerns for their own houses and their personal well-being. Haggai\'s message from\r\nGod was firm and heart-piercing, convincing the people of their error and complacency.\r\nZerubbabel, Jeshua, and the rest of the workers rose up and continued the work only after\r\nthis prophetic voice intervened.', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(556, 157, 'The lesson for us here is that we should never put our own comfort or pleasure above God\'s\r\nwork. “For all seek their own, not the things which are Jesus Christ\'s” (Phil. 2:21). This is a big\r\nchallenge hindering revival today. Many seem to be more concerned with obtaining material\r\nthings that will help them live a pleasant lifestyle of ease, rather than performing the\r\nnecessary sacrifices that revival demands. God is not a sadist who is asking us to not live well,\r\nbut what He wants is for His people to make Him and His work their first priority and every\r\nWeek 22 ends here and week 23 starts below\r\nother thing becomes secondary.', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(557, 157, 'The lesson for us here is that we should never put our own comfort or pleasure above God\'s\r\nwork. “For all seek their own, not the things which are Jesus Christ\'s” (Phil. 2:21). This is a big\r\nchallenge hindering revival today. Many seem to be more concerned with obtaining material\r\nthings that will help them live a pleasant lifestyle of ease, rather than performing the\r\nnecessary sacrifices that revival demands. God is not a sadist who is asking us to not live well,\r\nbut what He wants is for His people to make Him and His work their first priority and every\r\nWeek 22 ends here and week 23 starts below\r\nother thing becomes secondary.\r\nJesus\' example and attitude towards God\'s work should inspire the rest of us. He consistently\r\nput the Father\'s assignment before His own earthly desires even though He was also fully\r\nhuman (Rom. 8:3, Heb. 4:15, Heb. 2:14). At the early age of twelve, He already knew that He\r\nmust “be about my Father\'s business” (Luke 2:49). His material needs, including housing,\r\nwere of secondary importance, as evidenced by His statement “Foxes have holes, and birds\r\nof the air have nests, but the Son of man has nowhere to lay His head” (Luke 9:58). After\r\nfasting for forty days, he was hungry, and the tempter tested Him, yet He still put God\'s Word\r\nbefore His own material need—“Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every Word of\r\nGod” (Luke 4:4). He echoed this same sentiment when His disciples brought Him food, and He\r\ndeclared that He already had food to eat which they were unaware of, before revealing that\r\n“My food is to do the will of Him that sent me, and to finish His work” (John 4:31-34). He\r\nconsistently viewed God\'s work as urgent, saying in John 9:4 “I must work the works of Him\r\nthat sent me while it is day, the night is approaching, when no one can work”.', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(558, 157, 'To further appreciate the issues of divine priority, Jesus left us with an instructive parable in\r\nLuke 17:7-8. In this parable, even though the servant had been working in the field all day\r\nlong, the Master does not expect him to sit down to eat and drink, until after the Master\r\nHimself has been served to full satisfaction. In other words, our own comfort is a secondary\r\nconcern in comparison to serving God and fulfilling His will. The Jews should have understood\r\nthis truth. We must never let our personal needs take priority over God\'s work. Our hearts\r\nmust always be set on what is of priority to the Lord at all times and this must be our 100%\r\ndesire.', '2018-12-03 19:29:18'),
(559, 158, 'The returnees made a mistake that caused a 15-year delay. They did not fight hard\r\nenough when the Samaritans hired counsellors against them and used other more\r\nworrisomes care tactics , they were more concerned with building their own personal houses\r\nwith less focus on the temple of the Lord.', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(560, 158, 'Blessed be God for two prophets who spoke to them in the name of the LORD, they made up\r\ntheir minds to finish the work at all cost (Ezra 5:2), this time not succumbing to the threats of\r\nthe adversary (5:5). They took a strong stand for the house of God. This is the attitude all\r\nbelievers today should adopt. We must be determined to finish God\'s work regardless of\r\nhow much troubleand the challenges we may face along the road. Paul gives us a powerful\r\nexhortation in 1Cor. 15:58—', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(561, 158, '<i>“Therefore, my beloved brethren, be ye steadfast, unmovable, always abounding in the work\r\nof the Lord, for as much as ye know that your labour is not in vain in the Lord”.</i>', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(562, 158, 'He says we must be unmovable and steadfast. This means that no matter what our spiritual\r\nenemies (Satan, evil spirits) or our human enemies throw at us, we should never allow that\r\nto stop us from doing what God is calling us to do. We should never compromise our walk\r\nwith Christ and our assignments on earth for any reason. “Always abounding in the work of\r\nthe Lord” speaks for itself. Ezra 5:5 says that Tatnai and his companions could not stop the\r\nJews from doing the work of the Lord. This is the right mind-set for Christians today. “Always\r\nabounding” includes that first word “Always”, which literally means “at all times.” This tells us\r\nthat God\'s work is continual, and we must keep our mission on our minds at all times, even\r\nwhen we are doing normal day-to-day mundane activities. Taking a strong stand for the\r\nkingdom will require determination on our part, to bring every area of our lives into\r\nagreement with the work which God has given us to do. We will begin to see the fruits of\r\nrevival and restoration only after we have made up our minds.', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(563, 159, 'As we saw in the introduction, Darius gave orders that a search should be made to ascertain\r\nwhether Cyrus ever made such an edict to rebuild the temple. The following outcome of\r\nthese events shows God\'s Hand in the affairs of His people on earth who have decided to\r\nwork for Him.\r\nLet us explore the various dimensions of divine interventions that was evident in the\r\nsituation:', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(564, 159, '<ol>\r\n<li>The finding of the scroll: The fact that a scroll which recounted Cyrus\' decree was\r\nfound is a testament to God\'s favour, support, and divine intervention. Not because a\r\nrecord of such a decree should have been difficult to find, but because of the specific\r\ncircumstances surrounding the search itself. Tatnai\'s letter advised Darius to search for\r\nthe record in the king\'s treasure house in Babylon (5:17), which is exactly what Darius did\r\n(6:1). There was no such record found at the treasure house of the rolls in Babylon. The\r\nsearch could have ended right there and then, and Darius could have concluded that the\r\nJews were liars, probably worthy of severe punishment for making false claims using king\r\nCyrus\' name. However, God\'s divine providence was not going to allow that to happen!\r\nHe will not allow His name to be brought into disrepute. Further search was made, and a\r\nscroll telling the official story of Cyrus\' decree was eventually found in a lesser known\r\npalace in the province of Achmetha (6:2).</li>', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(565, 159, '<li>The funding for the building: Cyrus\' original decree included that the building project\r\nbe funded by the royal treasury (6:4). Darius did not fail to acknowledge this as he gave\r\norders to Tatnai to make funds available to the Jews from the royal treasury in Tatnai\'s\r\nprovince (6:8). He also ordered that animals and ingredients needed for offerings to God\r\nshould be made available to the Jews (6:9). Again, this shows us God\'s Hand in the\r\nmatter, because Darius could have concluded that the commandment to help the Jews\r\nfinancially and materially was ordered under Cyrus\' reign, and Darius could easily have\r\nseen no responsibility on his part. Further confirmation is seen in 6:10, where Darius has\r\nexpectation that his goodness will be recognised and reciprocated through the Jews\'\r\nprayers for him and his sons. Can you imagine how an unbeliever can now trust the God\r\nof the Jews as worthy of being prayed to?</li>', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(566, 159, '<li>The strong warning against any opposition: Verses 11-12 have Darius making a\r\nstrong proclamation against anyone who disagreed with his commandment or tried to\r\ndestroy the temple. This is God\'s indirect power moving, ensuring that His people will\r\nfinish His work without further defeat from the enemy.</li></ol>', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(567, 159, 'This is the three-dimension hand of God on a matter, which are proofs that God is committed\r\nto supporting His work inspite of adversity or threats from the enemy. God will intervene on\r\nbehalf of His people until He has accomplished His purpose. The mandate of revival cannot\r\nbe stopped by any man and this must be our assurance, as opposition comes, God will\r\nalways rise on our behalf. As a fellowship, TACEF has learnt again and again that God truly\r\nstands for His people at all times.', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(568, 159, 'God is still here for us today. When a person takes a stand to obey God rather than men, he or\r\nshe can be assured of Heaven\'s backing and support. We must never give up when things get\r\ntough, but forge ahead in whatever mission God has given us to fulfil.', '2018-12-03 19:43:50'),
(569, 160, 'The concept of making sacrificial offerings unto the Creator and Giver of life has been known\r\nsince the time of Cain and Abel. Offerings of both animals and foodstuff continued during the\r\ntimes of the Genesis patriarchs, and was officially instituted by God in the Law of Moses. At\r\nthe completion and dedication of the second temple, it was necessary for the Israelites to\r\nexpress their gratitude towards God not only verbally but also by offering sacrifices on the\r\naltar. Verse 17 shows us that not only Judah, Benjamin, and Levi were represented, but\r\nIsraelites from all the twelve tribes. About 712 animals were offered altogether, a meagre\r\nfigure in comparison to the total number of animals offered at the dedication of Solomon\'s\r\ntemple (142,000...1Kings 8:63).', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(570, 160, 'However, before God, the quantity of the offerings is not the most important thing, but the\r\nHEART of the giver(s) behind the offering. God is very keen about the spirit behind our\r\nsacrifices and not the volume. Jesus pointed this out in Luke 21:1-4, when He declared that\r\nthe poor widow who cast in two mites had done better than the wealthy. She gave her all, but\r\nthey only gave a small fraction of their abundance. Revival will require us giving our all to the\r\nwork of the Lord both spiritually and materially. Giving requires a heart that is right with the\r\nLord. If our hearts are right, then what weoffer will be acceptable to God. Cain\'s offering was\r\nrejected, not because he was a farmer who brought the natural fruit of his labour in contrast\r\nto Abel who was a shepherd, but because his HEART was not right with God (Gen. 4:5-7). As\r\nlong as his heart was not surrendered to God, whatever he had to offer was of secondary\r\nimportance.<b>Revival is a game of the heart and any sacrificial service that does not come\r\nfrom the heart is never acceptable.</b>', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(571, 160, 'If we desire to see the true flames of revival ignited, then we must offer our entire beings to\r\nGod in holiness and righteousness. We have learnt that our most reasonable service is to\r\noffer ourselves as living sacrifices unto the Lord (Rom. 12:1-2).', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(572, 161, 'Throughout history, God has always wanted His people to be separated from uncleanness.\r\nThe popular words “consecrated” and “sanctified” carry the meanings of not just holiness or\r\npurity, but also mean to be set apart. After the temple was completed, it was also dedicated.\r\nThe word \'dedication\' (6:16-17) is the Hebrew-Aramaic word Hanukkah, which means \'an\r\ninitiation unto consecration\'. It means that something (or someone) has become set apart or\r\ndedicated for the service of God. The thing or the person has now been separated from other\r\npurposes unto one particular purpose (in this case, the worship and service of God). This is\r\nwhy Jesus was offended when He saw that the temple was being used for other purposes\r\nsuch as business (buying & selling animals for sacrifice, and money exchange) in John 2:13-\r\n16, instead of its sole purpose of being a house of prayer which is a form of worship (Matt.\r\n21:13).', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(573, 161, 'We are the temples of the living God today; the agents of revival, and He still expects the\r\nsame consecration, dedication, and separation, as we clearly see in 2Cor. 6:14-18. As Jesus\r\ndrove out the people who had turned the house of God into a business, we must get rid of\r\nphysical and spiritual strangers in our bodies. The same must be done for the corporate\r\nchurch which is now being reduced to a business venture. It is a sad story today when a\r\nminister is posted to a church with an underlying objective to use such minister to raise\r\nmoney. It is sad when we measure the success of a church or a growing parish by how much\r\nmoney they have and not by how many souls have been won to the Lord. “Ye cannot serve\r\nGod and mammon” (Matt. 6:24). The house of God MUST be dedicated to worshipping Him\r\nalone, and only then will a powerful, transformative, Holy Ghost revival break out and be\r\nexperienced by all involved.', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(574, 161, 'Separation of God\'s people is a key ingredient in bringing about revival and restoration. We\r\ncannot keep one foot in the Spirit and the other foot in worldliness. An individual cannot\r\nclaim to serve God but yet continue to wallow in filthy practices with no remorse, even as the\r\nChurch cannot claim to be the house of God while serving mammon. We cannot see any true\r\nrevival until the temple has been dedicated (or re-dedicated).', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(575, 162, 'The completion of the temple was not an end in itself, but rather it was the beginning of\r\ngreater things to come. It opened the doors for Jerusalem as a city to be rebuilt along with its\r\nwalls, and it paved the way for the Jews to be re-established as a legitimate nation in their\r\nown land with a place to connect to God. This is the same parallel of what Jesus did for\r\nthe Church 2,000 years ago when he laid the foundation of the church. His death was not the\r\nend but the beginning of greater things to come. Christ Himself was the solid rock and the\r\nfoundation of the New Testament Church (Matt. 16:18).', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(576, 162, 'The Church remains strong and still standing, although throughout the Church age there\r\nhave been several challenges for the house of God. But through revival, the Church of Christ\r\nalways gets back on track. Today\'s generation of Christians should be aware of the prophecies\r\nand promises of God that there will be a second outpouring (the “latter rain”) before our Lord\r\nand Saviour returns to this earth. Joel 2:28-32 is where the prophecy of the first outpouring is\r\nfound, which was fulfilled at Pentecost, as Peter expressly confirmed (Acts 2:16-21). Hosea\r\n6:1-3 mentions another prophecy that says God will come to us as the latter and former rain.\r\nThis indicates that the Outpouring prophecy of Joel 2 was only partially fulfilled at Pentecost\r\nin Acts 2 (the \'former rain\'), but there will also be an Outpouring of the latter rain right before\r\nJesus returns, which will bring unusual signs and wonders with it\'s coming (Joel 2:30-31). This\r\nis the understanding that captures the burden of revival that TACEF has for our generation\r\nand we believe this outpouring will happen soon to lead many unto the Lord in preparation\r\nfor the final harvest. We must be ready for this latter rain that will cause a flood of grace and\r\ndivine visitation and power missionary work into all the nations of the earth.', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(577, 162, 'The closer we draw to the Second Coming of Christ, the more we should expect and position\r\nourselves for this great revival of His Church.', '2018-12-03 19:56:31'),
(578, 163, 'By this time, eighty years had passed since the first wave of exiles returned to Jerusalem\r\n(Ezra 1 & 2), and Ezra was probably not even born yet during that first event. Ezra was born\r\nand raised in Babylon, he must have been a man after God\'s own heart in similar fashion as\r\nDavid. This is because of the way he is spoken of in chapter 7. He rejected the Babylonian\r\nsystem and sought the way of God of Israel. Even though he was born in Babylon and has\r\nnever been to Jerusalem, he has a longing for the city of the Lord. Verse 10 of our passage\r\nreveals a three-step procedure which enabled Ezra to become an agent of revival in his\r\ngeneration. As TACEFites, this is a critical ingredient we must understand to lead the process\r\nof revival in our church and generation.', '2018-12-03 20:08:34'),
(579, 163, '<ol>\r\n<li>Set the heart to seek the word of God:“For Ezra had prepared his heart to seek the\r\nLaw of the LORD.”This is the beginning of every revival move—a heart for God. The\r\nword “heart” in the Hebrew was recognised as the central organ in a human body\r\nand therefore represented the innermost being of a person. The Jews used the word\r\nto denote a person\'s deepest desires, thoughts, and intentions. So, we see that\r\nEzra\'s heart was “prepared” (literally, “set”) to seek God\'s Word. This reminds us of\r\nDaniel, who purposed in his heart to follow God\'s Law (Dan. 1:8). The word \'seek\' is\r\nthe Hebrew darash and it means to tread passionately, follow after, pursue, or\r\nsearch. Ezra pushed all distractions aside and set his heart to persistently dive into\r\nthe Scriptures and bring out the life of God in His word. He is like the man in Psalm\r\n1:1-2...”Blessed is the man that walketh not in the counsel of the ungodly, nor\r\nstandeth in the way of sinners, nor sitteth in the seat of the scornful; But his delight is\r\nin the Law of the LORD, and in His Law does he meditate day and night.” He was\r\nwholeheartedly committed to God\'s Word.</li>', '2018-12-03 20:08:34'),
(580, 163, '<li>Do God\'s word: Verse 10 says Ezra had prepared his heart to seek the Law of the\r\nLORD, and to do it. We can immediately refer to James 2:22-25, where we are\r\nexhorted to be doers of the Word and not hearers only. Verse 25 of that passage in\r\nJames says that those who look into the perfect law of liberty and do what is\r\ncontained therein will be blessed in their deeds. No wonder Ezra was blessed in his\r\ndeed, and obtained favour from God with the king, successfully leading a mass\r\nrevival from Babylon to the holy city of Jerusalem!\r\nThe DOING of God\'s Word is indispensable and cannot be replaced or substituted\r\nwith anything else. All forms of praise and worship, prayer and fasting, are short circuited\r\nif there is no obedience to the will of God. David said,“I delight to do your\r\nwill, O my God. Yes, your Law is within my heart” (Psalm 40:8).</li>', '2018-12-03 20:08:34'),
(581, 63, '<li>Teach God\'s word: Ezra did not stop at seeking and doing God\'s Word, but followed\r\nthrough to complete the process of revival by teaching others also. Act1:1 mentions\r\nthat Jesus began both to “do and teach” during His earthly ministry. So, there is order\r\nto the procedure of revival, with teaching being the last nail in the coffin of the\r\nspiritual enemies of revival. The temple had been completed and dedicated six\r\ndecades prior to Ezra\'s arrival, with offerings and worship being observed steadily,\r\nbut proper exposition of the Scripture had been missing. Ezra was a “ready” scribe in\r\nthe Law of Moses (v. 6). That word in the Hebrew is mahir which means skilled or\r\nskilful. The word also means quick or rapid. In other words, Ezra became skilled and\r\nquick asa result of his wholehearted seeking and performing. In as much as a temple\r\nexisted the word was missing and God was sending Ezra to bring a revival through\r\nthe word.</li></ol>', '2018-12-03 20:08:34'),
(582, 163, 'Any form of revival where the word of God is missing is like pouring water into an\r\nempty basket. If all the gatherings we call revival do not draw men into a new\r\nunderstanding of God through His word, they are all jamborees, even if its 100 days\r\nfasting and prayer with every day vigil. You cannot encounter a God that you do not\r\nknow and we only know Him by His word and this He honours more than His name\r\n(Psalm 138:2).\r\nIn the pursuit of revival, we must elevate Bible study or else we raise prayer\r\nmachines who are praying emotions and sensationalism and not the word of God.\r\nWe must pursue a revival of the word of God because no soul can come alive unto\r\nrighteousness without a new insight into God\'s word.', '2018-12-03 20:08:34'),
(583, 164, 'God on multiple occasions has used ordinary men to lead people out of apathy into\r\nawakening and renewed consciousness of who He is. This time, that man would be Ezra.\r\nBecause Ezra was a seeker, doer, and teacher of God\'s Word, the Lord granted him\r\nrecognition by the king, who in turn granted more Israelites freedom to go up to Jerusalem\r\nwith him (v. 11-13). Verses 7-9 of chapter 7 give a summary of how the Israelites went on the\r\nfour-month journey with Ezra from Babylon to Jerusalem, while chapter 8 gives the full\r\ndetails. It is amazing how God can use one surrendered heart to draw so many people unto\r\nHimself, after activating His word in the heart of that individual.There is no revival without\r\nmen in whose lives the word of God has become a living experience. The implication of a\r\nword-filled life was captured in the parallel of the sower (God), good ground (heart) and seed\r\n(word of God). We saw here that only the good ground (that is, the good heart) retained the\r\nWord and brought positive results (Luke 8:15). Some thirty fold, some sixty fold, some a\r\nhundred fold (Matt. 13:23). A sown seed (word)must multiply and bring forth more, so also\r\nthose who have prepared their hearts to receive, do, and teach God\'s Word will bring a\r\nmultiplication of people into God\'s harvest. This is the essence of personal and corporate\r\nrevivals. This is why the Word of Christ must dwell in us richly in all wisdom (Col. 3:16). Jesus\r\nsaid,“If you abide in me, and my words abide in you, you shall ask what you want, and it shall\r\nbe done unto you” (John 15:7). God\'s Word abided in Ezra, so, he could ask what he wanted\r\nfrom the king and it was done unto him, due to the favour and good hand of God upon him\r\n(Ezra 7:6, 27-28).', '2018-12-03 20:08:34'),
(584, 165, 'The total number of men from verses 1-14, including the heads of the families, is 1,496 + 16 =\r\n1,512 (not counting women and children). Of these men, some priests were found. Priests\r\nwere Levites who were specifically descended from Aaron, and they alone were authorised\r\nto offer the burnt sacrifices on the brazen altar, offer incense on the golden altar, and minister\r\nin the holy place, with the high priest alone appointed to enter the most holy place once a\r\nyear. But the other descendants of Levi who were not of the Aaronic lineage were simply\r\ncalled \'Levites\', and they were helpers of the priests with temple work such as gatekeeping\r\n(porters), washing the instruments used for killing and preparing offerings, playing musical\r\ninstruments, etc.<br/>\r\nEzra and his company abode by the Ahava River in Babylon for three days, and during that\r\ntime he identified some priests, but could not find any Levites. Perhaps the Levites did not\r\nwant to leave Babylon to go and engage in ancestral responsibilities of the temple. They were\r\nindifferent to the call of God, but that did not discourage Ezra. He saw the necessity of\r\nsending people out to go and inspire these Levites to be partakers of the revival mandate. He\r\nmade a leadership step of searching for more men rather than lament that there were no\r\nmen. Ezra initiated a local outreach of eleven men to go to Casiphia, a place in Babylon,\r\nwhere Levites could be sought out and recruited (v. 16-17). He was very focused and knew\r\nwhere to go. Sometimes there are potential men and women of God who will remain idle or\r\nindifferent to their calling until someone wakes them up. Our local fellowships are full of\r\npotential servants of God, but we must embark on local outreaches to find these people and\r\nbring them on board for the journey of revival.<br/>\r\nJesus was one man who started a local outreach to recruit labourers for the spiritual harvest.\r\nHe started by first calling two ordinary fishermen, Andrew and Peter, with the popular quote\r\n“I will make you fishers of men”. He called two more fishermen (James and John...Mark 1:16-\r\n20), before assembling the twelve, who were comprised of people from different walks of\r\nlife, including a tax collector. These would become His main agents whom He would use to\r\nspread the preaching of the Kingdom (Luke 9:1-6), before sending an additional seventy for\r\nfurther revival ministry (Luke 10:1-12). There is still a great need for local outreach today.\r\nCongregational Christianity where we gather once or twice a week is good, but we need\r\nteams of dedicated people (like the eleven whom Ezra sent), that will go into the local\r\nhouseholds to identify more men and women to invest in and commission for the work of\r\nthe kingdom. Of a truth, how shall they hear without a preacher? (Romans 10 vs 14).', '2018-12-03 21:01:54'),
(585, 165, 'It is important to note that Ezra specifically sought “chief men and men of understanding”.\r\nHe knew clearly that the kingdom task is not just for anyone that is available but for the best.\r\nHe understood the importance of quality in recruiting kingdom workers. It is a pathetic\r\nreality today that low-quality, untrained and less-qualified experts are tasked with the\r\nkingdom assignment and no surprise they reduce the work to their comfort level—lowering\r\nthe standard and doing it anyhow. If the best technical expert is used for the work of God, the\r\nfellowship will save more, achieve more and inspire others within the group to learn, but\r\nwhen we put the round peg in a square hole, we weary others and make a mockery of the\r\nkingdom with men with no sense of optimal value that the kingdom must represent. It is sad\r\nthat this lack of quality standard has seen the church lose many professionals and experts\r\nwho cannot stand the ridicule of low-quality.', '2018-12-03 21:01:54'),
(586, 166, 'Ezra was a priest and a skilled scribe who had been granted favour by the king through God\'s\r\nSovereign Hand, to gather as many Israelites with him to return to Jerusalem. In spite of his\r\nqualifications and privileged position, he understood that he needed other competent\r\nministers if the hope of revival was going to become a reality. His recruitment process\r\nbrought him eighteen men from the family of Sherebiah, twenty men from the family of\r\nHashabiah and Jeshaiah, plus two hundred and twenty Nethinim (“Temple Servants”),\r\nmaking a total of two hundred and fifty eight ministers. Though Ezra was in an exalted\r\nposition, he was humble enough to clearly see that he would need help for the work of God\r\nto be perfected. He knew clearly that a tree cannot make a forest. God needs more men with\r\nvarying and broad-based skill sets for the work of revival. Don\'t surround yourself with\r\npeople who are not better than you in various areas of expertise where capacity is needed\r\nfor the kingdom task.', '2018-12-03 21:01:54'),
(587, 166, 'We are reminded of Moses, who was admonished by Jethro his father-in-law to seek out\r\njudges with whom he could divide the work in a hierarchicalmanner (Ex. 18:13-27). They had\r\nto be “able men, such as fear God, men of truth, hating covetousness” (v. 21). Christians\r\ntoday who like isolation must understand that God deals with us individually first and that\'s\r\nwhere revival starts, but the Body of Christ is a unity of many members, and therefore we\r\nmust connect with others who share the same vision and burden of revival with deep desire\r\nto see the Holy Spirit move and bring about a great awakening. “No man is an island”, as the\r\npopular saying goes, not even the best of us such as Ezra or Moses.', '2018-12-03 21:01:54'),
(588, 166, 'Revival starts with an individual but it never ends there. Different members of the Body are\r\ngranted different gifts by the Spirit, and Paul emphasised that the different parts of the Body\r\nall need each other (1Cor. 12). We must bring as many “Levites” with us to Jerusalem, as no\r\none can accomplish this task alone. Revival move can be wasted like a harvest if there are no\r\nsufficient labourers to take in and manage the souls for the Lord in follow-up, counselling,\r\nwelfare, intercession, visitation etc.', '2018-12-03 21:01:54'),
(589, 167, 'The Christian life has been compared to a long and continuous journey. The road to revival is\r\none of those embankments where we as God\'s agents must be properly prepared. Nothing in\r\nthe kingdom can be done anyhow and the spiritual implication of our journey must never be\r\ntaken for granted. Whether it is a local revival or a missionary journey to help people in an\r\nunknown territory, we must make sure we have God\'s power and support with us before\r\ngoing in to do the work. Do not go out to do God\'s work unprepared. Never attempt to make a\r\nstep for God when your knees have not stayed enough with Him.', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(590, 167, 'As Ezra was aware that there would be challenges and adversity along the way, we must\r\nrealise that there are demonic adversaries and forces of darkness who will resist any form of\r\nrevival that seeks to bring souls to Christ or awaken those who have backslidden. The place of\r\nspiritual preparation in fasting in this spiritual warfare cannot be overemphasised. Jesus said\r\nthere are some particular kinds of kingdom onslaught where it has to be by our prayers with\r\nfasting (Matt. 17:21).', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(591, 167, 'Fasting and prayer must be a common experience of anyone that wants to be a revival agent.\r\nNo one can go far in the call of revival without putting under the flesh through fasting and\r\nhumbling our hearts in long sessions of high-impact prayers. Below are examples of men who\r\nused the power of fasting to accomplish kingdom exploits:', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(592, 167, '<ul>\r\n<li>MATTHEW 4:1-2 – After Jesus baptism, the Holy Spirit led Him into the\r\nwilderness, where He fasted for forty days and nights in preparation for the\r\nfulfilment of His mission on earth.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(593, 167, '<li>ACTS 13:1-3 – The disciples were in a state of fasting before the Holy Ghost\r\nselected Paul and Barnabas for their first missionary journey.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(594, 167, '<li>ACTS 14:21-23 – Paul and Barnabas fasted with prayer before leaving the\r\nelders whom they had ordained into the hands of God, so that He could help\r\nthem with wisdom and ability to properly guide the churches in Lystra,\r\nIconium, and Antioch-Pisidia.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(595, 167, '<li>2COR. 6:4-5, 11:26-27 – Fasting became a regular part of Paul\'s life after he\r\nbecame an agent of revival.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(596, 167, '<li>ACTS 10:30 – Cornelius was fasting when God answered him by sending an\r\nangel to tell him what to do in order for him and his family to be saved.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(597, 167, '<li>DANIEL 9:2-3 – Daniel fasted in his search for understanding of future\r\nevents.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(598, 167, '<li>ESTHER 4:15-17 – Esther and the Jews fasted for three days before she went\r\ninto the king\'s chamber to make an untimely request, which had the\r\npotential to be punishable by death.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(599, 167, '<li>DEUT. 9:9-11 – Moses fasted for forty days and forty nights while he was in\r\nthe mountain of God, before receiving the Divine Law for Israel.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(600, 167, '<li>2CHRON. 20:1-3 – King Jehoshaphat called for a national fast after Judah\r\nwas threatened by a multitude of enemies and his people didn\'t know what\r\nto do. God delivered them because they fasted, prayed, and sought His\r\ndivine intervention.</li>', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(601, 168, 'Verse 22 of our study text gives us insight into the kind of confidence that Ezra had in God of\r\nIsrael. He had declared to the king that “The hand of our God is upon all them for good that\r\nseek Him...” This bears resemblance to the declaration which Peter made—“For the eyes of\r\nthe Lord are over the righteous, and His ears are open unto their prayers; but the face of the\r\nLord is against them that do evil” (1Pet. 3:12, quoting David in Psalm 34:15-16). Ezra\r\nunderstood this about God and therefore could confidently expect the Lord to protect him\r\nand his entourage throughout the four-month journey. Yes, about a 120-day journey on the\r\nroad! Looking at all the people plus the valuables they were travelling with, he resorted to the\r\nsure safety of the Lord and not human protection. The lesson for us here is: <b>Don\'t tell others\r\nthat God will help you with something, and then turn around and ask those people for help.</b>\r\nThis only encourages unbelievers to have more reasons to doubt or even mock God. Do not\r\ncheapen God because of your fears and inability to receive divine backing. Don\'t reduce God\r\nby begging unbelievers for help. A person who has preached how he always trusts the Lord to\r\nhelp him pass his examinations, who goes to bribe lecturers for good marks is an\r\nembarrassment to the kingdom.', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(602, 168, 'We must look to God alone as our supreme source of protection when weare at the centre of\r\nHis will. Besides protection, we will need His wisdom, revelation, insights, and direction in\r\nour quest for revival. We must look to Him for everything we need and not put our\r\nconfidence in the carnal methods of man.', '2018-12-03 21:20:03'),
(603, 169, 'We have no written Biblical history for the time period between the temple\'s dedication and\r\nEzra\'s arrival, but we know that an interval of about sixty years existed in between and we\r\nsaw clearly how the Jews had abandoned the essence of the “temple” in strict consecration\r\nunto the Lord to living a life of the unbelievers, whom they mixed with in lifestyle and even in\r\nmarital relationship (Ezra 4:3). Most (if not all) of the generation of Zerubbabel, Jeshua, and\r\nthe former elders had died by this time, and this new generation did not understand the need\r\nfor separation. They freely mixed and married with the pagans, even “doing according to\r\ntheir abominations”. That phrase in 9:1 means that they participated in the idolatrous\r\nworship of the Gentiles and were involved in their ungodly practices. This all happened even\r\nthough the temple in Jerusalem had been rebuilt and dedicated, with service and worship\r\nsteadily going on.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(604, 169, 'What we see then is that there\'s a place for excitement in worship which God\'s temple\r\nbrings, but our LIFESTYLE outside the building is what matters most. Christianity is not only\r\nabout constructing the church building and attending fellowship or being active in\r\nsubgroups, but more about our day-to-day practical way of life. This includes separating\r\nourselves from the ways of the ungodly world in which we currently live. Paul\'s attitude was\r\nthat the world was crucified unto him, and he himself crucified to the world (Gal. 6:14). John\r\ngave us the famous exhortation in 1John 2:15-17 to love not the world, and that anyone who\r\nloves the world does not have the love of the Father within him. This was the problem with\r\nDemas, who was a Christian and companion of Paul. He loved the world and forsook Paul\r\nduring the apostle\'s time of great need (2Tim. 4:10). He was like one of the Christians\r\ndescribed in James 4:4, a spiritual \'adulterer\' who was a friend of the world and unwittingly\r\nbecame an enemy of God in the process.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(605, 169, 'To emphasise the importance of separation, our Lord Jesus Himself affirmed that we are in\r\nthis world, but not <b><i>of</i></b> this world (John 17:14-16). To clarify, this does not mean that God\'s\r\npeople are not allowed to associate with the unbelieving people of this world, because, as\r\nPaul says, “for then must ye need go out of the world” (1Cor. 5:9-13). In that passage, Paul\r\nwas saying that we will necessarily have to associate with the ungodly people of this world\r\nto some degree, e.g. work, school, business etc. But all those passages above about\r\nseparation mean that we don\'t live how they live, or think how they think. The life of Jesus\r\nmust be evident and a clear boundary must be set because “bad company corrupts good\r\nmanners” (1Cor. 15:33).', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(606, 169, 'Revival calls for whole-hearted commitment to the life that God wants us to live unto Him.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(607, 170, 'Ezra 9:2 states that the Jews had intermarried with the Gentiles that were around them.\r\nThis obviously played a role in why 9:1 says the Jews also did “according to their\r\nabominations”. Their wives had no doubt influenced them to worship the pagan gods,\r\nreminiscent of Solomon in 1Kings 11. When God gave Moses the commandment for Israel\r\nto refrain from marrying non-Israelites, the commandment was specifically for only non-\r\nIsraelites who refused to convert to Judaism, that is, to join with Israel in the Old Covenant\r\nand observe the Law of Moses.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(608, 170, 'For Christians today, the principle still applies. Two people cannot work together except\r\nthey agree (Amos 3 vs 3) and the basis of agreement is entrenched in common purpose and\r\nshared destiny. There cannot be an agreement if both partners share different beliefs,\r\nprinciples and practices. No one can serve two masters and as marriage bring two people to\r\nbecome one, it is not possible for a marriage to exist if both partners have different spiritual\r\nallegiance. 2Cor. 6:14 says “Be ye not unequally yoked together with unbelievers”.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(609, 170, 'God desires sanctity in Christian marriage. A Christian who is single should not marry a non-\r\nChristian with hope that they will convert the unbelieving spouse later in the marriage.\r\nThere is simply no guarantee that this will happen, and the problems that come with being\r\nunequally yoked far outweigh the joys that marriage should bring. Paul was very clear about\r\nthis and admonished that all marriage must be “only in the Lord” (1Cor. 7:39).', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(610, 170, 'There is no spiritual unity between a believer and an unbeliever. The Holy Spirit comes to live\r\nin a born-again Christian at the new birth experience, which results in a new life and a new\r\nway of thinking. The unbeliever has not had this experience, so there will be friction and a\r\nsense of disagreement in many issues of life in regards to joint decision-making and even\r\nraising of children. Do you want to be in a marriage where only one person is depending on\r\nthe Name of Jesus to fight spiritual battles and deal with the challenges that life may throw?\r\nBuilding godly marriages founded on Christ Himself is a strategic part of building God\'s\r\nkingdom on earth. Anything outside this contradicts God\'s masterplan to use Christian\r\nmarriage to raise for himself “godly seed” AFTER His own nature, character and purpose.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(611, 170, '<h1>Week 31 ends here and week 32 starts below</h1>', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(612, 171, 'Intercession is the oil that powers true revival and rebuilding work. We cannot see God move\r\nuntil we stand in the gap in prayer. In verses 5-15, we see a record of Ezra\'s intercession to\r\nGod on behalf of the nation, genuinely admitting and confessing that they as a people were\r\nundeserving of God\'s goodness that He had showed them thus far. He mentioned the sins of\r\ntheir fathers and how God had been gracious in leaving them a remnant instead of\r\ndestroying the entirety of Israel. He spoke of God\'s mercy in granting them a revival through\r\nthe rebuilding of the destroyed temple (v. 9). The “wall” he speaks of in that verse was “in\r\nJudah and in Jerusalem”, not just Jerusalem alone, so this is not the physical wall but a figure\r\nof speech denoting God\'s protection and preservation of both Judah and Jerusalem. Ezra\r\nsays to God that “ <b>we</b> have forsaken your commandments” (v. 10), and goes on in verses 11 &\r\n12 to acknowledge what God had warned them about in the book of the Law and the\r\nprophets concerning Israel\'s current transgression in mixing with the heathen. He says that\r\nGod\'s punishment through Babylonian exile is less than what their trespasses should have\r\nincurred (v.13), and declares God to be righteous even as Israel has yet again broken His\r\ncommandment (v. 14-15).', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(613, 171, 'This remorseful intercession by Ezra produced deep spiritual results as evidenced in the\r\ncorporate repentance and restoration concerning their marriage of pagan wives and their\r\nindulgence in the abominable practices of the heathen. The guilty Israelites became\r\nsimilarly remorseful after hearing Ezra\'s words of intercession to God (Ezra 10:1) in a manner\r\nsimilar to what Paul meant when he said,“Godly sorrow works repentance unto salvation...”\r\n(2Cor. 7:8-11).', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(614, 171, 'The ministry of sorrowful intercession is an important part of revival. We cannot do much in\r\nour church and generation if we do not feel the burden of their sin and genuinely carry such\r\nto the Lord in heartfelt intercession. True revival agents always have a genuine concern for\r\nthe salvation of others, even when they are not deserving of the mercies of God.', '2018-12-03 21:35:53'),
(615, 172, 'The Holy Spirit worked through the ministry of Ezra to prick the hearts of the guilty Israelites\r\nand to convict their consciences. This conviction in a sinner\'s heart means he or she has now\r\nrealised their own unrighteousness and it has been brought to their undeniable attention.\r\nHuman vessels of God may or may not be used, but in either case it is the Holy Spirit Himself\r\nthat is the real agent who does the convicting, as Jesus shows us in John 16:8. After the Holy\r\nGhost fell at Pentecost and Peter gave his first sermon, Acts 2:37 records the response of the\r\npeople: “Now when they heard this, <b>they were pricked in their heart</b>, and said unto Peter and\r\nto the rest of the apostles, \'men and brethren, what shall we do?\'” The convicting power of\r\nthe Holy Spirit was present, and it always leads to men and women seeking repentance\r\nbefore God. Throughout the Church age, the move and Presence of God\'s Spirit has usually\r\nbeen marked by people being convicted of their sin and feeling uneasy until they confess and\r\nforsake it.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(616, 172, 'In Ezra 3:2, we see that conviction led to confession and genuine acts of repentance. A\r\nrepresentative spokesman for the people said to Ezra: “We have trespassed against our\r\nGod...”Acknowledgment of sin is the beginning of true revival. It is like a man who is known to\r\nbe mad coming to himself to ask, “What has happened to me, why am I dressed like this?”.\r\nWhen the power of the madness of sin is broken in a man, he comes to himself like the\r\nprodigal son in Luke 15 vs 17. At this critical moment, he realises his sin state and genuinely\r\nseeks for divine help and forgiveness with a deep sense of repentance. 1John 1:9 says if we\r\nconfess our sins, He is faithful and just to forgive us our sins and cleanse us from all\r\nunrighteousness. Same as Proverbs 28:13, which says he that covers his sins shall not prosper,\r\nbut whoever confesses and forsakes them shall have mercy. Confession of sins is like vomiting\r\nout bad food and purging the spiritual interior of the sinner\'s conscience. It is the next step\r\nafter conviction, which begins to lift the load of guilt from the individual. It is a conscious\r\neffort to break the power of sin in our lives.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(617, 173, 'The road of repentance does not stop at conviction and confession. Shechaniah, who spoke\r\nfor the Israelites after Ezra\'s open intercession, went further to say: “Now therefore let us\r\nmake a covenant with our God...” (10:3), to which the people of Israel agreed by oath (10:5).\r\nThese people became ready to cooperate with God after the Holy Spirit through the ministry\r\nof Ezra has done His work of convicting their hearts. They made a new commitment to the\r\nLORD God of Israel, and dedicated themselves to obedience and righteousness. The ministry\r\nof any TACEFite who is called to be a revival agent must be like this. Our ministration must lead\r\nmen to make a new decision for God and not to enjoy the message or just leave as they have\r\ncome.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(618, 173, 'Newly born-again Christians who are having a first time experience of conversion make an\r\ninitial commitment to Christ at that point, but those whose commitment to God has reduced\r\nwith time can also re-dedicate their lives to the Lord. The call for rededication is a continuous\r\ndemand on our lives as revival agents. Rededication is a genuine act of deliberately rejecting\r\nsin and renewin glove for Christ. It is the moment when our dying or half-hearted devotion to\r\nthe Lord is turned into a desire to pour out our lives for His service in the utmost sense of total\r\nconsecration. It is the moment of spiritual lifting when we abandon our shallow devotion to\r\nChrist and devote ourselves to Him more fully.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(619, 174, 'It has been said that action speaks louder than words. This statement is also true in the realm\r\nof the Spirit. Confession of sins and making a commitment to walk in righteousness will add\r\nup to zero if no practical actions are taken towards restitution. But what exactly is restitution?\r\nIt is the restoration of something stolen to its proper owner, making amends for wrongs done\r\nto others, and correcting any damages that occurred due to a person\'s sins. The guilty\r\nIsraelites said they were making a covenant with God “to put away all the wives, and such as\r\nare born of them...” (10:3). Verses 6-44 give us the practical steps they took to make the\r\nneeded corrections for their trespass.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(620, 174, 'Let us explore a practical case study. A student stole a shirt in a student\'s hostel as an\r\nunbeliever. A few months later, he had a personal encounter with Jesus and became born\r\nagain. As part of his post-salvation experience, he was taught and encouraged to do one-onone\r\nevangelism. During one of the evangelical visits from one hostel to another, he wore the\r\nshirt he stole when he had not accepted Jesus. While he was preaching to a particular boy, the\r\nboy was fixated on a mark on the preacher\'s shirt and not on the message being\r\npreached.Eventually, the boy shouted and created a scene, accusing the preacher of stealing\r\nhis shirt. He drew a massive crowd of students and quickly went to his room to bring pictures\r\nto prove that the preacher actually stole his shirt. The preacher could not lie and his\r\nexplanation that he committed the act when he had not received Jesus was not acceptable.\r\nThe ridicule was terrible and the name of the Lord was tarnished. As a revival agent, what\r\nshould the preacher have done as soon as he accepted Christ? This is where the principle of\r\nRESTITUTION becomes important.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(621, 174, 'Genuine repentance is always followed by restitution. A Christian who wronged others in any\r\nway must make amends. This may include things like paying debts, apologising to the\r\noffended party, returning money gained by fraud or illegitimate means, etc. Restitution must\r\nbe made whether or not the victim is aware that you wronged them, because God Himself\r\nknows everything (Heb. 4:13), and also because we want our conscience to be at peace\r\nbefore God and man (Acts 24:16). The Old Testament had clear instructions concerning\r\nrestitution, including verses like Ex. 22:1-7, Lev. 6:1-7, Num. 5:6-8, Prov. 6:30-31, and Ezek.\r\n33:14-16. The theme continues in the New Testament, a few examples includes Jesus\r\ninstruction to make amends with your brother before giving offerings to God (Matt. 5:23-24),\r\nZaccheus\' restoration of unjust gains (Luke 19:8-9), and John the Baptist\'s exhortation to the\r\nrepentant people to make corrections in their dealings with others (Luke 3:8-14).', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(622, 174, 'Like the apostle James said, “to him that knows to do good but does not do it, to him it is sin”\r\n(James 4:17). A repentant heart seeks to correct past errors and hurts wherever possible.\r\nWhen unbelievers see people who profess Christianity actually repaying their debts,\r\nrestoring unjust gains, and fixing all damages to the best of their ability, it is a strong\r\ntestimony that something divine has happened in that person\'s heart. In addition, the\r\nindividual making the restitution is also blessed, because the peace of God will flow into his\r\nbeing and living with a pure conscience. He will have joy and confidence towards God, as the\r\nsense of guilt and shame is removed (Rom. 8:1). This is the evidence of personal revival on\r\ndisplay. And God will use the new spiritual strength of that individual to influence and reach\r\nmany more people.', '2018-12-03 21:46:33'),
(623, 175, 'As we shall see in the study after this, Nehemiah was the king\'s cupbearer (a position of high\r\nresponsibility in the palace). However, his secular job was not his complete earthly\r\nassignment, and he knew that God wanted more from him. He was doing well financially and\r\nenjoying the benefits of the king\'s court, but deep down in his heart there was a desire to see\r\nthe progress of God\'s kingdom on earth, and he was concerned as to what role he could play\r\nin the bigger picture. This is why he asked about the condition of Jerusalem and the Jews\r\nthere. It is very similar to our Week 2 study about the lamentation of the men who sat by the\r\nrivers of Babylon but whose heart longed for the God of Israel.', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(624, 175, 'The burden and response of Nehemiah is the core of the entire book, including his trip back\r\nto Judea, his leadership style, managerial approach and project management skills in seeing\r\nto the reconstruction of the wall, and other reforms he set to rebuild Jerusalem and catalyse\r\na path of true revival.', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(625, 175, 'God\'s people today must maintain the kind of mindset Nehemiah had. We all know the\r\nimportance of working hard in our different careers and earning a living, but we must never\r\nforget the higher calling of God on our lives. An excellent example of such a person from the\r\nNew Testament is the apostle Paul. He was a tentmaker by profession (Acts 18:3), and\r\nworked diligently to succeed in his craft (Acts 20:33-34, 2Thess. 3:8). But Paul\'s heart and\r\nmind were always set on the greater goal of seeing the gospel spread throughout the world,\r\nand also edifying the churches who had come to faith in Christ. This is what God still expects\r\nfrom us today. It is He that gives us power to work and get wealth (Deut. 8:18), and He\r\nexpects us to use our resources for His glory and kingdom. For we know as TACEFites that\r\nevery increase in our lives must increase God\'s work in our hand. <b>Every son and daughter of\r\nthis vision understands that God prospers us financially not to raise our standard of living,\r\nbut to raise our standard of giving.</b>', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(626, 175, 'It is important that we also see our work as a ministry. It is a platform where our light will\r\nshine and men will see our good work and glorify our father in heaven (Matt 5 vs 16). The\r\nexcellence we bring to our work and the amazing result we produce is a proof of God\'s\r\nnature that we carry. We must see our secular job as a way to advance God\'s kingdom. Our\r\nwarm personality, friendly disposition, impeccable integrity, outstanding result, quality work\r\nethic and uncompromising success is one of the best ways of bringing the light of God to the\r\nwork.', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(627, 176, 'The report from Jerusalem was a negative one: <i>“The remnant who are left behind from the\r\ncaptivity there in the province are in great affliction and reproach. The wall of Jerusalem also\r\nis broken down, and the gates thereof are burned with fire”(1:3).</i>', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(628, 176, 'Jerusalem had no protective wall surrounding it, and this contributed somewhat to the\r\naffliction and reproach the inhabitants were suffering. In ancient times, large cities were\r\nalways fortified with walls. The walls had gates and high towers, with watchmen posted who\r\nwere on the lookout for invading enemies or other approaching problems. Nebuchadnezzar\r\nand his Babylonian army had destroyed Jerusalem\'s wall, and it still had not been rebuilt up\r\ntill this time of Nehemiah. Just as there is a direct relationship between a wall-less city and the\r\nwelfare of its inhabitants, there is also a direct relationship between a Christian who is wall less\r\nand the welfare of that Christian. Walls give a city its due value and honour and\r\ncomplement the presence of the temple. The temple alone is not sufficient, it must have walls\r\nof glory and this is the reality of a Christian experience where we complement the temple ( a\r\nsymbol of our spiritual experience) with built and standing walls ( a manifestation of a\r\nglorious life that has value and honour). The temple could be rebuilt, but never made\r\nbeautiful, because anything valuable would be taken easily.', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(629, 176, 'The bad state of the people and the bad state of the city walls were linked together. In the\r\nancient world, a city without walls was a city completely open and vulnerable to its enemies.\r\nThey had no defence, no protection at all. An unwalled city has nothing valuable in it. If there\r\nwere anything of value in an unwalled city, it could be stolen away easily because there was\r\nno defence to stop it. Therefore, those living in an unwalled city lived in constant stress and\r\ntension; they never knew when they might be attacked. When a city has no wall, its people\r\nlive in constant distress, in constant disgrace, living only as survivors and hustlers and not as\r\nconquerors (Romans 8:37).', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(630, 176, 'Revival is not complete with a temple that is not secured. Revival is threatened when we have\r\nlives that are truly connected to God but whose lives are unwalled. Revival is not sustainable\r\nwhen our spiritual experience is not manifest in an excellent career, fulfilling marriage,\r\nprogressive path and God-glorifying results. The desired honour and value comes when our\r\ntemple is complemented by a life that is not in ruins of failure, dejection and backwardness or\r\nbroken walls (broken marriages, broken career, broken future etc.)', '2018-12-03 21:58:55'),
(631, 177, 'Nehemiah found himself in a role where he had many privileges and advantages from being\r\nclose to the king. But all those privileges came at a cost—namely, he was the man who would\r\ndie in the event of someone trying to poison the king. Nehemiah could have said,“This job is\r\nnot worth me risking my very life, I will run away and be a poor servant in a remote part of the\r\nkingdom!” But he did not do that.He was voluntarily willing to lay down his life for the king if\r\nnecessary. As servants of Christ and a revival army in our generation, God has called us to lay\r\ndown our lives if need be for the sake of eternity. Jesus said,“Whosoever will save his life shall\r\nlose it but whosoever will lose his life for my sake, the same shall save it” (Luke 9:24).', '2018-12-04 07:10:22'),
(632, 177, 'So how about modern day Christians? Do we live our lives with this same mind-set? Are we\r\nwilling to be the King\'s cupbearer and wine taster? Are we willing to take risks for the mission\r\nof His kingdom? Or are we afraid of what people will say, how friends will abandon us or\r\nopportunities that we will lose for our uncompromising position. If we truly seek revival, we\r\nmust pay the price of taking a risk for the Lord. Our fellowship, TACEF, stands on the\r\nfoundation of many sacrificial risks made by many. Many people\'s career path, life pursuit,\r\nhealth, savings etc. were laid on the altar and at risk for the sake of kingdom expansion.\r\nLarge-scale revival will surely call for taking risks. Only those who have entrusted their very\r\nlife into the hands of the Lord can make significant impact where He leads them to go and\r\nmake a change.', '2018-12-04 07:10:22'),
(633, 178, 'Nehemiah learnt all he could while serving in the king\'s palace. The years spent under Persian\r\nservice improved his management and leadership skills. It is therefore no surprise that this\r\nexperience and training helped him expedite the rebuilding of Jerusalem\'s wall which was\r\ncompleted in just 52 days! (Neh. 6:15). No education is ever wasted for God\'s people.\r\nNehemiah was learning all he could in Persia without knowing that those acquired skills\r\nwould be useful in serving God in the future. Proverbs 10:14 is indeed right: “Wise men lay up\r\nknowledge.”Incremental capacity building is key for meaningful kingdom impact.', '2018-12-04 07:10:22'),
(634, 178, 'Luke was a medical doctor (Col. 4:14). This may seem to be an unrelated field to spiritual\r\nthings, but he would become the author of the most well-written and detailed Gospel (the\r\nGospel according to Luke). The second part of his recorded communication with Theophilus,\r\nwhich we now know as “The Acts of the Apostles” (Acts 1:1), continued to show his unique\r\nwriting style and attention to detail. His secular education enabled him to use his talents for\r\nGod\'s glory and the worldwide distribution of the Gospel message in written form. Matthew,\r\nalso known as Levi, was a government official who collected taxes from the public (Matt. 9:9),\r\nand Jesus called him to be one of His twelve original disciples. After the Lord\'s ascension back\r\nto heaven, Matthew\'s knowledge of the governmental system of that era must have helped\r\nhim in preaching the Gospel to higher ranking officials, who other Christians may not have\r\nbeen able to approach properly. Moses was learned in all the wisdom of the Egyptians (Acts\r\n7:22), and his education played a role in fulfilling his assignment of managing the Israelites\r\nthrough the years in the wilderness.', '2018-12-04 07:10:22'),
(635, 178, 'So wherever we find ourselves today, we must continue to lay up knowledge. Do not be like\r\nthose who are just acquiring certificates without the appropriate skills that can deliver value.\r\nLet every opportunity to learn be taken very seriously. Be sure to learn outside your domain\r\nof interest and be the best in your area of expertise. Do not waste your time on social media\r\nwhen you can read up on new trends and discoveries in your area of specialisation. It is a\r\ndishonour when one\'s academic degree doesnot match the current knowledge in the chosen\r\nfield because the individual doesnot learn through professional groups, online learning\r\ngroups and regular publications.', '2018-12-04 07:10:22'),
(636, 179, 'A holistic view of the Bible reveals that God always prepares a person\'s heart before any major\r\nrenewal or revival. Since the Fall of Man in the Garden and his subsequent exit, God has been\r\nplacing burdens in the hearts of men and made them see things they naturally would not\r\nhave seen. God has determined to use humans to bring spiritual and physical resuscitation to\r\nothers. Church history also reveals that every true renewal begins with the preparation of the\r\nheart in prayers of a few individuals. The first example that comes to mind is the work of\r\nMartin Luther, the great Reformer who called the Church back to the authority of the Bible,\r\nabove the false authority of corrupt clergymen who were deceitfully offering people\r\n“salvation” in exchange for money. One can also see the likes of John Calvin, John Knox, and\r\nother Reformers whose love for God\'s word facilitated revival in different parts of Europe.\r\nWilliam J. Seymour in 1906 is another notable revivalist who spearheaded the unforgettable\r\nAzusa street revival in the United States. Every one of these revivals came with intense\r\npreparation in the form of prayers, fasting, and the study of God\'s word.', '2018-12-04 07:21:21'),
(637, 179, 'Our Lord and Saviour Jesus Christ prepared here on earth for about thirty years (Luke 3:23) for\r\na foundational work of three and half years, and since then the world has still not recovered\r\nfrom His work. When there is a shallow preparation such moves do not stand the test of time.\r\nThe tougher the preparation, the greater the manifestation.', '2018-12-04 07:21:21'),
(638, 179, 'Considering the work of Nehemiah and Ezra, there is a great connection between the works\r\nof these individuals. The two assignments started with a heart preparation(See Ezra 7:10,\r\nNehemiah 1:4). From the above passage they both started their work with the\r\naforementioned preparation of the heart in fasting, prayers, and study of the word of God. It\r\nis therefore not a surprise that the wall of Jerusalem was completed in fifty-two days because\r\nNehemiah had invested a lot more time in spiritual preparation long before the physical work\r\nbegan. Every true revival begins with deep and deliberate preparation. Without adequate\r\nand solid preparation it would not stand the test of time.', '2018-12-04 07:21:21'),
(639, 180, 'God was going to use Nehemiah to do something about this situation. But first, God did\r\nsomething in Nehemiah. Any great work of God begins with God doing a great work in\r\nsomebody. God\'s ability to begin a work of revival in a church and generation is proportional\r\nto the work He can do in the life of a ready, willing and prepared man. God does not deal with\r\nthe crowd first. He always seeks for one man who is well made in the crucibles of His hand.', '2018-12-04 07:21:21'),
(640, 180, 'In as much as God will start with a ready man, no man can do the work of God alone. God\r\nstarts with a man and the man will now expand the work, hence the personality profile of the\r\nchosen man is critical in how successful the work can be. In this case, Nehemiah must have a\r\nstrong spiritual life and at the same time he must be a leader—one who influences other\r\npeople—to get this job done. We saw a man who could inspire people through a shared\r\nvision and create an environment where people feel valued and fulfilled to complete a\r\nspecific task. <b><i>No revival work can go far without a strong leader who can motivate,\r\nmobilise and be at the forefront of the delivery of the work with utmost excellence,\r\nmanagement skills and resourcefulness.</i></b> A lazy, unprepared, undisciplined and unmotivated\r\nman whose life has no proof of what he advocates cannot win the trust of the followers to\r\ndeliver on divine mandate. Leading a revival move starts by becoming the best of the revival\r\nin all spheres of life as this is the only way to win the trust and respect of the people who look\r\nup to the leader. When this is missing, the work cannot go far.', '2018-12-04 07:21:21'),
(641, 180, 'One of the critical levers of leadership as seen here is vision. Vision is a clear picture of the\r\ndesired future. It is the sense of a destination. Vision is the fuel of revival. Nehemiah had a\r\nclear vision to rebuild the walls of the city of Jerusalem and this was birthed by God. It was\r\nnot a personal agenda or spontaneous thought of a selfish desire. It came through as a\r\nburden and was crystallised in prayer and fasting. It was a download from heaven and\r\nconfirmed by God Himself. This reminds every TACEFite how the vision to “raise an army with\r\na vision of revival” came. The pioneers had a burden of the need for a change in the church at\r\nthat time and this could have been expressed in many ways. E.g. they could have started a\r\npreaching society, organised a revival programme, enrolled at a college of theology to\r\nbecome ministers or left the church altogether, but they went the way of Nehemiah which is\r\nto labour in prayer and fasting until the burden grew into God\'s own vision with specific\r\ndivine instruction on what is to be done, how it should be done, where it will be done and\r\nwhy it must be done. This will also include with whom it will be done and when it must start.\r\nEvery vision of God must pass through this structured phase that is beyond a feeling or\r\nemotion but God-birthed instructions plus a clear sense of the destination. This process of\r\nenvisioning is very important because many people have acted only on emotional burden\r\nand have wasted away because there was no clarity as to what was to be done and the sense\r\nof the measure of success. Burden alone is not enough if the breath of God has not come\r\nupon it to become God\'s own series of instructions and long-term picture of resultscalled\r\nvision. This only comes from the Holy spirit. For TACEF vision to evolve, many days of longterm\r\nfasting, daily prayers and vigils were spent to activate the burden, download specific\r\ndetails, understand God\'s ultimate plan and develop these into a well-articulated vision on\r\nhow to address a gap which has consequences on issues of eternity of a people.', '2018-12-04 07:21:21'),
(642, 181, 'God\'s people must always look and think ahead. Vision and foresight work together with the\r\nburden on one\'s heart to provide practical steps for arriving at the desired goal. Nehemiah\r\nhad a burden for the welfare of his homeland and his people, and now he expressed his vision\r\nfor a practical solution: “send me unto Judah, unto the city of my fathers\' sepulchres, that I\r\nmay build it.”', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(643, 181, 'He saw beyond the broken walls and ruins of the city. We also must see beyond problems and\r\nlook to the solution. Proverbs 29:18 says “Where there is no vision, the people perish.” After\r\nwe have prepared ourselves spiritually by prayers, fasting, and searching the Scriptures, we\r\nmust also look for tangible ways to bring about the result. It has to move from vision to action.\r\nHowever, this requires clarity of thought and engaging communication skills. In Habakkuk\r\n2:2, we read these words: “And the LORD answered me, and said, Write the vision, and make\r\nit plain upon tablets, that he may run that reads it.” God Himself wants us to be very clear\r\nabout our focus, hence the need to document because it is easier to communicate what is\r\nintently expressed in written format. Writing down the necessary steps that need to be taken\r\nwill motivate and propel us into continual action until the goal is realised. The idea here is that\r\nthe more we visualise the end result and communicate it with conviction and passion, the\r\nmore your entire being is encouragedto become whatever is necessary to see that end result\r\ncome to pass.', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(644, 181, 'Communication also requires us to project the desired end and not focus on the current\r\nsituation. A great vision communicator is a man who motivates from the sense of a sure\r\ndestination in ways that inspire, encourage and mobilise others to follow the path, even in\r\ntimes of little or no encouraging beginning. No matter how gloomy the present situation\r\nmight look, a great communicator starts by painting a mental picture that is full of colours and\r\nvibrancy of the expected future, and write down the practical steps that must be taken to\r\nphysically attain that glorious place. It is not sufficient to excite people with the image of a\r\ndestination when you are not supporting the same with the right action needed to get there.\r\nEven though Jerusalem lay in ruins, with broken down walls, burnt gates, and distressed\r\npeople, Nehemiah saw beyond the gloomy situation and painted a bright picture in his mind.\r\nWith God\'s blessing, he accomplished everything he set out to do before the end of the book.\r\nWe also can turn any situation around when we have vision, faith, God\'s blessing, practical\r\nsteps on what to do and inspiring communication skills to mobilise others to share in our\r\npassion. The best way to communicate a vision is to live it with the whole of your life!', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(645, 182, 'Proverbs 3:4 reads, <i>“So shalt thou find favour and good understanding in the sight of God and\r\nman.”</i>\r\nIn Nehemiah\'s quest to see to the repair and revival in Jerusalem, there were two entities he\r\nneeded to gain favour from. The first and most important, of course, is the Lord Himself.\r\nNehemiah was in a state of consistent prayer and fasting from the months Chislev to Nisan, a\r\nperiod of four months. He understood that any attempts at revival without God would be a\r\nfutile endeavour. Any ministerial work that is not backed with long-term prayers will be\r\nswept away with time.', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(646, 182, 'After Nehemiah has spent a good time in seeking God\'s face and favour, it was now time to\r\ntake the next step, i.e., seeking the favour of the human king Artaxerxes. <i>“And I said unto the\r\nking, If it please the king, <b>and if thy servant have found favour in thy sight</b>, that thou\r\nwouldest send me unto Judah, unto the city of my fathers\' sepulchres, that I may build it”</i>(Neh.\r\n2:5).', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(647, 182, 'It was God\'s initial favour that placed Nehemiah in this place where he could now obtain\r\nfavour from man also, in order to fulfil the vision of revival. As God\'s agents,He expects us to\r\nrely on Him first and foremost above all else. In addition, to bring the spiritual into physical,\r\nwemust cultivate the acts of favour through a good relationship and high reputation that can\r\nhelp us command the right favour to deliver on the Lord\'s assignment. The Bible records\r\nmany such cases where God\'s favour met with man\'s favour, thereby blessing God\'s people in\r\nthe process. We can speak of Joseph and Pharaoh, Daniel and Nebuchadnezzar, the exiled\r\nJews and Cyrus, Esther and Ahasuerus, etc.', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(648, 182, 'The mistake many Christians have made is to exalt the favour of man above the favour of\r\nGod. We look to men before we look to God. Do you distribute your CV to anyone without\r\nfirst praying to know the best place that God has arranged for you? Do you start “shadowing”\r\na sister when God has not communicated His will? Do you relocate abroad when your help is\r\nmeant to come from above? Do you place your hope in friends when God has arranged\r\nsufficient help in many places for you? <b>It is the spiritual favour received in the place of\r\nprayer that activates favour with men and never the other way round.</b> It is because you\r\nhave prayed that God will cause an unknown man to pick you out of thousands for a job even\r\nwhen you think you do not qualify. In fact, the heart of the king is also in God\'s hand, so it is He\r\nwho determines whether we will obtain favour from that person or not (Prov. 21:1). So\r\nwhether we are seeking revival or seeking a personal need, we must be like Nehemiah and\r\nthe other Biblical heroes who operated with the knowledge of God\'s sovereignty and\r\nsupremacy, while leveraging the advantage of man\'s favour as the Lord makes it available\r\naccording to His perfect will.', '2018-12-04 07:31:50'),
(649, 183, 'Nehemiah\'s initial entry into Jerusalem should have been noticed by many people because\r\nhe came with an escort of Persian soldiers, and also a load of timber from the king\'s forest.\r\nThe likelihood is that Nehemiah arrived very late after midnight when most people were\r\nasleep. In any case, he kept his plans for Jerusalem to himself for three days after his arrival.\r\nBut why the silence? The main reason is that he did not want anyone involved in one of the\r\nmost pivotal aspects of the rebuilding plan, i.e., counting the cost of what was damaged and\r\nwhat would be required to finish the work (Luke 14:28). Proverbs 29:11 says—“A fool utters\r\nall his mind, but a wise man keeps it in till afterward”. Nehemiah was no fool, so this is exactly\r\nwhat he did. Verse 16 of our study text shows us that there were Jewish “rulers” who acted as\r\noverseers among the people, along with the priests and nobles. If Nehemiah had told these\r\npeople his plan before evaluating Jerusalem for himself, there was no telling what their\r\nreaction would be. Some may have become jealous of him, and even try to confuse or\r\nmisinform him concerning the details of the project. Nehemiah knew this and had to critically\r\nanalyse the situation for himself without any bias or outsiders\' influence. Only after he was\r\ncontent and had gained a thorough understanding did he later reveal his intent to everyone\r\n(v. 17-18).', '2018-12-04 13:10:34'),
(650, 183, 'Ecclesiastes 3:7 says—“there is a time to keep silence, and a time to speak.”Silence is not\r\nempty; it is full of answers. It is actually a source of great strength. We must realise that the\r\nquieter we become, the more we are able to hear. Silence is a great way to humble ourselves\r\nbefore the Lord until He gives us instruction to speak.For how can a man speak when God has\r\nnot yet asked him to? He is no different from a man who leaks privileged information that has\r\nbeen confided in him. Many of us have leaked divine information when God has not asked us\r\nto speak.', '2018-12-04 13:10:34'),
(651, 183, 'Like Nehemiah, we must understand that there are some things that are best kept between\r\nGod and the man whom God has given the divine assignment. Timing is highly important.\r\nThere is a period of time where we must be alone with God and nurture the burden He has\r\nplaced on our heart. We must work out the details of the vision with Him alone, until the\r\ntime is right to include others in the execution of the plans of revival.', '2018-12-04 13:10:34'),
(652, 183, 'Many have revealed too much, too early and destroyed divine assignments that had\r\npotential to touch nations. Be quiet until God gives the go-ahead.', '2018-12-04 13:10:34'),
(653, 184, 'Nehemiah went about the city, critically inspecting the different parts of the walls, gates,\r\nports, wells, pools, etc. The word “viewed” in verses 13 and 15 is the Hebrew shâbar, which\r\nmeans to “scrutinise”. The word also has a medical association, as in when a doctor probes a\r\nwound to see the extent of damage. For those of us who did Biology practical, we can relate\r\nwith the word, “dissect”, that is to carefully examine, inspect and analyse for things that are\r\nnot normally obvious to the naked eye. This is what Nehemiah did. This is the same concept\r\nas discussed in one of our 2018 convention expositions on 2 Kings 12 vs 5, where the priests\r\nwere instructed to look for breaches, “wheresoever any breach shall be found”. We cannot\r\ndo the work of revival and repairing if we do not fully understand where the gaps exist. We\r\nmust be able to understand the issues, dissect them in detail, understand what is wrong both\r\nstructurally, spiritually and operationally as these form the basis for our prayers and actions.\r\nIn the same vein, we must also have this same diagnostic mind-set to check issues of our lives\r\nbeyond the surface. Someone who is having delays in marriage may need to do a honest\r\npersonality check—am I unfriendly, bad mannered and unwelcoming. Sometimes, what\r\ntakes us to the mountain for weeks of fasting only requires a change of attitude.', '2018-12-04 13:13:30'),
(654, 184, 'There are many broken individuals, families, businesses, and communities. Like Proverbs\r\n25:28, many people today are like a city broken down and without walls, living in constant\r\nfear, poverty, disease, and insecurity. They are seeking for God-sent Nehemiahs who have\r\nnot only heard God with a clear vision but who have also done a detailed dissection of the\r\nproblem, loaded with the right message and motivated with a workable solution.', '2018-12-04 13:13:30'),
(655, 185, 'To delegate a task means to give a task to somebody else with responsibility to act on your\r\nbehalf. It means to give somebody else the power to act, make decisions or allocate\r\nresources on your behalf. This is what Nehemiah did with the Jews as we see in chapter 3. In\r\nthe previous chapter, he had showed them what he wanted to do, and the rulers and\r\ncommon people all agreed that it was a good work to be accomplished (2:16-18). The first\r\nperson mentioned in chapter 3 who started his allocated portion of the work is the high\r\npriest himself, Eliashib, along with the other priests (3:1). Looking through the long list, we\r\nfind that Nehemiah had wisely allocated many people to work on parts of the wall that were\r\nclose to their houses. The people who did this work also included people from different\r\nwalks of life such as perfume makers, merchants, and goldsmiths. This shows that multiple\r\nskill sets and varied capacities are needed as we bring together all the members of the body\r\nof Christ to achieve great things for the Lord.<br/>\r\nToday, some leaders try to do everything alone thinking they are heroes, but they get\r\nburned-out or give up entirely after much failure. Many do not trust their fellow man and\r\nfear that they may become a future traitor who will cause problems down the road. In our\r\nannual study of Exodus, we saw how Moses was wearing himself out from morning till\r\nevening judging all of Israel alone by himself. His father-in-law Jethro gave him godly counsel\r\nto delegate work to competent men, and handle only the difficult cases himself. He followed\r\nthe advice and employed overseers (Ex. 18:13-26). This greatly reduced the amount of\r\nconfusion and brought a sense of order.<br/>\r\nDelegation of the work always brings better success, especially when you are blessed with\r\nthe right subordinates who have similar passion and the right skill sets. It is a painful reality\r\ntoday that many leaders do not delegate because they will end up doing the work again after\r\nprolonged waiting and delays because the man to whom the job was delegated has no\r\ncapacity to deliver.<br/>\r\nNo local fellowship will grow if it is the same person who runs a prayer session, praise and\r\nworship, ministration, announcement and even collects the offerings when there are ten\r\nother people seated. Oftentimes, the reason why many fellowships collapse, when an\r\nindividual leaves is because we do not consciously build people into roles. We must\r\ndeliberately challenge people to grow into kingdom responsibilities by delegating tasks, and\r\nstand by them and watch them grow into it, even with the expected successes and failures.\r\nWe must trust people to handle tasks and provide constructive feedback, which can help\r\nthem to know what they did well and areas where they can improve each time they are given\r\nan opportunity to do a task.', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(656, 186, 'Nehemiah was an effective leader and delegator because he made each person accountable\r\nfor his own portion of work. It is inspiring to note that this chapter is filled with the names of\r\nmore than 50 people who handled different parts of the assignment. Each man had a section\r\nof wall he was responsible for.There was a clear sense of expectation. Leadership must help\r\npeople know how to focus on something specific and not just throwing all of themselves into\r\neverything and ending up doing nothing.Apportioning roles in piecemeal fashion allows for\r\nfull attention to details.', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(657, 186, 'Let us look into 6 key leadership areas where Nehemiah excelled:', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(658, 186, '<ul>\r\n<li>Efficiency: Work organised for maximum efficiency. Everyone had their section, and\r\nthe work was well organised around specific gates.</li>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(659, 186, '<li>Inclusion: Nehemiah brought every class of people to join with the work. Someof the\r\nrich leaders worked together with the poor man who lived in a single room. There\r\nwas no segregation or feeling of class—I am bigger than you”. Everyone had a stake in\r\nthe kingdom delivery and there was no form of intimidation or feeling inferior.</li>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(660, 186, '<li>Accountability: By giving each man a sense of responsibility for a specific part of the\r\nwork,Nehemiah ensured each man felt accountable. There was a clear sense of who\r\ndid what.</li>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(661, 186, '<li>Inspires Innovation: Nehemiah encouraged innovation in the process of building the\r\nwalls. Goldsmiths, merchants, priests, and perfumers all became construction\r\nworkers (v. 1, 8, 32) which allowed for richer perspective and more creative outcome\r\nas diversity of opinion enhanced the quality of the common output. If the walls and\r\ngates of our church are going to be rebuilt, then everyone would have to play their\r\npart and everyone has something to offer.</li>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(662, 186, '<li>Emotional connection: A great leader must emotionally connect with the people he\r\nleads and must find a way to relate with what is most important to them. If you are\r\nleading students, always be concerned about their grades (Grade Point Average,\r\nJAMB scores) and ask questions about their courses. Be inquisitive about their career\r\ninterests and passions. Be the one to share international scholarship opportunities\r\nwith them. If you lead those who are into entrepreneurship, be vast to engage them\r\non latest trends and emerging opportunities. This leadership practice connects\r\nemotionally and builds a feeling of genuineness. In this specific instance, we see how\r\nNehemiah made the people focus on their own houses first; they started the work by\r\nrepairing the wall that was closest to their own homes, giving them motivation to do\r\nmore and more.When you connect with a man on the level of what is most important\r\nto him, he will go the extra mile.</li>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(663, 186, '<li>No distraction from uncooperative followers: Nehemiah 3:5 mentions that the noble\r\nmen of Tekoa refused to join the project, for whatever reasons.Nehemiah did not\r\nwaste his time, he got the ordinary people there who built two sections of the wall,\r\nand some nobles from other towns rolled up their sleeves and went to work (3:9, 12).\r\nNehemiah did not expend any energy on the nobles of Tekoa, rather, he worked with\r\nthe many willing workers.</li></ul>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(664, 186, 'Effective leadership calls for the ability to see what is needed and to be able to put the right\r\npeople in the right places to deliver the right results. There is no sentiment here. Never\r\nallocate a role out of family or friendship sentiment. There were ten different gates of\r\nJerusalem that were mentioned in this study and Nehemiah had specific builders that\r\nhelped rebuild each.', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(665, 186, '<div class=\"img-responsive\"><img src=\"Pictures/biblestudy/1.png\" /></div>', '2018-12-04 13:31:03'),
(666, 187, 'Nehemiah and the workers had legal protection from the king (Neh. 2:7-9), but since he\r\nhanded the letters to the officers it was addressed to, there may have been no other solid\r\nproof that Nehemiah was authorised to do work there. However, all Sanballat had to do, as\r\nan official of Samaria, was send messengers to inquire from the other governors whether\r\nNehemiah had given them any official letters from the king. That confirmation would have\r\nbeen enough, but Sanballat was a jealous and malicious person who wanted to harm the\r\nwelfare and progress of the Jews. As believers in Christ today, we have been authorised by the\r\nKing of kings to do His work, but the enemy will continue to pretend that this is not so and will\r\ninstead choose to fight against us by different means.', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(667, 187, 'Sanballat was already known previously for his mockery, but now he stepped up his method\r\nof oppression a notch. First, he came with a large group of people (“his brethren and the army\r\nof Samaria”, 4:2) to intimidate the workers in a way to instil fear in their hearts. Then he\r\ncombined this with negative words of discouragement: “What do these feeble Jews? will they\r\nfortify themselves? will they sacrifice? will they make an end in a day? will they revive the\r\nstones out of the heaps of the rubbish which are burned?” His partner Tobiah joined him:\r\n“Even that which they build, if a fox go up, he shall even break down their stone wall.”Satan\r\nfrequently uses ridicule against those who take a stand for the Lord. They openly make jest\r\nand call us various names like holy Mary. They may even be waiting for you to fall into some\r\nsin, so that they can make jest of you. We must not give in to mockery.', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(668, 187, 'They not only called the Jews “feeble”, they also used many words to make them feel their\r\nefforts were useless and that they could never rebuild a strong wall from the great damage\r\nthat had been dealt by Nebuchadnezzar\'s army. Discouragement is such a powerful weapon\r\nbecause it directly challenges our faith. What if the Jews allowed those words to get into their\r\nheads, what if they started paying more attention to the great pile of debris, and become\r\nshaken in the vision Nehemiah had shared with them?', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(669, 187, 'In the early days of TACEF as a fellowship, someone of repute once said that the fellowship is\r\nfull of the children of nobodies and that the fellowship will die as a village fellowship. It is very\r\nhumbling today that TACEF is a blessing to the life of this same individual and God has used\r\nthe platform of the fellowship to secure good jobs for the children of this individual. Never\r\ngive in to wrong statements made about you, your marriage, your children, calling, or your\r\neffort to go back to school to learn new skills. Believe God\'s report about you and never give in\r\nto mockery of the devil. Never be ignorant of his devices (2Cor. 2:11)', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(670, 188, 'It is important to understand that Tobiah and Sanballat were well-known to the high priest of\r\nthat time named Eliashib. Tobiah was affiliated with him (Neh. 13:4, 7), and Sanballat was\r\nactually an extended family member (Neh. 13:28). These two men were related to the high\r\npriest, yet they were the biggest enemy of the work which God wanted to do through\r\nNehemiah. Sometimes our enemies will not be total strangers, but people who are\r\nconnected and close to us in some way, even immediate family members sometimes or even\r\nour best friends. Indeed, a man\'s enemies shall be those of his household (Mat 10:36). But\r\nwhichever the case, we know that those people are only channels because we have only one\r\ntrue enemy, the devil himself, who is the master manipulator who masquerades in different\r\nforms (Matt. 16:23, Luke 22:3, John 6:70-71, Acts 13:10).', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(671, 188, 'Nehemiah\'s immediate response is very important for us to note as a revival army called to\r\nrebuild the old waste places in our church and generation. He did not scream or make claims\r\nthat he was rightfully authorised by the king himself to do this work, but his first response\r\nwas to take the matter to God in prayer. He knew that the battle was not about who can shout\r\nmost in the church committee or church council but who can cry most at the feet of the\r\nowner of the work in the place of prayers. Many of us today will first explore human means to\r\nprove our point before going to God as a last resort when all else fails. This is a wrong mindset,\r\nand we should be like Nehemiah in seeking God first in all things.', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(672, 188, 'When opposition hits, keep your mind focused on the Lord! Don\'t let the enemy take your\r\nfocus off the Lord and onto your own problems.', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(673, 188, '<h1>Week 42 ends here and week 43 starts below</h1>', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(674, 189, 'After the prayer in Nehemiah 4 vs 5, the next verse in Neh 4:6starts with the word, “SO”\r\nwhich means that after they have prayed, they moved into action on the strength of the\r\nenergy they have received in the place of prayer. They got empowered in prayer and the work\r\ncontinues with greater and greater strength. “So we built the wall, and the entire wall was\r\njoined together up to half its height, for the people had a mind to work.”', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(675, 189, 'God answered the prayer by giving them all a mind to work. A mind to work is a gift from God,\r\nand no significant job will ever be accomplished until people come together with a mind to\r\nwork. It is in the place of prayer that our mind gets renewed and reunited to go the extra mile.\r\nThe more a family, a team, subgroup etc. pray together, the more our mind is united to work\r\nfor the Lord. A couple that prays less together will find it difficult to unite in their minds to\r\nmake their marriage work.', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(676, 189, 'The second principle of a balanced spiritual life is captured in Nehemiah 4 vs 17 where the\r\nbuilders build with one hand and carry the sword with another. They were spiritually sound\r\nto wage war against the enemy in a violent situation without losing sight of the need to\r\ncontinue to build lives, careers, ministries etc. Spirituality must never be a reason for\r\nstagnated life, it is actually the reason why you must progress and be the best in all facets of\r\nlife. We combine the dual excellence of an excellent minister and a world-class high performing\r\nprofessionalism the same way as we can be an awesome positive\r\ninfluencer /mentor to people while being the best spouse to our partner in glorious marital\r\nbliss. You can be a first-class student and still be a spiritual giant!', '2018-12-04 13:45:49'),
(677, 190, 'Proverbs 27:6 says—<i>“Faithful are the wounds of a friend, but the kisses of an enemy are\r\ndeceitful.”</i>', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(678, 190, 'The fake friendship of Sanballat were surely deceitful as he continually tried to get\r\nNehemiah to meet with him. When some of our human enemies realise that they cannot\r\novercome us directly, some will become a snake in the grass, pretending to want to be\r\nfriends. The closer they can get then the more easily they can carry out the harm they\r\nactually desire to do. Many Christians make the mistake of falling for this trick. They reason\r\nthat God is Love and commands us to follow peace with all men. While that is true, following\r\npeace with all men does not mean allowing them to deceive us into a compromised position.\r\nWhy will you follow a room-mate or friend to a late-night party just because they made you\r\nfeel bad about not being friendly and social? It is also of note that many Christians in reality\r\njust get tired of standing for God and thus agree to become friends with the enemy, but they\r\nare unaware of what the outcome and results of that friendship will be in the end.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(679, 190, 'Five times, they made efforts to get to Nehemiah but he had a great answer, “I am doing a\r\ngreat work, so that I cannot come down. Why should the work cease, whilst I leave it and\r\ncome down to you?” He was inspired by what he was doing for God. He had focus, he knew\r\nwhat God wanted him to be doing, and he did it. He would not be distracted or side-tracked\r\nby things that sounded good but were not of God. In terms of his language, Nehemiah was\r\nnot being arrogant; he was too convinced and persuaded that what God had given him to do\r\nwas important for the Lord\'s sake and for His people\'s sake. And it was not quite finished.\r\nWalls without gates were as effective as no walls at all. His priority was to finish the wall. He\r\ndid not allow an unnecessary meeting with the enemy in one unknown village of Ono to\r\ndistract him from that one aim.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(680, 190, 'James 4:4 says—“…know ye not that the friendship of the world is enmity with God?\r\nWhosoever therefore will be a friend of the world is the enemy of God.” The thief does not\r\ncome but to steal, but to kill, and to destroy. This was Sanballat\'s true intention, but he\r\nfeigned a false desire for peace and friendship. Those who oppose us and oppose God\'s work\r\nin our lives do not mind stooping to such low levels in order to achieve their aim. They can\r\nmake you feel like a superstar and buy you special gifts, all with the intention to deceive and\r\nattack. We must walk in discernment to know if an enemy has truly repented or if they are\r\nonly pretending, since wicked people do genuinely repent sometimes. There have been\r\ninstances when a so-called converted “harlot” invites a Christian brother to her house with\r\nan intent to lure him into fornication, whereas the brother is serving in the zeal of the Lord\r\nwith no caution. Be careful where you are invited to and never be pushed into a corner to do\r\nthings that will put your spiritual life at risk.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(681, 190, 'This was exactly the same mistake Joshua and the Israelites made in Josh. 9:1-19, as they did\r\nnot inquire of the Lord concerning one group from the enemy\'s camp. The Gibeonites were\r\nCanaanites (who were Israel\'s enemies). God had given the land to Israel and commanded\r\nthem to wipe out the Canaanites for their abominations. The Gibeonites knew they were\r\ndoomed so they came up with a plan to pretend they were not Canaanites but foreigners\r\nfrom a distant land who were on a journey. They put on old worn-out clothes and carried\r\ndried mouldy bread as evidence to Joshua and his army that they were indeed foreign\r\ntravellers that had come to Canaan. But Joshua failed to inquire from the Lord concerning this\r\nmatter (Josh. 9:14), and was deceived into making an agreement of peace, and swore by oath\r\nthat he would not destroy them. It was three days later before the Israelites realised that\r\nthese were Canaanites, but they could not kill them because they had sworn by oath to God\r\n(v. 18). They had to live with the pain forever.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(682, 190, 'Be careful of false friendship when you are at the peak of completing the wall of your life. Be\r\naware of strangers who will like to become friends as soon as you rise to the peak of your\r\ncareer. Be sensitive to many who will flock around you as soon as your ministry breaks forth\r\ninto the next level of impact. The enemy of revival always comes as a friend and the closer\r\nthey come,the easier they can attack. Watch and pray.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(683, 190, 'Clearly, in this study we see that Nehemiah was equipped to see through the outward\r\nappearance, and to understand what Sanballat\'s friendly offer was all about. He had the gift\r\nof discernment to separate the fake from the original, hence he completed the work and his\r\nown life was also preserved.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(684, 191, 'Now the enemy went spiritual to deceive Nehemiah on the platform that he should be most\r\nsensitive to. It was a combination of deception with intimidation and fear. A “prophet” by\r\nname Shemaiah called for Nehemiah and then suggested that the two of them meet within\r\nthe temple and close the doors, adding the fear element, “for they are coming to kill you,\r\nand they are coming to kill you at night” (6:10). Here was a man claiming to have a word from\r\nGod that could save Nehemiah\'s life! If Nehemiah had followed this counsel, his example of\r\nfear would have spread fear among the workers on the wall and the work would have been\r\nstopped while he loses his life.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(685, 191, 'Beware of men like Shemaiah who use “thus saith the Lord” to set traps of deception. Be\r\ncareful of sugar-coated prophets of hell who are wolves in sheep\'s clothing. Be careful when\r\na strange prophet invites you to church for a special “sleepover” like they asked of\r\nNehemiah or a call to have a bath in the river or to break an egg by the intersection of a road.\r\nBe careful when someone claiming to be a man of God invites you to do something that you\r\nknow is wrong. He will use scare tactics to get you to go along with whatever it is. He\r\nspiritualises it with stories of how it has worked for many people and you are tempted.\r\nPlease don\'t fall for false prophets. They destroy destinies! In the case of Nehemiah, the\r\nenemy went the extra mile to hire multiple prophets as spiritual deceivers to destroy the\r\nglorious future of Nehemiah, which he captured in vs 14 <i>“…prophetess Noadiah and the rest\r\nof the prophets who would have put me in fear”</i>. The enemy will go to any length to attack a\r\nman of great destiny. So do watch and pray and then victory is sure.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(686, 191, 'Let us explore how Nehemiah\'s survived this deception. First, we saw that in vs 12 the gift of\r\ndiscernment worked again, “…And lo, I perceived that God had not sent him”. Spiritual\r\nsensitivity and clarity in knowing the mind of God is a strong weapon for every revival army\r\nto survive the deception of time. Are you sure the lady inviting you to become a business\r\npartner is of the Lord? Are you convinced that the person asking to be your roommate in\r\nyour rented apartment is not an agent sent from hell to destroy your future? Are you sure\r\nthe man that has been investing in your business idea is not sent to destroy a kingdom\r\nwealth platform. Be aware that not all breakthroughs are of God. Many so-called\r\nbreakthroughs are road to eternal breakdowns.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(687, 191, 'Now to Nehemiah\'s response to this “spiritually-coded” threat. He said, ““Should a man like\r\nme flee? And could one such as I go into the temple to save his life? I will not go in” (6:11).\r\nNehemiah was challenging the prophet by the written word of God. He knew the word of\r\nGod and he was bold and confident in the word of God He knew that only the priests were\r\nallowed in the temple, and he was not a priest. He would have been disobeying God if he had\r\ndone what Shemaiah suggested as we can see in 2 Chronicles 26, how King Uzziah—who\r\nwas not a priest went into the temple, and got struck with leprosy. When a prophet comes\r\nand says you must sleep with a man before your wedding or that you must divorce your wife\r\nto become successful, then you know that he or she is completely out-of-the-word. Be\r\nimmersed in the word of God because this is the only shield that will preserve you from the\r\ndeception of these fake prophets.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(688, 191, 'We also acknowledge how Nehemiah progressed the matter to God, asking God to take care\r\nof his enemies (6:14). <b>When Satan sends people to intimidate you to disobedience, respond\r\nwith fearless obedience and prayer.</b>', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(689, 191, '<h1>Week 45 ends here and week 46 starts below</h1>', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(690, 192, 'The walls that were in ruins for more than 100 years were rebuilt, re-fixed and renewed in a\r\nperiod of only 52 days! How awesome! The immediate secret is clear—Nehemiah prayed for\r\nfour months, but the work itself took less than two months. Nehemiah worked longer in\r\nprayer than they needed to work to do the job. Clearly, the time spent on the knees was\r\ndouble the time spent on their feet. This shows that building on the knees is actually greater\r\nthan the constructing on our feet! Any great revival move will be accomplished only by the\r\nquantum of prayer backing it.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(691, 192, 'A curious scholar of the word of God may also want to ask why the wall was left in ruins for\r\nmore than 100 years before? Definitely, it was not that no one saw the problem; it was not\r\nthat the walls were not wanted for safety. Many people saw broken walls, knew how they\r\nruined the lives of the people of Jerusalem, but no one got past the place of just wishing\r\nthere were walls.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(692, 192, 'Everyone saw the problem, passed and did nothing. But one man went the extra mile. He did\r\nmore than wish Jerusalem had walls; he grieved, he prayed, he was burdened. He had a clear\r\nvision, he planned, he asked boldly, he went, he fought, he encouraged, he stood strong, he\r\nsaw the job through to completion. He was driven to finish. He was not in it to make an\r\neffort, he was set for a finishing. He was committed to changing the story of his generation\r\nand merely making an attempt was never part of the deal. This explains why he continued to\r\npress towards the mark like Apostle Paul (Phil. 3:14), even in the midst of mockery,\r\nintimidation, discouragement, offers of false friendship, outright lies, and even conspiracies\r\nwith false Jewish prophets. Nehemiah\'s spiritual and physical preparation with a strong\r\nsense of focus enabled by discernment provided the energy that saw them finishing within\r\nan impressive time frame of fifty-two days.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(693, 192, 'May you finish every good work that God has started in you, through you and for you in\r\nJesus name.', '2018-12-04 19:22:02'),
(694, 193, 'Nehemiah and the Jews did not rest on their oars as soon as the wall was completed. It was\r\nnow time to set guards at the gates and high up in the towers, who could control entry/exit\r\nregularly, and also identify enemy forces coming from afar. Without this extra measure,\r\ninvaders could still take advantage and infiltrate the city through unguarded gates and\r\nwithout no one in the towers to see them coming.', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(695, 193, 'The ministry of watching over the walls and gates of our lives and the lives of many who we\r\nlead is a must for every revival army. No casualty must fall when you are the watchman in\r\nyour home, church or campus. We must raise God\'s standard and guard lives from invaders\r\nwho creep into families, jobs, ministries, etc. Jesus commands us to WATCH, so that the\r\nadversary does not work evil when he sees us sleeping (Mark 14:37-38). It is our\r\nresponsibility to protect the territory that God has given to us. We must mark our boundaries\r\nand keep the devil from getting in. We must fortify our gates and push back every invader of\r\nhell.', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(696, 193, 'The first verse of our study text (Neh. 7:1) hints that the singers and temple ministers could\r\nnow rejoice again. The act of worship can now be sustained because the wall is built. When\r\nour lives are secure, our worship and praise will be greater than ever without fear of the\r\nenemy (Luke 1:74). The walls of Jerusalem were not rebuilt just so people could stare at nice\r\nwalls; they were rebuilt so the inhabitants of the city could worship God with dignity, joy, and\r\nfreedom from outside threats, with greater happiness and peace than ever before. Every\r\nvictory in life should take us deeper into praise and worship of our God. Every lifting of wall,\r\nmust make us go tall in service. <b>If your lifting does not translate into more of God, then it will\r\nnot last for God.</b>', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(697, 194, 'The king had appointed Nehemiah as governor of Judah during the initial period he was in\r\nJerusalem (Neh. 5:14). But he knew he would return to Persia at the appointed time as he had\r\nagreed with the king (2:6). Nehemiah\'s gift of strategic leadership informed him that he\r\nwould need to raise up leaders whom he could pass the baton to, in order to ensure the\r\ncontinued welfare of the Jews after he was gone. He appointed Hanani, who was the same\r\nperson that brought the original report of Jerusalem\'s problems to Nehemiah (1:2). We can\r\nidentify this man as a man of initiative and concern who can ignite burden in others and thus\r\nwell qualified to govern. He also appointed Hananiah—a man that was described as faithful\r\nand God-fearing.', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(698, 194, 'Nehemiah was not political. He chose the right men with glorious testimonies.\r\nWe also today must raise others who will be able to stand in our place at all times. Nehemiah\r\nunderstood the need for succession planning. In the process of revival, one should look into\r\nthe future and have full range plan of 1, 3, 5, 10, 25 and 50 years and project on how to\r\ncontinuously sustain ready pipelines of vibrant men who will perpetuate God\'s lineage of\r\ntrue revival from generations to generations. Many moves of God that started with great fire\r\nand zeal have today become redundant because there was no vision for the future, and the\r\ncharisma of the first generation could not be sustained after a few years. Many works of\r\nrevival have become moribund, even buildings where God was worshipped have now been\r\nsold, and are now being used as disco halls. May our success in God transcend time. May the\r\nfire we ignite continue even when we are not there in Jesus name. The secret was Nehemiah\'s\r\nconscious and calculated plan for succession.', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(699, 194, 'Nehemiah saw years ahead. He led by example and showed others how to be a true leader.\r\nHe equipped them spiritually, morally, and financially. His prayer life, generosity, care for the\r\npeople, and ethical standards were witnessed by all, and now Hanani and Hananiah had a\r\nsolid pattern to follow. Great revival army are exemplary and deliberately train those they\r\nleave behind. Revival must not die with a man, but the torch should be passed on to others\r\nwho can keep the flames burning many years later.', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(700, 194, '<h1>Week 48 ends here and week 49 starts below</h1>', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(701, 195, 'This chapter has over 50 verses of names. This long list of names may not mean anything to\r\nus, but means so many things to God because He knows His people by name. Jesus, the Good\r\nShepherd, “calls his own sheep by name,” and they follow Him because they know His voice\r\n(John 10:3-4). The fact that individuals matter to God also means that they should matter to\r\nus as revival agents.We must never take people issues for granted.', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(702, 195, 'In TACEF, we often reframe Proverbs 29 vs 18, “Where there is no vision, the people perish” in\r\nanother way as “Where there are no people, the vision perish” because vision and people are\r\nmutually inter-related and thus their position can be exchanged in that scripture for\r\ncontextual application. Every revival must focus on people—their spiritual well being and\r\nalso their physical fulfilment. Nehemiah was such a revival agent who wanted to see how\r\nbest to bless the people and the city. The population was small and mostly poor, but he\r\nwanted Jerusalem to grow and prosper. Before that could be achieved, he had to first know\r\nwhat he was dealing with, so he took a census of the people (Neh. 7:5). He also matched\r\nthem to their families of origin using the old registry that was recorded when the first wave of\r\nreturning exiles came to Jerusalem (Ezra 2:1-70). The first group of Jews arrived late in the\r\nfirst year of Cyrus and Nehemiah rebuilt the wall in the twentieth year of Artaxerxes so this\r\ncensus happened about 93 years after those initial Jews came back from Babylon. The people\r\nhere with Nehemiah were children or grandchildren of those original returnees, and he could\r\ngroup them by families. Nehemiah helped them make this connection between their\r\nparents\' past success and their own present success, and showed them the importance and\r\npower of cooperation. \\', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(703, 195, 'Nehemiah saw that the Jews were few and poor, but he had to inject a vision of growth and\r\nprosperity into their thinking, and using the old records helped in accomplishing that. Revival\r\nis ultimately about the people. God Himself is of course above all, but He works by getting His\r\nglory through the spiritual and material prosperity of His people (Psalm 35:27).', '2018-12-04 19:34:52'),
(704, 196, 'Verse 1 says that the people gathered themselves together in unison with a desire to seek\r\nGod\'s Word. This is a strong demonstration that the Spirit of God was at work in the midst of\r\nthe Jews. Humans will not assemble en masse of their own freewill to seek God unless the\r\nSpirit is behind it. This mass desire for the things of God was a sign that revival was starting to\r\ntake effect. They became hungry and thirsty for God\'s Word. When the Word and the Spirit\r\nwork together in our lives we begin to see tremendous results.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(705, 196, 'Ezra came to Jerusalem in the 7 year of Artaxerxes (Ez. 7), while Nehemiah came in the 20\r\nyear (Neh. 2). Ezra had already begun to return the people to proper worship of God through\r\nobedience to the Law of Moses (Ez. 9-10), and now the process must continue many years\r\nlater. The Holy Spirit was moving again and people were hungry for the Word. Verse 3 of our\r\ntext says Ezra preached to the people from morning until midday. “Morning” is the Hebrew\r\nword ôr which means illumination (i.e. daybreak/sunrise, which by approximation is 6am),\r\nwhile “Midday” is approximately 12noon. That is 6 hours of preaching the word and the\r\npeople listening with attention and with great result. Only the Spirit of God can explain why a\r\ncongregated mass of people received the message of the Lord for six hours straight. This is\r\none of the stories that we heard of the old revivals in Nigeria when the spirit of the Lord\r\ninterrupts meetings at will and with heavy revelation of the word of God with attendant\r\nimpact in the hearts of men unto salvation, rededication, consecration, brokenness and\r\ngenuine revival.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(706, 196, 'Ezra\'s sermon was not the African Magic story. It was downloaded from the throne of God in\r\nthe place of prayer and it was filled with the fire of the Holy Ghost (the Spirit of Truth, John\r\n16:13). There was no way any of those Jews thought the sermon was too long or wanted to\r\nleave to go and do something else. It was as if they became unaware of everything else and\r\nwere completely taken by God\'s word. They were transfixed by an usual encounter with the\r\nword of God where you do not even have a feeling of time. This is what happens when the\r\nword is preached by the indwelling Spirit of God. Revival won\'t happen in the hearts of men\r\nand women without the Holy Ghost speaking through the minister who has also taken time\r\nto speak to God in prayers.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(707, 196, 'We need a true revival of the word of God. We need deeper revelation of His word that\r\nmakes the audience go home weeping, and with a hunger for more of God\'s word. This is the\r\nconvicting power of the Holy Spirit, who reproves the world of sin, of righteousness, and of\r\njudgement (John 16:8). This is what happened after the Jewish people heard Ezra\'s\r\npreaching. They knew their own personal sins and wept (Neh. 8:9). 2Cor. 7:8-10 shows a\r\nsimilar scenario where a written sermon from Paul convicted the people and caused godly\r\nsorrow that led to repentance. Peter was filled with the Spirit on the day of Pentecost and his\r\nfirebrand message pricked the hearts of his audience, and about 3,000 people were\r\nconverted that very day (Acts 2:37-41). When the Holy Spirit is present with the Word,\r\ngenuine revival is birthed and lives are transformed. We must stay long in God\'s presence to\r\nbe able to speak the word of God as His oracle.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(708, 197, 'In Ezra\'s sermon, we see an emphasis placed on not just hearing the word but also on\r\nunderstanding it. Verses 7-8 mention the names of some of Ezra\'s assistants who helped the\r\npeople to understand the law of Moses. It is very important for us to understand the\r\nScriptures because that is how God\'s mind is revealed to us, and how we can know His will. In\r\nthe parable of the sower, only one group of people understood the word, and therefore\r\nproduced the fruits of revival (Matt. 13:23).', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(709, 197, 'The Jews understood the preaching of Ezra and wept because they were convicted of their\r\nsins and were sorry for those transgressions. But they received more understanding and\r\nrealised in the Mosaic law that God was more than willing to forgive and bless those who\r\nrepent and turn to Him. This truth set them free, and sparked great joy in their hearts (v. 12),\r\nand their entire mood was uplifted. The joy of the Lord is indeed our strength! (v. 10). More\r\npeople, including priests and Levites, came to seek understanding of God\'s word from Ezra\r\n(v. 13). The process of reformation had begun. It was the seventh month so they stirred the\r\npeople to keep the appointed feast of tabernacles, which lasts seven days and an extra day.\r\nWe see how understanding God\'s word can produce results. A minister of the gospel must be\r\nconcerned about preaching a message with understanding. We must make effort to simplify\r\nand make practical in ways that is clear as the Holy spirit Himself breathes out through our\r\nvoice.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(710, 197, 'The understanding of God\'s word sparked revival. It did not stop in one or two days, but\r\ncontinued day by day for seven days straight as the word was preached each day (v. 18). We\r\nwill see similar results today when we welcome the Holy Spirit to preach through us and\r\nimpart understanding to our audience. People will be willing to hear the word of God day\r\nafter day for several days in a row because it is not us that they\'re listening to, but what God\r\nhas to say to them.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(711, 197, 'The impact of the word is also a function of the speaker. You will observe here that Nehemiah\r\nis not leading this aspect of the revival even with all his outstanding previous exploits. Why\r\nEzra? Until now, Nehemiah has been in the forefront. He was a gifted administrator who\r\ncould organise and mobilise people to get the wall built. But when it was time to teach the\r\nWord, he took a back seat to Ezra, who was skilled in the law of Moses, who had set his heart\r\nto study it, practice it, and teach it (Ezra 7:6, 10). These two men illustrate beautifully the\r\nprinciple of team ministry and a sincere appreciation of staying in your place of strength.', '2018-12-04 19:44:33'),
(712, 198, 'The people have heard the word of God from Ezra. They were convicted by the righteousness\r\ncontained in the law and wept, but they had also rejoiced because that day was a holy day\r\nand because there was also forgiveness available from God. On the twenty fourth day of that\r\nsame month (two days after the feast of tabernacles ended), the congregation came\r\ntogether to fast before God corporately. Wearing sack-cloth and pouring sand on their heads\r\nwas an ancient Israelite way of showing self-humility, guilt, grief, or acknowledgement of\r\ntrespasses (9:1).', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(713, 198, 'True repentance always originates from a contrite heart and broken spirit. This was how\r\nDavid felt in Psalm 51 after his great sin of adultery and murder. Verse 17 of that Psalm says:\r\n“The sacrifices of God are a broken spirit; a broken and a contrite heart, O God, thou will not\r\ndespise”. The Lord knows when the person is sincerely sorry for his wrong. In Isaiah 66:2 God\r\nsays He looks to the man that is poor and of a contrite spirit, who trembles at His Word. James\r\n4:6-10 also gives us a picture of what a truly remorseful person or people should exhibit.', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(714, 198, 'The second part of chapter 9 is mostly a confession of the sins of the fathers. When any nation\r\nseeks true revival, we must be willing to not only admit our own wrongs, but also the wrongs\r\nof those long before us who did not do right by God. This includes both our spiritual and\r\npolitical leaders from years past. This is what identification repentance and intercession\r\nmean. The Levites freely confessed, not dealing with sin on an individual level alone, but also\r\non a national level. This way, God could deal with the Jews both as individuals and as a nation,\r\nand be willing to heal their land. 2Chron. 7:14 says “If my people, which are called by my\r\nname, shall humble themselves, and pray, and seek my face, and turn from their wicked\r\nways; then will I hear from heaven, and will forgive their sin, and will heal their land”.', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(715, 198, '<b><i>The realisation of national revival and restoration will only be experienced when a nation\r\nacknowledges their departure from God and return to Him in full remorse and repentance.</i></b>', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(716, 199, 'Chapter 10 shows how the people entered into covenant with God and vowed by oath to live\r\nby the laws He gave to Moses for Israel. The princes, Levites, and priests were the signatories\r\nto the contract, and their names are listed within 9:38 – 10:27. The rest of the Jews who had\r\nseparated themselves from the heathen to follow God\'s law also made an oath of obedience\r\nand dedication (10:28-29). The rest of the chapter (verses 30-39) goes into the details of\r\nsome of the laws which were to be kept.', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(717, 199, 'Revival is never full until practical obedience and righteousness are executed. We can be\r\nsorry for our sins but if we do not <b>forsake</b> them,no real transformation has taken place. “He\r\nthat covers his sins shall not prosper, but whoso <b>confesses</b> and <b>forsakes</b> them shall have\r\nmercy” (Prov. 28:13).', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(718, 199, 'The Jews were ready to follow God\'s laws both as individuals and as a nation collectively. True\r\nrevival must activate deliberate changes in how we live our lives as individuals, families,\r\nbusiness partners, communities and even as a nation. Peter once said: “Of a truth I perceive\r\nthat God is no respecter of persons; but in every nation he that feareth Him and worketh\r\nrighteousness is accepted by Him” (Acts 10:34-35). God is the Creator of all humanity. He has\r\nalso told us what to do in order to be blessed as a nation – Proverbs 14:34 –“Righteousness\r\nexalts a nation, but sin is a reproach to any people”. Practical righteousness and obedience to\r\nGod are the only way we will see the transformation that most of us so greatly desire in our\r\ncommunity. This, however, starts first in the place of intercession, which will lead to\r\nimpactful changes in the society. Our country is in serious need of this move of God.', '2018-12-04 19:54:19'),
(719, 199, 'Our country is known for corruption, greed, and lies. 419 is the second name associated with\r\nus in many countries and the green passport can cause anyone a long delay on arrival at any\r\nairport. This situation will never be turned around until revival agents rise up in serious\r\nintercession to birth a new country where the fear of God reigns. We must use prayer to\r\nchange the spiritual atmosphere of our country. <b>We have wasted too many hours of prayer in\r\nselfish prayers that have no impact in the world we live in. True national revival starts when\r\nprayers melts the heart of men unto remorse towards God.</b> This genuine change of HEART\r\nwill definitely lead to changes in our external conditions and society. Our nation must\r\nexperience God like never before in our generation.', '2018-12-04 19:54:19');
